democratic presidential candidate michael dukakis said thursday the reagan administration has ``walked away from the american dream'' with policies to help the rich at the expense of working people
i'm running for president because during the past seven years i've seen too many people thrown out into the streets after decades on the job. ... i've talked to too many local leaders who've seen their communities become ghost towns of boarded up hopes and foreclosed dreams,'' the massachusetts governor said
his speech at serb hall, a traditional rallying spot for presidential hopefuls in wisconsin, came with polls suggesting dukakis is in a virtual dead heat with jesse jackson heading into tuesday's primary
jackson has been making a strong pitch in wisconsin to blue-collar workers, asking them to support him as he supported striking meatpackers and paperworkers as well as kenosha autoworkers about to lose their jobs because of a plant closing
while hitting hard at the reagan administration, dukakis refrained from criticizing other democratic candidates. one day earlier, he had spoken in general terms of his differences with jackson and then had criticized gore for demanding he be more specific
at a news conference after the speech, dukakis, responding to questions, said he felt he was better qualified than jackson to be president because of his experience as a governor of massachusetts. but he stopped well short of criticizing jackson
dukakis also called for the resignation of attorney general edwin meese iii
asked why he felt he was better qualified than jackson, dukakis said: ``i think i am going to be a better president because i think i have the strength, the experience and the values to lead this country, because i am somebody who not only believes in good jobs and good wages for people, i've helped to create them.''
in his speech, dukakis reserved his criticism for the reagan white house
this administration has walked away from the american dream,'' dukakis said thursday. ``they've walked away from the basic contract that says if you work hard and pay your taxes and live within the law, you have a right to a good job; and the right to a life where you don't have to go to bed every night worried about whether that job will still be there in the morning.''
dukakis said the reagan administration has done nothing to move people from welfare to jobs, to fight adult illiteracy, to preserve good-paying jobs or to provide adequate health care to the needy
he said he is running for president ``because i believe that every american should have a house _ not a slab of concrete or a heating grate _ that they can call home.''
dukakis also promised what he called a real war on drug and alcohol dependency and asked, ``how can we tell our children to say no to drugs when this administration can't say no to one of the largest drug peddlers in this hemisphere?'' _ an apparent reference to panamanian strongman gen. manuel antonio noriega. bgng: ``forty makes</note>
democrat albert gore jr. defended his criticism of rival jesse jackson on thursday and took issue with michael dukakis for being ``afraid to say a single word about jesse jackson.'' later, he called for the removal of attorney general edwin meese
at a florida fundraiser, gore said the attorney general should step down because it is ``time to remove the cloud over the department of justice.''
how long will it take this administration to understand the importance of integrity in government?'' gore asked a crowd at the posh grove isle resort. ``we cannot tolerate a situation where the nation's chief law enforcement officer is constantly testifying as a suspect before grand juries, constantly operating under a cloud of suspicion.''
the tennessee senator pointed to the departure of top justice department officials and reports that they had quit because they believed meese was hurting the department by staying on
president reagan and vice president bush say, `oh, it's no bid deal. there are resignations all the time.' what insensitivity! what contempt for the american people!'' said gore
the gore campaign raised about $108,000 at the florida event, said mitchell berger, one of the organizers
earlier, gore commented after a capitol hill celebration marking his 40th birthday, an event that came as a relief to the candidate who has grown weary of answering questions about running for president while still in his 30s
forty makes all the difference,'' he said
gore reacted to questions at a news conference about his remarks on monday in new york, when he criticized jackson as without experience and said he was dismayed by the candidate's associations with plo leader yasser arafat and cuban president fidel castro
gore said that by his criticism he was holding jackson, the civil rights activist, to the same standard as other candidates
i've said exactly the same thing i've said over the last year, and all of a sudden it's a big deal,'' gore said. ``well, the only reason it seems to some people like a big deal is that mike dukakis is afraid to say a single word about jesse jackson.''
dukakis, however, began cautiously speaking of differences between himself and jackson on the middle east and domestic policy on wednesday. dukakis said ``from time to time differences will arise ... and those will come out over time.''
dukakis and jackson have won the most democratic delegates so far, with gore in third place
the tennesse senator spoke to reporters in the sunshine in front of the capitol after joining in a birthday celebration in a senate office building
you know, jack benny was perpetually 39,'' gore said. ``i've been doing a kind of reverse jack benny in this campaign _ i've been trying to turn 40.''
gore planned to spend the next four days campaigning in wisconsin before tuesday's primary there
his campaign began airing a new television ad in that state attacking chrysler corp. chairman lee iacocca for closing the chrysler assembly plant in kenosha. it shows gore stating that iacocca was paid $20 million in 1986. ``i'll make these corporations pay their share of the taxes and create jobs here in america,'' gore said in the ad
gore was asked about his criticism of jackson a day after his rival said gore's comments amounted to a personal attack and canceled a meeting between the two. gore called that characterization ridiculous, and he faulted dukakis for what he termed a ``ludicrous'' hesitancy to engage jackson in debate or criticism
gore is still trying to restart his campaign in the north, where he has failed to duplicate his southern success _ or even to register in double-digits in the illinois primary and michigan caucuses
he reacted strongly when asked by a questioner whether he has been privately encouraged to rop out of the presidential race in order to stop splitting the white vote _ a question that suggested jackson was profiting by the battle between gore and dukakis
gore said the ``question has a racial if not racist premise.'' he said he had not been so urged and called it inappropriate to talk about such racial divisions. update with report on fried asking meese to resign and being rebuffed. inserts 3 grafs after 21st graf pvs bgng: the criminal ... to update with rappaport now apparently not cooperating with investigation. deletes last few grafs to tighten.</note>
republican sen. strom thurmond met thursday with attorney general edwin meese iii and expressed ``deep concern'' on behalf of congress about problems at the justice department in the wake of the resignations of two of meese's top aides
meese's meeting with thurmond, the ranking republican on the senate judiciary committee, was the strongest signal to date of growing bipartisan concern in congress over whether the attorney general, the focus of an 11-month criminal investigation, can continue to run the justice department
a number of people on capitol hill have expressed deep concern about the problems at the justice department,'' thurmond said in a statement after the meeting. ``i went today to talk to the attorney general to convey these concerns to him.''
minutes after the meeting, meese refused to answer reporters' questions about the resignations when he attended a news conference at fbi headquarters on a drug bust
meanwhile, the new york times reported in friday's editions that solicitor general charles fried, the justice department's fourth-ranking official, this week urged meese to resign but was rebuffed
according to the newspaper, fried told meese in a meeting wednesday that the attorney general's legal problems were creating turmoil within the department
after the meeting, meese said he hoped and expected that the solicitor general would stay on. department officials told the times that fried had stressed that he was making no judgment on whether meese was guilty of a crime. they said fried told meese that the mounting dispute over his leadership and ethical standards was hindering the department's work
charles feels strongly that meese has to go for the good of the department,'' one official told the times
fried, reached at home thursday night by the associated press, refused to discuss any aspect of the story
i'm not going to comment on that,'' he said
the times also reported that lewis f. powell jr., the retired supreme court justice, said fried called him monday evening ``very upset and concerned, and very perplexed about what he should do.''
meese, who said wednesday ``there's no reason'' for him to resign, said he would answer questions on the resignations of his aides ``within the next several days'' when ``i hope and i fully expect ... to be announcing various appointments to fill those vacancies.''
the business of law enforcement is going forward energetically and without interrupton,'' meese said. ``our strong management team is on the job.''
the attorney general, a longtime confidant of president reagan, stood somberly next fbi director william sessions as the fbi chief praised deputy attorney general arnold burns and assistant attorney general william weld, who quit tuesday because they felt meese's continuing legal troubles were hurting justice department operations
i think they're very fine gentlemen, served their government well, are to be commended for the service that they performed,'' sessions said when asked about burns and weld, who oversaw all federal criminal investigations
meese, in response to a reporter's question, said he had no plans to meet with thurmond later in the day, neglecting to mention that he had already done so
after the news conference and after thurmond already had issued his statement, justice department spokesman terry eastland issued a clarifying statement confirming that the meeting had occurred before the news conference
thurmond said at a senate judiciary subcommittee meeting in the morning that he wouldn't ``countenance any corruption in any way, shape or form in the justice department or any other department.''
the washington post reported thursday, and justice department sources subsequently confirmed, that weld had told meese during a meeting tuesday that the criminal investigation of the attorney general was a close call in terms of whether the attorney general should be prosecuted
weld went on to say that if he were the independent counsel investigating meese, he would present the case to a grand jury seeking indictment, according to the sources, who spoke only on condition of anonymity
sen. arlen specter, r-pa., said thursday that reagan should meet with weld and then reconsider whether meese should stay on the job. specter said weld's reported remarks require a presidential inquiry and decision
on wednesday, sen. bob packwood, r-ore., said flatly that meese should resign. senate democratic leader robert byrd of west virginia also called for his resignation, saying meese was ``the crown jewel of the sleaze factor in reagan administration history.''
sen. daniel evans, r-wash., told reporters thursday that if meese encounters difficulty in finding capable replacements for burns and weld and there is evidence the department is not functioning well, and ``he ought to step aside.''
but sen. alan simpson, r-wyo., the senate's deputy gop leader, said he was ``appalled'' at the hue and cry over meese
they've never laid a glove on him yet,'' simpson said, adding there is no indication meese is guilty of anything
nancy reagan's press secretary, elaine crispen, said reports that the first lady was campaigning for meese's removal were ``absolutely not true.''
she hasn't talked to anyone and no one has talked to her about the issue,'' mrs. crispen said by telephone from los angeles, where mrs. reagan was visiting before joining the president at their california ranch friday for an easter vacation
the criminal investigation of meese launched last may 11 by independent counsel james mckay is continuing, and so far has delved into his involvement through longtime friend e. robert wallach with scandal-plagued wedtech corp. and a proposed $1 billion iraqi pipeline project
a partner in the pipeline project, swiss financier bruce rappaport, had been scheduled to give a deposition about the case to mckay last month but backed out and has apparently decided not to cooperate with the investigation, the washington post reported in friday's editions
the newspaper, quoting unidentified sources in washington and abroad, said rappaport was scheduled to give sworn testimony at a meeting in london with mckay and his aides but changed his mind at the last minute because he was afraid he might not remember everything accurately
rappaport was to have been given immunity from prosecution in the case
mckay widened the probe this week by subpoenaing payroll records and other documents of the washington chapter of the multiple sclerosis society in connection with a $40,000-a-year job meese's wife, ursula, got with the charity in 1985. investigators are examining wallach's role in helping mrs. meese get the job. suggests</head>
comets do not deserve a reputation as pure samples of material from the birth of the solar system, because they have been altered in deep space, suggests an analysis published today
heat from very bright stars and star explosions called supernovae has altered their characteristics, researchers from the university of colorado at boulder propose
there's no such thing as a pristine comet,'' said j. michael shull, who presented the analysis with colleague s. alan stern in today's issue of the british journal nature
comets are essentially dirty snowballs that formed at the birth of the solar system. scientists study them for clues to the conditions surrounding the formation of the sun and planets
trillions of comets are thought to orbit the sun some 10,000 to 100,000 times as far away as the earth's orbit, shull said. those comets have never been seen, but astronomers do spot comets that have left that orbit and swung in toward the sun
while still in their distant orbits, the analysis contends, the comets have been heated to differing extents by passing stars and by supernova explosions. that caused boiling that obliterated the original structure and chemical composition of the comet surfaces, the analysis says
paul feldman, professor of physics and astronomy at johns hopkins university in baltimore, called the proposal intriguing
comets that return to view on a regular schedule have certainly been heated and modified by repeated trips near the sun, he said, but comets making their first trip to the inner solar system are thought to contain pristine material
their hypothesis is not likely to be easily tested by remote observations from the ground or from earth-orbiting observatories, but will await future missions to comets which can actually measure the composition and structure of the ice directly'' he said. scheme</head>
the nephew of kenya's founding president has been fined $5,000 and credited for time served for his role in a 1,900-pound marijuana importation conspiracy
for your greed, you ... have failed your government and certainly your family,'' u.s. district judge alfred m. wolin said wednesday in sentencing samuel muigai, 36, nephew of kenya's first president jomo kenyatta
muigai walked away a free man after paying the fine and serving more than five months in jail since his arrest in october on charges of conspiring to import the marijuana. three co-defendants were sentenced to prison
muigai pleaded guilty to conspiring to import an unspecified quantity of the drug, which carries a maximum term of five years in prison
wolin, who sentenced two kenyan co-defendants to six years in prison and a third to nine years for their guilty pleas, found that muigai played a ``truly passive'' role ``limited to greed,'' in the scheme
a fifth kenyan, millionaire arms dealer and land developer stephen mwangi, 49, was found innocent after a trial earlier this month. a ugandan defendant, mpigi kabasha mbogo, 39, is to be sentenced monday
the six men were arrested after they traveled to gloucester city, where the pot had just arrived aboard a ship. they were to be paid $1 million in the deal, negotiated through undercover agents in telephone calls to kenya
though muigai's crime was an ``affront to the people of the united states,'' wolin said he was satisfied muigai was remorseful and had learned a ``bitter lesson.'' he also took note that muigai was the first to plead guilty
muigai, dressed in a gray pin-stripped suit and white loafers, apologized for his involvement in what he called an ``unfortunate incident.''
i would like to assure you, sir, that i don't intend and i don't think i will ever stand in another court of law for charges of any sort of criminal activity,'' he told the judge
muiga's his attorneys argued that muigai's co-defendants invited him to meet with wealthy american businessmen interested in developing some of his property
even after learning the discussions with the ``businessmen,'' who turned out to be federal agents, concerned marijuana, muigai went along, hoping still to discuss the land deal, the court papers said
the stiffest sentence, nine years, went to steven thuku, who wolin determined was the principal in the deal for making the contacts with the sources of the marijuana and the other defendants
wolin found that geoffrey m. tumbo, 45, and daniel m. githegi, 36, had less culpability and gave them six-year prison terms
they pleaded guilty to conspiring to import more than 110 pounds of marijuana, a charge carrying a 20-year maximum penalty. impropriety</head>
attorney general edwin meese iii's friend e. robert wallach says he should have been more sensitive to an appearance of impropriety in helping meese set up a financial partnership with an investment manager who wound up on the board of wedtech corp
in an interview published thursday in the san jose (calif.) mercury news, wallach said that he ``missed the boat completely'' on the potential conflict of interest in linking meese with the investment manager, w. franklyn chinn of san francisco in may 1985
meese knew at the time that chinn was doing work for wedtech. chinn subsequently become a member of wedtech board of directors
wallach and chinn were indicted in december on racketeering charges for allegedly extracting payments from wedtech as part of a scheme to influence meese and other public officials to assist the defense contractor
in 1981 and 1982, wallach wrote meese a dozen memos urging the then-white house counselor's support for the bronx, n.y. defense contractor. meese interceded on wedtech's behalf in connection with the company's efforts to get a $32 million no-bid contract to build small engines for the army. wedtech ended up wining the contract in 1982
i just missed the boat completely on the wedtech connection,'' wallach said, referring to the potential for a conflict of interest. ``wedtech at the time was just an irrelevancy
i knew that my memos (to meese) had had nothing to do with the award of the (wedtech) contract in 1982. ... we (wallach and meese) were trapped by our own honest conduct. we never thought of wedtech. ... our state of mind in april '85 was, we had not played a major role in wedtech.''
wallach also insisted that neither he nor meese was aware of memos in 1981 and 1982 from then white house counsel fred fielding warning meese's top deputy and other administration officials not to intercede in wedtech's military contract discussions because of ethical and procedural considerations
on reflection, a more cautious approach on my part would have been wise,'' said wallach. ``a more cautious approach on his (meese's) part would have been wise.''
in the interview with the san jose newspaper, wallach also said meese had ``nothing absolutely'' to do with a $150,000 payment to wallach in 1985 in connection with a $1 billion iraqi oil pipeline deal
the $150,000 was a legal fee to wallach by one of his clients, swiss oilman bruce rappaport, a partner in the pipeline project
the $150,000 wound up in a stock trading account owned by chinn and the money was, in effect, pooled with that of other investors, including meese, to generate profits in highly speculative stock trading of brand new stock issues which were bought and sold on the same day
under this arrangement, chinn turned a $40,000 profit for meese on a $50,000 investment in just 18 months
the pooling of money from chinn's various investors, including meese, helped the financial manager obtain the funds to get new stock issues. it would have been difficult for chinn to obtain the new issues of stock with meese's money alone
wallach said that when all of the facts are known, his and chinn's handling of the $150,000 originally paid to wallach will emerge as ``the classic bureaucratic error.'' he declined to elaborate
wallach said the main reason he introduced meese to chinn was because meese stood to make more money investing with chinn than with more conventional institutions
i probably was influenced disproportionately by frank's offering a high return,'' wallach said
should i have been more prudent and recommended him (meese) to a more major investment firm?'' wallach asked. ``in retrospect, yes.''
a recent survey shows that while about 70 percent of u.s. adults indicate they watch television during the evening hours, only 12 percent said it is their principal activity
we found that most people are not just simply couch potatoes, but do a number other things with their free time,'' said carol hess, a research consultant for lexington-based decision research corp
most adults reported they combine television viewing with other activities, such as cooking, cleaning and doing crafts, hess said wednesday
the drc survey, a follow-up to a previous leisure time poll released last year, asked 1,000 adults during october, november and december to describe how they spent the previous evening from 5 p.m. to 1 a.m
reading was the second most popular activity, particularly among older respondents, with 22 percent reporting books or magazines as part of their evening
men comprised the majority of the 18 percent saying they worked during the evening, while the 9 percent reporting they shopped were mostly women, according to the survey
other top activities included dining out, 12 percent; with sports or exercising, going to a meeting or having sex each noted by 2 percent of the respondents. one percent went to a movie
we had a lot of other responses from knitting to spent last night in jail to skinning a raccoon,'' said hess
yet only 15 percent rated their evening as ``great,'' with satisfaction higher among older or married respondents or people with annual incomes above $50,000
the recent survey was launched after drc researchers last year found that many respondents felt their leisure time was diminishing
we thought this was curious considering all the labor-saving equipment and that, in theory, people have a five-day work week,'' said hess
drc research, however, indicates that people perceive they have less leisure time because of the trend toward highly structured activities outside of work, said hess
when i ask you what are your favorite leisure activities, you might say sailing or something,'' said hess. ``you are not likely to say you love going swimming at the health club five mornings a week, although that is something you chose to do. it's not a question that people have less leisure time. it's that people are losing their discretionary time; time that is for myself.''
hess noted that the low percentage of inveterate ``couch potatoes'' suggest people are seeking to gain more control over their free time
i think we are looking here at people exercising more freedom of choice,'' said hess. ``it shows they can exercise their discretionary power to pick what gives them pleasure rather than accepting what's out there in a passive way.''
ronald james says he drove with a radar detector in his car for years without an accident. but his insurance company dropped him anyway and eventually hit a roadblock that forced it to restore his coverage
the maryland insurance commissioner two weeks ago, citing data that drivers like james are no more likely to crash than drivers who don't carry radar detectors, threw out geico corp.'s rule against underwriting drivers who own radar detectors
it was under that rule that geico canceled james' policy, but a trade association called radar won him reinstatement and filed a complaint with state officials
i've never had an accident,'' said james, 45, who commutes to work in washington from suburban maryland. he said he bought the detector after speeding unintentionally and getting a ticket. ``i don't speed anymore, i outgrew that years ago.''
an estimated 4 million people nationally use radar detectors, and advocates hope the ruling in maryland will help keep them legal
this is the first ruling of its kind in the country,'' said janice lee, president of the cincinnati-based radio association defending airwave rights inc., the trade group
the devices, which alert drivers that police may be tracking them by scanning for certain radar frequencies, are illegal in virginia, connecticut and washington, d.c
legislation to ban the detectors was introduced this year in 12 states and still has a chance of passing in michigan, new jersey, new york, mississippi and massachusetts, said ms. lee, whose organization represents about a dozen manufacturers with an estimated $300 million in yearly sales
geico tried to make law, and the commissioner told them they had to play by everybody else's rules,'' ms. lee said
the ruling, written by associate deputy insurance commissioner thomas p. raimondi, criticized geico's ``vision (of) itself as the good witch of the north who, alone among the 800 property and casualty insurers, is pointing the magic anti-radar wand of the good corporate citizen in condemnation of the use of radar devices by the citizens of this state.''
highway safety groups say the detectors ought to be illegal because they are used primarily to break the law
speed is not a function of emotion or economics or politics,'' said robert w. o'brien, spokesman for the national safety council. ``speed is a function of physics: the faster you go, the more likely it is that you'll have an accident.''
companies such as state farm insurance co., the nation's largest auto insurer, and aetna insurance co. said they have no detector rules because most states recognize the devices as legal
insurers also cited the dearth of direct evidence. the insurance industry does not know how many accidents or how many claims are related to detectors, said harvey seymour of the industry-funded insurance information institute
we oppose speeding and the use of radar detectors. (but) it's very hard to statistically support that people with radar detectors have more accidents,'' said richard doran, director of automobile underwriting for allstate insurance co., the nation's second-largest auto insurer
allstate has concluded that, although it might lose money on drivers with radar detectors, its data would not support a ban in court, doran said
(geico's) guideline was a little arbitrary,'' doran said
geico, based in washington, d.c., last week failed to win an injunction against the maryland order, but says it will appeal in baltimore circuit court
and a study in texas may show whether speeders are likely to be using radar detectors
the federally financed study by the texas transportation institute at texas a&amp;m university is slated for completion late this year. it will use two radar units to clock car speeds in four states. one undetectable radar _ using a specially licensed frequency _ will observe speeds before and after a detectable signal is turned on
using the same method last year in maryland and virginia, the industry-backed insurance institute for highway safety found that 29 percent of cars going faster than 70 mph, and 19 percent going 66 mph to 70 mph, slowed down abruptly when they encountered the second radar
we know the effects of speed, and we know that these (radar detectors) cause drivers to go faster. therefore, our conclusion is that people who use radar detectors would cause higher'' numbers of fatalities, said john cook, vice president of the institute
arguing before the commission, geico used that study and others to calculate that drivers using detectors are equal to drivers ``with two more more violations and would have 2.41 times as many accidents.''
radar, on the other hand, cited a survey showing that drivers using detectors were involved in fewer accidents and were more likely to wear seat belts than drivers as a whole
there are at least four men in new york prisons who have something in common with a new inmate, robert chambers: they all killed somebody in new york city on aug. 26, 1986
but the similarities end there. unlike the killer of jennifer levin, they are serving their time in obscurity. no camera-wielding mobs hounded them when they surrendered, no tabloids splashed their names in headlines
all four cases were in the impoverished south bronx, uptown from the grassy spot in central park where the former prep school student killed miss levin, from the bar on manhattan's east side patronized by chambers, miss levin and other affluent young people
it isn't fair,'' said angel traverso, 16, a neighbor of one of the victims, rosa dueno, 44. ``they make such a big deal out of jennifer levin's death and rosa's death means nothing.''
chambers, 21, started a five- to 15-year sentence saturday for killing miss levin, 18, during what he initially called an episode of ``rough sex.'' the day before, while a jury deliberated murder charges against him, he pleaded guilty to first-degree manslaughter
chambers and the other defendants all killed people they knew, and they were arrested quickly. three of the four bronx killers pleaded guilty after bargaining with prosecutors, as chambers did
but none went through the protracted litigation that chambers did, and all but one are serving longer sentences
the one who received a lighter term was ms. dueno's killer, juan enrique. he had a history of beating ms. dueno, who was his girlfriend, and on aug. 26, 1986, he stabbed her to death
he was never charged with murder. he pleaded guilty to second-degree manslaughter and was sentenced may 19 to two-and-a-third to seven years in prison
in a city that averages about five homicides a day, the deaths of ms. dueno and the others were largely unnoticed. the disposition of the cases went unnoticed as well:
_ santos cuello valdez, charged with second-degree murder for shooting daniel alvarez to death, pleaded guilty last may 14 to first-degree manslaughter. justice elbert hinkson sentenced him on june 26 to seven to 21 years in prison
_ a grand jury charged juan quinones with second-degree murder in the stabbing of rachel pajooh, 48. she allegedly had shot at him once when he tried to rob her and had reported him to police. after a non-jury trial, justice lawrence bernstein convicted quinones of first-degree manslaughter and sentenced him on oct. 7, 1987, to 12{ to 25 years in prison
_ ronald matthews, indicted on a charge of second-degree murder after he smashed his father's head with a sledgehammer, pleaded guilty to first-degree manslaughter and was sentenced by justice ivan warner on oct. 13 to six to 18 years in prison
there is no indication as to whether the families of the victims were consulted when the guilty pleas were negotiated; prosecutors gave the levin family the right to veto their agreement with chambers
and no news conferences were called when the bronx cases were wrapped up
ed mccarthy, a spokesman for the bronx district attorney's office, said the assistant district attorneys who prosecuted the cases were not available to discuss them, or to compare them with the more celebrated case in manhattan
it's apples and oranges,'' he said. ``what happened there, happened there. what happens here, happens here.''
for $2 or so, you can hungrily cradle a barrel of popcorn while watching characters in ``babette's feast'' ravish blini with black caviar, quail stuffed with foie gras and other magnificent morsels in what has to be one of the most inspiring meals ever shown on the screen
for $88 more, you can follow this feast for the eyes with one for the body
one thing will happen after you see this movie: you will be starving,'' said dro e. proudian, general manager at petrossian inc., whose restaurant is one of several around the the country serving the seven-course feast during the run of the movie, denmark's entry for an academy award as best foreign film
when you see the film, how complicated the meal is, how expensive, all the marketing,'' there will be a greater understanding of the art of preparing a great meal, said yannick cam, chef and owner at le pavillion in washington, which begins serving the feast in april
the movie, based on a story by isak dinesen, tells of two unmarried and pious sisters who take a french political refugee, babette, into their home on the bleak coast of norway, in return for housekeeping. fourteen years later, when babette wins 10,000 francs in the lottery, she repays them with a feast so strange to them that one sister, in anticipation, compares it to a witch's sabbath
but babette fills the hearts, as well as the bellies, of her 12 guests, mostly members of the sisters' religious community
it was a whole experience, that's why we did it,'' said stella geller of west orange, n.j., who with her husband followed the film with dinner recently at petrossian. ``i didn't leave a bite of anything. i ate every bite.''
so far, plans have been made for the feast at restaurants in philadelphia, miami, los angeles, washington, san francisco and laguna niguel, calif., according to alfred rosenthal, orion classics' gastronomic consultant for the dinners. prices will vary slightly, with $80 the lowest, without wines, he said
that will buy: turtle soup; blini with black caviar; quail stuffed with foie gras baked in a pastry nest with truffle sauce; salad; cheeses; rum cake with candied fruit; fresh fruit; coffee. add $35 for four wines
as the movie opens in more cities, theater owners and restaurateurs can use a guide written by rosenthal to help them present the feast and find such ingredients as turtle meat
while the meal is expensive, proudian called it a bargain, noting the normal prices of just three ingredients: 30 grams of fresh russian sevruga caviar ($21); 2{ ounces of fresh foie gras ($15); three-quarters of an ounce of black truffle ($30)
the people who come here are adventurous, a lot of romantic people,'' proudian said in a recent interview at petrossian, a mirrored and marbled restaurant near carnegie hall
to meet their expectations and recreate the sense of abundance evident on babette's table, he said, ``the caviar has to be heaping, you have to see the truffles, not just a speck here, a slice there. when you put your knife into the quail, you have to feel the foie gras.''
it was extraordinarily difficult, because we had to recreate a visual image on a plate,'' he said
petrossian's chef, michel attali, said he encountered one problem. in the film, the quail is served sitting in its pastry nest with the head on. believing that would not be acceptable here, attali fashioned pastry ``heads'' for the tiny game birds
but no matter how faithful, diners will not experience the same mood as in the film, cam said: ``first the house in the film, and it was a little religious dinner. i don't think we can reproduce that.''
still, proudian said, ``the star of the movie is the food. so if you are in this business, it's nice to see all of this dignity and respect given to the preparation of food.''
it looks more and more as though president reagan will leave office without achieving his stated goal of making daniel ortega say ``uncle.''
in the view of many latin american experts, reagan's policy of keeping the pressure on ortega's nicaraguan government to bring about peace and democracy has failed
you have peace, but you don't have freedom,'' says neil pickett, an expert on national and international security affairs at the hudson institute in indianapolis
they're about to leave office, and they've got a contra program that's falling apart on them,'' says ed king, latin american adviser to senate majority leader robert c. byrd
as g. pope atkins, senior associate specializing in south american affairs at the center for strategic and international studies, sees it, the stated goal of the policy has kept shifting
the first one was simply to interdict nicaraguan arms to el salvador,'' atkins said. ``then it was rather strongly implied that the idea was to bring down the regime. and now the idea is that if they (nicaragua's leaders) will change, everything will be all right.''
marlin fitzwater, the president's chief spokesman, says the administration's goal remains the same: ``the situation is that we need aid to the contras in the worst way.''
but questions remain whether wednesday's house vote to continue non-lethal aid and leave the door open for military aid, and the expected senate vote today, will help further reagan's objectives
reagan has said his goal is to keep pressure on the sandinistas so they will live up to the promises of democratic reform that they made when they took over from dictator anastasio somoza in 1979
at a news conference feb. 21, 1985, reagan was asked whether he was advocating the overthrow of the nicaraguan government. his reply was: ``not if the present government would turn around and ... say, `uncle. all right, come back into the revolutionary government, and let's straighten this out and institute the goals.'''
now that the two sides have agreed on a cease-fire, will nicaragua's marxist-led sandinista government reform? and if it doesn't, can the contra rebels the reagan administration has backed survive as an effective force?
many think not
i think it would be awfully difficult to reorganize them,'' said atkins. ``i doubt if they would be particularly interested in that. i don't think they would want to go through the convolutions of u.s. policy again.''
king added that ``it's over for the time being unless the sandinistas back up on what they say they are going to do, and have done, and the contras change their orientation from where they are, which is: let's get some kind of political opening going.''
pickett, too, sees ``the end of the resistance'' in the latest developments, ``barring some miracle or barring some violation before the truce is signed.''
if the sandinistas do something stupid before that, the contras can be saved,'' he said
king, the adviser to byrd, said: ``the objective of the whole exercise in the beginning was to protect u.s. security concerns in the region. u.s. security concerns in the region are removal of the soviet and the cuban advisers, guarantees of no bases, reduction of soviet weapons and guarantees of no border crossing
now they are at a point where they don't have any of those things arranged, they're about to leave office, and they've got a contra program that's falling apart on them,'' king said. ``i think the whole thing is a disaster, frankly.''
the less partisan sources are not calling it a disaster, but they aren't proclaiming it a success either
w. dale nelson covers the white house for the associated press
alaska continues to lead the nation in per capita federal spending, but virginia is closing in, new federal figures show
the u.s. government spent about $5,421 per resident in alaska last year, making it the leading state in per capita spending
but second-place virginia _ which moved up from third a year earlier _ wasn't far behind at $5,317 per capita, according to the census bureau
that $104 per capita difference in spending between the states was down from a $246 spread in 1986
maryland, which had been second in 1986, dropped to third place with 1987 spending of $5,113
both maryland and virginia benefit from their location adjacent to the nation's capital. many federal agencies have offices in the suburbs, which also are home for consultants and suppliers of goods for the government
if it were a state, the district of columbia would easily lead in per capita spending, averaging $23,360
nationwide, federal spending averaged nearly $3,433 per american last year, about $41 more than the year before
the report, ``federal expenditures by state for fiscal year 1987,'' broke down spending totaling $848 billion, covering virtually everything except interest on the national debt
direct payments to people was the largest share, totaling $384 billion. that includes social security, medicare, food stamps and other such programs
buying goods and services was second, with $196 billion spent. salaries for federal employees totaled $127 billion, with $108 billion sent out to state and local governments and $33 billion spent on research grants, agriculture subsidies and various other purposes
per capita, that amounts to $1,555 paid to individuals; $795 in procurement; $514 in salaries; $437 in grants to state and local government and other spending of $133
alaska's top finish included high levels of aid to state and local governments as well as pay for federal employees, but it was way down the list in payments to individuals
florida topped that category, with social security and medicare benefits for its large elderly population raising the state's average
california was easily the leader in total federal spending, with its large population, military bases and industry helping bring in $100.7 billion. even so, the golden state finished only 14th in per capita spending
congressional investigators say the defense logistics agency should tighten controls over its ``fast-pay'' program to avoid paying for supplies that are never delivered
according to a general accounting office report released today, one dla purchasing office failed to take action to ensure collection of more than $7 million in overpayments
i'm appalled that dla is paying money for supplies that it never received,'' said sen. john glenn, d-ohio, who, along with sen. pete wilson, r-calif., released the gao report. ``we need sound business management at dla.''
the agency purchases food, clothing, fuel oil and other supplies for the armed services
under the fast-pay program, the agency pays vendors based on shipping invoices instead of verifying receipt of the supplies. the procedure is designed to expedite payments for small purchases
internal controls established by the dla purchasing offices do not prevent possible fast-pay program abuse,'' said the gao, the investigative arm of congress. ``potential missing depot shipments are not always detected for timely follow-up and resolution.''
the gao said that in 52 fast-pay shipments valued at $71,267 to the defense electronics supply center in dayton, ohio, the center could not document the receipt of 16 shipments valued at $18,618. in addition, the center failed to notify some of the vendors of the missing shipments within 90 days
it also said action had not been taken as of last may to collect more than $7 million in previously identified overpayments owed the defense personnel support center in philadelphia
the gao also said that vendors with performance problems on previous contracts have continued to receive fast-pay awards and that controls have not been established to ensure the receipt of supplies sent directly from vendors to overseas locations
in 1985, the office of management and budget issued instructions to limit the use of fast pay, saying it should not be used to replace stocks in depots or when timely payment can be made. the gao said dla believes it is not required to follow the requirements until they are incorporated into the federal acquisition regulations
however, dla spokesman larry wilson said the agency plans to be in compliance with the omb requirements by the end of the year even though it is expected to cost an additional $2.5 million to process the extra paperwork
legislation calling for the rehiring of 1,000 air traffic controllers fired nearly seven years ago has won strong approval in the house, although the senate has yet to consider a similar bill
the reagan administration has steadfastly refused to rehire any of the 11,400 controllers who were fired after they walked off their jobs in 1981. the transportation department has urged that such legislation be vetoed by president reagan if it clears congress
the 234-180 house vote wednesday calling for some of the fired controllers to return to the federal aviation administration came two years after similar legislation was defeated by a 193-226 margin
supporters of the legislation argued that there are too few controllers to handle air traffic needs, especially at some of the busiest towers and traffic control centers, and that the former controllers could become fully trained more quickly than trainees off the street
rep. guy molinari, sponsor of the house resolution, said a selected number of fired controllers should be rehired by the faa ``for the sake of safety and the convenience of the flying public.''
today it's clearer than ever that the air traffic control system is still severely strained,'' molinari, r-n.y., said during floor debate. the legislation calls for selectively hiring 500 of the fired controllers this year and another 500 next fiscal year
the general accounting office, the investigative arm of congress, has estimated that as many as 6,000 of the 11,400 former controllers still have an interest in returning to the faa. under the legislation the faa would be free to select the controllers it wants to rehire
the faa has steadily been increasing its controller workforce and now has 14,450 controllers at various experience levels, compared with 16,375 before the 1981 strike. the transportation department plans to hire another 1,350 over the next 1{ years
while support for rehiring at least some of the fired controllers was widespread, some congressmen continued to have deep concerns about such a move
putting the strikers and their replacements in the same control tower is sure to create animosity between the two factions,'' suggested rep. john paul hammerschmidt, r-ark
rep. gerald solomon, r-n.y., said the legislastion is ``sending the wrong message'' to government workers and their unions. ``the right to fire illegal strikers must not be compromised,'' solomon declared
the reagan administration is being urged to lead the industrialized world into new, tougher action against the chemicals that scientists say are destroying the earth's stratospheric ozone layer
the call for strict international controls on chlorofluourocarbons, or cfcs, is coming from senators, scientists and two quarters that often are in deep disagreement: environmentalists and chemical companies
we need a massive diplomatic mission,'' sen. john chafee, r-r.i., said wednesday as two environment committee subcommittees heard renewed warnings that cfc's are depleting the ozone that shields humans from the sun's cancer-causing ultraviolet rays
committee members and witnesses took turns saying that the united states must take the lead to push other industrialized nations into taking stronger measures against cfcs than contained in last year's montreal protocol
that agreement could lead to a freeze on global cfc production in 1999 at a level of 50 percent of the cfcs manufactured in 1986. to take effect, the protocol needs ratification by nations representing two-thirds of cfc production. so far, only the united states and mexico have acted
cfcs are widely used as refrigerants and industrial solvents and in the production of foam products. they also serve as propellants in aerosol cans, although such use was banned in the united states in 1977
witnesses said the administration should not only be pushing for ratification but also be lobbying for an emergency international gathering to consider a larger production freeze or even a ban on cfcs
the protocol provides for a cfc review meeting sometime in 1990. lee thomas, administrator of the environmental protection agency, said tuesday he would press to have that meeting very early in 1990
sen. max baucus, d-mont., called on president reagan to make an accelerated schedule for cfc reductions a priority item this june when he and leaders of other industrialized democracies hold their annual economic summit
also calling for faster action was sherwood rowland, the university of california-irvine professor who in the 1970s was one of the first scientists to warn of dangers posed by cfcs
clearly the protocol is not going to do much of anything for 10 years,'' rowland said. ``we need more rapid action than that.''
david doniger, senior attorney for the environmentalist natural resources defense council, said a swift international response is needed in light of the conclusion announced march 15 by a panel of 100 scientists convened by the national aeronautics and space administration
the panel said ozone depletion is occurring faster than previously thought. doniger said the losses cited by the panel already are at levels epa has projected for the year 2050 under the production cuts specified by the montreal protocol
i think we can attain a new worldwide agreement in a year and end the use of these chemicals by the end of the century,'' doniger said
joining the call for a stepped-up diplomatic effort were representatives of two major u.s. producers of cfcs, e.i. dupont de nemours &amp; co., and allied-signal inc
all of us need to work to get as many nations as possible to ratify the protocol as quickly as possible,'' said marilyn montgomery, vice president and general manager of allied-signal's genetron products
elwood blanchard, dupont's executive vice president, said his company believes that cfc-producing countries should be convened as soon as possible ``to review the scientific findings and to establish appropriate global responses to these findings.''
he and ms. montgomery said their companies have begun efforts to develop safe substitutes for cfcs, but neither could say when they might be available
dupont announced last week it was phasing out production of cfcs
the widow of slain civil rights leader martin luther king says congress has ``acquiesced too long to the gun lobby'' and she is urging lawmakers to vote to restrict sales of handguns
speaking on the seventh anniversary of the shooting of president reagan outside a washington hotel, coretta scott king cited the significantly lower murder statistics from countries that control handgun sales
such restrictions, she said, ``are more effective than capital punishment'' in deterring killings. ``we need to end the needless sacrifices of men, women and children on the altar of congressional inaction.''
she later added: ``congress has acquiesced to the gun lobby. the only thing that will bring an end to this inaction is an aroused citizenry.''
mrs. king then signed a giant-size petition, sponsored by the national coalition to ban handguns, that calls for restrictions on the sale of handguns. she will be honorary chairwoman of the petition drive along with ethel kennedy, the widow of sen. robert f. kennedy
the petition drive, called ``a time to remember, a time to end handgun violence,'' coincides with the 20th anniversary of the deaths of king and kennedy. king was assassinated on april 4, 1968, and kennedy on june 6, 1968
in a separate statement, sarah brady, wife of white house press secretary james brady, who was wounded in the attack seven years ago on reagan, pleaded to congress for stronger handgun control laws
mrs. brady said she supports legislation that would require a seven-day waiting period for handgun purchases to allow police to conduct a background check
i'm firmly convinced that had such a proposal been in effect seven years ago, john hinckley would have been prevented from purchasing the handgun he used to shoot the president, my husband and two law enforcement officers,'' mrs. brady said
the national coalition to ban handguns petition does not endorse any specific piece of legislation. but michael k. beard of the coalition said ``we hope it will stimulate this congress to enact a national waiting period requirement before a handgun may be purchased, to ban the sale of non-detectable (plastic) handguns and to ban saturday night specials, the kind of handgun used to kill robert kennedy.''
audiences seem to know what he means, but vice president george bush doesn't always get the words out exactly right as he campaigned this week in wisconsin
during an appearance at lawrence univeristy in appleton, wis., the republican presidential candidate told his audience, ``i want to be the education president.''
there is a need for help at the federal level ... so you can afford to send your college to children,'' bush declared
at another time in the same speech, he meant to talk about the ``high cost of college,'' but it came out: ``the high cost of courage.''
speaking to a rally in a milwaukee suburb, bush appeared to invent a new federal tax on farmers, declaring he favored a lower ``capital grains tax.''
no doubt, he was referring to the capital gains tax. bush has urged a partial repeal of the part of the 1987 tax overhaul law that taxes capital gains _ such as from the sale of a house, stocks or business assets _ at the same level as other income
bush's verbal tongue-twisting seems to be catching
introducing the vice president at another milwaukee-area function, wisconsin gov. tommy thompson asserted: ``as the reagan presidency ends, it's time for the bush pregnancy to begin.''
as he campaigned in the area, bush was repeatedly reminded by local reporters of a previous campaign visit here, when he went to a milwaukee bowling alley _ and wound up sprawled on the lane. questions like ``plan to do any bowling this time?'' have abounded
you have a good memory,'' he told one inqusitor
i did fall down. but so did nine pins,'' he said in defense of his technique
at an aviation musuem in oshkosh, bush was presented with a brown leather aviator's jacket and he climbed readily into the cockpit of a 1949 bearcat fighter
the plane was billed as similar to one he had flown as a navy pilot during world war ii, a past his campaign strategists would like to have remembered as often as possible
well, it wasn't exactly like the kind of planes he used to fly, ``but it has the same engine,'' bush said
then bush, who frequently has posed on and in various kinds of heavy equipment during his campaign, held his right arm over his head and flashed a ``v'' sign for photographers
is this the red baron look?'' he asked
then bush was led to a full-scale replica of the voyager, the lightweight plane that set a record for flying non-stop around the world
i'm anxious to learn about this,'' bush said. ``this looks like it may be a little tough.''
he elaborated further. ``there's the inevitable question,'' he said. ``how does one go to the bathroom?''
a british mountain climber set off for the himalayas to find out whether the abominable snowman is myth or monster
chris bonington, who left london on wednesday, intends to return to the 23,237-foot menglungtse, where last year he found footprints from an unidentified creature on a failed attempt to climb the mountain
it would be fantastic if we could come back with some proof,'' he said during a visit to the natural history museum in london before his departure
bonington and a five-man team discovered 7-inch-by-4-inch footprints 16,000 feet up the mountain last year. periodic sightings of the creature, also known as the yeti, have been reported for decades
the restored presidential yacht uss sequoia is making a national tour before being returned once again to the president of the united states after an 11-year hiatus
the sequoia, which was sold in 1977 by president carter as part of an austerity move, has been repaired by a private group. it was launched wednesday on a 100-city, 22-state tour that will enable thousands to see the vessel before it is officially returned to the white house nov. 15
what we have here is a fourth of july celebration every weekend in cities throughout the country,'' said michael mcgehee, a member of the group that raised money to repair the 105-foot yacht. ``we're taking a piece of american history to the american people.''
private and corporate funding paid for the sequoia's restoration, and josh lanier, who chairs the nine-member presidential yacht trust's board of trustees, hopes the tour will raise money for an endowment to pay for the ship's upkeep
this tour is a little like running a campaign,'' he joked. ``we have a good candidate, no opposition, and we're confident she won't screw up on the evening news.''
the sequoia was built in 1925 and sold to the commerce department in 1931. in 1933, after president hoover wintered on it in florida, the sequoia was acquired by the navy and became the president's official yacht
over the next 44 years, the sequoia served eight presidents. it was the site of talks on nuclear controls during the truman administration, the venue of gala celebrations by president kennedy and the place where president nixon told his family in 1974 that he would resign the presidency
in 1977, as part of a widespread retrenchment program, carter directed that the vessel be sold. it was purchased for $286,000 by a group of private investors
over the next four years, the craft changed hands three times and began to deteriorate. in 1981, a private trust was established to purchase and restore the boat
after reading news accounts in 1983 about the boat's dilapidated condition, lanier, a former aide to sen. herman talmadge, d-ga., joined the effort to refurbish the craft
i remember thinking it was a crying shame that this boat had fallen on such bad times, because i remember how it was used in the nixon and ford administrations,'' he said
minor repairs were made, and a little-publicized, 16-state tour during the summer of 1984 drew surprisingly large crowds
everyone told us it was a mistake for the federal government to have sold the sequoia,'' lanier said. ``we then started raising money for a full restoration, with the intention of returning the vessel to the office of the president.''
in june 1986, a six-month, $3.5 million restoration was completed, and the sequoia sailed to new york for the statue of liberty centennial celebration. since then, the sequoia has been moored in washington and used for government functions
the sequoia's tour will include ports in virginia, south carolina and florida in april, and to gulf coast cities in alabama, louisiana and texas in may. it then will sail up the mississippi river in june and july, stopping at ports in mississippi, arkansas, tennessee, missouri, illinois and michigan
after visiting great lakes ports in august, the sequoia will stop at cities between boston and baltimore in september. the tour will end oct. 30 in alexandria, va
a newspaper said vast oil deposits have been found in northern kenya, but the minister of energy downplayed the discovery
it is true that encouraging results have been achieved, but conclusions drawn by the paper are rather grossly exaggerated,'' nicholas biwott said
biwott issued a statement wednesday after the kenya times reported the energy minister had confirmed the presence of vast oil deposits and had said that kenya was ready to begin looking for pump sites
the newspaper of the governing kenya african national union party also quoted biwott as saying two of five international companies prospecting in kenya had struck oil
biwott said test wells in the northern turkana, marsabit and isiolo districts had confirmed the presence of gas and oil, but none of the wells had ``yielded hydrocarbons in commercial quantities.''
