here is a brief summary of provisions in the $47.9 million contra aid bill taken up wednesday by the house:
_ $17.7 million for the contra rebels over the next six months. the money would flow at a rate of $2.7 million monthly to buy food, clothing and medical supplies for the rebels. it also could include $1.5 million for communications equipment, if that is deemed in accord with a nicaraguan cease-fire agreement
_ $17.7 million to establish a program to pay for medical care for children who are victims of the nicaraguan civil war
_ $10 million to pay the expenses of a commission set up to verify compliance with the provisions of the cease-fire
_ $2.5 million for the state department's agency for international development to pay costs of administering the aid program. 9th-12th grafs pvs, bgng, `the fetal...'. picks up 13th graf, `in alcoholics...'. national institute on alcohol abuse and alcoholism is cq, 4th graf</note>
memory problems in rats caused by chronic alcohol intake were mostly reversed with brain tissue transplants, and such therapy may someday help alcoholics and victims of alzheimer's disease, a researcher says
i think that really means there's hope, if you blow your mind with too much whiskey, maybe we'll be able to repair it with transplants,'' or similarly ease mental deficits in alzheimer's, said jeffrey gray of the institute of psychiatry in london
but experts in alcohol-induced memory problems were skeptical, questioning the resemblance of the rats' condition to that of alcoholics and cautioning that any implication for treatment is only speculation
still, ``i think it's going to stimulate lots of excitement and lots of further research,'' said michael eckardt, chief of the clinical brain research section in the laboratory of clinical studies at the national institute on alcohol abuse and alcoholism
gray, head of the psychology department at the psychiatric institute in london, reports the research with colleagues in thursday's issue of the british journal nature
about 10 percent of alcoholics develop long-lasting memory loss, either by itself or as part of an overall loss in intellectual abilities, according to the federal alcohol institute
in the new work, 78 male rats drank an alcohol solution as the only fluid in an otherwise normal diet for 28 weeks. four weeks later, they did poorer than other rats in learning to find food in a maze
but rats that then got transplants of fetal rat brain tissue to two brain areas, the neocortex and the hippocampus, later performed almost as well as normal rats, the researchers said
the fetal tissue was rich in a substance called acetylcholine, which some brain cells use to communicate. the transplants apparently worked by raising inadequate levels of the substance in the brain, gray said
alzheimer's is not related to alcohol. but an acetylcholine defect has also been identified in that disease, which involves problems in memory and thinking, gray said
david drachman of the university of massachusetts in worcester, an alzheimer's expert, said previous research has shown that impairment of the brain's acetylcholine circuitry can hinder mental performance. treating that impairment has helped in regaining mental powers, he said
but alzheimer's affects far more of the brain than just acetylcholine-using cells, and whether gray's strategy would significantly help alzheimer patients remains to be seen, he said
in alcoholics, memory loss without other intellectual decline is called korsakoff's psychosis. eckardt said scientists are still studying whether it is caused by excessive alcohol intake, by a deficiency of the vitamin thiamine in the alcoholic's usually poor diet, or by a combination of those factors
the new research did not involve thiamine deficiency, so connecting its results to korsakoff's is speculative, eckardt said
the rats did not display a type of brain damage, called diencephalic lesions, that is characteristic of korsakoff's. the researchers said that suggests the lesions are not responsible for the memory problems
but that is ``much too speculative,'' and clashes with evidence that does implicate the lesions, said philip langlais, a korsakoff's researcher at the university of california, san diego
the lesions are generally accepted as causing the memory deficits in the condition, so the rats did not truly have an animal version of korsakoff's psychosis, said marlene oscar berman, professor of neurology and psychiatry at the boston university school of medicine
since president reagan took office in 1981, his policy of financing the contra rebels in their war against nicaragua's sandinista government has been one of the most divisive foreign-policy questions facing congress and the nation. here is a chronology of the ups and downs of that policy:
1981 _ congress, late in the year, approves $19 million in covert military aid to the rebels. the money, to be managed by the cia, is part of a classified intelligence bill
1982 _ a second infusion of $19 million, again part of a classified bill, is approved. this time, restrictive provisions are added that prevent any of the money from being used to overthrow the sandinista government. there are reports, as well, that the cia has used an additional $10 million from its contingency fund
1983 _ the house votes to end contra aid, but a later compromise results in the appropriation of $24 million for the rebels. this time, the money is appropriated openly, and the cia is barred from using any money from its contingency fund to supplement the new aid
1984 _ in april, reports surface that the cia has supervised the mining of three nicaraguan ports, and congress votes to cut off aid to the rebels. but at the end of the year, lawmakers vote to set aside $14 million for the rebels, to be released after feb. 28, 1985, if congress approves in a separate vote at that time. congress adds new restrictions, saying the cia and the pentagon may not use the money to support paramilitary operations in nicaragua unless specifically authorized by congress
1985 _ in april the senate votes to release the $14 million, but the house votes against the resolution, denying the money to the rebels. that summer, congress approves $27 million for the contras but restricts its use to food, clothing, medicine and other ``humanitarian'' aid. the money is directed to be used by the administration as leverage to promote peace negotiations, and the cia and defense department are barred from any role in distributing the money
1986 _ in the fall, congress approves $100 million _ its largest single appropriation for the rebels _ the bulk of it for military aid. restrictions on the cia's role are lifted, except that the agency remains barred from using its contingency fund
1987 _ in march, the house passes a moratorium on contra aid in an effort to hold up the final $40 million of the aid bill approved in 1986, but the measure dies in the senate. at the end of the fiscal year, on sept. 30, congress begins a series of stopgap funding measures that include money for ``non-lethal'' aid for the rebels totaling another $20 million
1988 _ under procedures laid out in late 1987, the house on feb. 3 kills president reagan's request for $36 million in rebel aid, including $3.6 million in military aid. a month later, the house also rejects a democratic alternative that would have provided $30 million in solely humanitarian aid. the rebels reach a negotiated truce with the sandinistas on march 23, and a new $48 million proposal is drafted in the house with bipartisan support
tenor alfredo kraus brought dignity and elegance to the title role of massenet's ``werther,'' the final opera to enter this season's repertory at the metropolitan opera
some tenors portray werther as a self-pitying nut case as he pines for his beloved charlotte, who has married another man to fulfill a promise to her dying mother
but in wednesday's performance kraus gave him the dignity of a man feeling overwhelming love. vocally he was lean, elegant, refined, distinguished
frederica von stade as charlotte sang well throughout but rather blandly in the first two acts, as she denied her love for werther and stuck steadfastly to her husband. in act 3, with her love churning to the surface as werther falls into suicidal depression, miss von stade came through with passionate vocalizing
dawn upshaw sang charlotte's sister sophie in a voice as fresh as spring. it almost seemed to lilt. richard stilwell did well with albert. all voices were well focused. jean fournet conducted his first ``werther'' at the met, beautifully shaping the music
the present production, last heard at the met eight years ago, was new in 1971. rudolf heinrich's sets for acts 1 and 2 are realistic and attractive. after werther's mind cracks, set walls meet at odd angles. in the finale scene, his room looks like a coal cellar
werther'' will be heard on the metropolitan's last saturday afternoon broadcast. the season ends april 16. message</head>
the message that jesse jackson has been preaching with startling success on the democratic campaign trail is ``stop economic violence against american farmers and workers. stop drugs. invest in our children. reinvest in america.''
there's nothing radical about his message,'' john white, the texan who was chairman of the democratic party during the carter administration and now a jackson supporter, said wednesday. ``it's neither liberal nor conservative. it's the core language of the democratic party.''
but much of jackson's platform is decidedly liberal and dovish. the candidate himself calls it ``the opposite of reaganomics.''
he has promised a universal, comprehensive health program for all americans, a goal of democrats since harry truman
he wants to double the budget for education and raise the minimum wage
and he would pay for his social initiatives by raising taxes on the rich and slashing pentagon spending
jackson, who has finished first or second in most of the democratic presidential primaries and caucuses and is close behind massachusetts gov. michael dukakis in the delegate chase, has cast himself as the candidate of the displaced farmer and factory worker, the hungry and the homeless, and those who fear their toehold on financial security is precarious
economic violence haunts the lives of most ameicans,'' jackson said in a policy paper
there is nothing wrong with the american worker, the family farmer, or the small businessperson. there is something wrong with the system.''
jackson has called for a moratorium on family farm foreclosures; civil rights legislation to protect lesbians and gay men; tapping public pension funds to build housing, roads, mass transit and water systems; debt relief and an ``international marshall plan'' for the third world; a national floor for welfare benefits; a phase-out of nuclear power; a freeze on nuclear weapons, and a halt to u.s. aid for the contra rebels in nicaragua and the unita insurgents in angola
he claims he could cut the deficit by one-third by raising taxes on ``the richest 1 percent'' of americans and on corporations
here are some of jackson's key positions:
jackson says, ``u.s. policy in the middle east is fatally flawed. it is not working for israel, for the palestinians or for the interests of the united states.''
he has called for an alternative policy that ``moves the process that began at camp david to the next progressive step.'' it would be built on such principles as ``the right of israel to exist (and) the right of the palestinian people to self-determination, including an independent state.''
jackson says there should be a universal, comprehensive health care program for all, not just the elderly, ``no matter what their income.''
it would cover long-term care as well as services medicare now leaves uncovered, and it would be administered by the federal government and ``paid for by earmarked health taxes and general revenues.''
most hospitals and other institutions would remain private, providing services under contract with the federal government at regulated fees. by emphasizing prevention, it could actually be cheaper than what americans now pay, jackson claims
jackson calls himself ``a true peace candidate,'' and boasts that he is the only democrat who opposed reagan's invasion of grenada and his bombing of libya. he also favors ending the u.s. military build-up in the persian gulf
he proposes to save $40 billion by not building two new aircraft carrier task forces, and ``tens of billions of dollars'' by negotiating further arms reductions with the soviets
he opposes building the midgetman missile, the stealth bomber, the trident d-5 missile, or any more mx missiles. he opposes deployment of the strategic defense initiative, and wants to halt u.s. troop maneuvers in honduras
we must fight back against runaway corporations. tax subsidies which aid u.s. corporations to invest abroad must be eliminated,'' he said
jackson has proposed borrowing with federal guarantees 10 percent of the $600 billion assets of public pension funds to create an american investment bank for development projects
he says american business needs a new code of conduct, tougher anti-trust laws and tax incentives to invest in new plants and equipment. he would shift federal research and development funds from the military to civilian uses, saying the united states is ``making what the world isn't buying.''
jackson would require advance warning of plant closures and making business pay ``a fair share of the costs of dislocation.''
he supports equal pay for jobs of comparable worth _ a key issue for women _ and wants to raise the $3.35-an-hour minimum wage to $4.65 and then index it to the growth of average wages
jackson's anti-drug crusade, the centerpiece of his campaign, calls for increased coast guard funding to stop the influx of drugs. he would offer drug-producing countries substitute crops to replace drug crops and tie cooperation to trade and foreign policy decisions
we need a moratorium on family farm foreclosures,'' says jackson
he would shift the focus of federal programs to family farmers and help producers of raw commodities ``band together to become their own processors'' and cut out the middlemen
he charges that four corporations control 80 percent of the grain trade, and five companies hold 58 percent of the beef industry
jackson would double the $21 billion federal education budget to boost aid for college students and provide ``full funding for compensatory, bilingual and special education programs,'' as well as head start, which now serves only a third of eligible children
jackson would guarantee annual cost-of-living raises for social security recipients and leave the program ``out of the budget debate (to) stop striking fear into the hearts of our seniors.''
jews are celebrating passover with an abundance of matzoh, the ancient symbol of freedom that is more available in moscow this year
other changes since last passover include a modest expansion of jewish culture, limited availability of some kosher foods and visits by soviet jews to relatives abroad
many of the capital's 200,000 jews have been flocking to the main synagogue to buy the thin, cracker-like unleavened bread eaten during the eight-day commemoration of the freeing of the ancient hebrews from slavery in egypt
several jews making purchases in the dark lobby of the moscow choral synagogue said matzoh is not as difficult to obtain as it has been in the past
times have become easier with glasnost,'' said sasha, 26, referring to soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev's policy of more openness on some issues. ``under (former soviet leader leonid i.) brezhnev, people gathering in large groups around the synagogue waiting to buy matzoh were driven away.''
earlier years also saw matzoh shortages
there were deficit problems with flour. now, everything is ok,'' said an elderly man who carried a rectangular package of matzoh
several afternoons before the start of the holiday at sundown friday, a steady stream of customers bought matzoh wrapped in white or brown paper marked ``kosher for passover'' in russian and hebrew
yuri a. korzhenevich, one of the synagogue's two rabbis, acknowledged in an interview that the government didn't provide enough flour for matzoh from 1965-1969 but said this year's allotment of 135 tons satisfied the demand
trucks made deliveries daily to the synagogue from what korzhenevich calls a ``matzoh bakery,'' a tiny two-story, pre-revolutionary brown building in downtown moscow
the chief matzoh maker, pavel n. spaskin, gave a reporter a tour of the bakery, tucked behind apartment buildings and across the street from a popular cooperative restaurant
we've been producing matzoh here for 20 years,'' said spaskin, a small gray-haired man of 38
the bakery already had stopped production for the year, and its stainless steel mixers and dough-rolling tables lay idle
spaskin said he recently compared his product with american matzoh
the american matzoh ``was more airy,'' he said. ``it would be interesting to know the technology americans use, or maybe it's a different flour.''
aside from abundant matzoh supplies, the government has allowed these improvements in jewish life since last passover:
_hungary's jews sent in some kosher wine, chickens and salami. religious books also have been imported
_a jewish museum and library have been set up in private moscow apartments
_last year, as relations with the west improved, more than 8,000 soviet jews were permitted to leave the country, nearly eight times as many as the year before and the highest total since 1981
among those who have left in recent months are longtime jewish activists and refuseniks josef begun, vladimir slepak, ida nudel, noam meiman and alexander lerner and pianist vladimir feltsman
soviet authorities also are allowing increased numbers of jews to travel to the west to visit relatives
in an exchange with the new york city jewish community, american rabbi marc schneier and cantor joel selter are scheduled to lead passover services in the moscow choral synagogue on friday, and the choral synagogue's chief rabbi, abraham shayevich, will be in the pulpit in new york
and there are more subtle signs of change. michael stolar, the 28-year-old son of chicago-born refusenik abe stolar, said he and a group of six friends meet daily in the choral synagogue to study the talmud, the writings on jewish civil and religious law
two to four years ago, you had to be quite careful about where you prayed or studied. you could have an unexpected visit by the militia,'' he said
still, problems remain
thousands of jews are waiting to leave. and anti-semitism persists: a soviet newspaper this week accused moscow's other synagogue of brainwashing jewish children into wanting to go to israel, and the word ``no!'' was scrawled in english next to a star of david on an outside wall of the matzoh bakery
barbara bush says her husband is not ready to start thinking about a republican vice-presidential running mate yet _ and even if he were, he'd keep it to himself
he ...said he didn't want to give it away now, or it would be a boring republican convention,'' mrs. bush said as she campaigned for her husband at a country club lunch here on wednesday
mrs. bush said she doesn't plan to change her style if her husband is elected to the white house. the white-haired, 62-year-old mrs. bush said she shrugs off remarks that she looks old enough to be the mother of her youthful-looking husband
i'd love to be a size 4, beautiful and twenty-years old,'' quipped mrs. bush. ``but i know i can't be that so i'll just be me. ... sometimes the comments can be brutal but most times i make a joke about it.''
she said she enjoys the campaigning but doesn't think her husband's public image reflects his real personality
people have no inkling how funny george is and how extraordinarily caring he is,'' she said. ``i adore george bush. it's easy to.''
former republican sen. barry goldwater says jesse jackson is the most intelligent democratic presidential candidate in the 1988 race
goldwater, a republican presidential candidate in 1964, said of jackson, ``he's the most intelligent man running on the democratic side, and not by a little, by a lot.''
whether he'll make a good president, well, that's something you can ask about any president,'' goldwater said wednesday
the 79-year-old former arizona senator spoke at a news conference prior to receiving princeton university's 1988 james madison award for distinguished public service
pollster mervin field says it is very unlikely that jesse jackson could win the june 7 california democratic presidential primary in a two-man race against michael dukakis
if jesse jackson wins in california, this would rank as one of the biggest political happenings since the country was founded,'' field told a luncheon of the sacramento press club on wednesday
but he said jackson could do better in a three-way race including albert gore
the san francisco-based political pollster, who publishes the california poll, said he doesn't think the california primary ``is as promising as michigan and the other industrial states'' for jackson
california is not as economically distressed as those states and jackson's appeal is to the economically distressed, he said. and the black population in california is not as large as in some other states: 8 percent of the general population and 14 percent of democrats, he said
an estimated 1.6 million voters are expected to go to the polls tuesday in wisconsin's presidential preference primary, a state elections board official says
that turnout would be about 45 percent of wisconsin's estimated 3.5 million eligible voters, said kevin kennedy, the board's executive director
in wisconsin's 1984 primary, voter participation dropped to 27.4 percent of the voting-age population
one factor in that turnout was the insistence of the national democratic party that wisconsin democrats use a caucus system instead of its open primary to select delegates to the national convention
this year, the open primary, in which voters are not required to state party preference, will again be used for delegate selection
mario cuomo supporters have failed to gather enough signatures to put the new york governor's name on california's presidential primary ballot, state officials say
but the head of a draft cuomo committee said his group plans to try to convince a court to add cuomo to the list of democratic candidates on the june 7 ballot
we knew that when we submitted the names that we did not have enough signatures, but we did it anyway because we felt that we had substantially complied with a law that has serious constitutional problems,'' said steven polard, a los angeles attorney who heads the california draft cuomo for president committee
committee members turned in about 16,000 signatures, polard said. they needed at least 22,500 _ a minimum of 500 from each of the state's 45 congressional districts, according to caren daniels-meade, a spokeswoman for secretary of state march fong eu
but state election officials had said earlier that even if the committee collected enough signatures they would not put cuomo's name on the ballot unless he authorized it
the new york governor has refused to enter the presidential primaries but he has not ruled out accepting a draft at the democratic national convention
daniels-meade said cuomo will not appear on the california ballot now unless he announces his candidacy for president, qualifies for federal matching funds and actively campaigns for the office
if those things happen, eu can add cuomo's name to the ballot, she said
a big boost for the space program along with cuts in aid to local and state governments are contained in the $1.1 trillion fiscal 1989 budget approved by the senate budget committee
the plan, closer to president reagan's priorities than the budget passed by the house earlier this month, was approved 18-3 on wednesday and sent to the full senate for consideration
committee chairman lawton chiles, d-fla., and sen. pete v. domenici of new mexico, the panel's senior republican, drafted the bipartisan compromise and it sailed through the committee in a single day
there's even an outside chance congress will meet its april 15 deadline for final budget action, although the senate doesn't plan to vote on the resolution until after next week's holiday recess
but opponents and supporters complained that while they were living up to the terms of last fall's deficit reduction agreement with reagan, the result was to put off much-needed fiscal reforms until next year
we need to get this out and then start showing what the problems are going to be,'' said chiles
sen. bill armstrong, r-colo., said it was mostly a plan to ``get past the november election.''
there's an old saying, `no guts, no glory,''' said armstrong. ``and this is a no-glory budget.'' armstrong and sens. steve symms, r-idaho, and kent conrad, d-n.d., voted against the plan
total deficit reduction in the senate budget proposal would be $7.2 billion, accomplished in part by holding spending on most programs short of the full inflation increases they would normally get. more than half the saving would come from selling off government assets
it would meet the $136 billion deficit-reduction target of the gramm-rudman budget balancing law only because the committee decided to use optimistic white house economic projections. the non-partisan congressional budget office predicts a deficit more than $30 billion higher
last fall's pact with the president set overall spending limits of $294 billion, $16.1 billion for foreign aid and $169.2 billion for domestic spending other than social security and entitlement programs
the agreement also included $14 billion in new taxes that were enacted last year and will be in effect for fiscal 1989, which begins oct. 1
the senate budget envisions spending $13 billion of the domestic allocation on space and science in the year beginning oct. 1, about the same amount reagan requested and nearly $1 billion more than the house approved
in addition to the 27 percent increase for the space program, that money would boost national science foundation programs by 11 percent and move ahead the proposed construction of a giant physics project known as the superconducting super collider
like the house, the senate committee declined to kill any programs, relying instead on across-the-board spending restraint to reach deficit-reduction targets without making those tough choices in an election year
but while most programs would get at least a partial inflation boost, community and regional development would be cut $100 million from last year's $5.8 billion last year
tom cochran, executive director of the u.s. conference of mayors, said aid to localities has been cut too deeply already during the reagan years. ``the priorities of this thing are out of whack,'' he said of the senate plan
a republican amendment to carry out some of reagan's plan to eliminate those development programs was withdrawn, and domenici was defeated when he tried to require selling off two federally owned oil tracts, and said that,
sooner or later, we're going to have to get rid of some programs.'' but it was, domenici said, still a ``a fair, balanced budget.''
the proposal would, like the administration and house budgets, call for big increases in spending on aids research, air traffic safety and education
the senate plan assumes that if legislation providing catastrophic health insurance for medicare recipients is approved, there will be an accompanying increase in premiums to cover the cost
an additional $500 million would be provided to continue supplying cheese and other surplus commodities to the needy
like the president's budget, the senate plan would grant 4.3 percent pay raises for the military and 2 percent for civilian federal workers. the house adopted a 3 percent across-the-board pay hike
lettuce prices bounced up again in march but didn't approach their winter peaks, and the farm prices of cattle eggs and broilers were up, too
but the agriculture department says this month's farm prices for hogs, milk, wheat and sweet corn were down, and that left the march index where it was in february
even so, the march average of prices received by farmers was up 7.4 percent from a year ago, the department's agricultural statistics board said wednesday
the price of lettuce increased sharply from february to march but was well below record levels during the november through january 1988 period,'' the report said. ``calf prices dropped slightly from february to march but were at the second highest level since june of 1979.''
prices of cattle sold for beef were the highest since may 1979, the report said. hog and wheat prices declined from february, while corn prices rose slightly
department economists say net cash income of farmers may be in the range of $50 billion to $55 billion this year, down from the record level of $57 billion in 1987. that is the difference between cash receipts and cash expenses during the calendar year
consumer food prices are expected to rise 2 percent to 4 percent this year, compared with a 4.2 percent average increase in 1987
according to the preliminary march figures, based mostly on mid-month averages, the index for crop prices was up 0.9 percent from february and averaged 10 percent more than a year ago
commercial vegetable prices rose 11 percent from last month but were down 7.1 percent from march 1987
higher prices for lettuce and tomatoes were major contributors to the increase in the (vegetable) index,'' the report said
lettuce prices were reported at $21.30 per 100 pounds, compared with $11.10 in february and $35.60 in january
the index for livestock and livestock products was down 0.7 percent from february but was 4.2 percent above march 1987. prices were higher for cattle, eggs and broilers but were lower for hogs and milk
march farm commodity prices averaged 130 percent of a 1977 base used for comparison, according to the preliminary figures, the same as in february. a year ago the march index was 121 percent
no new figures for farm production costs were included in the report. those have been confined to quarterly averages because of budget cutbacks
in january, however, farm expenses were unchanged from last fall but averaged 4.4 percent above a year earlier. the next quarterly figures will be reported in april
the report said:
_cattle averaged $68.40 per 100 pounds of live weight nationally, up from $67.40 in february and the $59.30 reported for march 1987. those are averages for all types of cattle sold as beef
_hogs averaged $41.90 per 100 pounds, compared with $45.80 in march and $47.40 a year earlier
_corn, at $1.84 a bushel, was up from $1.83 in february and the average of $1.47 per bushel a year earlier
_wheat prices at the farm, according to preliminary figures, averaged $2.64 per bushel, compared with $2.79 in february and $2.57 a year earlier
_rice averaged $8.46 per 100 pounds, compared with $8.97 in february and $3.62 a year earlier
_soybeans were $5.93 per bushel, compared with $5.97 in february and $4.73 a year earlier
_upland cotton was reported at 56.9 cents per pound, compared with 56.8 in february and 47.5 cents in march 1987
_eggs were 50.8 cents per dozen, compared with 46.9 cents in february and 54.4 cents a year earlier
_milk was $12 per 100 pounds, compared with $12.30 in february and $12.50 a year earlier
_broilers were 27.5 cents per pound, live weight, compared with 25.7 cents in february and 29.1 cents a year ago
the national association of wheat growers says its producers should receive incentives from the agriculture department to sell grain on the open market rather than have to forfeit it to the government when price support loans come due
frank johannsen, association president, said wednesday that wheat producers deserve the same kind of consideration given corn producers who are being allowed to keep their grain under federal price support for an additional year
that was a reference to agriculture secretary richard e. lyng's announcement tuesday that price support loans for some old-crop corn and sorghum will be extended a year longer than their normal maturity dates
johannsen, a bayard, neb., wheat farmer, said in a statement released here that the association is ``seeking a way to encourage growers to settle their maturing loans'' by paying them off with generic certificates
the certificates are issued by usda as payment-in-kind under crop programs and can be exchanged for surplus commodities owned by the department's commodity credit corp
if the price support loans are not repaid, a farmer must forfeit the grain to the ccc, which cancels the debt
once the ccc takes over the grain, it must be moved into government storage. much of the ccc wheat is currently being sold back into the market in weekly auctions
since current estimates are that it costs the government at least 20 cents a bushel to move, store, catalog and exchange forfeited wheat through weekly auctions, our proposal won't cost anything extra and it will reduce some of the government's logistical problems,'' johannsen said. ``it has the added benefit of keeping wheat moving in the pipeline of our much-improved market.''
besides, he said, grain farmers ``have a right to expect even-handed treatment'' from the department
the nikkei stock average closed at 26,260.26 down 59.81 points, on the tokyo stock exchange on thursday
the teamsters union has eliminated a rival in trying to unionize the once bitterly anti-union adolph coors co. after organizing anheuser-busch's newest brewery just two weeks ago
the afl-cio on wednesday awarded sole organizing rights to the teamsters at coors' lead brewery at golden, colo., less than 50 miles away from the new anheuser-busch facility at fort collins, colo
the labor federation ordered one of its veteran affiliates, the machinists union, to withdraw from its campaign to organize the same 3,200 coors workers, saying the teamsters had a much better chance of succeeding
the decision was an outgrowth of the teamsters' decision last october to reaffiliate their 1.6 million members with the afl-cio. the union was expelled from the federation 30 years earlier on charges of corruption
a major factor in the afl-cio's decision to readmit the teamsters was ending the expensive fights and membership raids that the two organizations constantly waged against each other. many employers often were able to avoid collective bargaining altogether by playing one union against the other
the afl-cio last september had awarded the sole organizing rights at coors to the machinists. the teamsters had challenged that ruling as soon as they were re-admitted to the federation last nov. 1
coors, in the face of an intensive organizing effort by the teamsters since early 1986, last august signed an agreement with the afl-cio ending a 10-year-old nationwide boycott of its beer by the labor movement
in exchange, the company agreed to forgo erecting the usual legal hurdles available to employers in opposing unions and allow an afl-cio affiliate an unfettered attempt to organize its golden work force
however, that was before the teamsters were back in the afl-cio. and teamsters officials admitted they now have concerns now about how the coors-afl-cio pact will hold up in the face of wednesday's action
we're elated,'' said charles klare, director of the teamsters' 100,000-member brewery and soft drinks division. ``but there's a lot to be found out yet. we've got to meet with coors and determine if they accept the fact that the afl-cio picked us.''
the machinists union had argued before an arbitrator picked by afl-cio president lane kirkland that the teamsters should give up the coors effort based on last september's decision
the teamsters countered they had an ongoing organizing campaign at coors a year before the machinists entered the picture and had gotten signatures on teamster union cards from more than 30 percent of the workers at golden
kirkland agreed with the teamsters, according to witnesses at the arbitration proceedings
it was a black-and-white case,'' said vicki saporta, the teamsters' director of organizing. ``we were there first and they didn't have a single card signed. we're also the predominant union in the industry. we have contracts at all 12 anheuser-busch breweries covering some 9,000 workers.''
ms. saporta said the teamsters have another tactical advantage in that it also has union contracts representing employees of more than 180 local distributors of coors' products nationwide
the teamsters just last week ratified a new contract with anheuser-busch raising the base pay for brewery production workers from its current $16.50 an hour to $17.25 over the next three years
just a week earlier, the union won a an organizing effort at anheuser-busch's newest facility at fort collins to represent its current work force of about 340 people, which is expected to grow to 550 by next january
that was one of the factors the arbitrator took into consideration,'' klare said. ``coors workers are averaging about $3.50 to $4 an hour less than our members. seeing how fellow workers down the road are doing gives them a big incentive to come in.''
people who have been putting off writing letters may want to get busy before sunday, when the cost of sending one rises to a quarter from 22 cents
the 14 percent increase in the price of first-class mail is less, however, than the 18 percent increase for mailing newspapers and magazines and the 25 percent increase for advertising mail
the rate increases, proposed last may, were designed to avoid continuing losses by the postal service, officials said. the agency was more than $220 million in the red last year
some 6 billion ``e'' stamps have been distributed to post offices across the nation to fill the gap until new 25-cent stamps can be printed. the new stamps, without any price on them, are good only for use within the country
they have no denomination because they had to be printed ahead of time, before officials knew what new rate would be approved by the indpendent postal rate commission
postmaster general anthony frank has ordered post offices to extend their hours during the next two weeks to help in the changeover
stamps are also being sold by mail and telephone. phone orders, by credit card, can be made by calling 1-800-stamp24. there is a $2 service charge
