novelist john clellon holmes, the first to describe 1950s youth as a ``beat'' generation, died of cancer. he was 62
holmes, who died wednesday, was a companion of jack kerouac, allen ginsburg, william burroughs and other chroniclers of the ``beat'' lifestyle in new york city after world war ii
his first novel, ``go,'' published in 1952, was about the beat world, and appeared five years before kerouac's more popular beatnik novel, ``on the road.''
holmes, a holyoke, mass., native, who was also a poet and a critic, wrote more about the period and its philosophy in ``nothing more to declare,'' published in 1967
however, he criticized the beatniks' 1960s successors, the hippies, saying they had a ``fad culture'' characterized by ``a feeling of helplessness.''
holmes became a visiting lecturer at the university of arkansas in 1957. in 1966, he became the school's first writer-in-residence. he also taught at yale, the university of iowa, bowling green university and brown university. holmes retired from teaching in 1986
displaced person: the travel essays of john clellon holmes,'' was published earlier this month by the university of arkansas press
holmes is survived by his wife, shirley allen holmes; his mother and two sisters. and sent, sub 6th graf: `the former ... development program.' picks up 7th graf, `the younger ... ^by barry renfrew</note>
the opposition today accused the government of concealing massive corruption involving hundreds of millions of dollars and demanded former president chun doo-hwan be questioned about missing funds
the country's two main opposition parties claimed the government had limited the scope of a probe into alleged corruption by chun's younger brother, charging information about the chun family's activities was being suppressed
the government has orchestrated another cover-up and fooled the people,'' the reunification democratic party charged
the party for peace and democracy demanded president chun be questioned about allegations of widespread corruption under his government and called for a full investigation
the governing democratic justice party denied there was any attempt to cover up corruption and said it was determined to expose any official wrongdoing
the former president's brother, chun kyung-hwan, was charged early today with embezzling $10.4 million as head of saemaul undong (new community), a semi-official development program
the younger chun, who was taken to a seoul prison in handcuffs, also was charged with taking bribes, influence peddling, evading taxes and violation of business, land and construction laws
if convicted under special laws covering massive public fraud, chun could receive a sentence ranging from 10 years in prison to death
ten other people, including aides of the younger chun and senior saemaul officials, also were indicted on embezzlement, bribery, influence peddling and corruption charges, officials said
the other suspects include chun kyung-hwan's two brothers-in-law
the opposition charged that the younger chun and his associates had embezzled hundreds of millions of dollars, and the government was concealing evidence to prevent a political backlash
chief prosecutor kang won-il said the younger chun amassed a fortune in money, land and stocks by using government and family connections during the seven years he headed saemaul
the former president had appointed him to the post
it is agonizing to me that i have caused trouble to my brother,'' the younger chun was quoted as saying by prosecutors
kang said the younger chun diverted government and saemaul funds, pressured corporations into making illegal donations, arranged to get private businesses government contracts and permits, and misappropriated land and buildings built with government funds
kang said the investigation was centering on charges chun diverted huge sums of money overseas for land speculation in the united states and australia. the prosecutor said the probe was continuing and further revelations were expected
saemaul was founded in 1971 to promote urban and rural development. the younger chun resigned as its chief in 1987 after being linked to gangsters
prosecutors are questioning government officials about charges they aided or concealed saemaul corruption to protect the former president and his family
former president chun, who left office feb. 25 after seven years in power, has not been implicated in the saemaul affair. he is on a private american tour and met last week with president reagan
several of the largest insurance companies are offering sharp discounts in premiums for drivers of cars with air bags, the safety devices that inflate and protect a driver in a serious accident
usaa, the country's sixth largest insurance company, announced wednesday a premium discount of up to 60 percent for personal injury and medical coverage for air bag-equipped cars
the company also said it would contribute $300 to the purchase or lease of a 1988 car equipped with an air bag
state farm mutual automobile insurance co. on tuesday announced a premium discount of from $3 to $24 for cars equipped with air bags or passive belts, which automatically wrap around a car occupant
robert f. mcdermott, chairman of usaa, told a news conference he expected air bags to be available as an option or standard equipment in several million cars within the next 18 months
the auto industry in the past has complained that while insurance companies have campaigned to get air bags into cars they have not offered car owners financial incentives to order the safety devices
a dispute between government agencies over the questions to be asked on the 1990 census has been settled, before friday's deadline for reporting to congress
the census bureau reported wednesday that it had settled its differences with the white house office of management and budget over how many households would receive the longer, more detailed form to obtain the national head count
omb had wanted to reduce paperwork by deleting some questions and reducing the number of people who get the more complex long form
the two agencies have agreed that all 106 million households in the nation will be sent the short form, while the more detailed long form will go to 17.7 million. census had wanted to sent it to nearly 20 million households, omb to limit it to 10 million
short form questions on plumbing facilities and condominiums will be switched to the long form, as omb suggested. but other questions will be retained, including the cost of uilities
some things that were asked in the 1980 census will be dropped in 1990. these include employment five years earlier, marital history, weeks spent looking for work, number of bathrooms, air conditioning and heating equipment, presence of an elevator and type of fuel used for cooking and heating water
william ball has become the nation's 67th secretary of the navy, pledging to keep his forces ``strong and prepared'' to meet any challenge
standing in an ornate old executive office building room first used by navy secretary richard thompson in 1879, ball said wednesday that by maintaining military strength, the united states ``preserve the peace and ultimately extend the special gift that is freedom the world over.''
president reagan, making remarks at the swearing-in ceremony for his former legislative liaison, said ball had ``won the respect of the leaders of both parties.'' he said ``i've repeatedly turned'' to ball for help and advice in recent years
white house chief of staff howard baker swore in ball as several cabinet officers, members of congress and military officers looked on. after thompson, who served under president rutherford b. hayes, 14 navy secretaries used the room, heavily decorated in naval motif
ball, 39, succeeds james webb, who resigned in a dispute with defense secretary frank c. carlucci over pentagon budgetary priorities, including a delay in reaching the 600-ship level for the navy
sears, roebuck and co. has agreed to halt sales of lawn darts, following a federal complaint about the potentially dangerous sports items, according to the consumer product safety commission
sears agreed in a consent decree to stop selling lawn darts within a week, the commission said wedenesday
the decree settles charges that the nationwide retailer offered lawn darts for sale without required warning labels and in areas near toy sales
sears' prompt response to the commission's concerns should serve as an example for manufacturers and other retailers of lawn darts,'' said commission chairman terrence m. scanlon
lawn darts are an outdoor game in which large, pointed darts are tossed at targets on the ground. they can pose a serious hazard, with three deaths reported in the last 18 years and an estimated 670 annual injuries, the safety agency said
the agency asked that consumers report injuries or improper sales of lawn darts by calling it at 1-800-638-2772
someday, doctors will have a system for identifying stress-plagued patients who are headed for heart trouble even though their blood pressure readings may look normal, says a heart researcher
dr. robert s. eliot, a cardiovascular researcher from denver, told cardiologists meeting in atlanta this week that new ways of testing can identify ``hot reactors'' _ stressed but seemingly healthy people
these are people who fight saber-toothed tigers 30, 40 times a day and don't even know it,'' eliot told reporters wednesday at the annual meeting of the american college of cardiology
a doctor can't tell from resting blood pressure (tests taken at rest),'' he said, adding that conventional blood pressure readings don't tell how much blood is pumping or how much resistance the heart is fighting
eliot, director of the cardiovascular institute at denver's swedish medical center, has worked 10 years on ways to measure the rapid, stress-induced fluctuations in the cardiovascular system
that work, he said, has yielded a 30-minute test using devices to monitor heart performance, blood pressure and other factors to find ``hot reactors,'' who apparently make up more than 10 percent of the population
with so many seemingly healthy people at risk of illness, within three to eight months in some cases, he said, ``i think it's worth testing in people.''
eliot and his colleagues plan to expand their efforts to three other locations next year. someday soon, he hopes, physicians will agree on a standard way of conducting such stress tests
we have a model,'' he said. ``it's been successful.''
those efforts are part of what eliot terms ``a new kind of medicine,'' emphasizing not just technical medical techniques, but beneficial lifestyle adjustments. some, he noted, have called it ``medicine from the 21st century _ teaching people what they can do for themselves.''
drugs and surgery are not sufficient for most people'' with cardiovascular problems, said dr. dean ornish, an assistant professor at the university of california at san francisco school of medicine and president of the preventative medicine research institute
cardiology has tended to ignore the role of the brain on the heart,'' ornish said
