the grandson of a former university of texas football coach has been charged with stealing a missing page of albert einstein's notes from a locked display case at the school, police said
samuel k. royal, 18, was arrested wednesday evening at his austin apartment, said ronald thomas, a university police lieutenant
the page of handwritten notes, owned by the university, was reported missing last week from a locked glass case on the fourth floor of the peter t. flawn academic center. it was among six pages on display from a series addressing the mathematical concept of euclidean rotation
investigators said a telephoned tip led them to the younger royal's apartment tuesday where the page was found in a photo album, along with photographs of his grandfather, darrell royal, the university of texas' football coach from 1957 through 1976
samuel royal is not a university student. his father, mack davis, is a custodian on the same floor of the academic center where the display case was located
according to a court affidavit, a woman named alissa chambers, who also lives at the apartment where the page was discovered, said samuel royal ``walked in and flashed some papers in front of my face and said, `these are the writings of albert einstein.'''
police could not immediately offer an explanation for the theft. the display case was locked and the glass unbroken when the document was discovered missing
the missing page is part of an archive of 60 or 70 pages ``upon which einstein wrote the notes representing his thinking as he was trying to work out his theories near the end of his life,'' said john chalmers, librarian for ut's harry ransom humanities research center
the university has owned the papers for 25 years. einstein apparently wrote the notes several years before he died in 1955
although the page likely could have been sold for a couple of thousand dollars, chalmers said, its value far exceeds that amount
for all of us, it's a piece of our heritage, and it is not to be replaced. in that sense, it has no price,'' chalmers said
darrell royal, who is special assistant to the president of the university, did not return a telephone call to his austin residence on wednesday
lady carroll bing, wife of opera impresario sir rudolf bing, was arrested outside carnegie hall for failing to appear in court on charges she slapped an executive of a performing arts management company
the arrest on 57th street on wednesday was the latest in a series of legal entanglements for the couple
lady bing, 48, has been visiting columbia artists management's midtown manhattan office frequently, often with her 86-year-old husband, according to police
she was apparently upset that her husband, general manager of the metropolitan opera from 1950 to 1972, had been dropped from columbia artists' board of directors, police said. columbia artists represents classical music artists and produces classical concerts
lady bing was arrested on a bench warrant issued after she failed to appear in court monday to answer charges of criminal trespass and harassment, according to detective joseph mcconville
the charges were filed last month by barbara quinones, vice president for administration at columbia artists, who claimed that lady bing entered her office without permission, harassed her and slapped her face
why lady bing returned to columbia's offices wednesday was not known, mcconville said
ms. quinones and her attorney, todd steckler, refused to comment on the arrest
shortly after the bings' wedding 14 months ago, state supreme court justice arthur blyn declared that bing suffered from alzheimer's disease and was unable to control his $900,000 estate
the judge appointed a conservator, barred lady bing from spending her husband's assets and allowed bing's lawyers to begin annulment proceedings. a pretrial hearing on the annulment proceedings is set for may 3
bing said last year that he loved his wife and that he believed allegations by longtime friends that she was misspending his money were wrong
blyn ordered lady bing not to take her husband out of the court's jurisdiction
however, she took him to florida and the west indian island of anguilla. the couple disappeared before turning up in great britain. they returned to new york late last year
in 1982, a washington court found that lady bing, then carroll douglass, was incapable of managing her own affairs, and appointed as conservators her brother and sister
bing, born in vienna, austria, went to britain in the 1930s, where he headed the glyndebourne opera and founded the famed edinburgh festival. he moved to the united states in 1949, but retained his british nationality and was knighted for his contributions to music
a former wedtech corp. official has admitted that he waited months before telling prosecutors about his alleged attempt to offer a $200,000 bribe to u.s. attorney general edwin meese iii
mario moreno, former vice chairman of the defunt bronx defense contractor, says prosecutors didn't ask him about meese and he didn't volunteer the information
a prosecutor, however, objected to defense attorney dominick amorosa's line of questioning wednesday at the racketeering trial of rep. mario biaggi, d-n.y., and six others
assistant u.s. attorney mary shannon explained, with the jury out of the room, that prosecutors in manhattan were barred from inquiring about meese because he was then being investigated in washington under the special prosecutor law
meese has not been charged with any wrongdoing, although a special prosecutor continues to investigate his dealings with wedtech, a local manufacturer that won millions of dollars in defense contracts
the attorney general's legal troubles have placed him under increasing pressure to step down, triggered in part by the resignation of some of his top aides earlier this week
ms. shannon also said the special prosecutor initially was investigating former white house aide lyn nofziger, not meese, until last may. nofziger was convicted last month of illegal lobbying for wedtech
biaggi, his eldest son, richard, and the other co-defendants are accused of turning wedtech into a racketeering enterprise that paid bribes to public officials and others
moreno is one of four former wedtech officers cooperating with the government in a bid for leniency
he has previously testified that he and former wedtech president anthony guariglia offered $200,000 to e. robert wallach, a close friend of the attorney general, ``to fix the case'' with meese
he also said that wallach never got back to them and the money never was paid
in his 12th day on the witness stand, moreno admitted under prodding by amorosa, richard biaggi's attorney, that he did not tell prosecutors about the bribe offer until at least august 1987, more than eight months after he and the other ex-wedtech officers began cooperating with investigators
wallach, former meese financial adviser w. franklyn chinn, and another man have been indicted in a separate case, charged with allegedly taking payoffs from wedtech to influence meese and other government officials
all three have pleaded innocent
a government official today confirmed that taiwan is replacing a research nuclear reactor. the united states long has worried the reactor could be used in an atomic weapons development program
liu kuang-chi, secretary-general of the government atomic energy council, said the united states was assisting in converting the reactor to a new system that would provide ``less possibility to produce plutonium,'' a key component in the production of atomic weapons
the comments were made one week after the new york times reported the reagan administration pressured taiwan to close the reactor and to stop work on a secret installation that could have processed the reactor's spent fuel to extract plutonium
liu had earlier confirmed that the research reactor at lung tan, 25 miles southwest of taipei, was closed in january but denied the move was made because of u.s. pressure
today, however, he acknowledged that ``maybe there's some influence (from) the united states'' behind the decision to replace the reactor, adding that washington ``did express its concern about our research.''
the energy official said the u.s. concern over lung tan goes back many years and may partly be caused by reports that india developed atomic weaponry using a reactor of the same design
liu reiterated taiwan's position of not developing atomic bombs and said of the lung tan overhaul, ``since we decided not to make (atomic) weapons, why not make them (the united states) happy?''
liu said the main reason for changing lung tan's design was to make it compatible with taiwan's nuclear power reactors, which run on a different system
it's a major change, the reactor is completely changed,'' liu said. ``it is a very major task ... it is keeping everybody busy.'' he said the conversion would take at least two years, but he did not have a cost estimate
according to liu, the united states is providing technical help and will provide assistance in obtaining fuel for testing the new core
the lung tan reactor, which opened in 1973, has used heavy water to control the splitting of atomic nuclei, a system that can use natural uranium as fuel. the reactor is being converted to a ``light water'' system that requires enriched uranium fuel
chang kuo-lung, professor of physics of the national taiwan university, said the high-tech production of enriched uranium is limited to a few countries, making the fuel comparatively difficult to obtain and its use easier to monitor. liu said taiwan cannot make the enriched fuel
liu also stressed that taiwan doesn't have facilities to process spent fuel into weapons-grade plutonium. when asked whether taiwan had worked on a secret processing installation, he replied: ``baloney.''
still, local newspapers have been filled with reports that the u.s. government learned from a missing top-level taiwanese nuclear researcher that taiwan had plans to make nuclear weapons
the media reports claim that col. chang hsien-yi, former deputy director of the official nuclear energy research center, is working for the cia and has moved to the united states since disappearing in january
liu, who previously worked with chang, said he did not know where the missing official was or what had happened to him
taiwan's nuclear policy is a particularly sensitive topic because communist china has said taiwan production of atomic weapons would be a reason for invading the island, which beijing views as a renengade province
a storm packing winds up to 40 mph swirled around the rockies today, spreading more than 5 inches of snow from utah to the great plains
rain fell across the tennessee and lower mississippi valleys, prompting flash flood watches in parts of mississippi and louisiana where recent rain left the ground saturated
forecasters said up to 2 feet of snow were expected in the foothills of the colorado rockies by friday morning. so far, more than 5 inches have fallen at fort collins, colo., and more than 3 inches in parts of wyoming
