a divorcing couple's legal battle over their unborn child apparently ended when the 18-year-old woman underwent an abortion before she could be served with a court order blocking the procedure
jennifer reynolds ended her 8-week-old pregnancy over her estranged husband's objections in less than an hour wednesday, between the time a district court allowed the procedure and the utah court of appeals blocked it, said rosemary gacnick, spokeswoman for the state court system
the abortion was performed before the appellate court could serve mrs. reynolds with papers reinstating a temporary restraining order vacated about an hour earlier by 3rd district judge david s. young, gacnik said
the appeals court had scheduled a monday hearing to consider 25-year-old michael jon reynolds' appeal of young's decision, but her husband's attorney said the hearing might be pointless if the fetus had been aborted
if the abortion has taken place, we're going to have to make some serious evaluation ... there's a pretty good argument that would make it moot,'' said the attorney, mitchell barker
young issued the original restraining order last week, when he ruled that mrs. reynolds could not have an abortion pending resolution of a divorce-related custody dispute involving a 10-month-old infant and the fetus
he vacated his own order on wednesday when he accepted arguments by american civil liberties union attorneys that a woman has a constitutional right to end her pregnancy
young said while reynolds may have the right to be consulted about any abortion involving mrs. reynolds, she had the ultimate authority over whether to carry the fetus to term
barker acknowledged mrs. reynold's right to privacy, but said her husband also had the right of procreation and that when the two clash, it is the courts which must decide who prevails
later, while barker filed an appeal to the appellate division, which reinstated the restraining order pending monday's hearing, mrs. reynolds drove off to have the abortion
nobody wins _ no matter who wins,'' reynolds said. ``it's not my right or her right. i think the child's got a right of its own. it's a baby. it's got a mind. it can't talk, it can't walk, but it's got a right to be born.''
mrs. reynolds could not be located for comment wednesday night. but television station kutv quoted her as saying she would not comment on the abortion, saying ``that's too sensitive and personal a question.''
legislation granting bank holding companies broad new securities powers is heading into the house after getting an overwhelming endorsement in the senate
senators voted 94-2 wednesday night to approve a bill that would permit the mingling of commercial and investment banking for the first time since the depression
the legislation substantially revises restrictions on banks in the glass-steagall act, passed in 1933 in reaction to abuses preceding the 1929 stock market crash
proponents of change argued that developments in the financial system, particularly in the last decade, threaten the ability of banks to compete. securities firms, for instance, offer bank-like services such as commercial paper and money market mutual funds
the senate bill would permit bank holding companies to underwrite and sell mortgage-backed securities, commercial paper and municipal revenue bonds immediately after the bill is approved by both houses of congress and signed by president reagan, who favors the bill
bank holding companies would be allowed to underwrite and sell corporate bonds and mutual funds six months after enactment. a vote by congress would be required in 1991 before bank holding companies could underwrite corporate stock, the most lucrative securities activity
wednesday evening's vote came after nearly six hours of debate in which senate banking committee chairman william proxmire, d-wis., warded off amendments that could have unraveled the delicate compromise adopted on an 18-2 vote by his committee earlier this month
the bill is seen as something of a swan song for proxmire, who retires next year after more than 30 years in the senate. just before its adoption, it was named the proxmire financial modernization act of 1988
donald ogilvie, executive vice president of the american bankers association, the biggest industry group pushing for the bill's passage, praised it as benefiting consumers
this should accelerate the momentum for enlightened financial reform legislation in the house,'' he said
however, the house banking committee is split into many factions. its chairman, rep. fernand j. st germain, d-r.i., has released a proposal that would grant banks only a few securities powers _ commercial paper, mortgage revenue bonds and asset-backed securities _ and places more restrictions on banks
ogilvie said bankers would work in the house to defeat limits on banks' insurance activities, but his industry faces tougher going there than it did in the senate
one provision of the senate bill would require banks to prove they are meeting the needs of poor citizens and neighborhoods before getting permission to exercise the new powers authorized in the bill
another prohibits misleading savings account advertisements, and another requires lenders to disclose terms of home equity loans
a former public guardian, convicted of stealing as much as $200,000 from mentally handicapped or elderly wards, may have to repay all the money, a prosecutor says
multnomah county circuit judge winston l. bradshaw on wednesday found paul e. nizdil, 44, guilty of 12 counts of felony theft and 12 counts of official misconduct, a misdemeanor. sentencing was set for may 24
nizdil, who was fired in october as the county's public guardian and conservator, was convicted after the defense and prosecution agreed to submit police reports as the only evidence
the agreement calls for nizdil to repay the stolen money, but the exact amount was not set, defense attorney janet hoffman said. the total could be upwards of $200,000, said deputy district attorney jeffrey martin
each theft count carries a maximum sentence of five years in prison. each misconduct count carries a maximum penalty of a year in jail
nizdil remains free on his own recognizance pending sentencing
ms. martin said the state had not yet prepared a sentencing recommendation, but said the state had made no sentencing concessions in its agreement with nizdil
nizdil was indicted on 22 counts each of theft and misconduct. ms. martin said there was evidence of additional thefts, but said that evidence will not be presented to a grand jury because of the agreement
ms. martin said an investigation into nizdil's conduct before his firing had not been completed. if nizdil continues cooperating with the investigation, the state will move for dismissal of the remaining counts, she said
ms. hoffman said nizdil suffers from a compulsion to gamble, and told the judge she would call two doctors to testify on nizdil's behalf at his sentencing
last month, nizdil repaid the county $65,334, the amount identified up to that point as having been stolen
since then, the state's estimate of the total amount taken from elderly or mentally handicapped wards has increased from $114,000 to $200,000
nizdil admitted to police that on several occasions he made checks payable to a fictitious name for repairs allegedly made to houses owned by wards. nizdil told police he used money from the checks to pay gambling debts
nizdil was fired for reasons unrelated to the thefts. county officials did not discover the missing money until january, when tenants renting a house owned by a ward complained that repairs had not been made
a 9-year-old nicknamed ``buzz'' is winging his way across america on a 10-day flight planned as the longest trip by a boy believed to be the nation's youngest unlicensed pilot
tony aliengena of san juan capistrano, who earlier this month made a one-mile solo in an ultra-light plane, was at the controls of his father's twin-engine cessna on wednesday as it left john wayne airport
tony was accompanied by his flight instructor, ed fernett, and don taylor, an observer from the national aeronautics association. taylor will verify that tony is at the controls throughout the flight
the goal is to do it by myself. even if we lose an engine, i'm gonna do it,'' tony said in an interview before leaving
tony's father, gary aliengena, said his son would fly four to seven hours a day during the 10-day trip. tony will not fly sunday so he can spend easter with relatives in massachusetts
tony wants to break the longest-trip-by-youngest-pilot record set by 10-year-old christopher lee marshall of oceano, who flew from san luis obispo county to fort lauderdale, fla., and back to burbank last august
on march 13, tony set a record as the youngest pilot to fly solo when he flew his father's ultra-light plane _ which is not regulated by the federal aviation administration _ around oceanside municipal airport
in order for tony to fly a larger plane like the cessna, tony must have a licensed instructor in the cockpit with him
his latest trip includes landings in el paso, texas; dallas; memphis, tenn.; gastonia, n.c.; richmond, va.; bedford, mass.; washington; evansville, ind.; st. louis; oklahoma city; tucumcari, n.m.; and phoenix, ariz
