kurt waldheim may have cooperated with u.s. and british intelligence services after world war ii in return for having his german army record purged of incriminating evidence, a british newspaper reported today
a panel of historians has concluded the austrian president was ``in close proximity'' to some nazi atrocities in the balkans, knew they were going on and made no attempt to prevent them. it also said waldheim concealed his wartime past and tried to make it seem harmless once he could no longer hide it
the international panel of historians left open the question of whether he was guilty of any crime. waldheim has denied any wrongdoing
the times of london said today it had unearthed evidence that british wartime documents and subsequent british foreign office papers likely to relate to waldheim's wartime role had been suppressed
the report, by correspondent robert fisk, said the suppression raised suspicion waldheim may have collaborated with the americans and british after the war in return for having his german army record purged
fisk quoted robert herzstein, a university of south carolina history professor, as saying he believes waldheim passed on large amounts of information after the war to allied intelligence agents, especially on communist partisans in yugoslavia and guerrillas in greece
herzstein is due to publish a book next week that suggests waldheim worked for the americans after the war
fisk quoted him as saying several records of the british element in the united nations war crimes commission appeared to be missing from the british government's public records office
fisk's report said the times had examined hundreds of wartime files at the public records office. fisk said that in one file on military activities in yugoslavia between may 1944 and the end of the war, when waldheim was in dubrovnik, an entire section listed in the index as ``allegations of murder of british prisoners of war'' was missing
the reporter said a government order had closed a file on the slayings to public access until the year 2021
he quoted officials at the public records office as saying they did not know when the order was issued. but he said the government decision to prevent public access was taken before 1982, when waldheim ended his 10-year term as u.n. secretary-general
allegations about waldheim's alleged links to wartime atrocities surfaced in 1986 during his campaign for the austrian presidency
fisk said attempts by the times to seek access to specific ``closed'' files and to obtain reasons for their retention were refused
two portable anti-aircraft missiles, tentatively identified as soviet-made sam-7s, were found aboard an iranian gunboat recovered by the u.s. navy last week, a navy spokesman said today
the weapons on the boat, found abandoned and drifting in the strait of hormuz, also included three ``chaff rockets'' of unknown origin and four other unidentified rockets with fusing devices
chaff is a material blown into the air to confuse the homing system of a radar-guided missile
maj. barry willey, a spokesman for the u.s. central command, said the twin-barrelled gun mounted in the cockpit of the 30-foot boat was a soviet-made zsu 23mm anti-aircraft weapon
the gun apparently had been used for attacks on ships in the southern persian gulf and the hormuz. it was rusty, but functional, and was loaded for firing when found
authoritative references say the soviet sam-7, a shoulder-fired missile similar to the american-made redeye, is known to be a part of iran's weapons inventory. but willey said he did not know whether it had previously been seen in the gulf
iran also is believed to possess some u.s.-made stinger missiles, a more advanced missile than the redeye. it fired at least one at a u.s. helicopter last october, but missed
several stingers and a spent launcher were found in a sunken iranian speedboat recovered by u.s. navy divers on jan. 3
the gunboat, an open-cockpit, twin-diesel craft, was found by the guided missile frigate reuben james, drifting in 10-foot seas in the hormuz passage last thursday
the boat's whereabouts were not disclosed. willey would say only that it was in u.s. navy custody
u.s. officers have said they do not know why the boat apparently was abandoned by the iranians. it appeared to have been recently vacated by its crew and was trailing a sea anchor
the fiberglass-hulled boat was the fourth iranian small craft captured by the navy in the persian gulf in the past six months, but the first taken in the southern waterway where iran's naval frigates and revolutionary guards concentrate their surface raids on neutral shipping
in addition to the rockets and missiles, willey said the boat yielded one soviet-designed ak-47 assault rifle and 203 rounds of ammunition, 500 rounds of ammunition for the mounted gun, and related items
the missiles apparently were contained in a sealed wooden box, six feet long, found in the bottom of the boat
officers on the reuben james did not open the box, but there was speculation at the time that it might contain stingers or other portable rockets
the sam-7, known as the ``strela,'' or arrow in russian, has an effective range of about two miles, atttacking aircraft by homing in on their engine exhaust
although it has been replaced in the soviet inventory by a newer portable missile, the sam-14, the strela is still being produced for soviet forces and for export sales
it also is manufactured by china and egypt, and more than 40 countries, including both iran and iraq, are believed to have the weapon in their arsenals
u.s. officials gave no further information on the chaff rockets found on the iranian boat. such rockets are carried aboard most warships and aircraft in the gulf. that concourse is not above ground; and subs 7th graf, ``we see xxx, to delete extraneous said</note>
the ``mole patrol'' is on a roll
for nine years, officer charles myers worked underground, patrolling the 3{-mile network of corridors, platforms and tunnels of philadelphia's mass-transit system. his unit was justly dubbed the mole patrol
he now helps run the police department's two battery-powered carts, which cruise silently through the concourse at the hub of the city's transportation system
the white and blue industrial carts, fitted with searchlights, rescue gear, two-way radio, roll bar and dome lights, can carry 8,400 pounds and have a top speed of about 10 mph. they cost $6,200 apiece
the new carts were quickly dubbed ``mole mobiles.'' after all, ``transit response vehicles'' just sounds too stuffy
before the carts came, if myers heard of trouble in another part of the concourse, ``it would be a footrace,'' he said. ``you'd be exhausted by the time you got there.''
we see a very positive response by all the store owners,'' capt. lawrence norton, commander of the transit unit, said wednesday
they see this cart, they come out and want to say hello. the public stops you all the time,'' he said. ``they get a real kick out of the fact that the police are down here in strength.''
within the next year the department hopes to add five more of the vehicles, because a cart is cheaper than paying for extra officers, norton said
the vehicles are parked and recharged during morning and evening rush hours, when the transit system's 350,000 daily passengers clog the passageways
myers said he and another officer arrested a burglar their first night, when they received a suspicious-person report and sped off to a far-off part of the concourse, which features stores, restaurants and banks
lo and behold, there's a man standing there inside a closed store,'' myers said. ``the only thing he said was, `i didn't hear you coming.''' ousted in 1971. pick up 5th graf pvs: ``prime minister...''</note>
sir william mcmahon, a former prime minister, died today after a long battle with cancer. he was 80
mcmahon died early today at st. luke's hospital in sydney and was cremated in a private service shortly afterward, family members said
mcmahon served as prime minister and head of the liberal party in 1971-72, and previously headed the treasury and foreign affairs department
he became prime minister on march 10, 1971, after john gorton was ousted as prime minister and liberal party leader in a dispute within the party. but mcmahon lost to gough whitlam the following year. mcmahon entered parliament in 1949
prime minister bob hawke of the labor party praised mcmahon's service
although on opposite sides of the political fence, i found sir william a generous opponent. he maintained an enormous enthusiasm for and interest in public affairs after his retirement from parliament and was constructive in his discussions on economics and political matters,'' hawke said in a statement
liberal party leader john howard said: ``few parliamentarians in the postwar period could boast a career as rich and diverse as sir william's.''
former liberal prime minister malcolm fraser called mcmahon a vigorous administrator and tenacious member of parliament who would be remembered for three decades of dedicated service
mcmahon is survived by his wife, lady sonia, his son, julian, and two daughters, belinda and deborah
a former preschool worker has been ordered to wear a sign around her neck about her sex offenses after she pleaded guilty to misdemeanor charges of sexually assaulting two girls
king county superior court judge warren chan on wednesday gave julia lynn guptill-gilbert of bothell a choice between spending 30 days in jail or wearing the sign for 60 days every time she goes out in public
ms. guptill-gilbert chose to wear the sign. she taught at a montessori school at the time of the assaults on two girls, aged 4 and 5
chan left it up to county prosecutors to decide the size and exact wording of the sign to be worn by the 19-year-old woman, who is five months pregnant
my words to her were that she must wear a sign saying: `i've been convicted of communicating with a minor for immoral purposes,''' chan said
chan also ordered ms. guptill-gilbert to write letters of apology to both victims, who were in court
both prosecution and defense attorneys objected to the ruling
our office has a preference for punishment that includes confinement, supervision and treatment, and we prefer those methods over the ones used by the judge in this case,'' said dan donohoe, the king county prosecutor's administrative assistant
you get to the matter of whether the punishment is cruel and unusual,'' he said. ``i'm not a lawyer, but i do think it's unusual.''
prosecutors had recommended a suspended one-year jail term for ms. guptill-gilbert, plus payment of counseling costs for the children and a mental health evaluation for ms. guptill-gilbert
defense attorney michael frost said ms. guptill-gilbert is likely to stay in her residence the entire 60-day period to avoid wearing the sign in public
ms. guptill-gilbert already has moved to california, raising questions about how sign order will be enforced
chan has scheduled a court hearing may 4 to find out whether california authorities will assume responsibility for monitoring the punishment. the 60-day period for wearing the sign isn't to begin until then
