a stradivarius violin fetched a world record auction price for a musical instrument of $889,240 at a sotheby's sale today, the auctioneers said
the violin, made in 1709 by italian craftsman antonio stradivari, is named after the master english violinist marie hall. composer vaughan williams composed ``the lark ascending'' for hall, which she first performed in 1920
an unidentified private south american buyer beat out two other dealers bidding by telephone in a tense, two-minute auction
it was quite drawn out and tense and there was a round of applause at the end,'' said sotheby's spokeswoman beth mchattie
the marie hall had been expected to sell for around $846,000, and bidding started at $376,000, sotheby's said
the previous highest auction price for a stradivarius was $728,000 for the colossus, dated 1716, which was sold at christie's auction house in london last april
the guinness book of records says the highest known price for a stradivarius was $1.2 million. but that was in a private sale of stradivarius' alard violin by w. e. hill and sons to a singaporean on an unknown date
about 700 of 1,116 violins by stradivarius have survived
marie hall, considered one of the finest violinists of her era, died at age 72 in 1956
she acquired the violin in 1905 and it was passed on to her daughter when she died. when it was last auctioned by sotheby's in november 1968, the violin sold for a then world record price of $52,600
the violin was included in a day-long sale of violins, violas and other stringed instruments
medical malpractice attorney harvey wachsman momentarily weighed the possibility of a lawsuit against the doctor who delivered his son in the back seat of his car on grand central parkway in queens
maybe i should sue, just for practice,'' he said on wednesday
but he immediately decided against it because the defendant would have been, well, himself
derek wachsman weighed in at 6 pounds, 9 ounces at about 1 a.m. wednesday in the back seat of a mercedes 560 sel about 200 yards west of la guardia airport
the elder wachsman and his wife kathy, also a malpractice lawyer, left their home on long island about 12:15 a.m., heading full-tilt for mount sinai hospital in manhattan
but the baby wanted out well short of the hospital so wachsman, who was a neurosurgeon before he became a lawyer, pulled over, delivered the baby and tied the umbilical cord with a shoelace
and what will derek be when he grows up?
a doctor and a lawyer,'' wachsman said. ^eds: corrects name to nusbaum, sted nussbaum, thruout</head>
ulysses s. grant was in the white house and gen. george custer was one year away from making his last stand when orpha nusbaum was born aug. 13, 1875
mrs. nusbaum, believed by the guinness book of world records to be the world's oldest person, died wednesday at age 112
she had pneumonia recently, but an official cause of death was not released, said diane hostetler, director of nursing at fountainview nursing home, where mrs. nusbaum lived
her condition worsened during the weekend,'' miss hostetler said
she couldn't do anything for herself anymore,'' said a stepdaughter-in-law, betty nusbaum. ``you can't do anything for a person who doesn't want to live anymore.''
betty nusbaum said she was saddened by the death, but said mrs. nusbaum had lived a good life
last month, guinness officials said they believed she was the oldest person alive
mrs. nusbaum was honored at a special ceremony in january when officials put the goshen city seal on census documents indicating she was born in 1875 on the family farm near middlebury about 10 miles away. she spent most of her life in middlebury until moving to the nursing home in 1982
florence knapp, who lived in a philadelphia suburb, had been recognized as the world's oldest person until her death jan. 11. she was 114 years and 94 days old
guinness restricts recognition to those who can provide birth records and other documentation
there had been some confusion whether mrs. nusbaum would be 112 or 113 last aug. 13. for years she had maintained she was a year older than she actually was
but a document found in the public library in this northern indiana city last september showed that the former orpha ulery was 4 years old when she was counted in the u.s. census of 1880, making her 112
mrs. nusbaum attributed her longevity to her strict obedience to a biblical command, betty nusbaum said. ``she honored her father and mother. that's it,'' she said
for many years mrs. nusbaum taught sunday school in the elkhart and goshen areas. when she was 93, she resumed writing poetry, a hobby she had stopped in the 1920s
mrs. nusbaum married john mischler, a minister, in 1897. after his death, she married frank nusbaum in 1947. he died in 1959
cardiologists should be aware that heart disease can be an early indicator of aids, and some patients can live longer with proper cardiac care, according to research presented at the american college of cardiology convention
in a 1983-86 study of 86 aids patients in paris and miami, 18 had heart disease and seven of those had heart disease before other aids-related ailments, dr. evlin kinney of the university of miami school of medicine said wednesday at the acc meeting
heart disease was present in 5 percent of all aids patients _ that's our estimate based on the patients we have seen,'' she said. ``cardiologists need to be aware of aids heart disease.''
while little could be done for aids patients suffering from tumor-based heart disease, she said, cardiac disease stemming from opportunistic infections such as tuberculosis _ rather than from tumors _ can be treated, prolonging the lives of terminally ill patients
there were patients who, with treatment, survived as long as (aids) patients without heart disease,'' kinney said. ``some of these patients, we did manage to prolong their lives for many months.''
aids cripples the body's ability to fight off disease, allowing a variety of ailments _ including heart disease _ to cause death
fourteen of the 18 aids heart patients were dead within four months of diagnosis, but the other four _ all with infection-related heart disease _ lived for about two years, she said
another participant in the study, dr. jean-jacques monsuez of hopital st. louis in paris, said early, specific diagnosis of the ailments plaguing aids patients can help physicians prolong life. tuberculosis, for instance, is a frequent ailment in aids patients, and it can be treated
if we can treat each organ involved, it's a very important thing,'' monsuez said
kinney noted that there were only eight women among the 86 aids patients studied, but half of them were suffering from aids-related heart disease. while noting that the number of female patients was small, she said, ``females seem to be more susceptible to aids heart disease ... the women were represented disproportionately.''
