you can carry your skis on the mount washington cog railway, but you better not try to use them to ski down the famous _ and treacherous _ tuckerman ravine
we don't plan to let the people who ride the train ski down tuckerman ravine,'' said u.s. forest service spokesman ned therrien. ``we will take some action to prevent people from trespassing under federal regulations.''
the railway last year proposed running a spring ski train to the top of new england's highest peak for the tuckerman ski season, normally april and may. the forest service denied the necessary permits
railway vice president wayne presby said the railway hasn't advertised for skiers this year, but officials don't intend to try to keep them off the rails
as a public utility, i can't discriminate against hikers, sightseers or skiers,'' he said
the forest service said it feared letting skiers ride the train up the mountain would increase the number of inexperienced skiers trying to make the dangerous run down the ravine and its famed headwall
skiers who make the run have to hike nearly three miles to the top of the mountain with their skis strapped to their backs
the forest service says forcing skiers to hike up the mountain limits those who attempt the hairy descent to only the heartiest and most experienced
presby said the railway will begin operating this year on april 16
meantime, forest service officials met wednesday with albert risch, who carries skiers to the headwall via chartered helicopter, and urged him to stop the flights. the helicopter uses private land, so the agency cannot order it to stop
risch said he has not decided whether he'll bow to the agency's wishes
