an abandoned fishing boat stacked with 3,765 pounds of cocaine was seized within sight of miami's skyline in the second largest cocaine haul ever made by the u.s. coast guard, officials said
it was in bales spread out on the deck,'' said coast guard petty officer joe dye on wednesday
the seizure ranked second to a two-ton shipment found on a fishing boat off puerto rico last fall. the cocaine was in an unregistered, twin-engine, 26-foot open fishing boat. there were no belongings aboard
a passing boater called us and basically said, `hey, there's a boat out here and it's loaded,''' dye said
at first, authorities thought it was loaded with marijuana, which is normally found in bales of 50 to 100 pounds, dye said
originally they thought it was pot because it was packed in marlboro (cigarette) cartons,'' dye said. ``they packed the cartons with the kilos (of cocaine) and put the cartons into cases, which were also marked `marlboro.'''
the wholesale value of the cocaine was estimated at about $26 million and its value on the streets could be as high as $169 million, said a spokesman for the drug enforcement administration task force in miami. talks fail</head>
pakistan said today it is ready to sign a settlement to end the afghanistan conflict and expects progress soon on deciding when outside military aid to the soviet-backed government and guerrillas will end
soviet foreign minister eduard a. shevardnadze said in an interview released today it was possible the afghanistan peace talks would fail, but he said that would not necessarily stop the soviets from withdrawing their troops
the new york times said wednesday that u.s. officials received indications the soviet union will consider allowing american aid to the rebels to continue after the 115,000 red army troops begin leaving afghanistan
u.s. and pakistani officials have said the issue of continued aid to the afghan government and the rebels fighting it is the last obstacle in the way of an accord to end the war
zain noorani, pakistan's acting foreign minister, said his country will sign ``any time during the day or after the easter break, when the other three parties are ready to sign.''
noorani spoke after his side and an afghan government delegation resumed the u.n.-mediated talks. pakistan represents the rebels, and the other parties are the soviet union and the united states
from our point of view, all the ... instruments (of the peace package) are complete,'' he said. ``we are hopeful that in the next few days there ought to be some kind of progress'' on the aid issue, he added
washington has said it will not guarantee a settlement unless the soviet union agrees to stop funding the kabul government at the same time the united states stops aid to the rebels
shevardnadze's interview with the bulgarian newspaper rabotnichesko delo was carried by the soviet news agency tass. shevardnadze was in bulgaria earlier this week for a warsaw pact meeting
not everything depends solely on us and the afghan government,'' shevardnadze said, referring to the outcome of the talks. ``this is why one cannot but take into account the possibility that the talks may not lead to the accords expected of them.''
shevardnadze said that if the geneva talks fail, the soviet union will withdraw its soldiers ``in a way convenient for the government of afghanistan and ourselves.'' he gave no indication whether the soviet union would stick to the nine-month timetable for withdrawal already agreed to in geneva
he said an agreement could be implemented without u.s. participation if pakistan was willing to sign a document spelling out the details of the soviet withdrawal
it would certainly be better if it (the united states) becomes a guarantor. but it is quite possible, in our opinion, to conclude the geneva process without the u.s. guarantees,'' he said
zoorani rejected this, saying everything would have to be renegotiated if one of the superpowers refuses its guarantor role
