a high-tech human-powered aircraft made a successful series of test flights today in preparation for a world-record distance attempt that also will recreate the ancient daedalus myth
but organizers of the daedalus project called off plans for a record bid on friday because southerly gales were expected with winds gusting up to 30 mph
flight director steve k. bussulari told reporters that the 68-pound ultralight daedalus 88 ``is in good shape ... and we may see favorable conditions'' for a flight on saturday or sunday
the aircraft completed six flights lasting less than three minutes each in calm dawn weather above a greek air force base adjoining iraklion airport
five athlete pilots took turns to pedal the shimmering pink-and-silver plane at speeds of around 14 mph, flying about 15 feet above the tarmac
the three-year massachusetts institute of technology project aims at breaking the world record for human-powered flight over the 74-mile distance from crete to the island of santorini, also known as thira
the flight also will update the myth of daedalus. according to the 3,500-year-old myth, the inventor and his son, icarus, tried to escape from crete on wings made of feathers and wax. daedalus succeeded, but icarus flew too close to the sun, the wax melted and he fell into the sea
after nine days of blustery weather, conditions today appeared near-perfect for the santorini flight, which requires temperatures below 70 degrees fahrenheit and almost dead calm, a rare occurrence on this wind-swept southern island
it feels like a day for the record, pretty calm. i was flying the plane with no hands,'' said frank scioscia, 27, a professional cyclist from scranton, pa
bussulari, an mit aerospace expert who will make the decision to fly, said the record probably could have been set today, although the plane would have met strong headwinds about five miles off santorini
but we felt we needed a test flight to shake down the aeroplane,'' he said
the pilots _ four americans and one greek _ are taking turns to stand by for 48 hours in readiness for the flight. the pilot who had been scheduled to fly friday is greg zack, 26, of wilmington, n.c., whose father was born in greece
the pilot pumps bicycle pedals that turn the contraption's propeller, and steers the plane with a joystick, coordinating with ground-based radio instructions
for the record the pilot must keep pedaling a steady 15 mph but the effort is equivalent to riding 23 miles an hour on land,'' said glenn tremml, a medical student from new haven, conn
tremml set the 37.2-mile world record for human-powered flight in california in 1987, flying a daedalus prototype
after an unassisted takeoff, the pilot will skirt the offshore island of dia and head due north hoping to land on a sandy beach on santorini
two greek navy patrol boats and a flotilla of inflatable crafts will escort the plane across the aegean sea, ready to pick up the pilot if he crashes and salvage the aircraft, although it probably would be unuseable
two backup flying machines are ready for assembly here if needed
like daedalus 88, they are constructed of lightweight composite material _ graphite epoxy, plastic fiber and mylar, an extra-thin plastic skin that covers the jetliner-sized 112-foot wingspan
the $1 million daedalus project, with its 36-member team, has produced new information on endurance and low altitude flying aerodynamics and meteorology during its three years of development, its organizers said
the project does have a research and educational application, particularly in human physiology and aeronautics,'' said john s. langford, the project director. ``the plane itself doesn't have any practical application. it should be seen as a work of art.''
here are the latest statistics on acquired immune deficiency syndrome in the united states, as reported this week by the national centers for disease control:
total cases reported since june 1981: 57,575
cases, year to date: 7,183
total deaths: 32,190, or 56 percent of all cases
homosexual or bisexual males: 36,234, or 63 percent
intravenous drug abusers: 10,192, or 18 percent
homosexual male and drug abusers: 4,226, or 7 percent
heterosexual cases: 2,285, or 4 percent
transfusion or blood cases: 1,500, or 3 percent
hemophilia patients: 621, or 1 percent
undetermined transmission cause: 1,815, or 3 percent
childhood cases (under age 13): 913, or 2 percent
cases among whites: 34,218, or 59 percent
cases among blacks: 14,755, or 26 percent
cases among hispanics: 8,082, or 14 percent
cases among other: 520, or 1 percent
these statistics are through march 28 and have been rounded by the cdc to the nearest whole percent. cumulative totals are for aids cases reported since june 1981, and include 75 cases subsequently found to have occurred prior to that date. the ``other'' classsification under age and race includes asians, american indians and native alaskans
march roared out of colorado like a lion today, pounding some areas with nearly two feet of snow and making travel treacherous on snowy and ice-packed roads throughout the state
the storm caused numerous minor accidents during the morning rush hour, giving motorists a longer-than-usual commute and creating visibilities of near zero at times
the roads will continue to be pretty nasty,'' said national weather service forecaster mike holzinger. ``i guess we would say this is a worse-than-average storm. but we do get this kind of weather in the spring.''
at stapleton international airport at denver, crowded with travelers for the easter weekend, public affairs officer norm avery warned that delays of two hours or more could be expected
the snow and gusting winds were expected to continue through tonight, with as much as 20 inches of snow possible in denver's western suburbs, holzinger said. the weather service was calling for total accumulations of up to 30 inches in the foothills
snow emergencies were declared for douglas, arapahoe and adams counties and for the city fo fort collins, where more than a foot of snow had fallen, but the colorado state patrol said there were no reports of serious accidents
stapleton officials said only the two main north-south runways were being used early today because of winds out of the north. snowfall by 8 a.m. measured 8 inches at the airport, the weather service said
stapleton has about 650 departures and about an equal number of arrivals daily, avery noted. ``i would anticipate we'll see some cancellations today and greatly impaired traffic operations because of visibility,'' he said
our biggest problem is we can't plow visibility. the snow is not the problem. it's the lack of visibility it creates that is the problem,'' he said
a leaky fuel pipe spilling oil onto a hot engine is believed to have triggered a fire that crippled the cruise ship scandinavian star earlier this month near cancun, mexico
the leak occured in an inch-thick pipe that carries oil to the main engine on the starboard side, said lou colucciello of the national transporation safety board. the pipe apparently leaked near the engine and the oil ignited when it spilled on the hot surface, he said
the fire march 16 on the st. petersburg-based ship stranded 447 passengers on the return leg of a mexican cruise about 35 miles off the yucatan peninsula
the passengers were flown back to tampa
a four-member team from the ntsb marine accident division spent last week inspecting the ship in miami and returned to washington to conduct more tests and analyze findings, colucciello said
he said investigators have found no other possible cause; however, the findings won't be conclusive until they test a piece of pipe and some of the ship's fuel at a laboratory
tamil militants attacked and set fire to two moslem fishing villages in eastern sri lanka today, and at least 17 people were killed, indian and sri lankan sources said
the sources said the attackers burned a mosque and more than 80 mud-and-straw houses in villages near kalmunai, 137 miles northeast of colombo, the capital. the sources spoke on condition of anonymity
some reports said the death toll was higher. there also was confusion over how many of the dead were tamils and how many were moslems because a battle apparently broke out after the initial attack
moslems make up 7 percent of sri lanka's 16 million people. they have been caught up only rarely in the tamil rebels' nearly five-year war against the dominant sinhalese for a separate tamil nation
but the moslems make up about one-third of the population in eastern sri lanka, which the rebels want as part of their homeland, and they recently have come under attack
under an indian-sponsored peace accord, a vote is be held in the island's north and east for a temporary council to rule the two areas as one province
both sinhalese and moslem leaders charge that the tamils are trying to drive out members of the other two communities to gain political advantage
an indian diplomat in colombo said indian peacekeeping troops investigating the attack found 17 bodies in the villages of sainthamaruthu and malaiyandu
the diplomat, who spoke on condition her name not be used, said six people also were injured. ``indian troops have now moved a battalion to the stricken villages,'' she said
india mantains about 40,000 soldiers in sri lanka under a peace accord signed last july
a police official in kalmunai, who also spoke anonymously, said 86 houses, all belonging to moslem fisherman, were burned to the ground. many people fled into the nearby jungle, he said
mohamad ashroof, general secretary of the sri lankan moslem congress, said in colombo that he had firm reports the death toll was 20 moslems, including six who perished after taking refuge in the mosque
but sources in the coastal city of batticaloa, north of kalmunai, said survivors' accounts indicated 17 died, including seven tamils killed when moslem villagers tried to repulse the attack
the largest rebel militia, the liberation tigers, have been operating in eastern sri lanka since being driven out of their stronghold in the north by indian troops
they have resisted the peace accord, which calls on the rebels to give up their fight in exchange for more autonomy for tamils
tamils, mostly hindus, make up 18 percent of the population. they claim they are discriminated against by the buddhist sinhalese, who form 75 percent and dominate the government and military
within the last month, nearly 150 civilians have been killed in sri lanka's eastern province in attacks blamed on the tamil rebels
within the past week more than 30 moslem-owned homes and businesses have been looted or set afire in kalmunai. two weeks ago seven moslem businessmen in the area were kidnapped and are still missing
twenty polish gypsies who were arrested at los angeles international airport while carrying jewelry-stuffed bags are part of an elusive nationwide burglary ring, authorities said
nineteen of the 20 men and women pleaded innocent in pasadena municipal court on monday and tuesday to charges of receiving stolen property. one suspect is still to be arraigned
sheriff's detective terry wiese, who has tracked members of the group since 1984, said they specialized in rifling senior citizens' houses from coast to coast, often while the victims were at home
group members are wanted in connection with a string of similar burglaries across the country and in canada, he said
we haven't even touched the tip of the iceberg, that's how big we believe this activity is across the united states,'' wiese said
los angeles police detective larry kagele, working with more than two dozen law enforcement agencies in the case, said the gypsies would drive through affluent neighborhoods looking for senior citizens standing outside their homes, watering their lawns or chatting with neighbors
while a man remained at the wheel of the car, a woman would ask the homeowner for directions or a drink of water. a second woman would sneak into the house and rummage through bedroom dressers and closets in search of jewelry, expensive heirlooms and silver, kagele said
if the woman was seen inside the house, she would make up a quick story that she's looking for a `joe' or `sandy' and must have the wrong address,'' kagele said. ``it wasn't all that sophisticated, but it worked.''
still wanted is the group's alleged gypsy ``queen,'' danuta reszuta, 31, authorities said
all 20 people arrested last week have been charged with one count of receiving stolen property and held in lieu of $500,000 bail each. police said the high bail was needed because alleged members of the group have fled before trial in the past
polish translators are assisting the gypsies because none of the 20 speak enough english to follow their court proceedings
immigration and naturalization service agents also are reviewing their files on the suspicion that several may be in the united states illegally
here is a rundown of the legal problems that have faced attorney general edwin meese iii in recent years
white house counsel fred f. fielding begins reviewing allegations that meese, then white house counselor, and michael deaver, at the time white house deputy chief of staff, received $118,000 in loans arranged by john r. mckean, a tax accountant later appointed to the postal service board of governors
an army inspector general finds that meese's promotion to colonel in the army reserve violated procedures, but said no evidence was found of use of ``undue influence.'' the investigative recommended against revoking meese's promotion. meese's promotion was approved by maj. gen. william r. berkman, whose reappointment as chief of the army reserve was confirmed by the senate on feb. 24, 1983, the same day meese's promotion was approved
attorney general william french smith asks for a special prosecutor to investigate allegations against meese, who had recently been nominated to be french's successor. the investigation was prompted by reports that meese failed to list on his financial disclosure form an interest-free $15,000 loan his wife received from edwin thomas. thomas, his wife and son were appointed to federal jobs. the investigation also would look into other transactions, including the loan from mckean
senate investigators begin looking into meese's failure to report reimbursements he received for more than 30 trips he took as white house counselor. one day later, former president ford suggests that meese should resign, although ford says he does not believe meese has broken any laws
special prosecutor jacob a. stein concludes there is no basis for prosecuting meese for ethical mistakes, and a three-judge panel accepts the counsel's report. stein had investigated 11 allegations concerning meese, including charges that meese played a role in awarding jobs to thomas and his family in exchange for a $15,000 interest-free loan
two office of government ethics staff concludes that meese, then attorney general-designate, violated conflict-of-interest rules, but is overruled by the agency director. the preliminary finding was changed after meese's lawyers submitted a rebuttal. the staff report found violations involving two individuals who helped meese financially and received high government jobs
after considerable debate, the senate votes to confirm meese and he is sworn in as attorney general on feb. 25, 1985
meese announces that the united states secretly sold weapons to iran and that profits of between $10 million and $30 million were diverted to the nicaraguan contra rebels. national security adviser john m. poindexter resigns and nsc aide lt. col. oliver l. north is fired
the justice department's office of professional responsibility investigates meese's decision to delay an fbi probe of an airline involved in iranian arms deals and weapons shipments to the contras. the justice department says poindexter asked meese in october to delay the inquiry of southern air transport, formerly owned by the cia. the fbi assists in investigating the 10-day delay
the justice department requests an independent counsel to investigate allegations that former white house aide lyn nofziger may have violated federal ethics laws by lobbying for the wedtech corp., a defense contractor, shortly after leaving public office in 1983. the decision requesting a counsel is made by a deputy to meese, who removed himself from considering the request because he knows nofziger
meese acknowledges that he intervened on behalf of wedtech to ensure that it got a fair hearing from the army in its effort to win the engine contract. meese also says his friend and former lawyer, e. robert wallach, sent him a series of memorandums in 1981 and 1982 discussing wedtech
the chairmen of the senate and house judiciary committees ask james mckay, the independent counsel, whether he can expand his criminal investigation to include meese's involvement with wedtech
meese asks the special prosecutor investigating nofziger's ties to wedtech to include him in the investigation. meese also announces that he has terminated his financial partnership with w. franklyn chinn. in february, chinn was forced to resign from the wedtech board because of allegedly questionable financial transactions
sources familiar with the grand jury investigation into the iran-contra affair tell the associated press that white house aides who complained that lt. col. oliver north may have been violating the law were told meese had approved north's actions
the sources also said meese and north held meetings on a regular basis before the iran-contra affair unraveled. the justice department says meese gave no legal clearance for north's activities
the office of government ethics says meese violated financial disclosure requirements after investing $60,000 with chinn. the agency's director said meese voluntarily invested the money in 1985 under an arrangement that fails to qualify as a blind trust under the 1978 ethics in government act
the general accounting office charges that meese failed to properly disclose the assets held, purchased and sold by a business partnership formed by meese and his wife. meese responded that any mistakes were inadvertant
investigators looking into meese's activities as white house counselor widened their probe to include his actions in connection with a friend's efforts to secure government backing for a pipeline project, sources report
the independent counsel investigation of meese was extended to include charges that he may have had a conflict of interest when he met with the heads of regional telephone companies to discuss legal restrictions on their firms at a time he and his wife still owned telephone stock
a memo to meese from wallach cited a plan to bribe a top israeli official to keep israel from interfering with the $1 billion iraqi oil pipeline project, sources familiar with a criminal investigation of meese said
meese said he didn't recall reading the portion of the memo from wallach on the iraqi pipeline project that refers to the payoff plan
wallach's sept. 25, 1985 memo to meese, in which the pipeline payment plan is outlined, was publicly released. it stated that a portion of the money paid to israel would go directly to the israeli labor party but that the diversion ``would be denied everywhere.''
meese and the late cia director william casey supported a plan to make secret payments out of the pentagon budget to gain israel's support of the pipeline, the washington post reported. meese's lawyers denied he knew of the pentagon payment proposal
a majority report from a senate subcommittee said meese's investment manager, chinn, allocated stock-trading profits to meese's brokerage accounts under a procedure that sen. carl levin, d-mich., said raises questions of ``possible financial favors or gifts'' to the cabinet member
mckay widens the probe by subpoenaing payroll records and other documents of the washington chapter of the multiple sclerosis society in connection with a $40,000-a-year job meese's wife, ursula, got with the charity in 1985, sources disclose. investigators are examining wallach's role in helping mrs. meese get the job
deputy attorney general arnold burns, the no. 2 official in the department, and assistant attorney general william weld, who oversaw all federal criminal investigations, quit along with four of their aides, telling associates that meese's legal problems hampered the operation of the department
a 9-year-old boy was in a coma thursday after he tried to hang himself, apparently after he saw a tv news report of a mass suicide
thaveesak rojanapitakcheep was sent to bangkok's phetchavej hospital tuesday after he was found suspended from a nylon rope, which was attached to a hook used to hold a punching bag, doctors said
dr. suchon suriyayothin quoted the boy's father, chaisit rojanapitakcheep, as saying that his son often talked about the highly publicized suicides earlier this month
in that incident, six members of a family hanged themselves at their home in nonthaburi province near bangkok in what police described as a fit of religious fanaticism
prime minister brian mulroney shuffled his cabinet today with major changes in the controversial trade and immigration portfolios. mulroney faces a re-election campaign later in the year
international trade minister pat carney, noted for her combative style, was replaced by former transport minister john crosbie, who will take over responsibility for implementing the free-trade agreement negotiated last year with the united states
the agreement dismantles tariffs and other trade barriers over the next decade. it faces a ratification battle in parliament later this year and stubborn opposition from at least two of canada's 10 provinces
carney takes over as president of the treasury board, a post formerly held by deputy prime minister don mazankowski
changing more than a quarter of his 38-member cabinet, mulroney replaced both immigration minister benoit bouchard and his deputy, gerry weiner, following two years in which canada has struggled to curb an influx of up to 2,000 illegal aliens a month
bouchard takes over as transport minister while weiner becomes minister of state for multiculturalism
barbara mcdougall, formerly in charge of women's affairs and privatization, becomes immigration minister
in a surprise move, mulroney reached outside parliament to name his old school friend lucien bouchard, recently canada's ambassador to france, his new secretary of state. he replaces david crombie, who resigned on wednesday to take up a new government job as head of a royal commission on the development of the lake ontario waterfront in toronto
the only other newcomer in the cabinet is vancouver-area member of parliament gerry st. germain, who becomes minister of state for transport, the equivalent of a deputy minister
mulroney's progressive conservative party was elected to a five-year term in september 1984. he is expected to call an early election this fall
the government has canceled a long-planned project to build a dam and hydroelectric power station in a river valley west of prague because it would cause ecological damage, it was reported thursday
ecologists said it was the first case when a major project has been canceled for ecology reasons in czechoslovakia, expressing the growing official and popular concern over increased pollution, the communist daily rude pravo reported
serious objections to the krivoklat dam, which was initiated in the 1960s, were raised by the ministry of culture and local officials, and that led to several postponements of the project
in 1977 the united nations educational and science organization declared that the area should be preserved
flooding in the berounka river valley would destroy fauna and flora surviving in the area since the ice age, as well as valuable forests which are to be used to revitalize the tens of thousands of acres of woods damaged by pollution in this country, ecologists say
the decision, however, was not expected to change official plans for czechoslovakia's most grandiose current project: the construction of a giant dam and hydroelectric plant on the danube where it crosses the hungarian border
hungarian and austrian environmentalists have said the project will alter water levels and damage forests and farmland across a wide area. but czechoslovakia's planners are still going ahead with a plant they say will provide enough power to reduce the burning of sulfur-laden brown coal by 3.8 million tons a year
brown coal and other materials used to fuel a rapid 1950s industrialization inspired by the soviets' stalinist efforts have inflicted great damage on the environment in czechoslovakia, a landlocked country whose natural assets are its forests and rivers
the damage grew unhindered throughout the 1970s, while the west woke up to ecological issues. now, a similar consciousness has arisen in czechoslovakia, causing popular alarm and forcing the government to finance projects designed to restore environmental standards to 1970 levels by the next millenium
communist party leader zhao ziyang is calling on the nation to eat less meat and more vegetables because farmers can't grow enough grain to feed livestock
zhao, speaking wednesday with delegates to the current session of the national people's congress, china's legislature, said china should learn from developed countries, where nutritionists are discouraging excess consumption of meat
zhao's comments, carried thursday by the official xinhua news agency, follow several articles in the official media warning that the rapid increase in meat consumption can't continue amid stagnating grain production
since 1983, consumption of meat, poultry, eggs and fish has risen 10 percent annually while agricultural production has gone up only 2 percent or 3 percent a year
last year, most large chinese cities for the first time in decades began rationing pork, china's favorite meat, because farmers strapped by rising feed costs and low government prices for pigs were not meeting the rising demand for pork
zhao backed up a statement by acting premier li peng, who in his report at the opening of the congress last week said that ``for a relatively long time, because of the restrictions imposed by the amount of grain held per capita, a major increase in supplies of meat, poultry, eggs and other animal food products will not be possible.''
zhao said the government should guide the eating habits of the nation just as it has held down population growth with its one child policy
since we've made world-acknowledged achievements in family planning, why can't we guide the people in their food pattern?'' he said
zhao suggested that higher prices for pork could be used to guide people to eat more chicken and rabbit than pork
china's grain production hit a record 407 million tons in 1984 but has failed to equal that since then. in the same period, grain consumption, largely because of increased demand for meat products, has increased by 15 million tons annually
the government must attain its optimistic goal of increasing grain production to 500 million tons by the year 2000 just to keep per-capita levels at the current 880 pounds because of population growth
last year, the average chinese ate a little more than 37 pounds of meat, including about 31 pounds of pork. the average american in 1984 consumed 143{ pounds of meat. further details on arrests. will be led after meese news conference scheduled to start at 12:30 p.m. est.</note>
the fbi cracked a major heroin-importing ring involving trafficking through sicily with the arrest today of more than 200 organized crime figures, justice department sources said
the arrests are the result of a lengthy criminal investigation in cooperation with italian authorities, said the sources, speaking on condition of anonymity
the government obtained warrants for the arrest of 45 people in new york city, 11 in the nation's capital and 160 in italy, according to one source
arrests were also expected in other cities, possibly including houston, charlotte, n.c., and los angeles as well as in florida, the source said
the operation began in washington in the fall of 1986 when an undercover agent began purchasing drugs from a waiter at a local restaurant, according to the source
large quantities of cocaine and heroin were purchased in washington between october 1986 and last fall, the source said
attorney general edwin meese iii and fbi officials were scheduled to disclose details of the case at a news conference later today at fbi headquarters in washington
a woman with a baby strapped to her back was seriously injured when a policeman opened fire on a crowd fighting for cooking oil and sugar at a state-owned store, police said thursday
officer constantino nzala said the 24-year-old woman's infant was unharmed in wednesday's shooting in the northern town of ndola
food shortages are common in zambia, and police are routinely deployed to keep order when stores receive deliveries. up 4th graf pvs bgng ``jackson was...</note>
president reagan may start campaigning for george bush early this summer, the white house said today, giving his vice president an early start on the fall campaign. democratic presidential contender albert gore jr. criticized jesse jackson anew and asked why the other democrats are reluctant to do the same
the republican party began to close ranks behind the certain nomination of bush in marked contrast to the disarray in the democratic party. one sure sign of the inevitability of bush's nomination is reagan edging closer to dropping his transparent veil of neutrality
we could see the president involved in some political activities before the nominating convention'' in august in new orleans, presidential spokesman marlin fitzwater said
fitzwater said a decision ``has not been finally made, although everyone is aware ... that the reality of the situation is such that the vice president is very close to having the nomination.''
the democrats campaigned mainly in wisconsin, with a primary on tuesday, and gore and michael dukakis argued about jackson's qualifications to be president
jackson was stung by gore's contention that, among other things, he lacks the experience necessary to be president. campaigning wednesday night in wisconsin, he told a crowd at a church in the working-class city of cudahy: ``some leaders don't hold office. but leaders stand with the people in the hour of hardship and challenge.''
earlier, jackson complained to reporters at washington's national airport that gore's remarks constituted an attack ``more personal than principled.'' gore, passing through the same airport a short while later, took issue with that, and criticized jackson anew
i think it's ridiculous,'' the tennessee senator said. ``he's a major contender for the white house. is he to be immune from any questioning of his position on the issues or his approach to the campaign? ... is there a separate standard?''
gore and jackson had planned to meet wednesday, but it fell through. in light of gore's comments a day earlier, jackson said, ``it's not necessary to meet at this time.''
on tuesday in new york, gore said jackson had a ``complete and total lack'' of qualifications for the nation's highest office and criticized his foreign policy views
gore ridiculed rival dukakis, saying the massachusetts governor's hesitancy to spell out differences with jackson was ``ludicrous.'' dukakis, campaigning in wisconsin wednesday night, replied: ``we can discuss issues without attacking each other...(voters) don't want to know what gore thinks of jackson.''
dukakis has been under pressure as a result of recent losses to jackson in illinois and michigan. but he managed to recoup with a solid 2-1 victory in tuesday's connecticut primary
with that victory, the massachusetts governor again took the lead in the national delegate race. according to the latest ap count, dukakis had 648.55, jackson 642.55, gore 367.8 and sen. paul simon 169.5, with 488.6 uncommitted
asked by reporters in boston on wednesday to detail the differences between himself and jackson, dukakis answered cautiously. he mentioned disagreements over middle east policy and some domestic economic matters, but provided no specifics, saying he would discuss the matter more fully in a wisconsin speech later this week
dukakis hinted that jackson's lack of any experience in elective office ought to be considered by voters. but he quickly moved to stress that any disagreements he had with jackson had always been ``friendly and respectful.''
that attitude got gore's dander up
is there supposed to be some unwritten rule why jesse jackson cannot be criticized, why his positions have to be just sacrosanct, and nobody can say anything about them for fear somebody will just misinterpret what you're saying?'' he said
sen. paul simon, campaigning in wisconsin, suggested that fear of alienating fervent jackson supporters was keeping other candidates from engaging in any real rough-and-tumble with him
you have to be careful. you don't want to be perceived as anti-black,'' the illinois senator said. jackson has been getting nearly unanimous black support in primary states, according to exit polls
a spokesman for bush said if the vice president faced jackson in the general election, he would have ``no reluctance'' to criticize him as warranted
if jackson is the nominee, we will feel very willing to attack him on the issues,'' bush spokesman pete teeley said. ``there will be no reticence, there will be no reluctance.''
the vice president virtually locked up the gop nomination when his principal rival, sen. bob dole, left the race tuesday. former television evangelist pat robertson is still formally in the running, but has acknowledged he's not likely to come from behind at this point
bush has 813 delegates, according to the latest ap count, to robertson's 17. to nominate, 1,139 delegates are needed
with little to do but stay out of trouble, bush sought to steer clear of meese and his problems
deputy attorney general arnold burns and assistant attorney general william f. weld quit tuesday. justice department sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the two left their jobs because they were concerned that meese's continuing legal difficulties were damaging the effectiveness and credibility of the department
meese, however, said wednesday he would not resign
bush said he was troubled by the resignations but added, ``i'm not going to pass judgment'' on whether meese should go
bush did say meese would not hold the top law enforcement post in a bush administration. ``it seems to me that the justice department has to be above reproach. it is an agency that has special responsibility,'' he said
republicans turned their attention to platform matters. the party opened platform hearings wednesday in washington, focusing on foreign policy. the next hearing is scheduled may 31 in kansas city, mo., and another is set in los angeles on june 30
u.s. officials point proudly to how many latin american countries have become democratic in recent years, but on the hemispheric issues of most concern to president reagan _ nicaragua and panama _ it's hard to find one willing to align itself with american policy
on tuesday, a day when the administration was issuing veiled warnings about the possibility of military intervention in panama, a regional conclave in caracas, venezuela, decided that the united states had already gone too far in its campaign against military strongman manuel antonio noriega
we urge the u.s. government to revoke immediately the coercive measures it has adopted against panama,'' the latin american economic system said in a communique after a two-day meeting. nations ranging from rightist chile to marxist cuba signed the declaration
the underlying message was clear: the 26 countries are worried that the united states is setting a precedent in panama that could be used against any one of them in the future
this consideration far outweighs the distaste that many have for noriega, named in two federal narcotics indictments. they believe they themselves might be an american target some day if they get caught smuggling drugs to the united states or run afoul of u.s. policy in some other way
over the past month, the administration has contributed to panama's economic collapse through measures that have had the effect of aggravating an acute cash shortage in panama
it has, for example, taken steps to deny noriega access to some $50 million in official panamanian funds deposited in u.s. banks and has withheld a $6.5 million payment due to panama for services related to panama canal operations
but many in congress, where opposition to noriega is virtually unanimous, believe the administration has not gone far enough. some advocate a comprehensive trade embargo
the administration has moved against noriega in the name of restoring democracy in panama, but none of the democracies which now dominate the hemisphere has seen fit to back the u.s. actions
the one source of comfort for the united states concerning panama is that the only nations that have provided overt support for noriega are cuba and nicaragua
another frustration for the administration has been the persistent refusal of latin american nations to support the nicaraguan contra rebels. some countries, such as mexico, have fought u.s. policy since the beginning while many others finessed the issue by refusing to take a stand
asked for an explanation, u.s. officials say many nations have expressed support for the contras in private but refuse to do so publicly
the reason, officials say, is that these countries fear a left-wing backlash at home if they side with the united states. to ensure domestic tranquility, disassociation from u.s. policy has been a time-honored tactic
all this generates considerable hand-wringing among administration officials. the united states was once routinely accused of backing unpopular dictators against the wishes of their subjects
but, particularly in the case of panama, the united states has not been able to count on latin american support even when it takes an assertive stand against a strongman like noriega
a generation ago, it was relatively easy for the united states to win diplomatic support in the hemisphere. with minimal opposition, washington orchestrated the diplomatic and economic isolation of cuba's revolutionary government and won latin american support, with some exceptions, for its armed intervention in the dominican republic in 1965
the sole recent instance in which the united states and latin america have been in harmony was in 1979, when there was a common effort to bring down the somoza family dynasty in nicaragua. the carter administration called on president anastasio somoza to step down and, within a month, he was gone
george gedda has covered foreign affairs for the associated press since 1968
prostitutes are masquerading as schoolgirls to lure clients wary of getting infected with aids, the head of uganda's task force on the disease said thursday
dr. samuel okware, the head of the national committee for prevention of acquired immune deficiency syndome, said his organization had started a nationwide program to warn people of the charade
men are ``diverting their attention to schoolgirls and ignoring bar maids and prostitutes'' because of their fear of catching the sexually transmitted disease, he said
prostitutes are donning school uniforms and carrying books during the late afternoon when students normally return home from school, okware said
he said in the last three months, the practice had become common among prostitutes in masaka, about 85 miles southwest of kampala, the capital
there are 2,300 confirmed cases of aids in uganda, said okware
the soap opera ``general hospital'' celebrates its 25th anniversary on friday showing no signs of ill health in the nielsen ratings, a recovery that began when it went on location and added such contemporary anti-heroes as luke and laura
the show, which began as a straightforward hospital drama on april 1, 1963, was almost dead in the ratings when gloria monty took over as executive producer in 1978, infusing the show with contemporary plots and characters. since 1979, it has been consistently no. 1 in daytime
in 1981, the wedding of shady characters luke and laura attracted an audience of nearly 17 million people _ in prime time, the equivalent might be a combination of a super bowl and the ``who shot j.r.?'' episode of ``dallas.''
the show was so popular, even elizabeth taylor did a guest shot. a popular song was inspired _ ``general hospi-tale.''
for the first quarter of 1988, ``general hospital'' tied with cbs' ``the young and the restless'' for first place in the daytime nielsens, with an average rating of 8.6 and 27 share. the rating is a percentage of 88.6 million u.s. households with televisions. the share is a percentage of the sets in use
john beradino, as dr. steve harvey, and emily mclaughlin, as nurse jessie brewer, have been with the show since it began. rachel ames, who joined the next year as audrey hardy, also still appears
under monty's guidance the show was expanded to an hour and took on action-oriented storylines that turned it into a pop phenomenon
general hospital'' was one of the first daytime dramas to go on location, shorten scenes to quicken the pacing and introduce more contemporary characters
wes kenney, who had produced cbs' ``the young and the restless'' and nbc's ``days of our lives,'' took over as executive producer when monty left a year ago
`general hospital' is an adventure-driven show that also depends heavily on its characters,'' said kenney. ``lots of shows rely on character and romance, but what gloria introduced was adventure and suspense, which no soap had ever done before. another thing gloria introduced was remotes (location shooting). last year we did more than 17. we got to nashville, niagara falls and mount rushmore. we blew up a whole mountain in pacific palisades. we had a snow storm at big bear
there's a tendency for all soaps to go on location, but i think `general hospital' has carried it out more successfully. we use the remotes to push the story ahead rather than just as an excuse to get out of the studio.''
since the departure of actors anthony geary and genie francis as luke spencer and laura baldwin, no one has heated up the airwaves the way they did. luke and laura were a departure from the good vs. evil staple of daytime drama. they became magazine-cover heroes, even though laura once killed off an old boyfriend, and when she was raped, the culprit turned out to be luke
among characters who now populate ``general hospital'' are:
_ the menage a trois of robert scorpio (tristan rogers), anna devane (finola hughes), and duke lavery (ian buchanan). scorpio and anna were once married and had a child, but scorpio later married holly (emma samms, before she went to ``dynasty''). anna and duke are now married, but there is a continuing competition for anna by the two men
_ bobbie spencer meyer (jackie zeman) and scott baldwin (kin shriner). troublemaker scott has just returned to the show and renewed his relationship with bobbie
_ lucy coe (lynn herring) and her husband tony jones (brad maule). lucy, who had been an in-house villain, has turned around with her marriage to surgeon tony jones. some people still don't like her, but her marriage gives her respect
_ felicia jones (kristina malandro) has not had a relationship since the departure of frisco (jack wagner) a year ago. frisco is supposedly away on a spy mission, but now that it appears wagner will not return, the writers will involve her in another relationship. her new story will center on her search for frisco
_ tom hardy (david wallace) has returned to the show and married simone ravelle (laura carrington) in the first interracial marriage on a soap opera
i think people like stories that continue so they can relate to these people,'' said kenney. ``they become like a family, and the viewer becomes emotionally involved. there seem to be two attitudes by viewers. one, that the stories are similar to what happened to them in real life, or two, thank goodness that isn't me.'' roberts cast demons out; inserts two grafs after 6th pvs, swaggart spokesman says only one telephone call involved</note>
television evangelist jimmy swaggart reportedly said preacher oral roberts freed him of ``demons with long fingernails'' digging into his body before swaggart decided to defy his church and return to the pulpit
swaggart, accused of motel trysts with a prostitute, intends to return to the pulpit may 22, three months after stepping down,bill treeby, his lawyer and a board member of jimmy swaggart world ministries, said wednesday
swaggart said several weeks ago that he has undergone extensive prayer and counseling with roberts, the rev. mike evans of euless, texas, swaggart's friend and a fellow tv evangelist, said in a television interview wednesday
and he said to me that oral roberts called him up and told him that he saw demons with long fingernails digging their flesh into jimmy swaggart's body and that he cast those demon spirits out of jimmy swaggart,'' evans said
evans told dallas television station wfaa he did not know whether roberts' counseling led to swaggart's plans to resume preaching may 22, but said that swaggart feels the process has freed him of his sin
i am proud to confirm that,'' oral roberts' son, richard, told the television station
gus weill, a spokesman for swaggart, said today that roberts had spoken to the evangelist only once
rev. oral roberts is one of hundreds and hundreds of ministers who have called rev. swaggart to pray with him and he deeply appreciates those calls,'' weill said. ``he spoke to rev. roberts about four weeks ago and that was the only time he called him.''
swaggart's return may 22 coincides with the end of a three-month suspension by the church's louisiana council. the national church's general presbytery on tuesday overruled that term as too lenient and barred him from the pulpit for at least a year and ordered him to undergo two years of rehabilitation and counseling
treeby said there was a conflict within the assemblies, the nation's largest pentecostal denomination, over whether the national presbytery or the louisiana council has the right to discipline ministers
he is willing to submit himself to the louisiana district,'' treeby told a televised news conference at swaggart's headquarters here. ``he will be considering an appeal to the national presbytery.''
however, juleen turnage, a spokeswoman for the national office of the assemblies in springfield, mo., said swaggart's option to return after three months ``does not exist anymore.''
the general presbytery overwhelmingly and without a dissenting vote affirmed the authority of the executive presbytery to make decisions on matters concerning ministerial credentials,'' she said wednesday
the 13-member executive presbytery acts as the church's board of directors, while the 232-member general presbytery is its oversight body
the rev. g. raymond carlson, the assemblies' general superintendent, said tuesday that if swaggart did not accept its ruling, ``the executive presbytery would no doubt take action to dismiss him.''
church officials originally said swaggart had 30 days to appeal the terms of his rehabilitation. however, mrs. turnage said wednesday church bylaws provide for an appeal only in cases of dismissal, not suspension
asked if a year away from the pulpit would ruin swaggart's lucrative ministry, treeby said, ``he is weighing all those considerations very carefully.''
the ministry has said it took in $150 million in 1986 from its worldwide operations, including sales. it contributes an estimated $12 million a year to the assemblies' foreign missions program
louisiana assemblies officials have close ties to swaggart's church, television and bible school enterprise. cecil janway, superintendent of the louisiana district, also sits on the board of jimmy swaggart world ministries
although the executive presbytery interrupted its regular bimonthly meeting to watch treeby's news conference, ``we don't consider that we've heard from jimmy swaggart, because we don't communicate through television news conferences with our disciplined ministers,'' mrs. turnage said
swaggart tearfully stepped down from the pulpit on feb. 21 after confessing an unspecified sin. church officials later said they had seen photographs of the evangelist with a prostitute in a motel room
according to the presbytery's terms of rehabilitation, swaggart must stop preaching and distributing videotaped sermons for at least one year, and undergo counseling and supervision by church elders for two years
swaggart is the latest evangelist to be forced from the pulpit. his accuser, marvin gorman, was forced from the assemblies of god when he admitted to an immoral act with a woman. jim and tammy bakker were forced from their ptl ministry in a scandal that included a sexual encounter between bakker and former church secretary jessica hahn
a house painter who was stabbed when he tried to help a woman he thought was being raped has received gifts of food and money and offers of a job
tom botsford, 27, has also gotten phone calls offering him encouragement and a check, accompanied by a short letter that said, ``you qualify to get to heaven.''
most importantly, botsford said, the admirers have rebuilt his morale
botsford was stabbed march 5 after he tried to break up a dispute between a man and woman outside his apartment building
botsford, who said he thought the woman was being raped, was stabbed by the man three times. authorities said there was not enough evidence to charge botsford's attacker
botsford has no insurance to cover his medical bills, and his pregnant wife, cecelia, is not working. he is not eligible for unemployment benefits
almost four weeks after he was stabbed in his shoulder and abdomen, botsford still groans with pain when he pushes himself up from the couch
but since his story appeared march 15 in the fort collins coloradoan, botsford's wounds _ and his pride _ have started to heal
admirers have sent $170, and one man offered him a sales job. another note said, ``give me a ring if you can't get a job.''
an anonymous writer said, ``i appreciate your efforts to help. i hope someone like you is around if one of my daughters are ever in trouble.''
two prosecutors involved in a high-speed chase have resigned in the wake of accusations that the driver was semi-nude and tried to intimidate officers who stopped her
assistant state attorney janine a. bamping, 32, was stopped march 20 and cited for allegedly fleeing and attempting to elude police in a chase through bradenton beach
her passenger, assistant state attorney jerome b. blevins, 27, wasn't charged
police said they didn't ask ms. bamping to get out of the car for a sobriety test because she was undressed from the waist down. belvins was fully clothed, officers said
when asked while she was only partially clothed, she became angry, flashed her state prosecutor's badge and used the name of a county judge suggesting retribution against them, the officers said
ms. bamping was suspended with pay last week while state attorney frank schaub was on vacation. schaub met with the assistants monday and accepted their resignations wednesday
both are competent prosecutors and their work will be missed,'' schaub said in a statement. he said he has asked the governor's office to assign an outside state attorney to review the charges, which ms. bamping apparently intends to fight
schaub heads a staff of 46 assistants in the 12th judicial circuit of three counties
the vietnamese government has informed the united states it will repatriate the remains of what it believes may be 27 american servicemen missing from the vietnam war, the pentagon said today
the remains will be delivered to u.s. military officials in hanoi on april 6 and transported to the army's central identification laboratory in honolulu for identification, the pentagon said in a statement
the u.s. government appreciates the initiative taken by vietnam to repatriate these remains and hopes it represents just one of many continued steps to resolve this long-standing humanitarian issue,'' the pentagon said
dan howard, the pentagon's chief spokesman, said the repatriation would be the largest single such transfer of remains since the end of the war. the largest previous tranfer occurred on aug. 14, 1985, when the vietnamese returned 26 remains
there are currently 2,404 americans still listed as missing in indochina as a result of the vietnam war, of whom 1,767 are listed as missing in either north or south vietnam. the remains of 152 americans have been repatriated to the united states and subsequently identified by the laboratory since the end of the war
on march 2, the vietnamese turned over 17 remains to u.s. officials. those remains have yet to be identified, however
the upcoming transfer would be the fourth since retired army gen. john vessey traveled to hanoi last august as a special presidential emissary, hoping to step up the process of accounting for missing americans
we've continued to press the vietnamese and we are getting some results,'' howard said today
asked if the pentagon could explain the sudden increase in repatriations, howard replied: ``it's really not for us to do that. the vietnamese are the ones who should be explaining to the american people and to the world what happened to the rest of the remains and where they are.''
lt. col. keith schneider, a pentagon spokesman, said the vietnamese government notified u.s. officials during technical meetings in mid-march that they were investigating 29 new reports of remains being found or information regarding servicemen uncovered
earlier this week, the vietnamese informed the united states it did have 27 remains to repatriate, schneider said
rumbling spring thunderstorms have announced the beginning of the unofficial tornado season that runs from april through june across texas and other tornado alley states in the nation's heartland
from 1951 through 1986, there have been an average of 118 tornadoes in texas per year, according to the state climatologist's office in college station
more than 60 percent of those occur between april and june, records show. in april and june an average of 18 to 19 tornadoes occur each month, but in may, when weather conditions are the most unstable, that average increases to about 36
a few twisters were already recorded in early march in texas but they did little or no damage. a tornado that touched down tuesday in central louisiana, near bunkie, destroyed two brick homes
people should have plans of what they'll do in tornadoes. if they wait until it gets there, it's going to be too late,'' said buddy mcintyre, a forecaster with the national weather service
last may 22, a killer storm flattened the small west texas town of saragosa, killing 30 people and injuring 162. in mid-november, 11 people died in east texas when a series of tornadoes trashed towns from cherokee county to the gulf coast
a tornado is such a devastating kind of storm. no matter how much preparation you do there is some property damage and some loss of life. but there are some things you can do to protect yourself and property,'' said laureen chernow, a spokeswoman for the governor's division of emergency management
one is to know the difference between the tornado watches and tornado warnings issued by the weather service
a watch means weather conditions are suitable for development of a tornado, and people should keep a careful lookout for potential funnel clouds
a tornado warning means one has already developed and has been spotted. take cover immediately and don't go outside, but if you are in a car or mobile home you will be safer taking cover in the nearest ditch or depression
at home, the best place to stay is a basement or underground storm shelter. if no such shelter is available, go inside a closet in the center of the house or bathroom or lie flat under a heavy table
mcintyre noted that most fatalities in a tornado are from flying debris, so ``we tell people to squat down, cover their heads and present a low profile.''
james r. mcdonald, director of the institute for disaster research at texas tech university, says many people mistakenly try to outrun tornadoes in their cars
during the 1979 wichita falls tornado that killed 53, mcdonald said, ``people jumped in their cars and drove down main street at 90 mph.'' twenty-six people died while trying to outrun the twister
another misconception is about opening windows. it was once believed that windows needed to be open to equalize air pressure between the storm and the inside of a house to prevent the house from exploding
mcintyre said there are enough natural openings in a house to equalize air pressure, and ``if that tornado wants to open your windows, it'll do that for you.'' pvs, the treaty, signed.</note>
the white house today hailed the advancement of a new arms treaty in the senate and said there is a good possibility it will be ratified by the time president reagan visits moscow for summit talks
democratic vote-counters said the senate will easily approve the u.s.-soviet treaty eliminating medium-range nuclear weapons, despite republican complaints over an amendment limiting future presidential interpretations of the agreement
sen. alan cranston, d-calif., no. 2 in the democratic leadership, said his counts show no more than five of the 100 senators are likely to vote against the pact. ratification requires approval of 67 senators
i think there will be hurdles, but i don't expect it to be turned down,'' said sen. claiborne pell, d-r.i., chairman of the foreign relations committee
both pell and cranston offered their assessments shortly after the foreign relations committee endorsed the pact wednesday on a 17-2 vote that included the support of 10 democrats and seven republicans. only sens. jesse helms, r-n.c., and larry pressler, r-s.d., voted against the treaty
at the white house, presidential spokesman marlin fitzwater said it was ``a very good action. ... we're hopeful for good, strong floor debate and passage as soon as possible
we certainly would like to have the treaty ratified before we go to moscow for the summit and it looks like that's a good possibility,'' fitzwater said. reagan will arrive in moscow on may 29 and remain there until june 2
the treaty, signed dec. 8 by president reagan and soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev, requires both sides to destroy all nuclear-armed missiles with a range of 300 miles to 3,400 miles
among the weapons that will destroyed are the soviet force of 650 ss-20s and other medium-range weapons aimed at western european targets. the united states will give up pershing ii missiles stationed in west germany and ground-launched cruise missiles stationed in five nato nations
the pact is the first in the history of arms control to require the actual destruction of the missiles that carry nuclear warheads. it is also the first to require on-site inspection to verify compliance
for the first time since hiroshima, you see the number of weapons going down,'' said pell
the treaty will probably come to the senate floor by late april and when it does, pell said, the most contentious issue will be the democratic-backed amendment
the amendment says that a future president cannot change the u.s. intepretation of the treaty without congressional approval
the fight stems from reagan's assertion that he can unilaterally change the interpretation of the 1972 anti-ballistic missile treaty, a view challenged by congressional democrats
sen. rudy boschwitz, r-minn., a supporter of the pact, called the amendment ``a great mistake'' and said, ``it very frankly may change my position in response to the treaty'' on the floor
pressler predicted the amendment ``will lead to the defeat of this treaty entirely because (with it), the votes aren't there.''
the foreign relations vote was the third overwhelming endorsement given the pact by a senate committee. the intelligence committee unanimously approved it and the armed services committee voted in favor by an 18-2 margin
the armed services committee did express some concerns, and maynard glitman, chief u.s. negotiator, tried to answer those fears wednesday in testimony before the foreign relations panel
glitman said ``futuristic'' weapons such as lasers and particle beam generators are banned by the treaty if they are carried on ``weapons delivery vehicles'' within the prohibited range
the soviets ``understand that all future (weapons) systems falling within the criteria will be banned,'' he told helms
and if an unarmed medium-range missile were to strike and destroy a target through impact alone, it would be considered a weapon if it had been designed for that purpose, he said
but sen. sam nunn, d-ga., armed services chairman, said he didn't think glitman's comments had settled the issue. nunn said he would seek a more definitive clarification during senate debate
nunn said he might seek an amendment to the treaty requiring the administration to obtain a specific statement from the soviets acknowledging that they had agreed not to produce, deploy or flight test futuristic medium-range weapons
new postal rates taking effect sunday complete a complex process that got under way 11 months ago
while most of the attention on the new 25-cent stamp has occurred in the last few weeks, the rate was actually proposed by the u.s. postal service in may 1987
since then, there has been so much discussion that some consumers may be confused about how many times rates have risen, said john griesemer, chairman of the board of governors of the postal service
when it was made an independent federal agency in the early 1970s, the u.s. postal service was directed to break even by raising rates to cover costs. the taxpayer subsidy that had been provided to the old post office was gradually eliminated
but to prevent sudden, sharp rate hikes, a separate postal rate commission was set up to monitor mailing costs
under the law, the postal service balances its funds over a term of years. when losses accumulate it raises rates. subsequently it may show a surplus for some years, until costs rise to push it back into the red and again result in another hike
the postal service lost $223 million in fiscal 1987, and the red ink was expected to increase this year despite cost-cutting efforts
the agency had a $305 million surplus in 1986, following sharp cost-cutting in the wake of 1985's loss of $251 million, agency managers reported
surpluses were reported in 1984, 1983 and 1982, following rate increases in 1981
after the postal service's board of governors proposed new rates last may, the case went to the postal rate commission, which is charged with listening to all interested persons and recommending whether the new rates should take effect
the commission has 10 months to reach a decision, which then goes back to the postal board of governors
the commission issued its ruling march 4, three days early. that decision on a rate hike, which was close to the original request, was then ordered into effect by the postal governors
americans are paying more to laugh less. but don't worry, the presidential election campaign should produce some cheap chuckles
the 1988 cost of laughing index, released to coincide with april fool's day and adjusted for inflation, showed a 5.8 percent increase in the humor scale over last year
the annual index, which measures 18 leading humor indicators, compares the punch line to the bottom line. it showed the wholesale price of rubber chickens increased $4.80 per dozen during the past 12 months
the trend in playful poultry is particularly worrisome,'' said malcolm kushner, a self-described humor consultant who compiled the index. ``over the past two years, rubber chickens prices have jumped 23 percent and dancing chicken telegrams have risen by 9 percent
funny fowl may soon become a memory for most american consumers.''
other increases included an 8 percent hike in comedy club ticket prices and an 11 percent jump in the newstand price of mad magazine. on the up side, the wholesale price of groucho glasses and arrow-through-the-head gags did not change
former attorney kushner, whose consulting operation is based in santa cruz, also gives seminars on how to use humor to communicate. his clients include ibm, lockheed and the notoriously funny irs
a man trying to return a neighbor's escaped pet wound up like an amateur facing pro wrestlers hulk hogan or andre the giant _ he was pinned on the first fall by a 700-pound wrestling bear
harry dodge, a retired cleveland heights animal warden, opened his door wednesday when he heard a noise on his porch and spotted his neighbor's trained and declawed black bear, smoky
he realized smoky apparently had broken out of his cage and took some apples to lure him back home
the 7-foot-tall bear just tripped him and sat on him
the bear thought it was a wrestling match,'' said lorain county deputy sheriff gary abicht
the bear performs under the stage name caesar at taverns or social events and wrestles with anyone who thinks they can beat him
when authorities tried to remove smoky from dodge's yard in this cleveland suburb, the bear wouldn't even budge for four lorain county deputies, three or four policemen from strongsville and two officers from olmsted falls. so they tied him to a tree with a rope until they located smoky's owner, salvatore mazzola
then, ``they gave him some peanut butter or something and lured him into a trailer'' used to transport him, abicht said
abicht said mazzola quarreled with a game warden at the scene and was charged with obstructing official business. he was freed on $1,500 bond
state game protector tom harrod said thursday he was preparing additional charges against mazzola for not having state licenses for smoky and a bear cub named magnum, or for a raccoon that lives in mazzola's house
harrod said he put the animals in the custody of another animal handler until mazzola gets the permits
dodge was treated at southwest general hospital for back and neck strain
a 1709 stradivarius violin named in honor of english concert musician marie hall was sold thursday for $889,240, the highest auction price ever paid for a musical instrument
the violin, acquired by miss hall in 1905, was bought by an unidentified south american dealer, sotheby's reported. the dealer beat out two other foreign rivals bidding by telephone in a tense, two-minute auction
the previous highest auction price for a violin by italian craftsman antonio stradivari was $728,000. ``the colossus,'' dated 1716, was bought last year by italian violinist luigi alberto bianchi
the guinness book of records says the highest known price for a stradivarius is $1.2 million, but that was in a private sale of stradivari's ``alard'' violin by british dealers w.e. hill and sons to a singapore dealer
bidding started thursday at $470,000, said sotheby's spokeswoman beth mchattie said
marie hall, considered one of the finest violinists of her era, died at age 72 in 1956. british composer vaughan williams dedicated his ``the lark ascending'' to her, and she first performed it on her stradivarius in 1920
miss hall bequeathed the violin, previously known as the ``viotti'' after giovanni battista viotti, to her daughter
the owner who sold it on thursday was not identified
the instrument was last auctioned in 1968, when it sold for $52,600 _ a record at the time
thursday's auction ``was quite drawn out and tense and there was a round of applause at the end,'' said ms. mchattie. ``we're absolutely delighted to be the record holders again.''
the violin, kept in very good condition, had been expected to fetch up to $846,000, she said. it has a distinctive tiger-stripe wood grain pattern and is varnished in a rich orange-brown color
about 700 of 1,116 violins by stradivari have survived
vice president george bush, his grip now firm on the republican presidential nomination, is shifting his focus to the fall election amid speculation that treasury secretary james a. baker iii will resign to oversee his campaign
reagan administration sources suggested that baker, a longtime bush ally, likely would not make such a move before the gop convention in new orleans aug. 15-18, despite the withdrawal this week of sen. bob dole
dole's exit from the race, virtually guaranteeing bush will be the gop candidate, heightened expectations that baker might speed up a decision to join the bush team
but a treasury department official, commenting only on condition of anonymity, said on thursday there was no truth to suggestions that baker might resign as early as august 1. the official would not elaborate
baker intends to participate in the seven-nation economic summit in toronto in late june, administration officials said
meanwhile, president reagan may begin campaigning for bush even before the party convention, spokesman marlin fitzwater said. the white house had previously said that reagan would remain neutral until the convention
fitzwater said that policy is being reconsidered ``in view of the way the campaign has developed, and in view of the vice president's now seemingly assured nomination.''
baker has longstanding ties to bush and managed his 1980 presidential bid. he also was chairman of president ford's 1976 camaign and senior adviser to the 1980 reagan-bush campaign
peter teeley, a bush campaign spokesman, said a discussion of what role baker might play in the bush campaign, if any, was only speculative at this time
however, teeley added, ``jim is very close to the vice president and has been for a quarter of a century. there's no secret what their relationship has been.''
baker could probably have any job in a bush presidency that he wanted, and there have been rumors for some time that he would like to be secretary of state rather than continue on as treasury secretary _ even though he has built an international reputation in his current post and appears to enjoy the job
bush on wednesday told reporters he intended to ``have a new cabinet'' if elected. the answer responded specifically to a query on embattled atty. gen. edwin meese iii but might also be taken as a signal that there would be a new treasury secretary in a bush presidency
baker became treasury secretary in 1985 after four years as reagan's chief of staff
bush was back in washington thursday after a three-day swing through wisconsin. he scaled back campaign stops in that state, which holds its primary election next tuesday, after dole's withdrawal
reagan had his regular weekly lunch with bush on thursday, but fitzwater said he did not know if campaign plans were discussed
the president's spokesman said a decision on any presidential campaign activity in bush's behalf before the convention ``has not been finally made, although ... the vice president is very close to having the nomination.''
pat robertson is still a candidate, in a declared sense, but he too recognizes the realities of the situation,'' fitzwater said
the vice president called his new status, without a major gop rival, ``exhilarating,'' and campaign aides made use of the time in washington to plot future strategy _ including ways to keep attention focused on bush now that the nomination appears sewn up
it does take us out of the spotlight,'' spokesman teeley acknowledged. ``but he is the vice president. he will be the nominee of the party. and he will be able to generate news.''
for now, bush is continuing with plans for campaign appearances in states that have upcoming primaries and that will also be important in the general election _ including new york, new jersey, ohio and pennsylvania
he is also planning fund-raising trips late next week to texas and florida, states where he has already won primaries
while running on the record of the eight-year reagan-bush administration, bush has also been seeking to develop and flesh out his own themes, including a heavy emphasis on educational issues
george bush's job now is to solidify the republican party. he can develop themes now for the republicans in november. that's something the democrats can't do,'' said rep. james sensenbrenner, r-wis., who traveled with the vice president in wisconsin this week
and, jokes bush, ``it's important for a vice president not to upstage his boss. and you don't know how hard it's been for me to keep my charisma in check for the past seven years.'' add details on child neglect charges and stevens' death; picks up 7th graf pvs, ``stevens' withered ... ''</note>
a woman who concealed her husband's death for eight years and tended the corpse as if it were alive pleaded guilty today to a felony forgery charge stemming from the death
but a former chicago-area dentist accused of assisting her in the forgery pleaded innocent and a jury trial was ordered
carole stevens, 42, entered her plea today in knox county circuit court before associate judge harry bulkeley
mrs. stevens was sentenced to two years probation and 12 days in the county jail, for which she received credit for 12 days already served. officials said mrs. stevens still faces a hearing on child neglect charges involving her two children, who are in foster care
besides probation, bulkeley ordered mrs. stevens to undergo a psychiatric examination and told her to have no further contact with her alleged partner in the deception, richard g. kunce, 56, a former aurora dentist
kunce, in a brief appearance today before judge stephen mathers, pleaded innocent and left the courtroom. he still awaits a court appearance on a felony charge of cruelty to children
in february, mrs. stevens and kunce both pleaded guilty in knox county court to misdemeanor charges of failing to report the may 1979 death of carl l. stevens, a diabetic who authorities say died shortly after he joined a holistic health cult and stopped taking his daily insulin shots
steven's withered corpse was found jan. 29 on a bed in the home, where officials said his widow had cared for the body daily over the past eight years, changing its clothes and moving it from room to room
following their guilty pleas on the misdemeanor charges, both mrs. stevens and kunce also faced felony forgery charges
mrs. stevens was accused of fabricating a power of attorney for her dead husband in 1984. kunce, who was a guest in the stevens house the past year, was charged with forgery for signing his name to the document as a witness
last week, kunce asked a judge to withdraw his guilty plea on the charge of failure to report stevens' death. the hearing on kunce's request was postponed until late april.   
in the year since peach bottom became the first nuclear plant shut down because workers slept on the job, shareholders have absorbed $72 million in replacement energy costs, its operator said thursday
philadelphia electric co. said in a blunt ``open letter'' to civic and governmental organizations in southeastern pennsylvania and northern maryland that the episode has been ``an embarassment'' and that the plant would not restart until the company is ``completely satisfied'' conditions had changed
on march 31, 1987, the nuclear regulatory commission ordered peach bottom closed indefinitely, citing a pattern of control room operators dozing on duty and saying continued operation posed ``an immediate threat to health and safety.''
to date, the shutdown has caused the company's shareholders to absorb approximately $72 million of higher replacement energy costs, while the pennsylvania public utility commission has ordered pe customers' rates to be reduced by $30.4 million per year until restart,'' pe said in the letter
there is no question that the public confidence has been shaken as the result of this shutdown and this is the type of communication with the public that will begin to rebuild that,'' pe spokesman neil mcdermott said
the letter was signed by pe president and chief operating officer joseph paquette, who took over three weeks ago, after james everett iii resigned in the face of mounting criticism over peach bottom's restart
paquette blamed problems at peach bottom in part on a lack of leadership by senior managers and a stagnant ``culture'' at the plant that was devoid of individual accountability and open communication
since the shutdown, pe has proposed reorganizing work crews, removed all supervisors who were at the plant one year ago, hired a former navy rear admiral as plant manager, instituted a new training program for operators, and fired four employees and suspended seven others for drug-related activities. most of the drug problems were said to be with maintenance workers
pe officials hope peach bottom, near the maryland border, will be restarted this fall. but officials must first apply to the nrc regional office, and the regional office would inform the nrc in washington when it was convinced the plant was ready
michael j. fox says he's pulled out of the fast lane to enjoy a quieter life with actress tracy pollan, us magazine reports in its april 18 issue
i definitely feel real settling going on _ almost on every level,'' said fox. ``in my personal life, i'm just calming down and really enjoying building a life outside work. ... and on the work level, i'm not freaking out about things.''
fox denied reports that he'll marry in may; but he and pollan have bought a vermont homestead together, us reported
the two became friends while playing a couple on television's ``family ties.''
i was goofing around at that point in my life. i was a little more prone to stay out late and drive fast and work hard,'' said fox. ``i hope i wasn't a jerk. but if i was, i have a sneaking suspicion not many people were going to tell me i was.''
one of the exceptions, he said, was pollan. ``we got along really well, but if i was a jerk, she just went, `that was a really particularly stupid thing to do.' and i just went, `wow! that's great!'''
after pollan left the show for other projects, the romance developed
the result, he said, ``is something i never, ever, in my wildest dreams thought would come to pass.''
michael jackson, whose ``bad'' album failed to win any grammys last month, was a big winner in the second annual soul train music awards
jackson was honored for 1987 male vocalist album of the year and the title song was named best single by a male vocalist wednesday
in the female vocalist category, whitney houston won best album for ``whitney,'' and natalie cole took the best single award for ``i live for your love.''
janet jackson, michael jackson's sister, won the best music video award for ``control.''
levert won best group jazz album for ``the big throwdown'' and best group single for ``cassanova.''
another double winner was ll cool j, whose ``i need love'' won best rap single, and ``bigger &amp; deffer'' was named best rap album
the night's biggest loser was jody watley, last month's best new artist grammy winner. she had tied michael jackson for most nominations with three, including best female single and album and best video, but came up empty-handed
eight hundred people turned out to honor musician les paul and his mother, evelyn polfuss, on her 100th birthday
at her home town celebration wednesday, mrs. polfuss received proclamations from gov. tommy thompson, the legislature and president reagan. paul was given a plaque for his induction into the wisconsin area music industry hall of fame. ``it is just one of the finest evenings we've had in this city,'' mayor paul vrakas said
comedian joan rivers has decided the show must go on, even if she has to pick up the tab
promoter doug east said wednesday he was canceling miss rivers' performances friday in myrtle beach and saturday in charleston because of poor ticket sales
but miss rivers, who says she only canceled performances for three months following the death of her husband last year, was adamant
i don't do that to people who have bought tickets,'' she said wednesday from her hollywood home. ``even if there's only one person in the audience, i'm going to do the show
i stand to lose about $50,000. i'm so (mad) i can't even discuss it. but, i just don't operate that way. maybe that's why i've been in the business 22 years.''
p0ntiac, mich. (ap) _ john z. de lorean is suing his tax attorney, saying he lost a $700,000 refund because the lawyer missed a filing deadline
the 63-year-old former auto executive said in a lawsuit filed wednesday in oakland county circuit court that he was entitled to $700,127 for overpayment of his 1982 federal income taxes, but tax attorney frank c. shaler missed the april 15, 1986, deadline
it's a friendly lawsuit,'' de lorean said by telephone from his home in bedminster, n.j. ``it was a slip-up on frank's part, and he reported it to his insurance company. it was something he just missed on the statute of limitations. he was the one who told me about it.''
he's still my accountant. he's a real sweet guy.''
shaler declined comment
de lorean, whose northern ireland-based sports car company collapsed in 1982, said he is preparing to get back into the auto business with plans to build a new, ``exotic'' sports car in west germany. in 1984, he was acquitted of federal charges of selling cocaine
guitarist chet atkins is $5 richer thanks to a fellow musician who borrowed the money 30 years ago and remembered it had not been repaid
atkins found the $5 in his mail slot wednesday from ed dettenheim of haynesville, la. in a note attached, dettenheim said he was repaying $5 that atkins had wired him in 1958 to bail him out of jail in humboldt, tenn., where he was being held on a traffic charge
at the time, dettenheim was playing guitar with the rhythm rebels band
atkins said thursday he doesn't remember the loan. but he added, ``i'm glad i was a good neighbor.''
costa rican president oscar arias sanchez will be the principal speaker at the harvard university commencement in june
the author of a central american peace plan, arias won the 1987 nobel peace prize for his ``outstanding contribution to the possible return of stability and peace to a region long torn by strife and civil war,'' the nobel committee said in awarding the honor
arias, 47, studied at boston university and attended harvard's summer school before continuing his education abroad. he spoke last year at harvard's john f. kennedy school of government
harvard announced the speaker thursday. the 337th commencement exercises will take place june 9
a woman running for congress says she's been barred from an annual stag dinner that has become a regular campaign event and which her opponent and several other candidates are likely to attend
this isn't just a woman trying to get tickets,'' marianne brewster said wednesday. ``this is a candidate for the house of representatives.''
brewster, a republican running in the 4th district race, said she won't try to gain admission to the forty &amp; eight lasociete's oyster dinner april 8 at mount view high school
i do plan to stand outside and shake hands and do it that way,'' said brewster, a bluefield businesswoman. ``i don't want to cause problems, but it's difficult to have to combat this.''
frank pisano, a member of forty &amp; eight, an offshoot of the american legion, said he expects up to 1,200 people to attend the dinner. dozens of local, state and national office seekers typically attend
u.s. rep. nick rahall, a democrat seeking re-election to the 4th district seat, previously has attended and he and several candidates for high state office plan to attend this year, pisano said
throughout its quarter-century history, the $15-a-head dinner has been off limits to women, he said
the policy that we've had is that it's a stag affair,'' pisano said. ``i don't have the authority to say we can open it up to these other people.''
former presidential aide lyn nofziger should be imprisoned because he showed a ``total lack of remorse'' when convicted of illegally lobbying the white house, independent counsel james c. mckay said today in court papers
mckay recommended that nofziger receive a prison term for three counts of violating the ethics in government act to ``impress present and former government employees, as well as the general public that congress intended those restrictions be taken seriously and that they will be enforced with meaningful penalties.''
the prosecutor noted that nofziger, 63, former white house political director, likened his crime to ``running a stop sign'' following his conviction feb. 11 on three counts of illegal lobbying his former agency within a year of leaving government
since being found guilty, defendant nofziger has made a number of remarks showing a total lack of remorse or contrition for his offenses,'' mckay said in a sentencing memo to u.s. district judge thomas flannery
that intransigent attitude is a consideration arguing in favor of a sentence that includes a period of incarceration,'' mckay said
as further evidence of nofziger's lack of contrition, mckay quoted a feb. 18 letter to the court in which nofziger wrote: ``i have never thought, and i do not think today, that i am guilty morally, ethically or legally of the crimes of which i am convicted.''
nofziger is scheduled to be sentenced april 8 and could receive two-year prison terms and a $10,000 fine for each of the three convictions of illegally lobbying on behalf of wedtech corp., a maritime engineers union and the manufacturer of the air force a-10 anti-tank plane
in addition to an unspecified prison term, mckay recommended ``that an appropriate fine be imposed for each violation and that the fines be imposed cumulatively for the three violations.''
nofziger's special entree to the most powerful officials in government, including the president himself, epitomized the very danger to public perception about the integrity of governmental decision-making that motivated congress to enact the one-year no-contact prohibition,'' mckay said
mckay also dismissed nofziger's argument that he misunderstood the ethics law, saying he had received a white house manual that instructed all members of president reagan's staff to review carefully the rules on post-employment lobbying
in addition, nofziger received extensive legal advice from a private law firm about the law, mckay said
the sentencing memo referred to an incident in which nofziger allegedly uttered a profanity when told by one of his lawyers not to make any white house contacts ``without first clearing it with his lawyers.''
during a bench conference out of hearing of jurors and the public, associate independent counsel merrick garland told the judge that after responding with a profanity, nofziger said ``these are my friends and i am going back to them if i want to'', according to the memo
mckay noted that ``defense counsel has attempted to minimize the significance of this episode by asserting that defendant nofziger's profanity in response to his lawyer's advice was characteristic of their client's jocularity.''
perhaps so,'' the sentencing memo continued. ``but his lawyers at the time took the incident seriously. they have told staff members of the independent counsel that this episode caused concern'' within the law firm
whatever his choice of words, however, it is evident that defendant nofziger was alerted to and deliberately chose to ignore written and oral advice that section 207(c) (of the law) applied to him,'' mckay said
during the trial, defense lawyers unsuccessfully sought to claim that nofziger had acted with the advice of his counsel when he lobbied the white house on behalf of at least one client. flannery refused to allow the defense to raise this argument, saying it was legally impermissible
president reagan may go on the road to campaign for george bush before the gop convention to give his vice president an edge going into the fall campaign, the white house said thursday
the move indicates that reagan is ending his official neutrality in the gop race before the party's convention, scheduled for aug. 15-18 in new orleans
i just want to signal you that that is changing,'' presidential spokesman marlin fitzwater told reporters
the president has always been ready,'' the spokesman said. ``he's ready at the drop of a hat to get out there on the road. he's ready to get into the campaign at any point.''
however, fitzwater said, ``the president has always wanted to get involved in the political process as soon as possible. it's simply that his position on neutrality required that that could not happen until after the convention.''
he said the president ``could decide to do some events earlier'' in the light of bush's string of primary and caucus victories, which have forced all other republican candidates except the badly lagging pat robertson from the field
i think that in view of the way the campaign has developed, and in view of the vice president's now seemingly assured nomination, that we would rethink that situation in view of those new realities, and that we could see the president involved in some political activities before the nominating convention _ activities that are directly associated with the nominee,'' he said
fitzwater said a decision ``has not been finally made, although every one is aware ... that the reality of the situation is such that the vice president is very close to having the nomination.''
pat robertson is still a candidate, in a declared sense, but, he, too recognizes the realities of the situation,'' he said
bush has more than 800 of the 1,139 needed to win the nomination, according to a count by the associated press. robertson has 17
bush was having his regular weekly lunch with the president thursday. fitzwater said he did not know what they planned to talk about
fitzwater said no decision had been made on an endorsement, and no events had been scheduled or were expected to be scheduled soon
i simply want to open the door to this new prospect,'' he said
reagan, who defeated bush for the gop presidential nomination in 1980, has often spoken of him in glowing terms, ranking him at or near the top among u.s. vice presidents
an alabama fugitive known as ``wolf boy'' faced federal charges today after a 16-year-old kidnap victim from illinois was found tied to a motel bed, fbi agents said
agent kevin rust said gary williams, 30, an escape artist who fled the county jail in decatur, ala., last october, was armed but offered no resistance when fbi agents surrounded the carro motel and arrested him wednesday night
agents had spotted the car of the kidnap victim at the carro, rust said
michelle yokum, 16, of casey, ill., was found wednesday morning tied to a bed in a motel in nearby corinth after employees heard her cries
yokum told authorities williams had left in her car. she said that she had been abducted at gunpoint tuesday night in illinois while making a delivery in her car from the restaurant where she worked. the teen-ager said she had not been harmed by williams
williams was scheduled for a hearing today on a federal escape charge in aberdeen, miss
williams reportedly has made 10 escapes in the last several years and became known as ``wolf boy'' while hiding out in caves in alabama's bankhead national forest. he was serving a jail term for grand larceny and had numerous property offenses on his record
authorities said williams apparently approached yokum's car, forced her at gunpoint to move over to the passenger's side, then started driving south
fbi agents said williams is a suspect in the abduction of a 24-year-old cedar key, fla., woman who escaped from her kidnappers in adell, ga., last week. rust said williams' brother, jerry williams, 20, was arrested in georgia in connection with that kidnapping. yokum said williams told her that he had abducted a woman in florida but she got away in georgia
the densely settled northeast has become the nation's least populated region, falling behind the west for the first time, the census bureau reported thursday
the bureau also projected that texas will surpass new york for second place behind california in population by 1995
and between now and the year 2000, half of all u.s. population growth will occur in just three states: california, texas and florida, the report said
the projections are based on assumptions about trends in births, deaths, immigration and movement within the country, bureau demographer signe wetrogen explained
the northeast has been declining in its share of the u.s. population, with less growth than other areas, wetrogen said in a telephone interview. ``it is the one region with the highest share of population in the older ages, and has low birth rates.''
population shifts to the south and west in recent years have drawn away many people in the prime ages of 18 to 24, ``so the (northeast) region is left with more older people, and it's left without anybody to have more kids,'' she said
the northeastern states, relatively smaller in land area than other parts of the country, remain the mosty densely packed, however. new jersey leads the nation with more than 1,000 people per square mile
between 1987 and 1988, the western region increased from 49.6 million people to 50.5 million, the report said. at the same time, the population of the northeast edged upward from 50.1 million to 50.3 million, to slip into last place
the 1988 estimates listed the south with 85.1 million people, followed by the midwest with 59.6 million
historical records show that, while it was the center of early american development, the northeast hasn't actually been the most populous region since 1820, when the south edged ahead. it remained second until 1880, falling to third behind both the midwest and south
by 1990, the projections call for the south to have 87.3 million people, followed by the midwest, 59.8 million; west, 52.3 million; and northeast, 50.6 million
by 2000, the counts are expected to be 96.9 million for the south, 59.6 million for the midwest, 59.4 million for the west and 51.8 million for the northeast
by 2010, the report added, the west could replace the midwest as the second-most-populous region
state population projections showed california remaining unchallenged as the largest state, growing from 28 million people today to 29.1 million in 1990 and 33.5 million in 2000
texas is expected to surpass new york for second rank by 1995. the empire state now leads texas 17.7 million to 17.2 million, but by 1995 texas is projected to have just over 19 million people, with new york at only 17.9 million
florida is expected to remain the fourth-largest state, although by the year 2010 it may be closing in on new york as well, the census bureau said
by the year 2000, illinois will have replaced pennsylvania in fifth place and georgia will move into 10th, displacing north carolina, the report said
the u.s. population was projected to grow from 243.3 million in 1987 to 267.7 million in 2000
in that period, california is expected to add 6 million residents, florida 3.5 million and texas 3.3 million. that means those states would have growth of 12.8 million people, 52 percent of the national increase of 24.4 million
pennsylvania, ohio, iowa, west virginia and the district of columbia were projected to lose population this decade
population losses in the 1990s were predicted for nine more states: indiana, illinois, michigan, wisconsin, north dakota, nebraska, kentucky, montana and wyoming. on the other hand, growth was predicted to resume in the district of columbia
during the 1990s, the maturing of the post-world war ii baby boom generation will be reflected in the growth of the 45-64 age group in all parts of the country. the number of people aged 24 to 44 is expected to drop in the northeast and midwest but grow elsewhere, the report said
the study said the south continues to have the largest percentage of blacks in its population, 16 percent. more than half of all black americans reside in the south, and that is expected to continue. activist</head>
a relative of india's revered pacifist revolutionary, mohandas gandhi, is working to erect memorials to him in 15 north american cities, but boston is having a little trouble finding a spot for its monument
the inspiration and money is coming from a foundation created by yoges gandhi, a grandnephew of the man who led india to independence in 1947 with non-violent protests
gandhi said wednesday he chose this city of monuments to revolutionary heroes as one of the 15 cities because he wants to remind people to be better to one another
the statue of gandhi will encourage people to follow the path of non-violence. we don't want to focus on the man, but what he has done,'' said gandhi
the founder and president of the 5-year-old gandhi foundation said he already has $250,000 for the project. he wants the statues erected by oct. 2 for a national celebration of the 119th anniversary of gandhi's birth
boston officials from mayor raymond flynn on down have welcomed the memorial
but finding a site for the statue or monument is a problem, because of the city's current state of construction upheaval, from its roads to its skyline
mary shannon is executive secretary of the boston art commission, the agency that decides what monuments look like and where they go. she said the five-member panel is leaning toward a bas relief that would include text to better convey gandhi's message
mrs. shannon said the site should be worked out within the next few weeks and the design selected by may
a statue of gandhi is not incongruous for boston, where revolutionary war generals are remembered as well as abolitionists and gandhi devotee martin luther king jr., said mrs. shannon
two years ago the foundation erected a statue of gandhi in new york city's union square
other cities on gandhi's list are atlanta, chicago, denver, honolulu, houston, los angeles, miami, philadelphia, san francisco, memphis, tenn., and, in canada, montreal, toronto and vancouver
a 77-year-old widower who lives in a tiny mobile home and depends on a bicycle for transportation has collected about $21,000 in interest from a long-ignored savings account
i didn't forget about it,'' henry kinslow said. ``that's why you put money in a bank _ to let it collect interest.''
kinslow closed his account at onebank in north little rock on wednesday, saying he didn't want to pedal 30 miles from conway to keep tabs on it
kinslow, a retired electrical engineer and former hobo, had been told by the state auditor's office that his $34,482.29 in savings was in danger of government seizure because of a lack of account activity
kinslow said the last bank statement he received showed a balance of about $13,500
that was in 1972. the statements stopped because he didn't give the bank his change of address
the state auditor's staff says $750,000 hasn't been claimed by nearly 2,500 people whose accounts or other scheduled transactions, like utility deposits, have been inactive for at least seven years
the office is conducting a drive, called the great arkansas treasure hunt, to notify owners of such accounts under a 1987 law which mandates that money from such accounts that is unclaimed by april 7, 1990, goes into state general revenues
kinslow's balance was the largest unclaimed amount, the auditor's office said
a news report about the notification drive caught the attention of a teller at kinslow's bank in conway. the teller notified the owner of the mobile home park where kinslow lives, and the park owner drove kinslow to the north little rock bank
i wanted my money. i worked for about 25 years to make it,'' kinslow said
what are his plans for the windfall?
put it in another bank,'' he said. dismmissal; pick up 5th graf pvs: ``i've been taking ...''; subs 11th graf pvs, ``the dismissal xxx to conform</note>
the state senate began working today on rules for its votes on two articles of impeachment to oust gov. evan mecham, and one lawmaker said he would try to reinstate a third charge that was dismissed
the senate, acting as judge and jury in the first-term republican's trial, met briefly and adjourned into separate party caucuses to discuss how the vote should be taken. it was expected to reconvene this afternoon
republican sen. john mawhinney, who voted against the motion wednesday to dismiss a charge that mecham concealed a $350,000 campaign loan, said some senators had second thoughts
mawhinney said his proposal would still allow the senate to vote next week on the first two charges, on which testimony already has been heard. the third charge would be heard if mecham was acquitted on the other two
wednesday's vote came as a surprise to many senators and set the stage for a vote as early as monday on two other charges against the governor, who also faces a may 17 recall election and an april 21 criminal trial
the motion to dismiss the third charge was approved on a 16-12 vote. however two gop senators who opposed the dismissal were ill wednesday but attended today's session. thus, lawmakers said they would have to change two other senators' minds to get the 16 votes to reconsider
one of the two who were absent wednesday, sen. greg lunn, said he believed it was a ``serious error'' to dismiss the third charge
meanwhile, lawmakers were considering whether to vote on each of the two impeachment articles as a whole or take separate votes on all 11 subsections of the two articles
i've been accepting the body blows for about 15 months now ... and the ribs are a little bit bruised,'' mecham, an auto dealer and perennial political outsider, told a group of gop supporters wednesday
but he said he still had plans for ``when i get back there'' in the governor's office
the vote to dismiss the third charge wednesday was a surprise to most involved, including the senator who made the motion, republican wayne stump
several of those who voted to dismiss said they wanted to avoid prejudicing mecham's upcoming criminal trial on felony charges that he concealed a $350,000 campaign loan. that would have been the subject of evidence on the third impeachment charge and stump said it would have put the governor in ``quasi-double jeopardy.''
the decision set the stage for a vote as early as monday on two other charges against the first-term republican, who also faces a may 17 recall election and an april 21 criminal trial
mecham remains accused of misusing $80,000 from the governor's protocol fund by loaning it to his auto dealership and of trying to thwart an investigation of an alleged death threat by a state official
those voting for the dismissal motion were an unusual coalition of all 11 senate democrats plus five republicans who have steadfastly supported the governor
lawmakers refused to predict whether there will be the two-thirds majority of the 30-member senate needed to convict on the remaining two charges.
democratic sen. peter rios disputed speculation that democrats voted for the dismissal motion because they think they have the votes to boot mecham
i think this needs to be brought to a conclusion,'' he said of the 5-week-old impeachment trial, ``and this is my view of one way to bring it to a conclusion.''
i've always been confident,'' mecham told reporters wednesday night. he refused to comment directly on the dismissal. defense attorney jerris leonard said he considered it a victory
if mecham is convicted, secretary of state rose mofford, who has been acting governor since mecham's feb. 5 impeachment by the house, would become governor
the senate was expected to receive jury instructions this afternoon. closing arguments are scheduled for monday morning, and a vote can be taken any time afterward
mecham has repeatedly insisted he is innocent of all wrongdoing and that he is the victim of persecution by the state gop establishment and the media
he has been surrounded by controversy since he took office in january 1987. the day after taking office, mecham canceled a martin luther king holiday for state workers on grounds it was illegally created by his predecessor, democratic gov. bruce babbitt
he also has made comments that angered blacks, homosexuals, women, jews and japanese
the governor said wednesday night that if he is returned to office he would be willing to declare that ``bygones can be bygones'' in his relations with the legislature. meeting</head>
benjamin netanyahu said thursday he resigned as u.n. ambassador to protest secretary of state george p. shultz's meeting with two arab-americans linked to the palestine liberation organization
netanyahu said the meeting saturday in washington endangered israel's security and ``raises a larger question of the value of american commitments to us when we have made huge concessions to obtain these guarantees.''
i could not speak freely (about this) as long as i was ambassador. so i had to make a choice,'' he told the associated press
the surprise resignation of the articulate, u.s.-educated netanyahu _ a rising star in prime minister yitzhak shamir's rightist likud bloc _ was the strongest signal yet of israeli displeasure over the shultz meeting
shultz, in remarks on israel radio, said it was unreasonable to suggest he could not meet american citizens
but netanyahu said shultz's talks with edward said and ibrahim abu lughod violated a 1975 u.s. pledge not to meet with plo members. the two are members of the palestine national council, the plo's parliament-in-exile. u.s. officials said their membership on the pnc doesn't make them plo officials
in addition, he said, the united states appeared to be clearing the way for plo participation in middle east peace talks and ``a plo state right in the heart of israel, threatening our very security, our very future.''
netanyahu, who had served as u.n. ambassador since 1984, said he was planning to resign in several weeks anyway to begin campaigning for a seat as a likud legislator in november's elections
i decided to resign early because of the critical developments,'' he said
likud activists hope the 39-year-old netanyahu will give an electoral boost to the entire party, which narrowly missed winning a majority in 1984 parliamentary elections
foreign minister shimon peres has suggested asher ben natan, a former ambassador to france and germany, as a possible replacement for netanyahu
netanyahu, considered a close friend of shultz, said he still had ``warm personal regard'' for the secretary of state but that his meeting with said and abu lughod had created ``a deep rift'' between the united states and israel
even friends can sometimes take steps which are unacceptable or dangerous,'' he said
he said the meeting heightened israeli concern about a u.s.-middle east peace plan, which calls for an international conference leading to direct peace talks between israel and its arab enemies
i will pound the pavement from city to city in order to explain to the public the dangers of an international conference,'' he said
shamir and fellow likud mambers have staunchly opposed an international forum, warning that israel would be outnumbered by its enemies and forced to make territorial concessions
the very clear possibility exists now that the plo will sit across the table from israel in this conference and will be the party we will be demanded to give land to,'' netanyahu said
shultz goes to israel on sunday in his second shuttle to campaign for the peace plan, and he is likely to hear plenty of complaints there about the meeting with said and abu lughod
shamir called the meeting ``a slap in the face'' and told party members ``it was possible to see on television how much they (said and abu lughod) hate israel,'' the daily yediot ahronot reported thursday
netanyahu, the son of a cornell university professor, has lived in the united states most of his life. he attended high school in philadelphia and studied business administration at the massachusetts institute of technology
netanyahu's brother, jonathan, became a national hero as the senior commander during israel's 1976 rescue of hostages in entebbe, uganda. he was the only israeli officer killed in the operation
pope john paul ii on thursday re-enacted jesus christ's last supper with his apostles by washing the feet of 12 priests in a solemn holy thursday ritual
some 3,000 worshipers gathered for the two-hour ceremony in the vast, marble-columned basilica of st. john lateran with its 16 rooftop figures of christ, the apostles and saints silhouetted against the early evening sky. the 17th century basilica, built on an ancient roman property, is the pope's church as bishop of rome
earlier thursday, the pontiff celebrated mass at st. peter's basilica in vatican city, leading catholic clergymen _ including 22 cardinals, 30 bishops and some 1,000 priests _ in renewing their vows of celibacy
during the evening ceremony, the 67-year-old pope, draped in white vestments, washed the feet of the dozen mostly elderly priests in a service symbolizing jesus' humility before he was crucified on good friday
wearing a protective apron, the pontiff poured water from a golden urn onto one foot of each priest, wiping it with a white cloth before bending down to kiss it
the priests, dressed in white, red and gold, were seated on a platform under the austere, gold-leaf nave of the basilica, which is said to contain the heads of st. peter and st. paul and where until a century ago popes were crowned
the service included hymns and chants by the sistine chapel choir, as well as a homily in italian by the pope on the theme of christian humility
the two rites thursday began four days of ceremonies that culminate on easter sunday, celebrating the passion, death and resurrection of christ
on friday, the pope is to carry a wooden cross in the traditional good friday ceremony starting from the torch-lit colosseum. he will celebrate the easter vigil on saturday night, and a sunday mass in st. peter's square
cher says she enjoyed making the movie ``moonstruck'' because it gave her a chance to be part of a big, traditional family
in real life, cher, 40, lives with a 23-year-old acting student and copes with the travails of motherhood. her 11-year-old son, elijah blue, is ``a little superficial,'' and her daughter, 18-year-old chastity, ``dresses like a bum,'' she complained in an interview with film comment magazine that was reprinted in the april issue of us
i'm not a cookie-baking mother,'' said cher, who is up for the academy award for best actress for her role in ``moonstruck.'' ``well, that's not true. i am a cookie-baking mother, but i'm not a traditional cookie-baking mother.''
her boyfriend, robert camilletti, on the other hand, makes bagels _ and cher said it infuriates her when people ``dismiss him as a bagel maker.''
do i feel insulted when they dismiss everything about him and boil it down to that, without a moment's thought to what kind of a human being he is? yes. i lived with him when he was a doorman, when he was a bartender. i don't really care what he is.''
the government thursday unveiled the long-awaited laws that release businesses from the shackles of state plans and promise factory managers and foreign joint ventures substantial autonomy in making decisions
the two proposed laws and a draft constitutional amendment legitimizing the private sector were submitted to the 2,970 delegates of the national people's congress, china's legislature
the delegates are expected to discuss the measures in small groups over the next week and approve them april 13, the last day of the congress' 20-day session
rather than break new ground, the proposed laws would formalize changes already under way in the economy and clear up confusion over the new practices. the proposed measure on joint ventures would provide a legal framework for foreigners doing business in china
lu dong, head of the state economic commission, said the proposed law on state-owned enterprises was essential to china's modernization
whether or not (state-owned) enterprises can have great vitality will have a great influence on the overall development of our national economy,'' he told the delegates, gathered in the huge great hall of the people
therefore ... we must separate government and industry and guarantee the autonomy of enterprise management,'' lu said
the government hopes autonomy will turn china's often debt-ridden, inefficient state stores and factories into lean, competitive production machines. they will be free to respond to changes in market demand and also will be free to go bankrupt if they make bad decisions
it is no coincidence that the government plans to implement a bankruptcy law later this year
more than 70 percent of china's 90,000 state-run enterprises already have signed contracts with the government giving their managers some degree of adminstrative autonomy. the new law is intended to erase lingering ambiguities over the roles of managers, local communist party officials, local government and unions
similarly, the proposed law on chinese-foreign joint ventures and the constitutional amendment allowing private enterprise serve to codify changes that have already been introduced
although the draft state enterprise law probably is the most widely discussed in chinese history, having been submitted to special seminars nationwide, thursday was the first time its actual wording was released to the general public
an enterpise shall, in accordance with law, make its own managerial decisions (and) take full responsibility for its own profits and losses,'' reads one of the 68 articles
enterprises also will be allowed to sell their products on their own after meeting state quotas, chose their own suppliers, set their prices and enter into contracts with foreign parties
senior leader deng xiaoping first suggested such a law in 1978, when he began his campaign to reduce central planning and revitalize the economy through monetary incentives. versions have been discussed by four previous legislative sessions, generating debate unprecedented in china's largely rubber-stamp congress
official media reports indicate the congress' standing law committee made revisions almost up to the last minute. one major criticism was that workers could be victimized by autocratic managers
late additions included several clauses that promise wide powers to workers, thus substantially eroding business managers' promised new autonomy
an enterprise shall ensure that its staff and workers enjoy the status of masters. ... (and) shall practice democratic management,'' the bill reads
it adds that workers' congresses must approve wage adjustments and bonus distribution plans, and have the right to supervise and call for the removal of top company officials
the draft law on joint ventures would help standardize the form of contractural joint ventures and promote their growth, zheng tuobin, foreign trade minister, told the congress
the bill states that the joint venture ``should not be interfered with'' in making managerial decisions, and allows either the chinese or foreign partner to chair the board
chinese companies already have formed more than 5,000 joint ventures with foreign companies, with a total foreign investment of about $3.38 billion
however, many foreign businesses have complained about the lack of a legal framework for their joint venture agreements
the proposed constitutional amendment declares the private sector to be ``a complement to the socialist public economy'' that is allowed to exist within legal limits. china currently has more than 18 million private-sector enterprises, most employing only one or two people
a companion amendment declares that rights to use land may be transferred. all land in china is considered owned by the whole people, but in the past year several cities have sold land-use rights for up to 50 years. legislature meets</head>
four legislative leaders on thursday said annual sessions were ``an experiment that didn't work'' and called for a return to sessions every other year
we have seen legislative expenses rise and we have seen good lawmakers make the hard choice not to run again because they cannot be in concord every year and at the same time make a living for themselves and their families,'' house speaker douglas scamman said at a news conference
scamman, house majority leader vincent palumbo, senate president william bartlett, and senate democratic leader robert preston support a proposed constitutional amendment that would put the change before voters in november
they (voters) should have the chance to judge the efficiency of annual sessions based on the experience of the last four years and to register their opinion with their vote,'' scamman said
on wednesday, the house constitutional and statuatory revision committee voted 12-4 to recommend legislation that would put the proposed constitutional amendment on the ballot. voters approved annual sessions in 1984
those supporting annual sessions, including house democratic leader mary chambers, say state business is too complicated for legislators to meet every other year
i haven't seen a piece of legislation (this year) that couldn't have waited until next year,'' bartlett said
two crosses made from lilies for separate easter flower shows were rearranged into pillars after the american civil liberties union objected that the displays promoted religion on public property
the crosses, part of the annual spring and easter flower show at the garfield park conservatory and the lincoln park conservatory, were altered wednesday, said nancy kaszak, general attorney for the chicago park district
ms. kaszak said she was contacted tuesday by an aclu attorney who contended the crosses were a display of religious symbols on public property
because of the protest, park workers converted the crosses at both conservatories into pillars of flowers, she said
jane whicher, staff counsel for the aclu in illinois, said the diplays were brought to her attention by a staff member who visited the lincoln park conservatory
my concern is that the cross put up by a public body on public property was a violation of the first amendment,'' whicher said. ``it shouldn't have been erected in the first place, but i commend the park district on removing it so quickly.'' 03-31 0719</first> metzenbaum comment.</note>
the fbi said today it had cracked a major heroin-importing ring involving trafficking through sicily and was arresting 233 people in the united states and italy
attorney general edwin meese iii told a news conference it was the largest international drug case ever developed by the federal government and said it has been a ``stunning success.''
the arrests were the result of a lengthy criminal investigation in cooperation with italian authorities, and involved the import of southwest asian heroin into the united states
the 69 defendants in the united states include 38 charged in new york city, six in los angeles and boston, 10 in charlotte, n.c., eight in san juan, puerto rico, two in cleveland and five in washington, d.c. in italy, authorities intend to charge 164 people, the fbi said
u.s. authorities seized six kilograms of heroin and four kilograms of cocaine during the course of the investigation. italian authorities seized 22 kilograms of heroin last month
meese said the purpose of the investigation has been to penetrate organized drug operations and not just to make random drug seizures
the tentacles of this network spread out across this country,'' he said
the attorney general declined to speculate on what impact the arrests will have on drug traffic in the united states
nobody knows for sure the quantity of heroin or any other drug coming into the united states,'' he said. but the fbi's strategy of penetration ``is going to the heart of drug trafficing networks rather than just cutting off the tentacles.''
during the news conference to announce the drug arrests, meese refused to answer reporters' questions on the resignation of two of his top aides amid increasing skepticism on capitol hill over whether he can continue to run the justice department
meese, who is the target of a broadening criminal investigation, turned aside at least half a dozen questions relating to the possibility that he might quit in the wake of tuesday's resignations of deputy attorney general arnold burns and assistant attorney general william weld
the business of law enforcement is going forward energetically and without interruption,'' meese said. ``our strong management team is on the job.''
sen. howard metzenbaum, d-ohio, who has called for meese's resignation, said, ``i think he has lost his credibility. it's a joke when he's talking about drug enforcement when everyone wants to know why he's still attorney general.''
frank story, chief of the narcotics section of the criminal investigations division of the fbi, said authorities also have seized business assets in connection with the arrests
suspects arrested today have been charged with conspiracies to import, possess and distribute drugs, the fbi said. authorities used physical and electronic surveillance during the investigation
authorities were alerted to the presence of a sicilian mafia drug network operating out of new york city and trafficking in heroin by a 1985 drug case involving a new york pizza restaurant, authorities said
a government affidavit filed in u.s. district court in manhattan said two of the defendants in the current case operate pizza restaurants in new york city and another is a former pizza restaurant owner there
two of the defendants in new york city and one of those charged in charlotte are fugitives from italian drug convictions, the fbi said
the sicilian mafia's drug trafficking plan involved exporting cocaine from the united states to italy, where it would be exchanged for heroin and then smuggled back to the united states, the fbi said
meese said the difference in the price of cocaine here and in italy made the scheme profitable for the network
meese and fbi director william sessions commended the cooperation of the italian government and law enforcement agencies in coordinating the investigation and arrests
sessions said italian law enforcement officials have made 68 arrests so far and are pursuing fugitives in italy, sicily, venezuela and several u.s. cities
the sicilian mafia that today's actions are directed against is one of the primary groups responsible for the importation of southwest asian heroin into the united states,'' he said
he said the three other primary groups bringing drugs into the united states are mexicans, colombians and asians. brother</head>
government prosecutors said thursday they would investigate allegations that former president chun doo-hwan's brother diverted millions of dollars in government money to real estate investments overseas
chun kyung-hwan was arrested early thursday on charges he embezzled $10.4 million while head of the semi-official saemaul undong (new community) development organization. he also was charged with taking bribes, influence peddling, evading taxes and violating business, land and construction laws
if convicted, chun, 46, could receive a sentence ranging from 10 years in prison to death
our investigation will continue to check other charges that he diverted a huge amount of money for land speculation in the united states and australia,'' senior prosecutor kang won-il told reporters
eight other people, including aides of the younger chun and other senior saemaul officials, also were arrested on embezzlement, bribery and other charges, officials said. they included the former president's two brothers-in-law
it is agonizing to me that i have caused trouble to my brother,'' prosecutors quoted the younger chun as saying
according to the arrest warrant, the younger chun amassed a fortune in cash, land and stocks by using government and family connections
he was named head of saemaul undong in 1981, the year after his brother seized power with military backing, and resigned the post in 1987 after reports linked him to criminals
meanwhile, opposition parties charged thursday that the government was covering up massive corruption in the scandal, and demanded the former president be questioned in the probe
the government has orchestrated another cover-up and fooled the people,'' the reunification democratic party said in a statement
the party, one of two main opposition groups, demanded chun be questioned about charges of widespread corruption during his seven-year rule, which ended feb. 24
authorities have questioned some 200 politicians and business leaders about corruption or trying to cover it up to protect former president chun and his family, but none has been formally implicated
kang said thursday he did not plan to expand the investigation to uncover other crimes under chun because most such cases were closed through trials
many observers here believe the probe of saemaul, which oversees rural and urban development projects, is part of efforts by president roh tae-woo to distance himself from his authoritarian predecessor
in his presidential campaign pledge in december, roh said he would investigate all irregularities under chun. the former president has not been implicated in the scandal
government officials said thursday that roh will register his assets with government agencies to show his determination to establish a clean government
the officials said roh has urged the ministry of government administration to carry out administrative reforms, including the property registration of high-ranking government officials
