officials here have hired an outside expert to generate noise in their courtrooms
court administrator eugene l. farkas said wednesday that some of the courtrooms in the county's new $15 million judicial complex are so well designed acoustically that jurors and spectators are privy to even whispered conferences between lawyers and the judge at the bench
in the circular courtrooms there is excellent paneling, recess lighting, acoustical tiles and the sound seems to ring the ceiling and come down upon you,'' farkas said
noise unlimited inc. of somerville is working on the problem. the firm is experimenting with a noise generator that utilizes the sound system in each courtroom to pump in low-level sounds that help mask conversations
men like to see women's legs. so what else is new?
what's new, according to a poll published thursday, seems to be that while 36 percent of men say they favor miniskirts on women, and 71 percent say they like skirts at the knee or above, follow-up interviews indicate men generally concede that women have to consider whether showing too much leg is a wise career choice
greg parker, of palm beach, fla., said he likes short skirts because they're ``attractive'' and ``sexy.'' but, the 25-year-old engineer said, ``if you're in a meeting and everyone's dressed conservatively, there's less distraction.''
in the new york times-cbs telephone poll of 1,654 adults, a quarter of the women questioned said they had worn a skirt above their knees in the past year, while 46 percent of the women said they prefer a length below the knee. the poll was conducted between march 19 and 22
the tepid response of women to the new short styles had already been made apparent at the cash registers to those in the fashion trade, prompting designers to show some longer skirts in their fall collections
snoopy pops up in the darndest places, but when the cartoon beagle was found cavorting with a grizzly bear and a laboring miner on the state shield, california officials thought some prankster had gone too far
the ``peanuts'' comic strip canine first surfaced in official circles on the february issue of the department of corrections newsletter. he appeared to have taken the place of the roman goddess minerva as she stood on guard, the sierra nevada range at her back, a cluster of grapes at her feet
frankly, we first thought it might be the inmates'' up to a prank, said corrections spokesman mike van winkle. ``if i still didn't know anything about it, i would think it was definitely a snoopy,'' he said
but, no. it was a simple case of bureaucratic thriftiness, according to curt soderlund, spokesman for the state department of general services. he said a thin line on a printing plate had worn out, creating the appearance of ``something canine.''
it cost $50 to fix, he said
house and senate negotiators agreed thursday to attach to their sweeping trade bill tough sanctions against toshiba corp. of japan and a subsidiary for selling submarine silencing equipment to the soviets
house members relented and agreed to the measure despite reagan administration warnings that a similar provision was too inflexible and could bring on a presidential veto
sen. jake garn, r-utah, urged lawmakers to ignore the warnings, declaring that he was embarrassed by the republican administration's reluctance to discipline toshiba
the state department has been kicked in the shins and instead of yelling `ouch,' they have chosen to surrender,'' garn said
the complex measure would ban u.s. government purchases of toshiba corp. goods for three years. it would ban all sales in the united states of products from its toshiba machine co. subsidiary. there would be no waivers, but exceptions could be made for national security
the measure calls for two- to five-year import bans to punish any companies that in the future might send militarily useful equipment to communist countries in defiance of cocom, an agreement among western nations that is designed to control the flow of such goods
retroactive sanctions contained in the measure also would apply to kongsberg vapenfabrikk of norway
like toshiba, that company allegedly was involved in the sale of computerized milling equipment that the administration says has been used to produce submarine propellors that are hard for detection equipment to hear
cabinet members warned lawmakers earlier this week that stringent sanctions against toshiba could mean a veto of the 1,000-page trade bill that lawmakers are drawing up in a house-senate conference committee
house members had been holding out for allowing the president to make the decision on whether sanctions should be mandatory. but after three hours of debate, they relented and accepted a somewhat softened proposal by garn
the full conference committee in theory could drop the provision or alter it, although that would be hard to arrange
there was considerable reluctance, but no outright dissent, as foreign affairs committee chairman dante fascell, d-fla., accepted the senate offer on behalf of the house
rep. stephen l. neal, d-n.c., repeatedly urged the panel to trust the judgments of the state and defense departments as well as the national security council that a toshiba ban would amount to a mistake
garn retorted: ``i was elected as u.s. senator to represent the state of utah in the u.s. senate, and not toshiba and not england and not the state department and not (defense secretary) frank carlucci.''
inflation and economic growth over the next four years will boost by one-third _ to almost $114 billion _ the gap between federal income taxes owed and voluntarily paid, the internal revenue service said thursday
however, irs commissioner lawrence b. gibbs cautioned congress against counting on that money as potential income to reduce the federal budget deficit. an undetermined portion of the ``tax gap'' represents taxes that would not be worth the effort to collect even if enforcement activities were stepped up
our estimates of the income-tax gap are measures of total non-compliance,'' gibbs told the senate budget committee. ``they are not intended to be measures of the potential for additional enforcement yields.''
using information collected in 1983, the irs estimates the tax gap at $84.9 billion for 1987. that is down from $95 billion in 1986. the agency projects an $87 billion gap next year and $113.7 billion in 1992
gibbs said the estimates for this year and the future are less than they would have been had not congress made significant changes in the tax law in 1986. those changes included cuts in tax rates, reduced itemized deductions and higher personal exemptions, which, the irs believes, will reduce incentives for cheating
that increase in voluntary compliance among individuals will be offset by inflation and growth of the economy, gibbs said
although the new estimates still indicate a sizable tax gap, the commissioner said, they are considerably below what the agency had forecast in 1983. the 1983 projection was for a gap of $115 billion for 1987
the irs said individuals accounted for $63.5 bilion of the 1987 gap and corporations were to blame for the remaining $21.4 billion. while the agency expects the voluntary compliance rate among individuals will increase slightly over the next few years, corporate compliance will decline, partly because the 1986 law shifted a significant part of the tax burden from individuals to corporations
individuals' underreporting of income was to blame for $48.3 billion of the tax gap in 1987; overstated deductions, $6 billion; overstated credits, $900 million; math errors, $1 billion; and the failure of many people to even file a required return, $7.2 billion
jerome kurtz, who headed the irs during the carter administration, cautioned against reading too much into the tax-gap figures, noting they are estimates based on small samples. he and donald c. alexander, who was irs commissioner during the nixon administration, agreed on a major point: the agency must be given enough money to provide a top level of service to taxpayers
recalling several years of what he said were underfunding of the irs, kurtz said, ``if you have to write a letter to the irs to straighten out an account, you're going to learn the meaning of frustration.'' in hiring and retaining employees, he said, ``the irs is not competitive with private industry.''
alexander added: ``how can someone whose salary is so low as to be eligible for food stamps be expected to answer all the complex questions thrown at taxpayer assistance (employees) during the current (return) filing period?''
the telephone ``assistors'' who field taxpayers' telephoned questions are paid as little as $13,000 a year _ considerable less than many garbage collectors, alexander said
jennie s. stathis, an associate director of the general accounting office, which oversees other federal agencies for congress, said the irs already is weighing several gao recommendations for reducing the tax gap
these include a capacity for matching business information documents against business returns just as computers already match individual wage and income statements against returns; stepping up efforts to improve the reporting of taxable tips; and trying to find a bigger share of illegal income to tax. official change in count.</note>
congress today gave final approval to $48 million in humanitarian aid for the contra rebels and for children injured in nicaragua's civil war. the white house signaled president reagan's eagerness to sign the measure
the senate voted 87-7 for the aid a day after the house broke a five-year record of partisan division on the issue and, with strong support from democrats and republicans, gave its consent to the package
federal officials said thursday they have decided against increasing medicare payments to hospitals for treating heart attack victims with an expensive new anti-clotting drug called tpa
there is a question as to whether the circumstances involving tpa are so unique as to justify some special accommodation,'' medicare chief william l. roper said in a letter to the american hospital association. ``we have concluded that they are not.''
the hospitals have been pressing the health care financing administration to take into account the high cost of tpa _ which runs about $2,000 a dose _ in paying for the treatment of heart attack victims
medicare pays hospitals a flat, predetermined amount for treatment of various illnesses rather than reimbursing hospitals for itemized expenses _ such as particular drugs or procedures _ used on a particular patient
those fees are adjusted annually to take into account rising costs and other factors and are predicated on the assumption that, while a hospital may lose money on one patient, it is just as likely to reap an excess profit on another patient with the same diagnosis
tpa costs about 10 times as much as other clot-dissolving drugs, such as streptokinase, which have been available longer and have been used on many more patients
nonetheless, an hcfa fact sheet issued in connection with the decision raises the possibility that use of tpa ``may even result in cost savings'' by reducing the length of time a heart attack patient would need to be hospitalized
it is too early to know what the exact outcome will be,'' the fact sheet said
it noted that if tpa use does prove to increase overall costs for treating heart attack patients, such a determination would be taken into account automatically in the annual hospital payment adjustments
although tpa, short for tissue plasminogen activator, has been judged safe and effective by the food and drug administration for quickly dissolving blood clots in heart attack patients, the evidence is less clear on whether it is significantly more effective than streptokinase in saving lives
trials making a direct comparison between the two drugs are about to begin in england, but results will not be known for a couple of years
study results released at the annual meeting of the american college of cardiology this week showed tpa reduced the number of heart attack deaths by more than 50 percent, when compared to a placebo, in a study of 700 patients. a much larger trial, involving about 17,000 patients, showed a combination of streptokinase and aspirin reduced mortality by nearly 60 percent
the hcfa fact sheet also said some of the warnings carried on tpa labeling ``include factors likely to be more prevalent in the medicare population than in the general population.''
for example, almost 50 percent of medicare beneficiaries admitted for (heart attacks) in fiscal year 1986 were 75 years or older, an age cohort for which physicians are cautioned to weigh the expected benefits of tpa against the risks,'' it said
the vietnamese government is prepared to make the single largest repatriation of american remains since the end of the vietnam war, the pentagon said thursday
we are announcing that vietnam will repatriate 27 remains to u.s. government representatives on april 6, 1988 in hanoi,'' said dan howard, the defense department's chief spokesman
once transferred in hanoi, the remains will be flown to the army's central identification laboratory in honolulu, hawaii, for identification, howard added
this will be the largest number of remains repatriated at one time,'' the spokesman said. ``previously, the largest turnover of remains was 26 on aug. 14, 1985.''
there are currently 2,404 americans still listed as missing in indochina as a result of the vietnam war, of whom 1,767 are listed as missing in either north or south vietnam. up to now, the remains of 152 americans have been repatriated to the united states and subsequently identified by the laboratory
on march 2, the vietnamese turned over 17 remains to u.s. officials. those remains have yet to be identified, however
the upcoming transfer would be the fourth since retired army gen. john vessey traveled to hanoi last august as a special presidential emissary, hoping to step up the process of accounting for missing americans
we've continued to press the vietnamese and we are getting some results,'' howard said thursday
asked if the pentagon could explain the sudden increase in repatriations, howard replied: ``it's really not for us to do that. the vietnamese are the ones who should be explaining to the american people and to the world what happened to the rest of the remains and where they are.''
lt. col. keith schneider, another pentagon spokesman, said the vietnamese government informed u.s. officials during technical meetings in mid-march they were investigating 29 new reports of remains being found or information regarding servicemen uncovered
then earlier this week, the vietnamese disclosed they did have 27 remains to repatriate, schneider added
the u.s. government appreciates the initiative taken by vietnam to repatriate these remains and hopes it represents just one of many continued steps to resolve this long-standing humanitarian issue,'' the pentagon said in a statement
high blood pressure patients given the drug metoprolol had a 48 percent lower death rate than patients given more commonly used drugs, researchers said thursday
metoprolol (pronounced muh-tah-pro-lawl) is one of the heart drugs known as beta blockers. the researchers said this is the first study to show that beta blockers can prevent more deaths in people with hypertension than can the widely used diuretics called thiazides
the american heart association estimates that 59 million americans suffer from high blood pressure, or hypertension
we now have scientific proof that if we start with a beta blocker ... we will have a substantial reduction in deaths,'' said the study's principal author, dr. john wikstrand of gothenburg university's sahlgrenska university hospital in sweden
customary practice in the united states had been to prescribe diuretics first for high blood pressure and to try beta blockers later if the diuretics weren't working, said dr. stevo julius of the university of michigan medical center in ann arbor
new recommendations by a committee of the national heart, lung and blood institute say that diuretics, beta blockers, or two newer classes of anti-hypertension drugs can serve as the first-line treatment for high blood pressure, said julius, an advisor to that committee
julius, who was not part of the study, joined wikstrand at a press conference at new york's plaza hotel to discuss the study's findings. the press conference was sponsored by metoprolol's developer, the astra pharmaceutical company of sweden, and by ciba-geigy pharmaceuticals, which holds the license to market the drug in the united states
the results of the study will appear friday in the journal of the american medical association
two earlier studies that compared beta blockers and diuretics failed to find any significant difference in the death rate, said dr. curt furberg of the bowman gray school of medicine in winston-salem, n.c
furberg, who recently wrote a medical journal article reviewing anti-hypertension drugs, called the new study interesting. but, he said in a telephone interview, ``i'm not sure how it's going to be accepted. it's possible we need to test it in a separate study.''
wikstrand and colleagues at 66 centers in europe and canada monitored 3,234 men given either metoprolol or diuretics for a median period of 4.2 years. the researchers found a 48 percent lower death rate among men given metoprolol than those given diuretics
the drop was mostly due to a reduction in deaths from stroke and coronary heart disease, two complications of high blood pressure, the researchers said. there was no significant effect on other causes of death, suggesting that the drugs are safe, they said
the thiazides make up one class of diuretics, which relieve high blood pressure by stimulating the body to expel fluid, thus lowering the total volume of blood in the bloodstream
beta blockers block the stimulating action of adrenaline, reducing the rate and the force at which the heart pumps blood through the body _ and reducing high blood pressure
a 23-year-old wall street ``whiz kid'' pleaded guilty to mail and securities fraud charges thursday, admitting he bilked $10 million from scores of investors and spent the money on himself and friends
i obtained money from investors, and told them i would invest their money in securities. ... instead i spent the money on art, automobiles, two homes and furnishings,'' david bloom told u.s. district judge david edelstein
bloom, a 1986 graduate of duke university, faces five years in prison and a maximum fine of double the amount lost by investors on each count
edelstein set sentencing for may 12. no sentencing agreement accompanied his guilty plea
several months before his scam was revealed, bloom was profiled in a new york times sunday magazine feature on new art collectors
according to court papers, bloom _ who was not licensed as an investment adviser _ used his clients' money to buy $5.5 million in art work, a $1.9 million east hampton beach house, an $830,000 manhattan apartment, $800,000 in furnishings for the two homes, and two cars worth $200,000
the defendant also bought ``numerous items of expensive jewelry and deluxe trips to the caribbean'' for himself, relatives and friends, federal prosecutors charged
investors were sent papers indicating their investments were turning a profit, sometimes prompting them to turn over more money, said prosecutor robert plotz
to lure additional investors, bloom claimed to represent the rockefeller family, the sultan of brunei and bill cosby, even though he did not
bloom stood with his hands behind his back at thursday's 25-minute hearing and politely answered edelstein's questions
asked if he realized his ``money management'' operation was illegal, bloom responded in a firm voice: ``yes, your honor.''
i said i was a money manager, but i did not invest their money as i told them i would,'' he told the judge
all the art will be auctioned at sotheby's near the end of may, with the chance that some investors could still make a profit, said bloom's attorney, peter morrison
bloom was arrested jan. 14 on a federal complaint; he had 130 clients at his greater sutton investors at the time of his arrest
foreign minister eduard a. shevardnadze said in an interview released thursday that he would not be surprised if afghanistan peace talks fail, and he accused the united states and pakistan of blocking their success
the ruling politburo discussed what action to take in the geneva talks in light of a u.s. ``departure'' from willingness to participate in a political settlement in afghanistan, the tass news agency said
tass also carried an interview shevardnadze gave to the bulgarian newspaper rabotnichesko delo earlier this week, when the soviet official was in bulgaria for a warsaw pact meeting
not everything depends solely on us and the afghan government,'' shevardnadze said. ``this is why one cannot but take into account the possibility that the talks may not lead to the accords expected of them
if this happens, we shall not see this outcome as unexpected,'' shevardnadze said
shevardnadze said that if the u.n.-mediated talks fail, the soviet union will withdraw its 115,000 soldiers from afghanistan ``in a way convenient for the government of afghanistan and ourselves.''
he didn't indicate whether the soviet union would stick to the nine-month withdrawal timetable already agreed to in geneva
shevardnadze accused the united states and pakistan, which represents the guerrillas in the talks, of putting up last-minute barriers with demands that soviet aid to the afghan government cease at the same time as u.s. aid to the insurgents
the demand is intended to give the guerrillas legitimacy ``as something more than a group engaging in armed struggle against a lawful government,'' he said
tass said the politburo, holding a regular weekly meeting thursday, reviewed shevardnadze's discussions march 21-23 in washington with secretary of state george p. shultz
note was taken of the actual departure by the american side ... from its earlier stated readiness to take part in a political settlement of the situation around afghanistan on the basis of the geneva accords. variants of our further steps in this question were studied with due consideration for this,'' tass said
the news agency did not say how the united states had backtracked or what steps the politburo was considering
talks aimed at ending the 10-year-old war in afghanistan recessed for the easter holidays. negotiations were scheduled to resume monday, but informal contacts were expected over the weekend
pakistan's acting foreign minister, zain noorani, said he was ready to sign an agreement anytime and hoped for progress soon on the issue of aid to the warring sides
he rejected shevardnadze's comments that an agreement could be signed even if the united states did not participate
the entire deal then would have to be renegotiated, the pakistani diplomat said
the new york times, in its thursday edition, quoted unidentified u.s. officials as saying washington was considering an arrangement under which pakistan would sign the accord, but the united states and soviet union would have a separate understanding on aid to the guerrillas
the frequency of autopsies is declining in the united states, possibly making it harder for researchers to determine causes of death, the national centers for disease control said
in 1985, autopsies were conducted in 14 percent of deaths in the united states, down from 17 percent in 1980, the cdc reported thursday, citing data from the national center for health statistics
the decline ``may have adversely affected the accuracy of determining the underlying cause of death,'' researchers with the atlanta-based cdc said in their weekly report
during the five-year period, the frequency of autopsies performed varied widely among causes of death, from 12 percent of natural deaths to 97 percent of homicides
autopsies in natural deaths dropped from 13 percent in 1980 to 10 percent in 1985, the cdc said. on the other hand, autopsies following unintentional injuries and poisonings rose from 46 percent to 51 percent, and autopsies in suicides rose from 48 percent to 52 percent
in 1985, 34 percent of autopsies performed in the united states involved deaths from other than natural causes, compared to 30 percent in 1980, the cdc said
directors of a new national award aimed at promoting the quality of american products said thursday they have raised $2.2 million to finance the competition and will announce the first winners in november
the malcolm baldrige national quality award was created by congress in august and named after the late commerce secretary, who was killed last year in a horse riding accident
officials said thursday that a maximum of six awards will be given annually _ two each for large manufacturing companies, large service companies and smaller companies engaged in either manufacturing or service
quality is a key weapon in america's arsenal in the international battle for markets,'' commerce secretary c. william verity said in making the announcement. ``this award, which will be america's nobel prize for quality, should help recognize the firms that are making a difference when it comes to quality.''
the competition will be supervised by the commerce department's national bureau of standards in conjunction with a private foundation created by the legislation to raise money for the contest each year
directors of the new foundation are: sanford n. mcdonnell, chairman emeritus of the mcdonnell douglas corp.; john j. hudiburg, head of florida power &amp; light co.; john young, chairman of hewlett-packard; and robert c. baldrige, brother of the late commerce secretary
they said $2.2 million of a total goal of $9.9 million already had been raised from american businesses
hudiburg said the new award would indicate to the world that ``we're willing to invest whatever it takes to insure that america's commitment to excellence is recognized both at home and abroad.''
officials said the winning companies would be picked on the baisis of such criteria as quality assurance programs, with the largest weight in the judging going to customer satisfaction
after a review of written applications, the contest judges will make on-site inspections to pick the winners. the prize will carry no monetary award but winners will be allowed to mention the award in advertising
the u.s. prize was modeled after the deming prize, which japan has been awarding since 1951 to recognize quality achievements by japanese companies
the japanese prize was named to honor w. edwards deming, an american quality control export revered in japan for his work with japanese companies after world war ii
companies interested in finding out more about the contest can write: malcolm baldrige national quality award, national bureau of standards, gaithersburg, md., 20899. officials said an application fee of $1,500 is being charged to cover expenses, with a deadline of may 20 for applications
a u.s. pharmaceuticals company signed an agreement with the chinese government thursday that officials say could lead to increased american drug sales in china and development of chinese drugs for world markets
officials of g. d. searle &amp; co. and representatives of the state pharmaceutical administration of china said it was too early to tell what specific drugs might be involved in the research agreement. but both sides said it could involve a range of products, including possible future aids treatments developed in china
this is a good beginning between the united states and china,'' said liu yonggang, a vice president of the chinese administration who signed the sino-searle research and development trust at the chinese embassy. speaking through a translator, liu said it was the first such agreement with an american company
the agreement says searle will have the right to license exclusively any products that result from research and development under the trust
richard u. deschutter, president of searle's international operations, said the company already sells seven products in china, although sales have been less than $100,000 annually. he said the agreement includes $500,000 for drug development, with provisions for increased funding later
deschutter said the potential chinese market for foreign drugs could be between $3 billion and $5 billion annually. imports of drugs and medical devices last year reached about $300 million, chinese officials said. they had no figures for the u.s. share of the market
liu acknowledged that china, where herbal medicine makes up a large share of the market, still lags behind other countries in product quality and research
he said more than 1,800 factories manufacture drugs or medical devices in china _ including 600 facilities producing 4,000 kinds of herbal medicines. liu said china doubled its production of pharmaceuticals between 1979 and 1987 and plans to put more emphasis on exports
dr. shen jiaxiang, deputy director of the chinese pharmaceutical agency, said there are some ``interesting findings'' related to aids in china, although the country has had only about a half dozen cases of the fatal disease, all involving tourists
shen, talking to reporters after the signing ceremonies, said researchers have identified several chinese traditional remedies that enhance the human immune system. aids, or acquiried immune deficiency syndrome, breaks down the body's resistance to other diseases. more than 31,000 americans have died of aids
we may provide some help, but we don't have a cure,'' shen said
he said aids research is not specifically mentioned in the agreement with searle, but it might be one area to discuss
deschutter said the company has been involved in aids research and the pact could lead to some cooperation in that area with the chinese
we have not had a chance to talk that out, but it's possible our approaches could be synergistic,'' he said after the news conference
searle, with headquarters in skokie, ill., develops, manufactures and markets prescription pharmaceuticals worldwide. it is a wholly owned subsidiary of monsanto co
