dwight eisenhower was surly, angry and disagreeable and ``didn't do a thing as president,'' according to his predecessor, harry truman
in notes for a book truman never completed, the former president lists eisenhower as one of eight presidents ``we could have done without,'' the others being zachary taylor, franklin pierce, james buchanan, ulysses grant, benjamin harrison, warren harding and calvin coolidge
in notes for a book truman never completed, the former president lists eisenhower as one of eight presidents ``we could have done without,'' including warren harding and calvin coolidge
i'm not one of mr. eisenhower's admirers,'' truman wrote. ``i tried so hard to be pleasant and cooperative when i was turning the office over to eisenhower, but he acted as if i was his enemy instead of the fellow who'd had the job just before him.''
once he was in the white house, ``eisenhower never made any effort to put forward the leadership to which he was entitled, and he didn't have any program,'' truman claimed
ike wasn't even nice, according to the missouri democrat
it's interesting that a single thing, that great smile of eisenhower's, gave him the reputation of being a sunny and amiable man,'' truman wrote, ``when those of us who knew him well were all too aware that he was essentially a surly, angry and disagreeable man, and i just don't mean to me, either.''
truman's comments, many of which were dictated to secretaries and relatives in the years between his departure from the white house in 1953 and his death in 1972, have been collected in a book titled ``more plain speaking,'' edited by his daughter, margaret truman, and scott meredith. parts of the book were published in the april 3 parade magazine
besides the eight worst presidents, truman listed his eight best: george washington, thomas jefferson, andrew jackson, james polk, abraham lincoln, grover cleveland, woodrow wilson and franklin roosevelt. deaths</head>
passenger deaths during airline flights are extremely rare, but crews are not adequately prepared and medical equipment aboard airliners is insufficient to deal with the problem, researchers conclude
airlines simply can't count on doctors being aboard flights,'' said dr. richard cummins, one of five authors of a study published in friday's journal of the american medical association
they should take a look at the duration of the flight, the number of passengers aboard and determine what additional measures are needed,'' added cummins, an associate professor of medicine at the university of washington at seattle
an average 72 passengers die during flights each year, which researchers called ``a vanishingly small rate'' of three deaths per 10 million passengers
the study reviewed deaths reported from 1977 to 1984 to the international air transport association, which has 120 members and carries 50 percent to 60 percent of the world's scheduled international and domestic air traffic
researchers concluded that 56 percent of the deaths appeared to be heart-related
nearly two-thirds of the deaths during flight involved men, whose average age was 54. doctors aboard the aircraft came forward to offer assistance in 43 percent of the deaths, the study found
researchers concluded, however, that programs are needed to train flight attendants in the skills of basic cardiopulmonary resuscitation and the use of automatic external defibrillators, the electric-shock ``heart starters,'' said cummins
they are not part of the on-board medical kits now, and we're not advocating they be added to every flight,'' he said. ``but some flights should have them.''
if flight attendants can be trained to open airplane doors in an emergency, they can be trained to operate a defibrillator,'' he said. ``and the machine provides a simple way to diagnose many kinds of cardiac arrest
william jackman, spokesman for the american transport association, a trade organization representing u.s. airlines, said flight attendants on most major carriers already receive training in cpr skills
earlier this week, delta air lines attendant nancy holt used cpr to save a stricken passenger for the second time in her career. a man collapsed just after boarding her plane in atlanta and an unidentified doctor on board helped her until paramedics arrived at the airport
cpr proficiency is part of flight attendants' training, ms. holt said, and ``you never forget it.''
jackman noted the federal aviation administration did not include defibrillators in its august 1986 guidelines on mandatory equipment for airline medical kits. those guidelines are scheduled for review this summer
basically, our policy has been to land as soon as possible, and in this country, that means no more than 20 or 30 minutes no matter where you are,'' said jackman
crews call ahead for medical teams at the runway and, once on the ground, we're certain that experienced, capable doctors are providing treatment,'' he added
and we just can't ask flight attendants to diagnose an ailment ... to know the difference between a heart attack and say, a diabetic one,'' said jackman
cummins countered that a delay of 20 minutes or longer could prove fatal in instances of sudden cardiac arrest
the law doesn't obligate the airlines,'' cummins said, ``but it's time they started taking responsibility in some of these emergencies.'' playwrights horizons studio theater</note>
the 1988 pulitzer prize for fiction was awarded thursday to toni morrison for ``beloved,'' a novel which was at the center of controversy when it did not win two other major literary prizes
the prize for drama went to ``driving miss daisy,'' by alfred uhry, which like ``beloved'' deals with race relations in the united states
the prize for general non-fiction went to richard rhodes for ``the making of the atomic bomb.''
the prize for biography went to david herbert donald for ``look homeward: a life of thomas wolfe,'' about the american novelist. donald also won the pulitzer prize for biography in 1961 for ``charles sumner and the coming of the civil war.''
the prize in history went to robert v. bruce, a professor at boston university, for ``the launching of modern american science 1846-1876.''
william meredith, an award-winning poet associated with connecticut college, won the poetry prize for ``partial accounts: new and selected poems.''
the prize for music was awarded to william bolcom, a professor at the university of michigan, for ``12 new etudes for piano.''
the focus of attention this year was on the fiction prize, which was awarded against a backdrop of controversy and literary politics
after ``beloved'' did not win either the national book award or the national book critics circle award, 48 prominent black writers and critics signed a statement deploring ms. morrison's lack of recognition
because she had never won the national book award or the pulitzer prize, said the statement, published as an open letter in the new york times book review, ``she has yet to receive the national recognition that her five major works of fiction entirely deserve.''
ms. morrison's ``song of solomon'' did win the national book critics circle award for 1977, but the two other awards are considered more prestigious
beloved'' is the agonizing story of a former slave in post-civil war ohio who struggles to cope with the brutal death of her daughter
ms. morrison uses flashbacks, multiple points of view and a singularly vivid ghost to describe the emotional trauma of slavery from the perspective of sethe, who kills her daughter rather than yield her to bondage
driving miss daisy,'' the drama winner, tells the story of an irascible white woman and her black chauffeur. the play follows their relationship over a quarter-century, ending in 1973
the play opened off-broadway in april 1987 at the playwrights horizons studio theater and later moved to a larger off-broadway theater where it is still running
the making of the atomic bomb,'' the winner for general non-fiction, won a national book award last fall in the same category
rhodes, who spent five years researching and writing the book, said in a recent interview: ``the making of the bomb is a story on the scale of `moby dick.' i don't see much of a difference between writing fiction and fact, except, of course, that fact has to be documented.'' pvs to shorten.</note>
