the post said weld told meese the attorney general's situation presented a close call but that if it were up to weld he would present it to the grand jury for an indictment
the new york times, in a similar report, quoted sources as saying weld had previously commented that ``he would have to seriously consider indicting meese.'' the newspaper said that weld, asked about that comment, would not respond on the record
specter, asked about the quotes attributed to weld, said, ``up until this moment, or perhaps yesterday, you had a situation where the independent counsel was looking ... but i think now is a different matter. the president has to talk to mr. weld, has to examine the facts and then has to make a presidential decision.''
specter earlier questioned ``whether the u.s. department of justice can function'' with meese in charge
you finally reach a place where there is a cloud of suspicion, a sufficient cloud of suspicion, that i think you owe it to the president to remove yourself,'' packwood said
weld told the times that he had become concerned about the collective ``damage'' being done to the justice department by having a man under investigation as its leader
the times quoted a source as saying weld told his aides in announcing his resignation that, to him, ``it was a question of moral authority and the tarnishing of the department.''
sen. howard metzenbaum, d-ohio, said today that reagan's ``duty'' is ``to bring about the resignation of mr. meese.''
the president owes a duty to the country that may be much higher than that which he owes to his personal friend,'' metzenbaum said at the start of a senate judiciary subcommittee hearing on antitrust matters
the question, said metzenbaum, is, ``if mr. meese does not shortly resign whether the public will be losing confidence in government as a whole.''
the boston herald, meanwhile, quoted weld as saying in an interview that, when he and burns told meese they were resigning, the attorney general ``thought we were joking. i told him it was so. he seemed a little taken jaback.''
for his part, meese said ``there's no reason to resign'' and reagan reiterated his support for his old friend, saying ``he's been a friend for over 20 years. i have every confidence in him.''
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater was asked wednesday why meese remained on the job when white house chief of staff howard baker, vice president george bush and first lady nancy reagan wanted him out
i don't think any of that is true,'' fitzwater replied
mrs. reagan's press secretary, elaine crispen, said today that reports that the first lady was campaigning for meese's removal were ``absolutely not true.''
she hasn't talked to anyone and no one has talked to her about the issue,'' mrs. crispen said by telephone from los angeles, where mrs. reagan is visiting before joining the president at their california ranch friday for an easter vacation
quitting with burns, the no. 2 official in the department, and weld, were four of their aides
meese predicted on wednesday that solicitor general charles fried, who had said he was reconsidering his future with the department, would not follow suit
meese, who met with fried on wednesday, said ``i have no doubt that mr. fried will remain a strong member of the management team.''
business is operating as usual at the justice department,'' meese declared. he said replacements were being sought for burns and weld and that ``everything is going along well.'' acquitted of charges</note>
presidents can be reluctant to fire their closest aides, and president reagan, who has shown great loyalty to top advisers in the past, is unlikely to oust his longtime friend, attorney general edwin meese iii, white house observers say
he's been a friend for over 20 years,'' reagan told reporters wednesday in response to questions about whether he would remove the attorney general, who faces mounting legal problems. ``i have every confidence in him.''
his statement recalled the time in the summer of 1984 when the president, arriving in dallas for the republican national convention, was quizzed about whether he would oust labor secretary raymond donovan, who faced a federal indictment
reagan declared that he wouldn't give in to a ``lynch mob atmosphere.''
when donovan finally was indicted, he saved reagan the decision by resigning immediately. donovan later was found innocent in new york court of larceny and fraud charges involving a construction company he co-owned
reagan so dislikes firing top aides that an embittered secretary of state alexander m. haig jr. had to try at least twice to quit before the president finally accepted his resignation in june 1982
reagan didn't fire interior secretary james watt after he made offensive remarks about blacks, women, jews and the handicapped in 1983. watt offered to step aside
after watching ronald reagan and reading about him all these years, i've come to the conclusion that it is a matter of leadership style that dictates that he not fire people,'' said robert a. bonatati, who was reagan's labor adviser early in the administration
he never gets on the side of firing people and he always defends people who are under attack.''
reagan has said steadfastly that he thinks public officials ought to be presumed innocent until found guilty in court. he's even gone further than that with two major figures in the iran-contra affair, saying he believes former national security aides oliver l. north and john m. poindexter are innocent of charges they conspired to defraud the government
reagan's close association with meese goes back to his days as governor of california from 1967-75, when meese was a valued counselor. during his first months in the presidency in 1981, writes reagan biographer lou cannon, ``reagan valued ed meese's advice above all others, believing that meese would see to it that conflicting points of view were presented to him without coloration.''
in quintessential reagan style, the president threw his arm around meese when reporters tried to question him about the attorney general early last fall, just after the two had appeared in the white house press room to announce anthony m. kennedy's selection for a supreme court vacancy
but reagan is not the only president who has shown great loyalty to his aides. a former high-ranking official in the carter administration, describing the difficulty that jimmy carter had in ousting budget director bert lance, said ``it's always difficult for presidents to let go of people close to them, and that was true of lance, and it's certainly true of meese.''
these are the toughest issues for presidents to face,'' said the source, speaking on condition of anonymity
presidents do sometimes swing the ax, however. president eisenhower ousted top aide sherman adams and president johnson got rid of close associate walter jenkins. gerald ford eased out agriculture secretary earl butz
it's a major problem for all presidents,'' said the university of virginia's larry sabato. ``but few presidents have been as reluctant and as reticent as this president to ditch people who become political liabilities. eisenhower thought it was important to be cleaner than a hound's tooth.''
bonatati noted he lost his job at the white house despite reagan's aversion to firing
he said that when faith ryan whittlesey arrived in early march 1983 to succeed elizabeth dole as director of the white house office of public liaison, whittlesey fired him and several other presidential advisers with short notice
she pretty much cleaned house,'' bonatati said. pulitzers each</head> banaszynski xxxx, to restore identification as knight-ridder papers</note>
the charlotte observer, the miami herald and the wall street journal each won two 1988 pulitzer prizes on thursday, with the observer receiving the gold medal for public service for its reports on jim and tammy bakker's ptl television ministry
the observer and the herald led knight-ridder newspapers to a total of six pulitzers
the pulitzer prize board cited the observer for revealing misuse of funds by the ministry ``through persistent coverage conducted in the face of a massive campaign by ptl to discredit the newspaper.''
the observer's doug marlette also won a pulitzer for his editorial cartooning in charlotte and at the atlanta constitution
the herald's dave barry won the commentary pulitzer for what the board called ``his consistently effective use of humor as the device for presenting fresh insights into serious concerns.'' his colleague michel ducille won the feature photography award for photographs of a housing project plagued by a cocaine epidemic
daniel hertzberg and james b. stewart of the journal won the award for explanatory journalism for their stories about an investment banker charged with insider trading and the day after the oct. 19 stock market crash
the journal also won a pulitzer in specialized reporting for walt bogdanich's series of reports on faulty testing by american medical laboratories
three chicago tribune reporters _ dean baquet, william gaines and ann marie lipinski _ won the investigative reporting prize for what the board termed ``detailed reporting on the self-interest and waste that plague chicago's city council.''
we're thrilled,'' said ellen soeteber, the tribune's assistant managing editor for metropolitan news. ``i think the team of reporters deserved this so much. it was their concept. it was their idea, and they brought it off beautifully. i'm so glad some of the leaders in our profession recognized it.''
two pulitzers were given for general news reporting. one went to the staff of the alabama journal of montgomery for an investigation of the state's unusually high infant mortality rate, which prompted remedial legislation. the second was awarded to the staff of the lawrence (mass.) eagle-tribune for an investigation that revealed flaws in the massachusetts prison furlough system and led to reforms
tim weiner of the philadelphia inquirer, another knight-ridder newspaper, won the national reporting prize for his series on a secret pentagon budget used to sponsor defense research and an arms buildup
the international reporting pulitzer was won by thomas l. friedman of the new york times for what the board called ``balanced and informed coverage'' of israel. it was friedman's second pulitzer for international reporting; his first was in 1983 for his reporting from lebanon
jacqui banaszynski of the st. paul (minn.) pioneer press dispatch, also a knight-ridder newspaper, won the pulitzer for feature writing for her series about the life and death of an aids victim in a rural community
tom shales of the washington post won the criticism award for his writing on television, and jane healy of the orlando sentinel won the editorial writing prize for editorials that protested overdevelopment of florida's orange county
the pulitzer for spot news photography was awarded to scott shaw of the odessa (texas) american for his pictures of little jessica mcclure being rescued from a well
except for the award for public service, which brings with it a gold medal, pulitzers carry a cash prize of $3,000. the winners are selected by the pulitzer prize board and announced by the president of columbia university, which administers the competition. system</head>
the head of the american federation of teachers said thursday that small groups of teachers should be given the autonomy and funds to create experimental schools within regular public schools
aft president albert shanker said the current public school system is not working for as many as 80 percent of the students and ``we've got to do something totally different.''
shanker suggested that groups of six to 12 teachers be allowed to organize their own schools, provided they can win the approval of principals, fellow teachers, parents and education authorities
it is time once again to take a major step forward in trying to improve the schools of our nation,'' said shanker, whose 665,000-member union represents teachers in some of the nation's largest cities, including new york and chicago
he said state-mandated reforms and more stringent standards imposed over the past five years have improved schools for students at the top, ``but unfortunately (reform) is bypassing about 80 percent of kids.''
we now need to seek ways that will enable any group of teachers ... and parents of children who want to do something different to opt for a different type of school,'' he said in a national press club address
the autonomous schools ``ought to get their per capita share of what the school spends,'' he said. public schools spend roughly $4,000 per pupil on average
shanker said, ``there would have to be a guarantee that such a school would be left alone for five or 10 years provided that parents wanted to keep sending their kids there.'' they would be strictly voluntary for teachers and students
if there's anarchy, the customers will be gone in no time at all,'' he said. ``this is not pie in the sky.''
he said such a system would give teachers an alternative to trying to ``shove reform down the throats'' of unwilling colleagues
shanker said only a handful of districts now are trying to restructure public schools. he claimed his idea could open the door for thousands of experimental schools
shanker said he would want the teachers to include in their proposals ways for teachers to govern themselves, to give students alternatives to sitting in class for six hours listening to lectures and to spur cooperative learning. the students also should ``reflect the composition of the entire school'' and not just be drawn from the top or bottom, he said
last week, mary hatwood futrell, president of the national education association, proposed that state leaders and teacher unions designate at least one experimental school district in each of the 50 states
paint that has built up on white house walls since 1797 is being removed as part of a project designed to spruce up the presidential residence for its bicentennial in 1992
the national park service said the job will involve removing some 30 coats of paint and repairing some of the carved stonework on the sandstone walls. work began this week
the work will be done on the exterior north walls and part of the south walls and will be the first time in nearly two centuries that these walls have been exposed
the walls will be kept bare until the spring of 1989 to allow the porous sandstone to dry so the paint will adhere to the walls better. repainting is scheduled for next spring
the paint is being removed by brushing chemicals on the walls and then flushing them with a stream of water
the work is being done by ramco technologies of hartford, conn., under a $384,200 contract
vincent palumbo, master carver for the national cathedral, will oversee repair of the stone carvings
the project is part of a long-range exterior restoration program to repair and replace deteriorated stonework, remove old paint, repoint and seal masonry joints and then repaint. the east wall was restored in 1980 and the north portico in 1984
the entire program is to be completed for the bicentennial of the laying of the cornerstone of the ``president's house'' in 1792. the white house has been the home and office of every president since john adams
democrats looking ahead to new york's april 19 presidential primary are focusing on the mystery of a cuomo endorsement and the status of jesse jackson's ticklish relationship with the state's influential jewish community
the questions are obvious:
will gov. mario cuomo endorse his fellow northeast governor, michael dukakis? or will he stay on the sideline, fueling speculation that he wants the nomination for himself?
can jackson overcome the sour taste lingering from his 1984 campaign when he infuriated new york jews by privately referring to new york city as ``hymietown?''
jesse got 26 or 27 percent (of the vote) in '84 after the `hymietown' crack and with a fritz mondale who had a very strong call on the black constituency,'' said cuomo. ``he'll do at least that this year and probably substantially better. if he does 10 points better, he'll be at 37 (percent). you have four candidates in the race, that's a big number.''
cuomo, perhaps the most prominent democratic non-candidate, has said his endorsement means little, but even his chief political adviser, son andrew, doesn't buy that
in new york, it has a particular importance,'' said the younger cuomo. ``it helps the candidate among those people who haven't made up their minds yet or who are soft in their support.''
the governor has said that within the next week or so he will either endorse someone or announce that he's sitting it out
in 1984, cuomo got behind walter mondale early, and with the governor's powerful political machine in charge, mondale scored an important victory to blunt gary hart's insurgent campaign
at times, the new york governor has appeared to lean toward dukakis, but lately he has been saying nice things about tennessee sen. albert gore jr. and has been proclaiming that jackson could win in november at the head of the ticket or would be good as the vice presidential candidate
and cuomo has said jackson could well win the new york primary, an outcome that would seriously damage dukakis, jackson's chief rival for front-runner status, and perhaps increase the likelihood of a deadlocked national convention
polls have thus far have shown dukakis in the lead and jackson doing only slightly better than the 26 percent he won in 1984
also on the new york ballot will be democrat paul simon and an uncommitted slate of delegates sponsored by a group of new york's elected county clerks who would like to see cuomo in the race. they say the uncommitted delegates could be valuable to cuomo if there's any move to draft him at the party's national convention in atlanta
while cuomo has said he doesn't want a draft, he has refused to rule out accepting one. new york city mayor edward koch, one of the state's most powerful democrats, has said he's ready to lead a draft-cuomo move at the atlanta convention
numbers make new york's democratic primary important. as the second largest state in the nation, new york's 275-member delegation will be second in size only to california's with 336 delegates. the new york primary results will determine the allocation of 255 of the delegates
for gore, new york could mark a new beginning or the end of the road
i have to have a result in the new york primary that convinces you that this campaign has gained a significant momentum,'' gore told a group of prominent new yorkers early this week
in an attempt to carry that off, gore has hired new york political consultant david garth, agreed to pump more than $1 million into new york and adopted a new campaign strategy of attacking jackson
in a speech to jewish leaders, gore contrasted his support of israel with jackson's recognition of the palestine liberation organization
in new york's democratic primaries, jews traditionally represent about 25 percent of the electorate with blacks at about the same level. while jackson is expected to capture the lion's share of the black vote, anything more than a single-digit showing for him among jewish voters would be considered something of a miracle
nonetheless, a recent poll by the marist college institute for public opinion found that among jewish democrats surveyed, jackson's favorable rating has jumped to 36 percent from 17 percent in january. but less than 4 percent of those jewish democrats surveyed in the most recent poll said they would vote for jackson
a gallup poll, conducted at the end of last week, had dukakis leading at 44 percent to 28 percent for jackson. gore was at 3 percent and simon at 2 percent
a cold shower won't do it, but a hot bath will be just fine for mangoes imported from mexico, the agriculture department said thursday
the dip in hot water is prescribed to destroy hitchhiking fruit flies that could come into the united states from mexico, said james w. glosser, acting administrator of the department's animal and plant health inspection service
about 65 percent of the mangoes eaten in the united states come from mexico and were previously fumigated with a chemical, ethylene dibromide. however, the environmental protection agency banned this treatment
glosser said the hot-water dip ``destroys all the fruit fly species that exist in mexico.'' ``war of cities.'' picks up 3rd graf pvs, in ankara ...</note>
iraq fired three missiles into iranian cities thursday, then said it would stop for three days. no further attacks by either side were reported in the month-old round of the ``war of the cities.''
the iraqi news agency said the cease-fire would begin thursday midnight (4 p.m. est) and last through the three days of a visit to baghdad by turgut ozal, prime minister of turkey
as the announced time passed, neither side had reported any attacks on each other's cities for hours
a cypriot supertanker set afire by an iranian warship earlier thursday meanwhile ran aground in the persian gulf
in ankara, the turkish capital, iranian embassy spokesman riza bagri said iran's missile launchings would ``automatically come to an end'' if iraq stopped attacking iranian cities with rockets and bombs
tehran radio did not confirm bagri's statement, but said iraq was the ``instigator'' of attacks on cities and iran took ``retaliatory measures.''
hundreds of civilians have been killed since the missile duel began feb. 29 and thousands have died in raids on cities since the iran-iraq war began in september 1980
an iranian warship pounded the 232,164-ton supertanker haven, loaded with 1.5 million barrels of saudi arabian crude, for 90 minutes at dawn thursday. the 45-member crew was rescued from the burning ship, which ran aground later off the united arab emirates
shipping executives believed the attack was a response to several iraqi attacks in recent days on tankers owned or chartered by iran. about 500 ships have been attacked by both sides
a u.s. navy spokesman said two portable anti-aircraft missiles, tentatively identified as soviet-made sam-7s, were found on a drifting iranian speedboat the navy recovered last week. the iranians use speedboats for attacks on neutral shipping
ayatollah ruhollah khomeini, iran's revolutionary patriarch, exhorted his people to new effort in the long conflict, declaring: ``today is the day of war. today we must rush to the war front in order to inflict punishing blows on the enemy, and with the help of god we will succeed.''
the enemy has proved his brutal actions by firing chemical weapons on residential areas,'' he said in remarks reported by tehran radio
a dispatch from iran's official islamic republic news agency said a team of swiss physicians arrived to visit victims of alleged iraqi chemical weapons attacks on border towns
it also said iraq dropped chemical bombs on marivan, a kurdish town about 25 miles northeast of halabja, killing ``a number'' of civilians
iran claims iraq dropped gas bombs on halabja and two nearby kurdish towns in iraq two weeks ago, after iranian troops captured them. iran said 5,000 people were killed in the attack and 5,000 wounded
iraq said it fired two surface-to-surface missiles thursday into isfahan, which was persia's capital in the 17th century, and one into qom, seat of iran's religious hierarchy
since the missile exchange began, iraq has reported launching 105 missiles at iranian cities. iran says it has fired 45 missiles at baghdad and dozens into other iraqi cities
turkish embassy officials in baghdad said ozal would arrive friday afternoon accompanied by senior officials. turkey maintains good relations with both iraq and iran and has tried to act as mediaor
an iraqi government spokesman was quoted by the official news agency as saying attacks on iranian cities would not resume ``until six hours after the turkish prime minister's departure'' on sunday
the cypriot tanker was attacked near the narrow strait of hormuz, through which all ships must pass to enter or leave the gulf. shipping executives said it drifted for more than three hours before running aground
crew members huddled on the stern, unable because of the fire to reach the engine room and stop the engines, and they were rescued a few at a time. tugboats brought the blaze under control later, said the informants, who spoke on condition of anonymity
maj. barry willey, a spokesman for the u.s. central command, said the sam-7s were found along with other weapons in an abandoned iranian speedboat picked up in the strait of hormuz a week ago
he said a twin-barreled gun mounted in the cockpit of the 30-foot boat was a soviet-made zsu 23mm anti-aircraft weapon
sam-7 missiles, which iran is known to possess, are shoulder-fired weapons similar to the u.s.-made redeye
senate majority leader robert c. byrd said thursday he will not call up the u.s.-soviet medium-range missile treaty for debate until the question of whether the pact bans futuristic weapons is better resolved
but sen. alan simpson, r-wyo., the senate's deputy gop leader, said the white house has put ``400 lawyers to work'' on the issue and added: ``i think it can be resolved.''
sen. chic hecht, r-nev., a member of the senate intelligence committee, said, however, that the general question of futuristic weapons is a serious one and must be addressed sooner or later
hecht said u.s. intelligence reports show the soviet union has 10,000 scientists working on the development of futuristic weapons using lasers and directed energy
hecht said the information came from a classified intelligence briefing, but that he had been given permission to release it
byrd told reporters that the question of futuristic weapons had been addressed inadequately by the administration and it was not clear that they are banned by the treaty's restrictions
it is too important to risk going ahead,'' byrd said. ``it is better to be sure, to be cautious and to be right. i intend not to call it up until it is better resolved than it is now.''
the treaty has to be good for us,'' byrd said, adding that his decision to delay action on the treaty is ``a signal to the administration not to do in haste'' what should be done with care
on another treaty issue, a group of republican senators told reporters at a luncheon meeting they believed compromise eventually will be reached on a move by democrats to attach to the pact language intended to bind future presidents to the current view of the meaning and impact of the treaty
sen. daniel evans, r-wash., a member of the senate foreign relations committee, called the democratic effort ``an egregious insult to president reagan'' and said it will not be settled without a pitched battle
the democrats will not let the treaty die because of this but we might come perilously close before someone backs down,'' evans said
there is one group trying to kill the treaty and another group trying to embarrass the president, and neither group will win,'' evans said
sen. mitch mcconnell, r-ky., said he also believed the controversy will be resolved
the democrats will not let the treaty die on this issue,'' mcconnell said. ``i cannot believe that when push comes to shove they are going to want to be held responsible by the american people for failure to ratify this treaty.''
the dispute grew out the reagan administration's reinterpretation of the 1972 anti-ballistic missile treaty to permit the deloyment of a strategic defense system
the senate foreign relations committee voted 17-2 vote on wednesday to approve the treaty and send it to the full senate, where it was expected to be taken up following next week's easter recess
ambassador maynard glitman, the chief u.s. negotiator for the treaty, told the committee that the treaty does ban future weapons and that the soviets understands they are banned
glitman said the treaty calls for the elimination of all ``weapon delivery vehicles'' with a range from between 400 miles and 3,400 miles, asserting this covers all weapons, not just those armed with nuclear warheads. selection</head>
five statues of the late president john f. kennedy were displayed on a tabletop thursday for members of a special legislative board who will select one of the designs for a monument on the statehouse lawn
selection of the winning sculpture design will conclude a yearlong competition that included hundreds of entries from artists around the country
three of the statues on display at the john f. kennedy library were made of white plaster, one of bronze and one, still wet, of clay. they ranged in height from 2 feet to 3 feet
all the finalists show kennedy in traditional design in full figure. in one submission, he is wearing an open overcoat, which is blowing in the wind
the five semifinalist sculptors are: frederick hart of markham, va.; penelope jencks of newton; robert white of st. james, va.; isable mcilvain of concord, and norman legassie, jr. of old lyme, conn
for the past 25 years, since the death of john f. kennedy, massachusetts has been without an official state monument to its beloved native son,'' said state rep. john macgovern, the commission chairman. ``the absence of the late president from this state's proud display of monuments is about to be corrected with a memorial that every citizen of the commonwealth can be proud of.''
after a brief introduction by former kennedy aide dave powers, macgovern said the nationwide search for a sculptor was almost over. paraphrasing winston churchill, macgovern said, ``this is not the beginning of the end, it is perhaps the end of the beginning.''
commission members will be casting their votes for a memorial finalist over the next few days
caroline kennedy, kennedy's daughter and a member of the commission, will attend the april 7 news conference annoucing the winning sculpture
the jfk statue, which will be the commonwealth's official monument to kennedy, will be erected on the west front lawn of the statehouse. it is hoped that the dedication of the memorial will take place may 29, 1989, which would have been kennedy's 72nd birthday
kennedy, a democrat who was elected president in 1960 and assassinated in 1963, began his political career in the 1940s representing boston in congress
the deployment of more than 3,100 troops to honduras as a show of force and warning to nicaragua will cost at least $5 million, the pentagon said thursday
dan howard, the defense department's chief spokesman, said final figures won't be available for 30 to 60 days. but, he said, ``the total cost of the operation is estimated at somewhere between $5 million and $10 million.''
howard was asked about the cost of the so-called emergency deployment readiness exercise after announcing the last soldiers from the 82nd airborne division had returned home to fort bragg, n.c., thursday morning
some logistical support people will be returning tomorrow (friday),'' he added. ``all the equipment and supplies not expended in the operation will be returned to the united states.''
soldiers from the 82nd airborne and the 7th light infantry division at fort ord, calif., were airlifted on march 17 and 18 after nicaraguan troops crossed into honduras to mount an attack on u.s.-backed contra guerrillas
the american soldiers were then flown to different parts of honduras for exercises with honduran army units
we're very pleased with the accomplishments of this exercise,'' howard said. ``it demonstrates the responsiveness and deployability of the army's light forces in a joint operation.''
numbers lovers can rejoice. the latest edition of the statistical abstract is at hand with detail on everything they ever wanted to know, and probably more
the 108th edition of the volume goes on for 970 pages, including 1,425 tables and charts, compiled by the census bureau from a wide variety of sources
selling for $25 _ $5 more for hardbound _ the volume is widely used by students, teachers, journalists, government workers, businessmen and the just plain curious
a sampling of facts from the volume:
_the nation produced $18.7 billion worth of computers in 1985, nearly nine times the worth of those manufactured a decade earlier
_the u.s. fish catch totaled 8.2 million pounds in 1986. the biggest item, menhaden at 2.4 million pounds
_there were 909,000 americans in hospitals on any given day in 1985, a total that has been declining in recent years
_some 5.57 percent of mortgages were delinquent in 1986, down from 5.84 percent a year earlier
