regional communist party officials admitted they are powerless to end an ethnic dispute that has led to a massive work stoppage by armenians in a southern city, and they appealed to moscow for help, a newspaper reported thursday
the government daily izvestia said the stepanakert city committee unanimously passed a resolution calling on national party leaders to again take up the issue of the nagorno-karabakh region of azerbaijan
armenians are demanding that the armenian-dominated region be made part of their republic, which neighbors azerbaijan
the local committee's appeal, adopted at a meeting wednesday, did not persuade people to return to work, according to one resident in stepanakert, the main city of nagorno-karabakh
people aren't even thinking of going to work,'' said the resident, a man answering the telephone at the sovietsky karabakh newspaper thursday. he refused to identify himself
izvestia said the plenary meeting of the stepanakert city committee was stormy and that one speaker broke down and cried
the majority of the communists decisively condemned the tactic of `forced pressure' on the country's leadership, and along with that every speaker underlined that the nagorno-karabakh problem has not been removed, that it still needs a settlement,'' izvestia said
izvestia said the work stoppage gave new ammunition to people who say soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev's reforms permit too much outspokenness
izvestia quoted a stepanakert party official, robert kocharyan, as saying that ``continuing worker absences give supporters of the old (way) grounds to say: `here's your result! you let the people get out of hand. you shouldn't give them such an occasion.'''
izvestia did not provide other details of the meeting, and a woman answering the telephone at the city committee's offices referred all questions to the party central committee in moscow
stepanakert workers have vowed to continue the walkout, which began march 24, until the central government and party reverse their decisions to keep nagorno-karabakh under the control of azerbaijan
the communist party central committee refused the armenians' demand in february and was asked by the local committee to reconsider the decision. the presidium of the supreme soviet, the national parliament, ordered cultural and economic improvements for the region on march 23 but did not address the territorial issue
all but bakeries and dairies, some stores and some public transportation and medical clinics have been closed in stepanakert since the strike began
kocharyan said just 308 workers, only one-fifth of the force, showed up thursday at the silk factory where he works
for me that's zero, and as a party secretary, i'm ashamed for myself and my comrades,'' he told izvestia
the man at the sovietsky karabakh newspaper said there were no demonstrations in stepanakert and that few policemen were on the street
soviet foreign ministry spokesman gennady i. gerasimov provided the first official confirmation that paruyr ayrikyan, a former political prisoner, was among armenian nationalists arrested last week in the armenian capital, yerevan
the spokesman, at a regular news briefing, said he did not know under which criminal statute ayrikyan was being held
the soviet government has forbidden foreign journalists from traveling to armenia and nagorno-karabakh. gerasimov was asked about that policy after he criticized israel's government for barring journalists from the occupied west bank and gaza strip, where unrest has raged since december
i have to reject your parallel,'' gerasimov said. ``we have not occupied anybody anywhere in this situation.'' he said journalists would have to ``wait a little while'' to visit the region, ``until the passions cool down.'' ownership.</note>
the pompidou center is displaying more than 400 works by the russian-born painter marc chagall that were turned over to the government in lieu of taxes
many of them have never been seen before in public
the value of the collection cannot be estimated,'' said finance minister edouard balladur. ``the government never could have afforded to allocate such sums to enrich the national heritage.''
chagall died in 1985 at his home in southern france at the age of 97. working steadily until the end, he left behind a vast private collection of oil paintings, drawings, mosaics, sketches, book illustrations, set designs, and engravings worth countless millions of dollars
the works, previously owned by the chagall family, are displayed in four galleries on the pompidou center's fourth floor
the works represent the second largest donation ever accepted in lieu of death duties. the largest one came from pablo picasso's heirs and constitute what is now the permanent collection of the picasso museum, housed in the hotel sale in central paris
government officials have not decided how the chagall collection will be dispersed among france's many national museums, but it is likely that works with biblical themes will go to the national museum of chagall's biblical message in nice
many of the works on show are known to have been among the ones the artist loved the best. they include ``bella au col blanc,'' (1917), a sensitive portrait of his first wife, bella, dressed in a low-cut dark dress, her graceful features and black hair set off by a wide, white collar
bella died in new york in 1944. chagall married valentina brodsky in 1952
the painting has a cubist touch, and many critics say it is reminiscent of picasso's masterpiece ``les demoiselles d'avignon.''
the paintings look fine in paris, but they weren't bad in my house either,'' said chagall's widow, known as vava, during a tour of the show
the exhibition, which runs until june 5, also features ``les maries de la tour eiffel'' (1938-39), set and costume designs created for moscow's jewish theater including those for gogol's ``revizor,'' and several self-portraits
the corporation for public broadcasting has published a booklet designed to teach ``latchkey'' children basic skills they will need to make their time at home alone safer
the 16-page booklet, titled ``what if i'm home alone? your family's guide to home and personal safety skills,'' teaches children such things as how to get home from school safely, how to use a telephone in an emergency, how to escape a fire and how to deal with strangers who knock at the door
the publication is written in an easy-to-read, entertaining style with large type and illustrations. it also includes a quiz at the end so parents can assess how well their children understand the safety tips
the booklet opens with a letter to parents suggesting ways they can make their home safer and includes a form for emergency and other phone numbers they can fill in and post near the telephone
the booklet is part of a cpb public service campaign designed to help american families cope with changes in society that have left a majority of families headed by a single parent or two working parents
an estimated 5 million to 6 million children ages 5 to 12 who daily come home to an empty house or apartment or have to care for younger siblings, cpb said
the campaign is being run in conjunction with public broadcasting's year-long, national ``child care america'' project being kicked off april 10. the project will focus attention on the issue throughout the year with outreach activities and programming, including a pbs documentary called ``who cares for the children?''
cpb is a private, nonprofit corporation funded by congress to develop noncommercial radio and television services
copies of the booklet are available for $1 each, by check, by writing to ``what if i'm home alone?,'' corporation for public broadcasting, p.o. box 33039-lk, washington, d.c., 20033. missiles and elections, reorder info. no pickup.</note>
the warning broadcast over the radio for the first time thursday was simple: three beeps, a pause, then three more beeps
that signal would mean iraq has launched a poison gas attack on tehran, where iraqi missiles have fallen day and night and where fears of chemical warfare by baghdad are growing
after the warning beeps on tehran radio, an announcer said: ``god willing, we hope no such thing will ever happen, but the enemy is so mean and despicable he could do anything.''
an official of the islamic guidance ministry escorting visiting western correspondents around the battered capital, a city of more than 6 million people, said the iraqis ``would pay dearly if they dared to do it.''
the city of tehran seems to have paid enough already. officials said half of its population has left since iraq's missiles began wrecking apartment houses, markets, shops, office buildings, hospitals and schools
on thursday, many tehran schools and stores stayed closed in case of attack, but people came up to the streets from underground shelters. there were few of the traffic jams for which tehran was notorious before the missiles
the missiles that have been rained on the city since feb. 29, when the iraqis began firing such weapons into tehran for the first time in the war
iraq says it has launched more than 100 surface-to-surface rockets at tehran in that period. others have have hit the holy city of qom, 100 miles to the south, and isfahan in central iran, which was the capital of persia during the 17th century
iran has fired about half as many missiles into baghdad, a city of 5 million
a statement by ayatollah ruhollah khomeini exhorted his people to ignore iraqi missiles and turn out for the april 8 parliamentary elections
even if the nation is subjected to missile and bombing attacks, it will go to the ballot box,'' said the statement, read on the radio by an announcer. ``i personally will participate in the elections under any conditions.''
by thursday, no iraqi missiles had exploded in tehran for three days, although other cities were hit. iraq declared thursday that it was suspending attacks for three days because of a visit to baghdad by turgut ozal, prime minister of turkey
officials in tehran said they believe the reason is the scheduled arrival monday of two u.n. experts, james holger of the united states and dr. manuel carmona of spain, to investigate the alleged iraqi gas attacks in kurdistan. a 1925 geneva agreement outlaws the use of chemical weapons
civilians usually have about four minutes notice of incoming rockets after they are detected by radar installations at the border, about 290 miles to the west
the radio and street loudspeakers blare warnings. people scurry to bomb shelters, basements and underground parking lots. yellow signs on walls show where shelters are located
state television broadcasts film of londoners sheltering in subway stations during the german blitz of 1940. the message seems to be that, like britain and its allies, iran will win the war
but it is poison gas that residents of tehran fear most, according to those questioned randomly on the streets thursday
iran said iraqi warplanes dropped cyanide and mustard gas bombs on three kurdish towns in northeast iraq on march 16-17 after iranian troops have captured them
the iranians, at war with iraq since september 1980, said 5,000 civilians and some iranian soldiers were killed, and another 5,000 people were wounded. they claimed the iraqis dropped chemical bombs because the kurds, long in rebellion against iraq, welcomed their ``liberators.''
iran's official islamic republic news agency also said thursday that iraqi warplanes dropped chemical bombs on villages in the marivan border region of northwest iran earlier in the day, killing several people
after months of international criticism for failing to comply with a cease-fire resolution the u.n. security council passed last summer, iran is making all the mileage possible from the claims of chemical warfare
tehran's official press has likened the alleged iraqi use of gas bombs in kurdistan to the americans dropping atomic bombs on hiroshima and nagasaki in 1945, and demanded international condemnation of iraq. iraq has denied the claims
an iranian gunboat was seized last weekend by oman after an incident at sea during which the boat's skipper was killed in an apparent mutiny, pentagon officials said thursday
the officials, who agreed to discuss the matter only if not identified, said a lone surviving iranian crewman remained in omani custody and that the body of the gunboat's skipper had been recovered
the sources stressed that details of the incident were still sketchy, primarily because the omani government had yet to share much information
but the officials said it appeared the captain was shot and killed by the surviving crewman after tossing a second crewman overboard to his death
a preliminary intelligence report suggests the altercation began when the two crewmen refused the captain's order to mount an attack on a nearby commercial ship, one source added
the officials said it remained unclear whether the iranian survivor had purposely motored toward oman after the incident or simply had become disoriented. in either event, he was intercepted by an omani patrol vessel and taken into custody sometime over the weekend, the sources said
the officials stressed the pentagon was not attaching any particular significance to the mutiny by suggesting, for example, it demonstrated widespread discord within iran's military
we think it's an isolated incident,'' said one source. ``but we think it's an interesting isolated incident.''
as recounted by the sources, the affair occurred aboard a swedish-built boghammer patrol boat. those vessels are about 43 feet long and have been modified by iran to carry machine guns and other weapons, and used extensively for attacks on persian gulf shipping
as best we can piece together, the two crewmen refused an order to mount an attack,'' said one source. ``so the skipper threw one of them overboard. at that point, the second crewman shot the skipper. then he either took the boat to oman or else got lost.''
a canadian military jet having problems with its oxygen system made an emergency landing thursday at charleston's yeager airport after the pilot became dizzy, officials said
the airport director said the single-seat f-a-18 and another traveling with it landed safely at 4 p.m. the pilot, who was not immediately identified, was treated at the scene and was reported to be ok
jeff bubar, the airport manager, said one jet experienced problems with its liquid oxygen supply and the pilot was forced to seek the nearest airport with military facilities
the pilot was having problems with his oxygen system and was feeling lght-headed and having problems breathing and decided to put it down,'' said robert greter of the civil air patrol
greter said the jets carry liquid oxygen that is coverted into gas
he didn't faint. he just felt slightly ill,'' said dr. jerill cavender, who treated the pilot
cavender said the pilot was flying at 33,000 feet when the system apparently had problems converting the liquid into gas
randy clark, air traffic control supervisor for the federal aviation administration, said the planes were en route from florida to canada on a training flight
the west virginia air national guard, which maintains facilities at yeager airport, refused to comment
firefighters late thursday afternoon still were keeping an eye on the slate-gray, 75-foot-long planes parked on a corner of the tarmac
the twin-engine attack jet, known as the hornet, was built by mcdonnell-douglas corp. the planes that landed in charleston appeared to have missiles beneath each wing, but it was not clear whether they were live
the plane is designed primarily for air-to-air combat and for air-to-ground bombings
one plane was decorated with an indian and crossed tomahawks on one of its two tailfins, and the other was decorated with a saber-tooth tiger
prime minister brian mulroney announced a major cabinet shuffle thursday, bringing in an old school friend and changing the key trade and immigration portfolios
this puts us in fighting trim for an election, when it comes,'' the prime minister said
mulroney is expected to call an election this fall or early in 1989, well before the august 1989 end of his progressive conservative party's five-year term. canadian governments traditionally call early elections when their popularity ratings are high
the most important change was the post of minister for international trade
the combative incumbent, pat carney, was transferred to presidency of the treasury board, which had been held by deputy prime minister don mazankowski
transport minister john crosbie, an affable newfoundlander noted for his witty ripostes in the house of commons, took over at trade
he will have the task of winning parliament's approval of the free-trade agreement reached with the united states last year and selling the country on the 10-year deal
at least two of canada's 10 provinces, including powerful ontario, oppose the treaty, which would dismantle tariffs and loosen other barriers in the world's largest trading partnership
once a contender for the conservative leadership, crosbie favored free trade long before mulroney was converted to the concept. referring to his reputation as a somewhat of a renegade, crosbie told reporters: ``i certainly want to be a cannon (but) not a loose one.''
the biggest surprise in the reshaping of the 38-member cabinet was mulroney's decision to bring in an old friend from his student days at laval university, lucien bouchard
bouchard, the canadian ambassador to france since 1985, was named secretary of state and a member of the inner cabinet as mulroney attempted to shore up support in quebec province following a series of scandals involving provincial ministers
bouchard is a former supporter of the separatist parti quebecois and voted in favor of autonomy for the province, dominated by french-speakers, in a 1980 referendum. the referendum was defeated, and bouchard eventually joined the conservative camp
i have to prove it is possible to be both a canadian and a quebecer,'' bouchard said thursday after new cabinet members were sworn in by governor general jeanne sauve in ottawa
a lawyer from chicoutimi, bouchard is not a member of parliament but can serve in the cabinet pending the next by-election for an empty seat from quebec. he replaces david crombie who resigned wednesday to head a commission on the development of the lake ontario waterfront
employment and immigration minister benoit bouchard and his deputy, gerry weiner, were both shifted from a department that has been criticized by the opposition for the influx of illegal aliens into canada, estimated at 2,000 per month. bouchard takes over as transport minister, while weiner becomes minister of state for multiculturalism
the bouchards are not related
the new immigration minister is barbara mcdougall, formerly in charge of privatization. her deputy is monique vezina, who moves from supply and services
foreign minister joe clark and finance minister michael wilson kept their jobs
the latest polls show the conservatives have rebounded this year from their third-place standing over the last two years
thanks to strong economic growth and a drop in unemployment to 7.8 percent _ a seven-year low _ the conservatives are neck-and-neck with the main opposition liberal party and socialist new democratic party
hog farmers continue to expand production, an agriculture department report showed thursday
as of march 1, the inventory of hogs and pigs in the 10 major pork states totaled an estimated 40.5 million head, up 6 percent from both a year ago and two years ago, the report said
the number of breeding hogs was up 4 percent and 10 percent from march 1 of 1987 and 1986, respectively, to 5.42 million head. that indicated further production increases in the months ahead
officials said the march 1 inventory of market hogs _ animals headed for slaughter and the consumer market _ totaled 35.1 million head, up 6 percent and 5 percent from the previous two years
the pig crop during the winter months of december, january and february was 15.8 million head, up 6 percent from the same period of 1986-87, the report said, and 11 percent more than in the winter of two years ago
looking a future prospects, the report said hog farmers surveyed intend to have 2.4 million sows give birth in the march-may period, 2 percent more than a year ago and 11 percent more than the actual farrowings of two years ago
the 10 leading hog states account for about 79 percent of the nation's pork. the following list shows the march 1 inventory. the first number, in thousands, is the total number of hogs in the state, the second is the march 1 figure's percentage of a year earlier
georgia         1,100  102 illinois        5,500  112 indiana         4,000  101 iowa           13,200  107 kansas          1,400  101 minnesota       4,270  107 missouri        2,850  104 nebraska        3,850  101 north carolina  2,400  104 ohio            1,900  101
the sovet union has bought an additional 101,600 metric tons of u.s. corn for delivery this year under a long-term supply agreement between the two countries, the agriculture department said thursday
a metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. the 101,600 tons of corn would be about 4 million bushels
corn prices recently have been averaging about $1.90 per bushel at the farm level, meaning the sale could have a farm value of around $7.6 million
the corn is part of the grain the soviet union is committed to buy during the fifth and final year of the agreement, which calls for the annual purchase of at least 9 million tons of u.s. grain. the pact expires sept. 30
according to the agreement, the annual purchases are supposed to include a minimum of 4 million tons each of wheat and corn. the soviets have the option of buying the remaining 1 million tons as wheat, corn or soybeans, with every ton of beans counting as two tons of grain _ up to a maximum of 1 million tons of grain equivalent
with the latest purchases, the soviets now have bought 4.1 million tons of corn, plus more than 7.48 million tons of wheat; 818,400 tons of soybeans, and 1.3 million tons of soybean meal. discuss case. no pickup. adds byline.</note>
the assemblies of god state council that wanted jimmy swaggart barred from preaching for three months will meet friday and may endorse the harsher penalty demanded by the church's national leaders, a member said thursday
the tv evangelist had cited the louisiana district council's recommendation for a three-month ban when he said through his lawyer wednesday that he would defy the assemblies national leadership's order that he step down for a year
swaggart stepped down from the pulpit feb. 21 after tearfully confessing to an undisclosed sin. a prostitute has said swaggart paid her to pose nude for him
risking dismissal by national church leaders, swaggart plans to return to preaching may 22, three months after he stepped down, said his lawyer, bill treeby
juleen turnage, national assemblies of god spokeswoman at the church's headquarters in springfield, mo., said the louisiana district presbytery would meet in baton rouge on friday to discuss swaggart's case. she said she had no other details and the national office did not plan to send a representative
the rev. ansley orfila of slidell, la., one of 19 members of the louisiana council, said there was little the council could do to challenge the penalty imposed by the national body. he said swaggart probably will leave the denomination
referring to the church's national leaders, orfila told the springfield (mo.) news-leader: ``the executive presbytery may not have the right to discipline him, but they have the power. i don't think we'll meet to defy them. maybe it will be just to decide how to handle things.''
contacted thursday, orfila confirmed what he told the newspaper but declined to comment further
state church officials decided to meet friday after discussing the case in a telephone conference call, the newspaper said. the call was made shortly after the church's national officials announced tuesday that they had rejected the three-month ban as too lenient
the rev. forrest hall, secretary-treasurer of the louisiana district council, said the state church will probably wind up supporting the national recommendation. ``but the men of the district are independent-minded,'' he told the news-leader
gus weill, a spokesman for swaggart, said thursday he was unaware of any meeting by the district council
meanwhile, one of swaggart's fellow ministers said that swaggart claimed evangelist oral roberts had cast demons out of him and that swaggart's feeling of being released from sin might have played a role in his decision to return to the pulpit this spring
but a spokesman for the tulsa, okla.-based evangelist said roberts did not recommend swaggart's immediate return to the pulpit
if anyone is to report that oral roberts is recommending that jimmy swaggart defy the assembly of god ruling from springfield, that is not accurate,'' said roberts' son richard. ``my dad had nothing to do with his decision. we believe that that is a matter that jimmy swaggart must make his own decision and follow the leading of god.''
the rev. mike evans, pastor of the church on the move in euless, texas, said wednesday that while he was visiting baton rouge in february, swaggart told him of roberts' prayer
oral roberts called him up and told him that he saw demons with long fingernails digging the flesh into jimmy swaggart's body and he cast those demons out of his body,'' said evans. ``i think this explains some of the rationale behind jimmy's decision to return to television after three months.''
toni morrison felt ``kind of a redemption'' when she won the pulitzer prize in fiction for her spellbinding and searing song of slavery, ``beloved.''
i thought it was quite possible that the value of the book would not be allowed to be the only consideration that the (pulitzer) committee would have to consider, and that saddened me,'' morrison said thursday
the editor, playwright and author had been the epicenter of a literary earthquake and controversy
after ``beloved'' did not win either the national book award or the national book critics circle award, 48 prominent black writers and critics signed a statement deploring the celebrated writer's lack of recognition
morrison's ``song of solomon'' did win the national book critics circle award for 1977, but the two other awards are considered more prestigious
the statement, published as an open letter in the new york times book review in january, was signed by such literary figures as the writers maya angelou, amiri baraka, john williams and john edgar wideman, the poet june jordan and critic henry louis gates jr
beloved,'' they said, was ``a gift to our community, our country, our conscience.''
the statement said morrison ``has yet to receive the national recognition that her five major works of fiction entirely deserve.''
although morrison said she didn't know a campaign was being mounted on her behalf, when she read the letter, she felt wonderful
it says you're valuable to us. it doesn't say you're flawless; it just says we esteem you. it's kind of obit information _ the kind of thing you never expect.''
however, morrison said she was hurt by charges that she had manipulated other writers
the only manipulations are between the covers of the book,'' she said. ``there was an article some one read to me on the phone about `affirmative- action prizes.' that's depressing
somebody told me that i should simply come out and declare that i did not want the pulitzer,'' she continued. ``so i dismissed all of it very happily from my mind until today. and i had genuine astonishment that the committee made a decision on the merits of the book.''
the fiction committee consisted of julian moynahan, critic and professor of english at rutgers university; critic richard eder, a former pulitzer winner; and the writer alice adams
moynahan said the jurors made their recommendations six weeks before the letter was published and felt no pressure to recommend morrison's book
i think her book is one of the greatest american novels i've ever read in my life,'' he said
the best-selling ``beloved,'' published by knopf, is partly based on a true account of an escaped slaved named margaret garner who decided to kill her child rather than see her returned to bondage. it was a chilling choice faced by many during the horrors of slavery; many africans chose suicide in the atlantic during the crossing on slave ships, and others killed their children or wives before leaving the continent
in language rich and riveting, morrison tells the tale of sethe, who escapes from kentucky and struggles to survive in post-bellum ohio in a house haunted by her dead baby
the 57-year-old morrison, who grew up in lorain, ohio, had heard the garner story and found herself curious and puzzled by the woman herself
in spite of all the political furor about her, the woman was elusive,'' the writer said. ``she was described always as being so serene, so calm. but she said very little. the mystery was not the situation but what goes on inside a woman like that; what was she feeling?''
morrison, a former random house editor whose other works include the novels ``tar baby'' and ``song of solomon,'' and the play ``dreaming emmett,'' said ``beloved'' is the best writing she's ever done. ``ed meese. note grafs 3-4 embargoed for 8 p.m. est</note>
democratic front-runners michael dukakis and jesse jackson sharply attacked the reagan administration on thursday as they pointed toward next week's primary showdown in wisconsin. the white house said president reagan was ready to begin working for george bush, the republican nominee-to-be
democratic hopeful albert gore aimed his fire at his party rivals, saying that dukakis was ``afraid to say a single word about jesse jackson.'' gore said he would continue to criticize jackson, adding he intended to treat him like he would any other combatant in the race

following 2 grafs embargoed for 8 p.m. est

dukakis, criticized for campaigning in an aloof manner, served lunch at a senior citizen center and then served up a stinging up attack on the reagan administration in an evening speech
this administration has walked away from the american dream,'' he said. ``i'm running for president because during the past seven years i've seen too many people thrown out into the streets after decades on the job...and i've talked to too many local leaders who've seen their communities become ghost towns of boarded up hopes and foreclosed dreams.''

end material embargoed for 8 p.m. est

jackson called on embattled attorney general edwin meese to resign. ``it is not a question of guilt or innocence. he simple cannot fulfill the requirements of the job,'' jackson said
ed meese deserves due process. we deserve an attorney general,'' he said, referring to meese's troubled legal situation and recent resignations by high justice department aides
on the republican side, bush and his aides were looking ahead to general election strategy, and gop sources said one serious possibility was for treasury secretary james baker iii to resign and oversee the campaign
baker was bush's campaign manager in his unsuccessful 1980 run
in contrast, democrats were still trying to clear up their muddy nomination picture
gore defended his own criticism of jackson and characterized dukakis as timid on the same score as the democratic field pointed toward wisconsin, next way station on the campaign marathon
suellen albrecht, the state party chairwoman, said either jackson or dukakis figures to win in her state. but gore began running a television commercial attacking chrysler corp. chairman lee iacocca for closing a plant in wisconsin, and sen. paul simon was campaigning in what could be his last stand
dukakis and jackson were in a close race for the lead in national convention delegates, although neither man had even a third of the 2,082 needed to win the nomination
jackson's victory in the michigan caucuses last week elevated him to the front rank of the race, to the dismay of some party officials who fear his race and liberal positions would lead to a massive democratic defeat in the fall if he should be nominated
rep. mickey leland, d-texas, a jackson supporter, told a capitol hill news conference that there is evidence of a ``stop jesse movement'' forming among southern democrats _ and he saw a certain irony in that
i would suggest to you that the people involved in this effort are probably people who did not want to see a mike dukakis or jesse jackson in this race. ... they're now coalescing behind a mike dukakis candidacy,'' he said
there is no question that jackson has been the talk of the race since his stunning michigan landslide last saturday
gore, who picked up the endorsement of the milwaukee sentinel on thursday, has criticized jackson in recent days for lacking experience and for associating in the past with plo leader yasser arafat and cuba's fidel castro
he said he was holding jackson to the same standard as he would any other politician, and added that dukakis ``is afraid to say a single word about jesse jackson.''
jackson spent the day foraging for votes in wisconsin, and he told an audience of high school students that it is not always the elected officials who lead the drive for change
the reality is that this drive for social justice, this drive for equal protection under the law was led by young america. i was part of the generation, of that leadership. i learned to lead by heading a student body as a college student,'' he said
jackson picked up an endorsemnent from richard congdon, an attorney who headed richard gephardt's now-defunct campaign in wisconsin
and he got some kind words from withdrawn candidate gary hart. the one-time front-runner in the race said jackson's campaign has been sending a message to the party's leaders that the voters are dissatisfied with politics as usual
jesse is as much a messenger to the party leaders as a bearer of his own message,'' hart said in an interview with the denver post. the former colorado senator also said he has advised jackson to deliver a series of speeches on the budget deficit, education, military reform and other issues _ and added that he was ``more than prepared'' to help himn write them
among the republicans, white house spokesman marlin fitzwater did not say when reagan would begin campaigning for bush. but he said the situation that once led the president to declare his neutrality in the gop race had changed following sen. bob dole's withdrawal from the campaign
pat robertson is bush's only active challenger, but fitzwater noted that the former television evangelist ``recognizes the realities of the situation.'' with defense comment and reference to april 8 sentencing date; inserts 2 grafs after 13th graf pvs bgng, `whatever his,' with additional defense comment</note>
former presidential aide lyn nofziger should be imprisoned for illegally lobbying the white house because he flouted the law and compared his offense to ``running a stop sign,'' a prosecutor said thursday in court papers
independent counsel james c. mckay said in a sentencing memo that remarks nofziger made following his conviction feb. 11 showed ``a total lack of remorse or contrition'' about violating the ethics in government act's ban on lobbying former colleagues less than a year afte leaving government service
nofziger, 63, should be fined and imprisoned to ``impress present and former government employees, as well as the general public, that congress intended those restrictions to be taken seriously and that they will be enforced with meaningful penalties,'' mckay said in the memo filed with u.s. district judge thomas a. flannery
minutes after the verdict, nofziger stood outside the u.s. courthouse and called the ethics statute ``a lousy law.'' he also said, ``i don't think i did anything wrong'' and compared the offense to ``running a stop sign.''
nofziger, president reagan's former political director, repeated his profession of innocence in a feb. 18 letter to the court that was quoted in the prosecution brief. ``i have never thought, and i do not think today, that i am guilty morally, ethically or legally of the crimes of which i am convicted,'' he wrote
mckay said ``that intransigent attitude is a consideration arguing in favor of a sentence that includes a period of incarceration.''
the sentencing is scheduled for april 8
to request jail time for a 63-year-old man with a spotless record of public service who did not intend to violate the law is ridiculous, unnecessary and totally lacking in compassion,'' said defense lawyer e. lawrence barcella
mckay said nofziger also ignored the advice of lawyers he consulted about the ethics law when he left reagan's staff in early 1982 to form a consulting business with mark a. bragg
the prosecution brief recounted an incident in which nofziger uttered a profanity when one of the attorneys, martin l. artiano, advised him not to make any white house contacts without first contacting the law firm
during the trial, associate independent counsel merrick garland related the episode to the judge during a bench conference out of hearing of the jury and the public, according to the trial transcript
garland told the judge that after responding with the profanity, nofziger said, ``these are my friends and i am going back to them if i want to.''
mckay noted in the sentencing memo that nofziger's defense lawyers have ``attempted to minimize the significance of this episode by asserting that defendant nofziger's profanity ... was characteristic of their client's jocularity.''
perhaps so,'' mckay wrote, ``but his lawyers at the time took the incident seriously. they have told staff members of the independent counsel that this episode caused concern'' within the law firm
whatever his choice of words, however, it is evident that defendant nofziger was alerted to and deliberately chose to ignore written and oral advice that section 207(c) (of the ethics law) applied to him,'' mckay said
lyn doesn't recall ever having such a conversation,'' barcella said. artiano only recalled it after ``a lot of prompting'' during ``repeated interviews with the independent counsel and numerous sessions with the grand jury,'' barcella said
even artiano has said lyn was joking when he said it and thereafter lyn came and asked for their advice about ethics in government act matters,'' barcella said
flannery did not allow the defense to argue during the trial that nofziger acted with advice of legal counsel when he lobbied the white house
nofziger could be sentenced to up to two years in prison and fined up to $10,000 on each of three counts of illegally lobbying the white house on behalf of wedtech corp., a maritime engineers' union and the manufacturer of the air force's a-10 anti-tank plane
mckay did not make a specific recommendation about the length of the prison term but said nofziger should be fined cumulatively for each of the three convictions
nofziger's special entree to the most powerful officials in government, including the president himself, epitomized the very danger to public perception about the integrity of governmental decision-making that motivated congress to enact the one-year no-contact prohibition,'' the prosecutor said. to mrs. reagan</note>
democrat jesse jackson called thursday for the resignation of attorney general edwin meese iii and said, ``it is not a question of guilt or innocence. he simply cannot fulfill the requirements of the job.''
the presidential hopeful, a longtime critic of president reagan's justice department, said he is ``appalled at the state of emergency'' there. he blamed the problems on reagan's tolerance of what he called a low moral tone in the administration
justice is the jugular vien of democracy. with justice, almost everything is possible,'' jackson told at rally of about 2,000 at the sheboygan armory. ``without justice, almost nothing is possible.''
jackson said meese must go because he is being consumed defending himself against allegations of wrongdoing. the candidate called the recent resignations of top justice officials ``a national disgrace'' because, he said, they left ``rather than have their reputations sullied in association with the attorney general.''
to an enthusiastic, mostly white crowd which cheered his attacks on meese, jackson said:
increasingly, the administration of justice is being sacrificed to the defense of the attorney general. ... this is not a question of the shameful prospect of an attorney general who spends more time in court as a defendant than as a prosecutor.''
the attorney general must take the lead in shaping national policies to cut drug traffic and reduce crime, activities that simply take a great deal of time, jackson argued
it is not a question of guilt or innocence. he simply cannot fulfill the requirements of the job. ed meese deserves due process. we deserve an attorney general,'' he said
jackson said meese will probably not resign, so reagan must ask him to leave
today in washington, once again there is a leadership vacuum in this collapsing administration,'' jackson said. ``ed meese does not have the judgment to submit his resignation. the president does not exercise leadership to ask for it. the vice president _ now leader of his party _ does not have the strength to get the president to act,'' jackson said. ``so the nation must depend _ once again _ on mrs. reagan.''
then, taking the line from mrs. reagan's drug campaign, the democrat added: ``when mr. meese asks mr. reagan whether he should stay on, mrs. reagan should advise him, `just say no.'''
jackson would not respond directly to attacks from fellow democratic candidate sen. albert gore jr. on his lack of govermental experience. but the civil rights activist did so by implication
some officeholders are not leaders,'' he said in sheboygan. ``all leaders are not officeholders.''
at pulaski high school in the heart of southside milwaukee, jackson talked to 2,000 students about the nature of leadership
he detailed major civil rights achievements _ the civil rights act, voting rights, open housing _ and then talked about who was responsible
these rich achievments are in some elected officials' resumes, but the reality is that this drive for social justice, this drive for equal protection under the law was led by young america. i was part of the generation, of that leadership,'' he said
southside milwaukee was the site of sometimes violent confrontations during the 1960s as activists marched into all-white neighborhoods to support open housing laws. jackson received a warm welcome from the mostly white crowd
in washington, rep. mickey leland of texas, who said wednesday he believes a ``stop jesse'' movement is afoot, told a news conference that ``while there is evidence that a movement aimed at stopping jesse has been mounted by jackson detractors, we have not yet identified exactly who they are.''
leland speculated that ``the architects of super tuesday are behind this.''
jackson picked up the endorsement of richard congdon, a waukesha lawyer who headed richard gephardt's campaign in the state
jackson is on the air in wisconsin with a $40,000 television buy, said campaign manager gerald austin. details of board changing categories on some awards</note>
the charlotte observer on thursday won the 1988 pulitzer prize for public service for its coverage of the ptl financial scandal that brought down jim and tammy bakker and created turmoil in televangelism
the north carolina paper, the wall street journal and the miami herald each took two of the awards
in its citation for the public service award, one of six pulitzers awarded to knight-ridder papers, the prize board said the observer revealed misuse of funds by the ministry ``through persistent coverage conducted in the face of a massive campaign by ptl to discredit the newspaper.''
the other prize-winning knight-ridder papers are the philadelphia inquirer, the herald, and the st. paul pioneer press dispatch
in the arts, novelist toni morrison _ whose failure to win other writing awards over the past year caused a literary controversy _ received the pulitzer for fiction for her novel ``beloved.'' ``driving miss daisy'' by alfred uhry and ``the making of the atomic bomb'' by richard rhodes won the prizes for drama and general non-fiction, respectively
winners reacted gleefully to the news. ``i'm in a state of slack-jawed dumbfoundedness,'' said tom shales of the washington post, who won the criticism award for his writings on television
tim weiner of the inquirer celebrated his national reporting award _ for a series of reports on a secret pentagon budget used to sponsor defense research and an arms buildup _ by climbing on a desk and lighting up a stogie, while listening to his colleagues' applause
weiner said he felt as if he had just received a ``$10 million check from ed mcmahon. i'm just a very happy guy and very lucky.''
pulitzers for general news reporting went to the alabama journal of montgomery for an investigation of the state's unusually high infant mortality rate, and to the lawrence (mass.) eagle-tribune for stories that showed flaws in the massachusetts prison furlough system
the chicago tribune's dean baquet, william gaines and ann marie lipinski won the pulitzer for investigative reporting for stories on ``the self-interest and waste that plagued chicago's city council.''
daniel hertzberg and james b. stewart of the wall street journal won the pulitzer for explanatory journalism for stories about an investment banker charged with insider trading and about the day after the october stock market crash. the journal's other pulitzer _ for specialized reporting _ went to walt bogdanich for a series on faulty testing by medical laboratories
thomas l. friedman of the new york times won the pulitzer for international reporting for what the pulitzer board termed ``balanced and informed coverage of israel.'' friedman also won a pulitzer for international reporting in 1983
the miami herald's two awards came in commentary and feature photography. dave barry won the former for what the board called ``consistently effective use of humor as a device for presenting fresh insights into serious concerns''; michel ducille won the latter for photographs of the decay and rehabilitation of a housing project with a cocaine problem
other journalism awards included:
_feature writing, to jacqui banaszynski of the st. paul pioneer press dispatch for her series about the life and death of an aids victim in a farm community
_editorial writing, to jane healy of the orlando sentinel for editorials that protested overdevelopment of florida's orange county
_editorial cartooning, to doug marlette of the atlanta constitution and the charlotte observer
_spot news photography, to scott shaw of the odessa (texas) american for his pictures of little jessica mcclure being rescued from the well into which she had fallen
winners are selected by the pulitzer board, which is guided but not limited by a series of finalists submitted by nominating juries in various categories
the alabama journal's investigation of infant mortality was entered in the public service category, where it was a finalist, but the board awarded it the prize for general news
weiner's series on the pentagon budget was entered in explanatory journalism and national reporting. it was chosen a finalist by the explanatory jury, but the board gave it a pulitzer for national reporting
other arts awards included:
_history, ``the launching of modern american science 1846-1876,'' by robert v. bruce
_biography, ``look homeward: a life of thomas wolfe,'' by david herbert donald
_poetry, ``partial accounts: new and selected poems,'' by william meredith
_music, ``12 etudes for piano,'' by william bolcom
except for the award for public service, which brings with it a gold medal, pulitzers carry a cash prize of $3,000. the winners are selected by the pulitzer prize board and announced by the president of columbia university, which administers the competition. attempt</head> appeared ... to correct friday to thursday.</note>
a sophisticated, ultralight aircraft run by human power made six successful test flights thursday preparing for a record distance attempt inspired by the 3,500-year-old greek myth of daedalus
the record attempt was to be made friday, but organizers of the 3-year-old, $1 million project postponed the flight until the weekend because gusts of up to 30 mph are expected friday
the massachusetts institute of technology project is aimed at breaking the world record for human-powered flight over the 74-mile distance from crete to the island of santorini, also known as thira
thursday's test flights each lasted less than three minutes in calm dawn weather above a greek air force base next to iraklion airport
flight director steve k. bussulari, an mit aerospace expert, told reporters the 68-pound daedalus 88 ``is in good shape ... and we may see favorable conditions'' for a flight saturday or sunday
five pilots _ four americans and a greek _ took turns pedaling the pink-and-silver ultralight at speeds of about 14 mph, flying about 15 feet above the tarmac
the craft is named in honor of the mythical inventor daedalus, who tried with his son icarus to escape from crete on wings made of feathers and wax. daedalus succeeded, but icarus flew too near the sun, the wax melted and he fell into the sea
the record flight requires temperatures below 70 degrees and almost dead calm
conditions appeared perfect thursday following nine days of blustery weather
frank scioscia, 27, a professional cyclist from scranton, pa., reported, ``it feels like a day for the record, pretty calm. i was flying the plane with no hands.''
but bussulari noted that daedalus 88 would have run into strong headwinds about five miles off santorini and that in any case, ``we felt we needed a test flight to shake down the airplane.''
the pilots are taking turns standing by in readiness for the flight. the pilot who had been scheduled to fly friday was greg zack, 26, of wilmington, n.c., whose father was born in greece
the pilot pumps bicycle pedals that turn the ultralight's propeller. he uses a joystick to steer the plane, coordinating with ground-based radio instructions
for the record the pilot must keep pedaling a steady 15 mph but the effort is equivalent to riding 23 miles an hour on land,'' said glenn tremml, a medical student from new haven, conn
tremml set the 37.2-mile world record for human-powered flight in california in 1987, flying a daedalus prototype
two backup flying machines are ready if needed
all the craft are made of lightweight composite material _ graphite epoxy, plastic fiber and mylar, an extra-thin plastic skin that covers the 112-foot wingspan
its organizers said the daedalus project has produced new information on endurance and low altitude flying aerodynamics and meteorology during its three years of development
project director john s. langford explained, ``the project does have a research and educational application, particularly in human physiology and aeronautics. the plane itself doesn't have any practical application. it should be seen as a work of art.''
israeli forces left their self-proclaimed ``security zone'' in south lebanon thursday afternoon in pursuit of lebanese communist guerrillas who tried to infiltrate, police reported
they said three guerrillas were wounded in a 30-minute firefight four miles into the foothills of mount hermon, north of the security zone. a guerrilla who escaped told reporters in the syrian-policed town of hasbaya there were at least four israeli casualties
israeli authorities did not comment on the claim and it could not be verified independently
police said the eight-man guerrilla squad was caught trying to infiltrate into the zone, which israel established north of its border in 1985 after withdrawing most of its occupation army from south lebanon
two helicopter gunships strafed olive groves on mount hermon's slopes as about 40 soldiers chased the fleeing guerrillas, police said
militiamen of the israeli-backed south lebanon army left the zone on wednesday to attack shiite moslem guerrillas in the village of kfar roumman, with the aid of israeli gunships
police said seven people, including two shiite guerrillas, were killed and 15 wounded in and around kfar roumman
the white house announced steps thursday to encourage american companies to withhold payments from panama and warned that mandatory action will be considered if the voluntary measures are not sufficient
the action follows the disclosure that some american firms are paying taxes and fees to panama for doing business there, undercutting the economic sanctions imposed by the united states to force the ouster of strongman manuel antonio noriega
announcing the new action, white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said, ``we are giving u.s. companies and persons an incentive and opportunity not to provide financial support to the noriega regime
should these measures prove insufficient, we will review additional legal steps that may be necessary to deny transfer of funds to the noriega regime from u.s. companies and persons,'' fitzwater said
fitzwater said u.s. government payments owed the government of panama will be deposited in the federal reserve bank in new york. the united states already is withholding canal fees, toll payments and other funds. fitzwater said withholding taxes for u.s. employes in panama and rental payments also will go in the new account
he also said the justice department will take part in legal cases by private parties who owe debts to panama, declaring president eric delvalle is the legitimate leader of the country. the u.s. treasury department will help establish an account for payment of funds in these cases
moreover, the internal revenue service will issue guidance explaining how tax credits can be claimed for panamanian income taxes paid into an account at the federal reserve bank in new york, instead of to the noriega government
fitzwater said he did know how much money would be involved by the action, but estimated it could deprive noriega of ``millions and millions.''
on capitol hill, meanwhile, the senate voted 92-1 to approve a resolution urging president reagan to act at once to cut off the flow of dollars from u.s. corporations to the noriega regime
panama has received an infusion of an estimated $19 million in quarterly tax revenues. about $5.5 million of that money reportedly came from taxes and fees paid by u.s. companies doing business in panama
texaco inc. and eastern airlines confirmed they had made payments to the panamanian government and said they were a routine part of their business there
fitzwater said the administration understands the legal concerns of the companies involved. ``i'm not trying to cast any blame or concern upon them. that was the system. they've got their laws. they've got things they've got to comply with and we're trying to help them through changes in irs regulation.''
he played down the amount of money involved, saying it was not significant
asked if it was not a setback for u.s. efforts, fitzwater said, ``it's a minor setback in the sense that one day there's zero (money) and the next day there's something, but these are fairly small payments in the total picture and are not going to solve mr. noriega's very serious and long-term problem.''
he said the administration was studying a plan by which the companies would make tax payments into an account in the united states controlled by president eric delvalle, who has been in hiding since demanding noriega's resignation
the united states continues to recognize delvalle as the legitimate head of panama's government
the senate resolution was introduced by majority leader robert c. byrd of west virginia
the use of these monies (paid by american companies) has enabled gen. noriega to buy himself time and prolong himself in power as he ruthlessly continues in his efforts to thwart the democratic will of the people of panama and crush the general strike,'' byrd said
the resolution urges reagan to use his authority under the emergency economic powers act ``to prevent future transfers to the noriega regime of currency and credit subject to the jurisdiction of the united states.''
it also urges reagan to consider placing such funds into an escrow account until noriega is ousted and democratic rule restored in panama
only sen. mark hatfield, r-ore., voted against the resolution. he did not explain the reasons for his vote
in another legislative move, sen. david durenburger, r-minn., introduced legislation to deny u.s. foreign tax credits to american companies which have made tax payments to noriega's regime
in effect, the u.s. taxpayer is not going to subsidize the illegal noriega government,'' durenburger said
texaco spokesman peter maneri said its payments covered corporate income, sales and excise taxes due for march. he said the company does not see any conflict with u.s. economic sanctions
we continue our operations in panama based on normal commercial considerations,'' maneri said. ``we do not become involved in any political activity in a host nation; we're just doing business down there.''
eastern spokeswoman virginia sanchez said the airline paid about $178,000 in cash for monthly operating fees, including navigational aids, communications, airport rentals and landing fees
there is nothing unusual or out of the ordinary about these payments,'' she said
meanwhile, a group of 13 senators urged the administration to make arrangements to help panama's banking system resume normal operations after noriega's departure
in a letter to treasury secretary james a. baker iii, the senators suggested the treasury use the resources of the exchange stabilization fund to provide the national bank of panama with a line of credit for the panamanian banking system
the senators said the funds should be made available only after the united states government is satisfied that panama acted to eliminate the use of panamanian banks ``by drug traffickers to shield illegal activities.''
the letter was signed by sens. robert w. kasten jr., r-wis.; daniel k. inouye, d-hawaii, edward m. kennedy, d-mass.; alfonse m. d'amato, r-n.y.; patrick j. leahy, d-vt.; dave durenberger, r-minn.; warren b. rudman, r-n.h.; tom harkin, d-iowa; john w. warner, r-va.; pete wilson, r-calif.; christopher j dodd, d-conn.; john f. kerry, d-mass.; and bob graham, d-fla
a bipartisan group of 31 senators urged the administration thursday to suspend all arms sales to saudi arabia until the arab kingdom withdraws the chinese-made missiles deployed in its desert
in a letter to secretary of state george p. shultz, the senators asked the administration to reconsider its planned notification to congress of a $450 million support package for awacs radar surveillance planes. the money is for training and maintenance of the sophisticated intelligence planes which the united states has sold the saudis
in light of recent revelations that saudi arabia is deploying chinese-made intermediate-range ballistic missiles with a range of about 1,850 miles, ``we strongly believe that our current policy toward arms sales to saudi arabia must be re-examined,'' the letter said
in light of the tremendous threat to regional security, the united states should reconsider any new arms sales to the kingdom until this matter is fully resolved and the chinese missiles are withdrawn,'' the senators wrote
they also urged the administration to ``make unequivocable its absolute opposition to the presence of the chinese missiles, which represent a new and grave threat to the peace of the region.''
shultz will be meeting with saudi officials in riyadh next week during a shuttle mission to the mideast which begins sunday. he will be lobbying for israeli-arab peace talks, but is also expected to bring up the chinese missiles
shultz already expressed u.s. concern about the sale of the css-2 rockets to the saudis when he spoke in washington earlier this month with china's foreign minister wu xueqian
the state department has said it views the missiles as part of a disturbing trend of missile proliferation in the gulf region and in the mideast
saudi arbia, an ally of iraq's, says it needed the missiles to protect itself in case of a further escalation in the iran-iraq war, especially in view of iranian threats
but u.s. officials say the saudis bought the missiles in frustration over repeated attempts by congress to block american arms sales
saudi arabia began negotiating the deal with the chinese in 1985, after congress blocked the sale of 48 f-15 jet fighters to saudi arabia. congress late last year agreed to sell the saudis 24 f-15s in order to maintain saudi air strength at its current levels
the css-2 rockets, which u.s. officials say are not yet operational, also have a nuclear capability. but both china and saudi arabia have assured the united states they do not intend to arm the rockets with nuclear warheads
we are also deeply concerned that the saudis hid the fact that they possess these weapons,'' the letter said. saudi arabia reportedly concealed from the united states the deal with china for two years, before u.s. aerial intelligence photos exposed the deal
i am most concerned that our intelligence services were unable to detect the acquisition of these missiles,'' said sen. jesse helms, r-n.c., in a letter to the chairman of the foreign relations committee. helms called on chairman claiborne pell, d-r.i., to hold hearings about the missiles when congress returns from easter recess next month
helms said the committee must discuss, among other things, ``what this (intelligence) failure suggests about our government's ability to detect'' intermediate-range nuclear missiles in the soviet union. helms is strongly opposed to the u.s.-soviet treaty which eliminates such missiles from both countries' arsenals
angola's main rebel movement called thursday for peace talks with the government of president jose eduardo dos santos to end a 13-year bush war
in a statement released in lisbon, the rebel national union for the total independence of angola said it was ``ready now to start talks with the (governing party) without preconditions.''
the note was signed by jonas savimbi, leader of the guerrillas, who receive aid from south africa and the united states. it said the future of angola ``depends on the will of all angolans to free themselves from foreign tutelage.''
the note also said ``peace will come necessarily from direct contact'' between the guerrilla group and the ruling popular movement for the liberation of angola
the guerrillas have fought the government since losing a civil war to the popular movement following angola's independence from portugal in 1975. the insurgents have demanded a power-sharing accord
angolan government officials estimate more than 9,000 south african troops are in southern angola aiding the guerrillas. soviet advisers and approximately 40,000 cuban troops aid the government forces
the note said the guerrilla group ``categorically rejects all fictitious interpretation of reconciliation in angola by way of amnesty, clemency or any so-called program of harmony.''
the point was an apparent reference to reports wednesday that the government was willing to offer amnesty to the guerrillas if south africa and the united states halt all support for the insurgents
the guerrilla proposal comes on the heels of discussions among the united states, angola, south africa and cuba on an end to foreign aid to both sides. with yakunin comments. picks up 10th graf pvs, filaret said ...</note>
church leaders said thursday they are working with the authorities to ease restrictions on religion in a society dominated by atheists, but may fail unless clerical dissidents stop causing trouble
metropolitan filaret of kiev and galitsky said the rev. gleb yakunin, a former political prisoner, and the rev. nikolai gainov were two of those in the russian orthodox church who seek ``to press on us methods of solving our problems that would lead to confrontation between church and state.''
he described the dissidents as a small group of priests and lay people
the church always has cooperated with the government, which is dominated by the officially atheist communist party, but its leaders say they want to moderate a 1929 law that requires registration of religious groups and prevents charitable activities and religious education of the young
although they did not directly attack the law during a news conference, their veiled criticisms appeared to be among the strongest in years
filaret stressed, however, that the church ``will continue to use the same method of solving problems it has used in the whole post-revolutionary period.''
last week, yakunin called for the resignation of patriarch pimen, 78, as head of the russian orthodox church on grounds he is ill and senile
the priest also has criticized the willingness of church leaders to subordinate themselves to the government, demanding greater freedom to practice religion and publication of more religious books
yakunin was excluded from the ministry for 20 years, but reinstated last year and assigned to a small parish outside moscow
contacted by telephone thursday night, yakunin said filaret's comments were moderate
earlier they (church leaders) would have taken our work away and imprisoned us. it's a sign of perestroika that they are willing to listen to us,'' yakunin said, referring to soviet leader mikhail gorbachev's word for restructuring of society
yakunin said he and gainov are not seeking confrontation between church and state but simply want to ``help the church improve its situation.''
we think church leaders are falling behind matters of perestroika and want them to work more actively,'' he said
filaret said the church has the right to discipline dissidents, but ``we are urging them to use common sense and join with us to solve the problems.''
archbishop kiril of smolensk said the government is rewriting the 1929 law and consulting russian orthodox officials, but described the consultations as a ``discussion of principle'' not involving the text
kiril said the law, adopted at the height of anti-religious fervor after the 1917 bolshevik revolution, was no longer appropriate for soviet society
he said the replacement statute should be ready soon, but the text was not complete and he could not provide details. the archbishop said church officials were optimistic that it ``will open the possibility for a fuller church life for all believers.''
a list was revealed of nine people who will be made saints during celebrations in june of the 1,000th anniversary of christianity in what is now the soviet union
metropolitan yuvenali of krutitsky and kolomensky granted that the list did not include anyone killed during the repression after the revolution, as critics have demanded. he said study of the issue would continue
yuvenali accused the russian orthodox church that split away after the revolution and now is based abroad of canonizing such people for political purposes
