a u.s. air force jet fighter slammed into the middle of this small town and exploded thursday, killing the american pilot and at least one resident, injuring 16 people and forcing scores to evacuate
the neighborhood looks like the bombed-out houses of world war ii,'' said herbert loef, a 52-year-old baker who lives down the street from where the f-16 crashed into at least five homes
in washington, air force spokesman capt. virginia cody identified the pilot as lt. thomas edward doyle, 24, of oroville, calif. he entered active duty in may 1985 and had been at hahn air base since september 1987. he graduated from the air force academy in 1985
wreckage was scattered over a wide area, and several hours after the flames had been doused, black smoke still billowed from forst, a town of 6,000 people
emergency crews evacuated more than 70 residents because the plane was carrying a canister of hydrazine, which is used to restart engines and which produces toxic gas when mixed with water. officials said there was no evidence of a gas leak
the plane crashed eight miles from a nuclear power plant, one day after a french jet fighter crashed and exploded just a mile from a nuclear plant in the west german state of bavaria. the pilot in that accident also was killed
the crashes sparked calls from members of west germany's opposition social democrats and the environmentalist greens party for more restrictions on military training flights
witnesses reported seeing smoke and flames pouring from the f-16 as it plunged toward forst, about 60 miles south of frankfurt. it struck the roof of one house, tore off the front of another and set several on fire, they said
hilde loef said her first thought when she saw the jet was, ``my god, the planes are coming awfully low today.''
then i saw smoke and flames streaming out of the jet,'' she said
the body of theo huber, 60, was found in the wreckage of his home, officials said. rescuers were searching for any other victims
twelve firefighters were hospitalized for smoke inhalation, two residents were treated for shock, and two more were being held for observation in a hospital after apparently suffering smoke inhalation, officials said
authorities said the 10 a.m. disaster could have been far worse had the plane crashed a couple of hours earlier, before residents left for work
u.s. air force maj. gregory smith told reporters at the scene that an investigation into the cause of the crash was under way. he said there was no live ammunition on the jet
the f-16 was part of the 50th tactical fighter wing based at the hahn air base in the nearby eifel mountains, said lt. col. edward neunherz, another air force spokesman
the crash occurred 185 miles west of wednesday's crash of the french jet fighter, which went down in the bavarian village of ohu near the isar nuclear plant
environmentalists maintained the country had escaped disaster by a ``split second,'' and the accident raised concerns about military flights over nuclear power plants. but officials said the concrete domes built over west german nuclear plants are designed to withstand the force of a plane crash, so there was no danger of a nuclear accident. mecham</head> charge. no pickup.</note>
after hours of backroom negotiations thursday, the arizona senate let stand its dismissal of the third and strongest impeachment charge against gov. evan mecham
the decision not to reinstate the charge cleared the way for final arguments monday on two other counts against the first-term republican. senators could vote monday or tuesday on whether he should be removed from office
is there any other matter to be taken up?'' asked arizona chief justice frank x. gordon as the senators convened in the late afternoon after a day of caucuses and private meetings. gordon's question was answered with silence
gordon then wished the senate luck in reading and understanding a thick stack of legal instructions given to them as they left for the weekend
mecham 63, is the first u.s. governor in six decades to face an impeachment trial
on wednesday, the senate decided 16-12 to dismiss a charge that he concealed a $350,000 campaign loan and to vote to convict or acquit on two other charges _ that he tried to obstruct an investigation of an alleged death threat by a staff member and that he misused $80,000 from a protocol fund
the campaign loan charge was considered the strongest of the three because there is more extensive documentation of what occurred and because it is the only one that also has led to a criminal indictment against mecham
in contrast, the obstruction charge boils down in part to which of two people to believe, and the other in part to technical definitions of whether the $80,000 was public or private money
several senators, in voting for dismissal, had said they feared they would prejudice mecham's criminal trial april 21 if they took evidence on the last charge
alan stephens, democratic minority leader, said thursday neither he nor the 10 other democrats who voted for dismissal were willing to reconsider
one of those who voted on the prevailing side would have had to seek reconsideration for the matter to be reopened
there was a lot of backroom manipulating today,'' said stephens. ``people apparently made their decisions on the merits of the arguments and that didn't change in 24 hours.''
only five of the 19 senate republicans supported the dismissal of the last charge. senate rules gave members 24 hours to rescind any action
stephens said his main concern was not letting the trial drag on past mecham's scheduled may 17 recall election. but some republicans argued that they were duty-bound to hear all the evidence on all the charges
republican tony west complained angrily that the democrats had divided the impeachment proceeding along partisan lines for the first time since it began feb. 29. ``that action yesterday was political roulette,'' he said
if there are not the votes to convict, and gov. mecham is back on the ninth floor (in the governor's office) on wednesday ... they have dealt themselves a losing hand,'' west said
it would require a two-thirds vote of the 30-member senate to convict mecham. if he is convict, the senate may then take a vote to disqualify him from ever holding office again
march went out like a lion in much of colorado on thursday, unloading more than 3 feet of snow, but the weather was more like the proverbial lamb in much of the east and south
in south-central colorado, 42 inches of snow were reported near rye by afternoon. near fort collins in the northern part of the state, buckhorn mountain logged 34 inches before noon, while bellevue recorded 27 inches
as the slow-moving storm continued to dump snow on the region, the weather service issued a winter storm warning for blowing and drifting snow and poor driving conditions as slush on roadways turned to ice at nightfall
at denver's stapleton international airport, crowded with holiday weekend travelers, spokesman norm avery warned that delays of two hours or more could be expected. snowfall at midafternoon at the airport was 8 inches
a winter storm watch was posted for northwestern kansas, where rain was expected to change to snow overnight and heavy snow was possible friday
advisories for snow and blowing snow were posted for southeastern wyoming and the southern nebraska panhandle. by midday, the snowy range ski area near laramie, wyo., reported 22 inches of snow
during the morning, high winds were reported in utah, where gusts reached 80 mph at centerville
elsewhere, a wind advisory continued in the mountains and deserts of southern california and in northwestern arizona. a freeze warning was posted for thursday night for higher elevations in southeastern arizona
skies were sunny in new england, and in much of the nation west of the rockies, while temperatures reached the 70s and occasionally the 80s from texas to the southern atlantic coast and in southern california
early afternoon readings were in the 30s and 40s in the upper mississippi valley, though, and were below freezing in the northern rockies
rain extended from the southern half of the great plains to the lower ohio valley, with thunderstorms mainly along the central gulf coast
temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. est ranged from 16 degrees at yellowstone park, wyo., to 84 degrees at avon park, fla., and fort myers, fla. the early-morning low for the nation was 8 degrees below zero at yellowstone park
heavier snowfall for the six-hour period ending at 1 p.m. est included 4 inches at denver and 3 inches at pueblo, colo. heavier rainfall included 0.68 inch at new orleans; 0.46 inch at memphis, tenn., and 0.45 inch at jonesboro, ark
the forecast for friday called for snow in the central high plains and the central rockies; showers and thunderstorms in the southern plains, the lower mississippi valley and the tennessee valley; rain showers from the central plains across the lower great lakes, ohio valley and mid-atlantic states, and fair to partly sunny skies will prevail across the rest of the nation
highs only in the 30s and 40s were forecast from northern new mexico and arizona to nebraska, and in the upper mississippi valley and the upper great lakes; in the 60s and 70s in much of oregon and western nevada, and across much of the southern tier of states and the mid-atlantic coast; up to the low 80s in california, the lower rio grande valley and florida, and in the 50s in most of the rest of the nation. engineer and that crash was amtrak's worst. pick up 3rd graf pvs, `the indictment ...'; adds two grafs at end with prosecutor's comment. adds byline.</note>
a former conrail engineer sent to prison on state charges in an amtrak crash that killed 16 people was indicted thursday on federal charges including lying to investigators about his drug use the day of the accident
rick l. gates, 33, of essex, was charged with conspiracy, obstruction of an agency investigation and making false statements, said u.s. attorney breckinridge willcox
the collision of the passenger train and three locomotives operated by gates was the worst accident in amtrak history
the indictment alleges gates lied under oath to national transportation safety board investigators after the jan. 4, 1987, crash near chase, saying he had not consumed any drugs that day
gates, however, shared a marijuana cigarette with brakeman edward cromwell that day, according to the statement of facts read into the record when he pleaded guilty in baltimore county circuit court on feb. 17
the indictment also alleges gates falsely testified about the status of the signals he saw in the three conrail locomotives and along the tracks that day and about what pre-departure tests he conducted
the conspiracy count alleges he joined with cromwell to develop a false story about what happened
gates was the only person named in the indictment. if convicted, gates faces a maximum of five years in prison and a $250,000 fine on each count
on tuesday, gates was sentenced to five years in prison and fined $1,000 on a misdemeanor charge of manslaughter by locomotive
sixteen people were killed and more than 170 others were injured in the crash. gates originally was charged with 16 counts, but gates agreed to a plea bargain, merging the names of all 16 victims into a single count
willcox said he had deferred any federal action against gates until the state prosecution had ended
now that those charges have been resolved, it is appropriate to vindicate the strong federal interest in ensuring that the national transportation safety board hearings are not obstructed by those with the most direct and relevant information,'' the prosecutor said
supporters of slain judicial candidate julian pierce asked gov. jim martin on thursday to convene a special legislative session to allow another minority candidate to seek the post
martin was noncommittal after the closed meeting in his office. he said he would consult with pierce's former opponent, party and legislative leaders and others, and expected to reach a decision next week
pierce, 42, a lumbee indian attorney, was shot to death saturday at his rural home in racially troubled robeson county, where he was running for a newly created superior court judgeship
at first, authorities said the killing looked like a political assassination. but tuesday they arrested a young indian man and said a second suspect committed suicide, and attributed pierce's killing to a romantic dispute
pierce and robeson county district attorney joe freeman britt, who is white, were slated to meet in the may 3 democratic primary
under law, if a candidate dies more than 30 days after filing for a primary has closed, his opponent wins the nomination. in this case, there is no republican in the race, so britt would also automatically win the general election in november
supporters of pierce asked for a special session to amend the law to let another candidate enter the race
the governor, who planned to meet with britt on friday, told reporters: ``i'm going to do my best to try to get input that i need and then take a brief time to think about it very prayfully and come up with the best answer that i can.''
the new superior court judgeship was created under a law intended to help a non-white candidate get elected in a county where blacks and indians make up 58 percent of the registered voters
two months ago, the robesonian newspaper office was seized for several hours by two lumbees who said they wanted to call attention to racial injustice and official corruption
harvey godwin, who was manager of pierce's campaign, said that was pleased with the discussion with the governor and that martin ``listened to every word. ... i was impressed with him.''
pierce supporters have decided on a replacement candidate, godwin said, but he declined to identify the person
britt has not commented on the special session question
earlier, martin said there was no reason to doubt that pierce's slaying resulted from a romantic dispute. he chided those who continue to suggest otherwise, saying some want to stir up more racial strife in robeson county
there are people who want to take advantage of the problems ... and they're going to make up all kinds of theories,'' martin said
sheriff hubert stone said john goins, 24, killed pierce and later took his own life. goins blamed pierce for disrupting goins' relationship with the daughter of a woman pierce was dating, according to stone
the other suspect, sandy gordon chavis, is described as a longtime friend of goins
martin said that goins had left suicide notes and that there was solid evidence linking him to the slaying
vernon bellecourt, a representative of the american indian movement, said wednesday that goins' personal feelings ``could have been manipulated by those that would have motives to see that julian pierce was out of the way.'' 7th graf pvs, `the jimmy ...'</note>
a bikini contest planned for thursday night by a university of massachusetts fraternity to raise money for charity was canceled hours before it was to begin after women students threatened to picket
joe giarusso, assistant general manager of the off-campus pink cadillac bar where the contest was to have been held, said the makers of miller lite beer withdrew as sponsors
there are no prizes and the event has been canceled,'' he said. he refused further comment
women had earlier vowed to picket the bar, and 34 students had signed a petition denouncing the contest organized by delta upsilon as sanctioning ``ogling and girl watching.''
robert o'brien, chairman of the fund-raising committee of delta upsilon, said the contest was canceled ``because of a small, vocal minority. we did not back down. it is our legal right to have the contest.''
sue madden, a umass graduate student and an organizer of the protest, was making placards for the demonstration when she learned the contest was off
we're all stunned,'' she said. ``we're pleased that miller lite was sensitive to this issue to help us achieve our cause.''
often women are reduced to their body parts in this society and we don't think men have a right to judge us for our bodies,'' protester becky lockwood said earlier. ``this is objectifying women to make money off us.''
delta upsilon fraternity brothers said they didn't understand the furor
it's ridiculous,'' said fraternity president paul kearney. ``why should they be upset if it's a fund-raiser? they do it everywhere else.'' he added: ``if they go to the beach, are they going to call that sexist too?''
o'brien had said proceeds of the contest would be used by the fraternity, which has $10 in its account, for its yearly beer keg roll, a charity event that benefits the jimmy fund
the jimmy fund, the official charity of the boston red sox, raises money to fight cancer in children. last year delta upsilon raised $3,000 for the jimmy fund rolling empty beer kegs from boston 100 miles west to amherst
the fraternity circulated fliers last week saying the bikini contest was being presented by ``delta upsilon &amp; the jimmy fund in association with the amherst police'' department, but the event is not sponsored by the jimmy fund
jimmy fund associate director michael rafferty said he asked the fraternity not to use its name for the event
police chief donald maia, who had accepted an invitation to emcee the contest, changed his mind over the weekend, saying he had thought the contest was a beauty pageant
it's gone beyond that now,'' he said. ``it would be inappropriate for me to be there.''
roger libby, a former umass sex education professor who tours campuses lecturing on safe sex, said he would replace maia as emcee
jimmy fund planning director mark cummings said the organization approves only those activities that turn over entire proceeds to the fund. he added, ``it is in bad form and bad taste to use the jimmy fund with this contest.'' with comment from knight-ridder, cartoonist doug marlette, miami herald; picking up 9th graf pvs, `at the...'. inserts 3 grafs after 15th graf pvs, `i think...', to add comment from wall street journal winners. picks up 16th graf, `scott shaw...'.</note>
tim weiner blushed happily and climbed on top of a desk thursday as his colleagues at the philadelphia inquirer applauded after he captured the pulitzer prize for national reporting
but tom shales of the washington post was in shock
i'm in a state of slack-jawed dumbfoundedness,'' said shales, the winner for criticism for his writing on television. ``i'm shocked and delighted and very proud of the paper. it's an award that really comes to the paper _ not to me; it's a nice feeling to have brought it to the paper.''
reporters at the inquirer, which claimed its 14th prize in 13 years, crowded around the newsroom and applauded when word of weiner's prize moved on the associated press wire
the recipient, who won for his series on a secret pentagon budget used to sponsor defense research and an arms buildup, climbed onto a desk to say, ``i thank you very much.'' he then puffed on a cigar
weiner, 31, who came to the inquirer in 1982 from the kansas city times, said he feels like he just received a ``$10 million check from ed mcmahon. i'm just a very happy guy and very lucky.''
toni morrison, winner of the fiction award for ``beloved,'' said joy was uppermost in her feelings because ``i really was thinking dark and difficult thoughts about what was available to this book in terms of recognition.''
the book became a center of controversy when it did not win two other major literary prizes, and morrison said she respected the pulitzer committee for ignoring ``outside matters of speculation and gossip and some slander.''
knight-ridder newspapers won six awards, including two each at the miami herald and the charlotte (n.c.) observer and one each at the st. paul pioneer press dispatch and the inquirer
jim batten, knight-ridder president, said the group has ``worked hard over the years to attract some of the best people in the american newspaper business and create a climate that encourages people to do their best work.''
dave barry, the 40-year-old miami herald humorist who won for commentary, said he hopes winning the pulitzer ``will make me taller.''
it's fun to win a pulitzer; everybody should do it,'' barry said
his fellow miami staff member, photographer michel ducille, garnered his second pulitzer for photos of apartments inundated by the drug crack
i don't want to lessen the pulitzers, but i feel more proud that the photos ... made changes in the community,'' ducille said
cartoonist doug marlette, 37, who moved from the charlotte observer to the atlanta constitution during the year, was honored for work done at both papers
he said his biting approach can be traced in part to ``a grandmother bayoneted by a guardsman during a mill strike in the carolinas. there are some rebellious genes floating around in me.''
at the alabama journal in montgomery, ``there was a lot of dancing and yelling and singing when the announcement came over the wire _ but that's not unusual for the journal newsroom,'' quipped jim tharpe, managing editor
the journal and the lawrence (mass.) eagle-tribune each won an award for general news reporting; the alabama paper's series dealt with infant mortality
the journal decided it was time to commit some resources to the problem,'' said bill brown, executive editor of the journal and its sister daily, the montgomery advertiser
a pulitzer prize is nice,'' said tharpe, ``but it's a plaque on the wall. if we hope something will come of our work as journalists, it's that the state will deal with the problem of infant mortality.''
at the chicago tribune, the winners were dean baquet, william gaines and ann marie lipinski for investigative reporting on ``on the self-interest and waste that plague chicago's city council.''
we're thrilled. it's been quite a few years since we've won one here for local news coverage,'' said ellen soeteber, assistant tribune managing editor for metropolitan news
i think the team of reporters deserved this so much. ... it was their idea, and they brought it off beautifully,'' she said. ``i'm so glad some of the leaders in our profession recognized it.''
the wall street journal captured two prizes: walt bogdanich for specialized reporting and daniel hertzberg and james b. stewart for explanatory journalism
i know many great people who have only been recognized after they died, but all else being equal, it's wonderful to get recognition,'' said stewart, 36
if i can win the pulitzer prize, the cleveland indians can win the pennant this summer,'' said bogdanich
scott shaw, a photographer for the odessa (texas) american, said he had not been expecting to win the spot news award for his coverage of the 58-hour operation that rescued little jessica mcclure and fascinated a nation
i am pretty young. i am just pretty surprised,'' said shaw, 24. ``ever since i took the photo that night, the editors said i was going to win. they were sure of it that night. and so it happened.'' reason to invade, ordering military not to invade, white house action; no pickup.</note>
the government accused the united states on thursday of looking for a pretext to invade panama, and said it ordered its military not to harm americans in the country
government offices closed thursday for a long easter weekend that looks bleak for 130,000 public employees, who were left without paychecks for the second time this month
an eerie quiet gripped the streets of panama city, which had been filled in recent days with demonstrations against gen. manuel antonio noriega, the defense forces commander who controls the civilian government
manuel solis palma, the president installed by noriega, said in a letter to u.n. secretary-general javier perez de cuellar that u.s. armed forces in panama and its waters constituted a threat to the country
in spite of the situation created by the mobilization of u.s. forces ... the defense forces of panama have orders to refrain from using lethal or destructive weapons at any time against the armed forces of the united states or against u.s. civilians,'' said the letter, released by the presidency
the ``mobilization'' of forces apparently referred to the passage this week of the u.s. helicopter carrier okinawa through the panama canal, and u.s. military maneuvers in panama that began in early march
aware of the overwhelming power threatening it, the republic of panama ... will not provide the foundation for fabrication of a charge of aggression that could pretend to justify the launching of acts of war against panama,'' the letter said
the reagan administration has raised the possibility that the u.s. military might be used to protect the estimated 50,000 american citizens in panama against possible harrassment by that country's security forces
it made the suggestion after panamanian soldiers arrested and beat several journalists, including american reporters, during a raid monday on a panama city hotel
with most businesses and industries observing an 11-day-old general strike against noriega thursday, the largest congregations of people in panama city were found in the food lines of welfare agencies
leaders of the national civic crusade were meeting to plan new strategies in their frustrated effort to oust noriega
we'll be talking over the weekend, discussing where we go from here,'' said roberto aleman, a director of the crusade, a coalition of about 200 professional, business, labor, political and other groups
in caracas, former president carlos andres perez of venezuela said he understood noriega had promised to resign in may, the unofficial start of a presidential campaign leading to elections in may 1989. the general is under indictment in the united states on drug trafficking charges
major supermarkets and drug stores, and a few small shops, were open thursday in panama city but most merchants observed the strike. the groceries and pharmacies reopened wednesday _ under heavy government pressure, according to reports
the government closed its doors without meeting another $33 million payday for most ot its 130,000 employees despite the collection this week of $19 million in quarterly tax revenues
about $5.5 million was said to be taxes and fees from u.s. companies doing business in panama, including texaco, eastern airlines and a banana-growing subsidiary of united brands
in washington, the white house announced tax incentives and other measures thursday to encourage american companies to withhold payments from panama. the reagan administration said mandatory action would be considered if the voluntary measures are not sufficient
most panamanians were short of cash and food as a result of the strike and the cash crisis, which was caused in part by a u.s. freeze on panamanian assets in american banks
the sanctions were imposed in february after noriega supporters in the national assembly voted to oust panama's civilian president, eric arturo delvalle, in retaliation for delvalle's attempt to fire noriega
banks have been closed since march 3
at a news conference in caracas, perez said noriega had promised monsignor marcos antonio mcgrath, the catholic archbishop of panama, that he would step aside upon completion of his term of service in may
but by law, military officers in panama are supposed to resign after 25 years of active service, and noriega's official biography shows that he entered the service in 1962, or 26 years ago
perez and the leaders of costa rica and spain asked mcgrath to serve as a mediator between noriega and his opponents. update with senate refusing to reinstate third charge.</note>
the arizona senate on thursday appeared to be just days away from the moment of truth in gov. evan mecham's impeachment trial after dismissing the third and most serious charge against him
senators declined to predict the outcome of next week's vote on the two remaining charges. a two-thirds majority of the 30-member senate would be needed to remove the first-term republican from office
i'm prepared to vote,'' republican sen. carol macdonald said one day after testimony was completed on the second impeachment count. like other senators, she declined to say what she had decided
many senators said they will wait until monday's closing arguments by prosecution and defense lawyers before deciding whether to remove mecham from office
the vote is likely to be taken monday or tuesday on impeachment charges that mecham tried to thwart an investigation of an alleged death threat by a state official and that he misused $80,000 from the governor's protocol fund by loaning it to his auto dealership
but before the vote could be taken, senators had to resolve a last-minute political imbroglio thursday over the dismissal of the third charge, that mecham concealed a $350,000 campaign loan
wednesday's surprise vote to dismiss that article and vote on the first two led to charges and counter-charges by republicans and democrats that each side was playing politics
after a day of backroom negotiations thursday, the senate decided against reinstating the third charge. wednesday's action was approved by all 11 democrats but only five of the senate's 19 republicans
attorneys had indicated wednesday it would take at least five weeks to present the case on the third charge
republican sen. greg lunn, who opposed throwing out the article, said the dismissal was a ``serious error'' and added, ``frankly, i'm resentful, at this late stage in these proceedings, that we're cutting deals as if this were an amendment to another piece of legislation in order to get us out before adjournment.''
senate republican majority leader robert usdane was more philosophical, saying, ``it's a political trial. it's just a matter of the way we work.''
mecham wanted the $350,000 loan count dismissed on grounds that having it tried first in the senate would taint his april 21 criminal trial on similar charges
the 16-12 vote to grant the governor's wish resulted from a combination of mecham's five staunchest gop backers _ who want all the charges dismissed _ and all 11 democrats, who have been trying for weeks to force the senate to vote on each impeachment article as evidence is completed
the democrats contended their strategy was aimed at ensuring a senate vote on whether to remove mecham from office well before he is to face a may 17 recall election
minority leader alan stephens, a democrat, said republicans possibly ``saw the potential for some to take advantage of this ... and create a situation where they would never, never have to cast a vote on this'' because mecham could be removed from office by the recall before the senate got a chance to vote
because the senate can make its own rules, lawmakers will not have to reach their conclusions ``beyond a reasonable doubt,'' as in a criminal trial. instead, they are to decide if there is ``clear and convincing evidence'' to convict mecham, and it's up to each of them to decide what that means
also, gop sen. bill delong noted, the governor does not have to be guilty of a crime to be convicted in an impeachment trial; mecham can be removed for malfeasance in office
there's more than just the guilt or innocence on the charges,'' delong said, adding that he expected senators to be told by the presiding officer that they must ``take action which is in the best interest of arizona ... based on (mecham's) ability to continue in office.''
