leaders of the palestinian rebellion called thursday for riots during the visit of secretary of state george p. shultz next week, and israel's prime minister vowed to crush the uprising
soldiers shot one palestinian dead, bringing the arab death toll to at least 124 since violence began dec. 8 in the occupied west bank and gaza strip, where 1.5 million palestinians live. an israeli soldier also has been killed
israeli officials lifted a three-day closure of the west bank as scheduled at 3 a.m. friday (8 p.m. est thursday), allowing residents to travel out of their towns and villages. a curfew that confined people in the gaza strip to their homes was also ended at that time
five-hour nightly curfews imposed before the shutdown were scheduled to continue in gaza. the end of the three-day confinement meant that journalists could travel freely in the territories
issuance of leaflet no. 12 from leaders of the rebellion indicated israel had not removed its leadership despite mass arrests last week of more than 1,000 people, including those israel said were responsible for publishing the leaflets
arabs known to be involved have said that, if the israelis caught some of them, other people would be ready to take their places
prime minister yitzhak shamir told hundreds of cheering jewish settlers israel would crush the rebellion in the lands it has controlled since capturing them from jordan and egypt in the 1967 middle east war
some arabs are going crazy down there. they are trying to harm what we have built,'' shamir said at herodion, site of the biblical king herod's palace
they say ... this land belongs to the rioters, the killers, the terrorists. but if somebody tries to harm this ... we will break his hand on these rocks.''
authorities put new restrictions on the 130,000 arabs of east jerusalem but greek orthodox christians, fearing for their safety, decided nonetheless to cancel pre-easter processions
soldiers allowed the 650,000 palestinians in the gaza strip to leave their homes for the first time in three days when the army lifted a curfew for five hours
street clashes between young arabs and soldiers soon began in khan yunis, rafah and the jabaliya refugee camp, and the army restored the curfew at jabaliya, israel radio said
one palestinian was wounded in rafah, the radio said. shifa hospital officials said another arab from khan yunis was shot in the neck and israel television said a palestinian was wounded in the west bank city of tulkarm
in the west bank city of yatta, soldiers shot an 18-year-old palestinian dead during several hours of clashes with protesters hurling rocks and bottles, the army said
mayor ismael abu hemaid said suleiman ahmed al jundi died of a stomach wound
the latest leaflet, signed by the palestine liberation organization, urged ``all the arab world to block shultz' plan and to stop him from killing the uprising.''
it ordered riots monday through wednesday of next week to protest the shultz visit and a proposed u.s. peace plan. the secretary of state is to begin a shuttle through the region sunday
we are telling the arab world, we don't need money. we are ready to starve. we will never kneel. we are going to die as martyrs,'' the leaflet said
shamir's equally tough declaration at herodion: ``we will continue to act against the violence until we stamp it out.''
military jeeps escorted shamir's car and a busload of journalists through an army roadblock sealing off the west bank. reporters saw six palestinian flags, which are outlawed, hanging from power lines
patriarch diodorus of jerusalem canceled three pre-easter processions of the greek orthodox church because of the violence, said the rev. thimoteus margaritis, church spokesman
he said it was the first cancellation since the 1967 war. margaritis said only 1,500 pilgrims were expected for the orthodox easter on april 10, compared with 10,000 last year
tourism to israel declined 13 percent in the first week of march compared with the same period of 1987, a tourism ministry spokeswoman said
benjamin netanyahu announced his resignation as israel's u.n. ambassador to protest a meeting between shultz and two arab-americans linked to the plo
it was the strongest indication yet of israeli displeasure over the meeting last saturday with the members of the palestine national council, which acts as the plo legislature
in remarks broadcast on israel radio, shultz said it was ``beyond the pale'' to suggest he could not meet with american citizens
the interior ministry imposed new travel restrictions on arabs in east jerusalem, requiring palestinians aged 16-35 to have special permits for trips to jordan, ministry spokeswoman tova elinson said. she said permits would be issued only for stays of nine months or longer
israel radio said the limitations were designed to stop the plo from sending couriers into the occupied territories. picks up 9th graf pvs bgng, `meanwhile, a bipartisan'</note>
despite an uncertain outlook, secretary of state george p. shultz was set thursday to try again to persuade arabs and israelis to open negotiations may 1
shultz made no prediction on how much progress the u.s. peace plan would make in the middle east during his shuttle diplomacy there next week, but he was cautiously upbeat, particularly about king hussein of jordan
the jordanians are quite intrigued with this,'' shultz said, ``and i look forward to intensive discussions with the king.''
he described the israelis, meanwhile, as having ``varying views.'' clearly referring to prime minister yitzhak shamir, shultz said he would point out that the peace conference he is proposing is not the active authority that is causing objections in jerusalem
it simply would set up direct negotiations between the arabs and israelis, shultz said
israel, jordan and syria all have neither accepted nor rejected shultz's proposal
when they are reluctant to say no, it means everybody understands the importance of trying to find a way to peace and security,'' he told reporters aboard his u.s. air force jet
after refueling here, shultz headed for rome for easter observances and meetings with italian officials. he is shopping for a new home for 72 u.s. f-16 jet fighters that spain will expel from the torrejon air base near madrid in 1991
italy is a prime candidate, along with portugal and turkey
then shultz flies to israel on sunday to begin a five-day mideast venture that also will take him to jordan, syria, egypt and saudi arabia. it will be shultz's second intensive tour of the middle east in a month
during his trip, shultz also hoped to make headway on lebanon in discussions with syrian president hafez assad
the state department's director of lebanon, jordan and syrian affairs, april glaspie, already is in damascus where shultz will see assad next week
u.s. and diplomatic sources said the syrian leader may be interested in arrangements for a new distribution of power among vying sects in lebanon's 12-year-old civil war
meanwhile, a bipartisan group of 21 senators urged shultz to refrain from meeting with members of the palestine liberation organization, saying his meeting last week with two palestinian americans ``sets a dangerous precedent.''
shultz met last saturday in washington with two university professors who are members of the palestine national council, the plo's parliamentary arm. he denied that his meeting violated u.s. law which forbids negotiating with the plo, saying that not all pnc members are also members in the plo
but the senators said they see ``no distinction between the plo and the pnc.''
the senators said they wished shultz success on his mission and hoped he would be able to meet with palestinians who are not plo members. an attempt by shultz to meet with 15 palestinians from the israeli-occupied territories during his last trip to the region several weeks ago failed when the plo refused to endorse the meeting and the palestinians did not show up
the mid-march deadline he set for a reply to his plan for negotiations has passed. but impelled by violence on the israeli-held west bank and in gaza _ 123 palestinian arabs and an israeli soldier have been killed in less than three months _ shultz is determined to keep trying
u.s. officials find some hope in the fact that while israel, jordan and syria have not accepted the plan they also have not rejected it. only egypt has given its endorsement
the plan calls for a mideast conference in april to launch the negotiations. they would open on may 1 and deal with providing some form of self-rule to palestinian arabs on the west bank and in gaza
israel would deal with a joint delegation of jordanians and palestinian arabs to work an interim arrangement to last three years
meanwhile, negotiations on an overall settlement of the arab-israeli dispute that also would involve syria would begin in december
primarily because of syria's key role in the middle east, shultz had drawn assad into the discussions after several years of icy relations, u.s. officials said
but they said shultz also was taking up with assad the possibility of new arrangements in lebanon, where the syrians have dominated politics. assad, meanwhile, may be interested in reducing syria's involvement in the country, said the officials, who spoke only on condition of anonymity. kabul if us could keep supplying rebels.</note>
secretary of state george p. shultz said thursday the soviet union could keep arming marxist forces in afghanistan as part of a peace agreement, provided the united states could maintain supplies to the rebels
it would be better to have a moratorium,'' shultz said as he launched another overseas trip to pursue peace in the middle east
but, he told reporters aboard a u.s. air force jet en route to rome, ``to date, the soviets have not wanted to do that.''
the issue of u.s. and soviet military aid to rival forces is the main roadblock to an agreement to end the war in afghanistan after more than eight years
shultz proposed in march to soviet foreign minister eduard shevardnadze that both sides declare a moratorium. it would be in effect while the soviets withdrew their estimated 120,000 trroops and for three months afterward
the soviets accused the united states of posing a last-minute obstacle to an agreement. negotiations between afghanistan and pakistan, which were held under u.n. auspices, stalled
shultz, who will go on to jerusalem on sunday to begin a five-day mideast shuttle, made it clear he preferred a suspension of soviet aid to the marxists and u.s. support for the resistance group. u.s. aid has included stinger missiles that were effective against soviet aircraft and helicopters
but shultz said the overall goal was ``a balanced outcome.'' he said there was nothing in the geneva accords on afghanistan ``that tells us we cannot support our friends.''
he said, ``if the soviets exercise restraint, we are prepared to exercise restraint.''
shultz said he did not know whether the soviets would go along with providing equal levels of aid to the two sides
but he stressed the united states was prepared to guarantee a settlement even while aid kept flowing to the combatants
if we have signed the accords and see a need to support our friends, we will be able to do it,'' he said
shultz said he discussed the idea on the telephone wednesday with pakistani prime minister mohammad kahn junejo and that president mohammad zia ul-haq then called president reagan
so these things are in place,'' shnultz said. ``where we will all come out remains to be seen.''
u.s. officials in washington said earlier that the reagan administration was seeking moscow's approval for continued outside aid to the afghan combatants after soviet troops are withdrawn
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said there has been no indication of approval from the soviets. other officials sought to dispel the notion that the soviets had even indicated a willingness to consider the proposal
the united states, the soviet union, their clients in afghanistan and the government of neighboring pakistan, have been involved for months in u.n.-sponsored efforts to bring about a withdrawal of the estimated 115,000 soviet troops fighting in afghanistan
the soviets have agreed in principle to begin the troop withdrawal two months after a settlement is reached and pakistan is eager for such a deal so that millions of afghan refugees on pakistani territory can go home
preventing a final agreement, however, has been a u.s. demand that the kremlin stop aiding the afghan government after soviet troops depart. until such aid ceases, the united states will continue backing the afghan rebels, reagan has said
during talks with shevardnadze in washington last month, shultz renewed a plea for what the united states has been calling a ``symmetrical cessation'' of superpower aid to the afghan combatants
the new proposal, rather than calling for symmetrical cessation of aid, envisions parallel continuation of assistance
we now express the policy in terms of `we will continue aid to the mujahadeen as long as the soviet union continues aid to the kabul government,''' fitzwater said
the basic point to make is that our policy has not changed in the sense that we will not desert the afghan rebels,'' the spokesman said. ``we will not cut off money to them as long as the soviets are providing aid.''
fitzwater did not explain how the new u.s. language might be more palatable to the soviets except to say ``there are some negotiating reasons why it could hopefully allow the agreement to be signed in geneva and clear the way for a pullout.''
a state department official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said ``it would go too far,'' to say shevardnadze signaled an interest in the proposal last week, although he did not specifically reject the idea
the source said that before the u.s. proposal was devised, some administration officials warned against making an agreement to continue aid to the afghan combatants part of a secret understanding with the soviets
it would be against u.s. law to sign an afghan peace accord that required a cutoff of aid to the resistance forces while agreeing privately with the soviets to continue such assistance, the official said
asked on thursday if a decision to continue aid would be part of an open agreement, state department spokesman charles e. redman said ``that's always been our stance.''
president mengistu haile mariam, in a rare mention of northern ethopian insurgents, said thursday his troops are fighting ``grim battles'' against secessionist rebels, radio ethiopia reported
it was the first government comment on reports of a new rebel offensive, which resulted in the capture last week of a strategic town and three soviet officers advising the ethiopian army
the rebel tigray people's liberation front claimed thursday it had also captured axum and adowa, two historic towns in northern ethiopia
assesa mamo, north american representative of the tigray people's liberation front, said rebels took the towns thursday after a three-day battle
mamo spoke from washington in a telephone interview with the associated press bureau in nairobi, kenya
state-owned radio ethiopia quoted mengistu as saying rebels in tigray and neighboring eritrea had launched a ``systematic and highly destructive campaign,'' disrupting transport and communications networks in their regions
western diplomats, speaking on condition of anonymity, said mengistu's statement indicated the fighting must be serious. they said there were reports the ethiopian leader is preparing a huge counteroffensive against rebels of the eritrea people's liberation front and the tigray rebel group
it is believed to be the first time mengistu has conceded publicly that the rebels, whom the government normally calls ``bandits,'' are in any way effective
mengistu inherited the insurgencies 13 years ago when, with a group of army officers, he dethroned emperor haile selassie and helped set up a marxist government
mengistu made the comments about the rebels in a report to the eighth regular meeting of the central committee of his marxist workers' party of ethiopia
he appealed to ethiopians to ``rise in unity in the face of this new challenge,'' according to radio ethiopia
the radio gave no further details of mengistu's speech and it was not clear whether his comments concerned the rebels' claims on axum and adowa
axum is 110 miles south of asmara, eritrea's provincial capital, and adowa is 30 miles from axum
eritrean rebels said sunday they captured the town of afabet, killing or capturing 18,000 ethiopian troops. the rebels said one soviet officer was killed and three taken prisoner. afabet is 100 miles north of asmara
the rebels claimed to have wiped out three government divisions and captured tanks, weapons and other military equipment worth millions of dollars
there was no way to verify the rebels' claims. but western diplomats in addis ababa said the figure of 18,000 troops, a third of troops stationed in the north, sounded preposterous
the soviet union confirmed three of its advisers were captured, but said nothing of a fourth officer being killed
eritrean rebels have been fighting for 27 years in africa's oldest civil war
rebels in tigray claimed they captured three towns and more than 3,500 government soldiers in march. there is no way to confirm independently such rebel reports, on which the government refuses to comment
the fighting has aggravated relief efforts in the north, the worst-hit drought region of ethiopia. most of the 6 to 7 million ethiopians threatened with starvation this year live in the north
because of rebel activities, the government often closes roads in the region, cutting off truck convoys
the u.n. world food program reported thursday that a relief convoy reached the town of wukro in tigray province, bringing the first major food delivery to the drought-stricken area since january
the emergency shipment of 1,500 metric tons, enough to feed 100,000 people for a month, arrived sunday, said david morton, the u.n. representative in ethiopia. not contain the following items from the news digest: pm-israel-media; pm-school guide; pm-reagan-nicaragua; pm-reagan-meese; pm-meese; pm-political rdp; pm-brain implants.</note>
house approval of $48 million in humanitarian aid for the contra rebels and for children injured in nicaragua's civil war marks the first time in more than five years that lawmakers have been able to set aside partisan divisions on the issue
the house voted 345 to 70 late wednesday to approve the aid package and send what the chamber's leaders said was a strong signal of support to the rebels and the leftist sandinista government, which are trying to forge a long-term cease-fire
the winning margin came from 179 democratic votes and 166 gop votes. the largest group of dissenters seemed to be liberal democrats, many of whom oppose any form of contra aid on principle
contra rebels said they attacked sandinista soldiers in two areas of the country in violation of a temporary truce that is to be expanded into a 60-day cease-fire on friday
but the rebels' chief field commander said on wednesday he supports the peace accord with the leftist sandinista government that brought the truce
the two sides have not yet agreed on logistics of the cease-fire, during which the roughly 10,000 contra fighters are to move into five zones while a lasting peace agreement is negotiated. talks resume tuesday
television evangelist jimmy swaggart vows to return to the pulpit in defiance of church elders, saying preacher oral roberts has freed him of ``demons with long fingernails'' digging into his body
swaggart, accused of motel trysts with a prostitute, intends to return to the pulpit may 22, three months after stepping down,bill treeby, his lawyer and a board member of jimmy swaggart world ministries, said wednesday
swaggart said several weeks ago that he has undergone extensive prayer and counseling with roberts, the rev. mike evans of euless, texas, swaggart's friend and a fellow tv evangelist, said in a television interview wednesday
and he said to me that oral roberts called him up and told him that he saw demons with long fingernails digging their flesh into jimmy swaggart's body and that he cast those demon spirits out of jimmy swaggart,'' evans said
