a 23-year-old wall street ``whiz kid'' pleaded guilty to mail and securities fraud charges thursday, admitting he bilked $10 million from scores of investors and spent the money on himself and friends
i obtained money from investors, and told them i would invest their money in securities. ... instead i spent the money on art, automobiles, two homes and furnishings,'' david bloom told u.s. district judge david edelstein
bloom, a 1986 graduate of duke university, faces five years in prison and a maximum fine of double the amount lost by investors on each count
the northeast has become the nation's least populated region, falling behind the west for the first time, but it continues to be the most densely settled, the census bureau reported thursday
the bureau also projected that texas will surpass new york for second place behind california in population by 1995. and between now and the year 2000, half of all u.s. population growth will occur in just three states: california, texas and florida, the report said
the projections are based on assumptions about trends in births, deaths, immigration and movement within the country, said bureau demographer signe wetrogen
the teamsters union and the trucking industry reached tentative agreement thursday on a new three-year national freight contract covering 200,000 drivers and warehouse workers
the new national master freight agreement, unless rejected by at least two-thirds of the affected union members, will replace a contract of similar length that expired at midnight thursday
terms of the accord were not disclosed. but teamsters president jackie presser said in a statement that it ``addresses the economic needs of our members and advances their legitimate claims for job security.''
the virus that causes aids actually changes and grows more powerful as the immune deficiency disease progresses, according to studies at the university of california in san francisco
in a report to be published friday, dr. jay a. levy, professor of medicine at ucsf, said he and a group of researchers discovered the changing virus by studying blood samples taken over a four-year period from four men who were infected by the human immunodeficiency virus, or hiv
the scientists found that as the aids patients became sicker, the virus seemed to evolve and strengthen
comedy makes a rare appearance in this year's academy awards, with stand-up comic robin williams vying with four dramatic performers for the prize as best actor
some critics of oscar's seriousness argue that steve martin should have been nominated for best actor because of his modern-day cyrano in ``roxanne.'' but in a year that saw a number of impressive performances by comedians, only williams drew the nod for his manic disc jockey in ``good morning, vietnam.''
williams plays adrian cronauer, the real-life announcer who regaled american troops with jokes and rock 'n' roll over the army radio service. the funny side of the role was a breeze for williams, and director barry levinson allowed him free rein
obviously, the radio part offered me a chance to do some open-field running,'' williams says. ``barry had been a comic himself, and he would spark to some of my suggestions and let me go with them. many of the things in the movie, like the james brown impression and playing records at different speeds, happened spontaneously.''
williams' depth of feeling in the later, dramatic scenes of ``good morning, vietnam'' surprised some reviewers. williams studied drama under john houseman at the famed juilliard school in new york, but even then his comedic side was emerging. one of his teachers chided him: ``you're mimicking people. where is your voice?'' he soon found it. after a broken romance, williams dropped out of juilliard and began playing west coast comedy clubs
the comic's contenders in the best actor race are thought of as being more dramatic thespians
michael douglas was considered for two powerful roles: as the venomous inside trader of ``wall street'' and the erring husband of ``fatal attraction.'' the actors branch of the academy decided to nominate him for ``wall street.''
it was a marvelous role that oliver stone wrote,'' douglas says. ``i don't know why he chose me for the part, but he must have seen something in me that even i didn't even know about
playing a heavy is just fantastic; it's so much more fun than being the good guy. i can understand the attraction that (villains) have for actors
all of us try to be civilized human beings, but deep down inside we have this feeling to tell everything like it is. the part of gordon gecco was a wonderful opportunity for this release. after playing moral redeeeming characters and goodie guys, it was a ball.''
can an actor win an oscar for a performance in a foreign language? sophia loren did it in 1961 with ``two women.'' now marcello mastroianni stands a chance for his role as the vain italian aristocrat who pursues a new love to russia in ``dark eyes.''
mastroianni has acted in 116 films, and he still averages three a year. why does he work so hard at 64?
basically, i am an empty person,'' he said. ``when i act i feel complete because i use the personalities of these characters to fill this emptiness. i am also a childish person, and what better way to live life than by traveling to all these countries and getting paid to have fun and act like a fool, no?''
what william hurt feels about acting is not publicly known, since he is one of the least interviewed of film stars. obviously, he is doing something right, since he has been nominated three times in seven films and won the oscar for ``kiss of the spider woman'' two years ago
his latest nomination came for his portrayal of tom grunick, the handsome but not-too-bright network anchor man in ``broadcast news.'' hurt's few interviews have produced somewhat turgid quotes. as he himself explains: ``i have, fortunately or unforunately, skill at going down paths of endless non sequiturs
in a recent premiere magazine interview, hurt expounded on what he considered the major question of ``broadcast news.''
what is the nature, to put it simply, of romance in our time? what are our motives in wanting to be together? how do we pair up? who do we mate with, and why do we do it? a lot of us don't know the answer, a lot of us feel in flux,'' he said
jack nicholson has also been recently scarce in the media, apparently content to do his work without theorizing about it in public. in 1987, he shone in three roles: as the devil in ``the witches of eastwick''; as the depression bum in ``ironweed''; as star network anchor in ``broadcast news.'' he won his ninth nomination for his role as the former big-league ballplayer in ``ironweed.''
despite the cynical roles he has played, nicholson has maintained that he remains an optimist. in a 1986 interview he remarked:
i don't want to do what i accuse other people of doing: not taking the time to smell the roses. something very wonderful has happened to me. i don't want the fact that i see this endless din and gloom in the world to make me incapable of expressing something that's quite frankly wonderful. i'm a very fortunate person to be where i am and do what i do.''
anne ramsey found out that she had been nominated for an academy award as supporting actress when a friend called her at 5 a.m
within 15 minutes a television crew was at the house,'' she said. ``i had time to wash my face, and that was about all. i was absolutely flabbergasted.''
the nomination of ramsey, danny devito's horrendous mother in ``throw momma from the train,'' provided one of the highlights of a race that includes a 60-year veteran of films, the cousin of a presidential candidate, a classic argentine actress and a young actress who stood her own against a galvanizing performance by glenn close
here is a look at the nominees:
norma aleandro played the mexican indian who devoted her life to be the constant companion of a severely handicapped girl in ``gaby.'' a distinguished theater actress in buenos aires, she was forced into exile by the military government of argentina. after the junta was overthrown, she returned home to star in the oscar-winning ``the official story,'' which dealt with the atrocities of the regime
gaby'' was miss aleandro's first film in english. she regrets that the movie has found a limited audience, apparently because people were scared away by its theme
it's not a sad movie,'' she says. ``we are not speaking about sadness. we are speaking about people, about seeking freedom. sometimes people forget that freedom is in the mind.''
anne archer was nominated for the part of michael douglas' wife in ``fatal attraction.'' considering the galvanic role afforded glenn close as the vengeful other woman, you might think that archer would have had reservations about her role
not at all,'' she says. ``i always thought that (the wife) was a strong and interesting character, and she got to go through an interesting change. that is something you always look for: it's important that a character be different at the end of a script than in the beginning
she was sexy and vulnerable and strong. an interesting lady. i never felt even remotely that she would be overshadowed.''
ann sothern made her first movie in 1929, according to the record books. after a long and diverse career in films and television, mostly in comedy, she won her first academy recognition for a serious role in ``the whales of august.''
along with co-stars bette davis, lillian gish and vincent price, sothern filmed ``the whales of august'' on a remote maine island
there was no hotel, only a tiny store,'' she recalls. ``we all stayed in private homes; mine was a lobster fisherman's. the weather was murder: beautiful and sunny in the morning, and stormy in the afternoon
there was absolutely nothing to do at night. fortunately, i brought my cook and my poker chips.''
olympia dukakis has long been a working actress in theater, films and television, but she didn't impress a national audience until ``moonstruck.'' her success came at the same time her first cousin, massachusetts gov. michael dukakis, sought the democratic nomination for president
she grew up in a greek family in which everybody argued politics. after graduating from boston university, she worked as a physical therapist to earn enough money to return and study theater arts
despite her newfound fame, she intends to remain in the theater; she is the artistic director of the whole theater in montclair, n.j
i'm not convinced this being a celebrity is going to be long-lived,'' she says cautiously
fame was also a long time coming for ramsey: ``thirty-nine years later, after everything i've tried to do and everything i've wanted, this has happened. what a curious moment. thank god, thank danny (devito, who directed `momma'), thank everybody.''
ramsey has more to be thankful for than an academy nomination. a year and a half ago, she underwent surgery for cancer of the tongue. she apparently has recovered, but reconstruction of her tongue gave her slurred speech. happily, it fit perfectly into the character of the fierce momma
the actress admits that she dreamed of an oscar as a child growing up in suburban new york
i have a diary in which i wrote about it,'' she said. ``i was a real movie buff when i was a little girl. i read all the fan magazines, and i wrote for autographs and pictures from the stars. i wanted to be an actress from the time my father took me to see `the petrified forest' at the age of 4
i fell in love with actors, especially in the romantic films _ tyrone power, errol flynn, greer garson, walter pidgeon. i just loved movies. and now this (nomination) has happened. it's unbelievable.''
oradour-sur-glane, france (ap) _ just after lunch on the warm afternoon of june 10, 1944, the nazi ss began rounding up people in this prosperous country town and dividing them into groups. then they tortured, shot and burned them
historians have long pondered the reasons for the slaughter of 642 children, women and men and the destruction of oradour-sur-glane, carried out four days after the allied invasion of normandy in a village with no history of ties to the french resistance
a new book by a british businessman, robin mackness, claims to solve the mystery, suggesting that the massacre was a desperate attempt by the nazis to find a lost fortune in gold
survivors of the massacre and the families of those who died have vowed to stop publication in france of ``oradour, massacre and aftermath,'' already no. 5 on the british bestseller list and scheduled for publication by random house in the united states this fall. they claim the book warps history and insults the memory of oradour's ``martyrs.''
robert hebras, 62, who says he hid under the bodies of his neighbors to escape nazi bullets, put it more bluntly
everyone makes money from the name of oradour-sur-glane. this must cease.''
oradour has been preserved _ in ruins _ exactly as it was the day the germans marched off after the slaughter. in 1945 the french government declared the centuries-old village near limoges a national historic site and it has been visited by more than 500,000 people each year
plaques mark the sheds, cellars and barns where men were shot in the knees, interrogated, then machine gunned and their bodies burned
a cross stands outside the church where women and children huddled in terror for hours listening to gunfire kill their menfolk before the ss came to gun them down and set the sanctuary ablaze
a piece of twisted metal in the corner of the altar was once a baby carriage. a car on the village green rusts where it was parked by the mayor's son
only 13 people survived
my wife lost all her family, her mother, sister, uncle, aunt,'' said rene montaigne, a spokesman for the survivors' association. ``she still goes to the ruins because she feels at home there. she sees them all, even though they are dead.''
the new oradour-sur-glane, built adjacent to the ruins, has taken decades to recover
no one got married here for 20 years and it was only a couple of years ago that we had a wedding in june,'' said dr. robert lapuelle, mayor of the town since 1959. ``it was 1963 before we had enough youngsters to make a soccer team
no wonder people here are upset about this book.''
mackness' story is full of intrigue and personal adventure involving smuggled gold ingots and a shadowy figure named raoul
mackness writes that raoul told him that the ingots were a part of more than half a ton of gold that he and a few french resistance companions seized during a midnight ambush of an ss convoy
according to the book, the only survivors of the ambush were raoul, who buried the treasure by the side of the road, and a german soldier who reported the event
the gold apparently was a sort of floating pension fund for some officers of the 2nd ss panzer division, planning to stash it in swiss banks for after the war, mackness writes
it goes on to say that following the ambush, ss maj. otto dickmann rushed to the scene and, finding nothing and panicking, dashed to oradour, the nearest village
about 10 books have offered different explanations for the slaughter. but all have left questions dangling
mackness claims to answer many of these, but he seems to be having trouble getting anyone to accept his story because his sources are concealed
dickmann and raoul are dead. mackness refuses to divulge the names of his living sources, many of whom, he says, fear prosecution for the massacre
for many historians, mackness' word isn't enough
no historic fact allows me to give this business the least credibility,'' jacques delarue, a french historian, was quoted by the french newspaper le figaro as saying
but mackness stands by his story
it fits the known historical facts,'' he said in a telephone interview from london
the people in france who object to my book haven't read it because it hasn't been, and may not be, published there.''
in oradour, mackness is accused of dancing on the graves of the dead
mr. mackness' ambush never happened, at least not near oradour,'' said mayor lapuelle, who added that the villagers want to preserve the simple, brutal truth of the event, so ``this will never happen again.''
i had a brother at khe sahn,
fightin' off them viet cong
they're still there
he's all gone.''
_ bruce springsteen
bruce springsteen has turned down untold amounts of money for commercial use of his song, ``born in the u.s.a.'' he gave it to the makers of hbo's ``dear america: letters home from vietnam'' for free
filmmaker bill couturie edited thousands of feet of archival footage into a backdrop for the letters in this devastating 90-minute documentary, premiering sunday on hbo
besides springsteen, the soundtrack includes vintage '60s rock from such artists as the rolling stones, bob dylan and marvin gaye. the letters are read off-camera by a star-studded cast of voices, including robert de niro, kathleen turner, robin williams and michael j. fox, who all donated their time
at a recent screening in new york, some members of the audience were so moved by the film they were unable to get out of their seats when it was over
the documentary is based on the book of the same name and plays on hbo throughout april
dear america'' is different from other vietnam movies in that it is told in the words of the vets themselves in the often strikingly eloquent letters they wrote to loved ones back home:
_ a lieutenant who had just seen a soldier lose his leg writes to his brother, ``i've never seen such bravery and guts before and i'm stunned by it. you shoulda seen my men fight. they were going after wounded men no one else would go after. you shoulda seen my brave men.''
_ writes army nurse lynda van devanter, ``i'm sick of facing, every day, a new bunch of children ripped to pieces. they're just kids _ eighteen, nineteen years old! it stinks! whole lives ahead of them _ cut off. i'm sick to death of it. i've got to get out of here ...''
almost all the footage came from the heretofore untapped nbc news archives. abc's vietnam footage had already been used in several movies, and cbs does not allow outside producers to use its archives. nbc's library had been closed to filmmakers until general electric bought the network and changed the policy
i happened to be at the right place at the right time,'' said couturie
hbo said that because couturie shot none of the film, the academy awards committee turned down the documentary for oscar consideration, but hbo plans to put it up for an emmy
couturie said his interviews with vets from an earlier project convinced him of the importance of the letters, virtually the only link between those in vietnam and ``the world.'' the other link was rock 'n' roll
the soundtrack is an '60s treasury. but springsteen's ``born in the u.s.a.'' became the anthem of vietnam veterans' disillusionment and courage in the '80s
springsteen had allowed the song to be used once before, in the vietnam play ``tracers,'' produced by tom bird, co-producer of the hbo film. couturie just had to have the song for the ending of ``dear america.''
we went to springsteen and asked him if we could use it, and he immediately said yes. it didn't take one second for him to say yes. in fact, his comment was, `it's the vets' song. of course, you can use it,''' couturie said
springsteen donated the song on the condition that all the music be donated, giving the producers leverage to obtain the other music without cost
the film is structured chronologically and punctuated by stark graphics describing the escalation of the conflict. the combination of music and pictures evokes the era, not just the war
but above it all are the words
couturie knew what he wanted in the reading of the letters _ a delicate balance of emotion that didn't go over the edge into melodrama. he found himself giving direction to the biggest names in acting _ de niro, williams, turner, fox, martin sheen, sean penn, willem dafoe, brian dennehy, john heard, harvey keitel, randy quaid, howard rollins jr. and john savage, among others
ellen burstyn reads the last, most devastating letter, from a mother to a son who died in the conflict 15 years earlier
when burstyn arrived at the studio, couturie said, she brushed him off, insisting brusquely that they just get on with it
my heart was sinking,'' he said. ``i was going, oh, god, this woman has a lunch date or something and wants to get out of here, and this is the most crucial letter in the film, and i really blew it, i've picked the wrong person.'' she was not the wrong person. she had been rehearsing the letter on her own and couldn't discuss it, she had to just do it
that's the only letter that was done in one take,'' couturie said. ``she went in and just nailed it. it was an awesome performance.''
elsewhere:
clapton talks _ rock guitar legend eric clapton will be the subject of a special on the bravo cable network in may. ``the south bank show: eric clapton'' features clapton and bass player jack bruce performing cream songs for the first time since 1969. it also includes interviews with clapton, elton john, phil collins, sting and pete townsend
