try as they might, lutherans in this proud mill town can't seem to forgive or forget the controversy that shook their church when a mild-mannered pastor added protest to prayer
sunday after sunday four years ago, d. douglas roth preached against ``corporate evil'' and the moral imperative of helping workers in this economically strapped area
often the sermons were delivered after he and others burst into services attended by steel industry executives. the protesters put dead fish in safe deposit boxes, and sprayed skunk oil at banks
the protests climaxed in january 1985 when seven of roth's supporters, including his wife, barricaded themselves inside trinity lutheran church in defiance of a court order, only to be routed by sheriff's deputies
now, many of the faithful are back in their pews, worshipping with a new minister. roth, now defrocked, conducts lutheran-style services every sunday for a smaller flock at a pentecostal sanctuary across town
the protest group, denominational ministry strategy, has changed its name to dmx to mimic its main target, usx corp., which used to be united states steel corp
and the controversy surrounding dmx's tactics rumbles on
this group can't back off and say, `well, maybe we were wrong. we've caused a lot of heartache and we're sorry,'' said mary gahagen, 70, a lay official at the newly organized lutheran church of the holy spirit in what used to be trinity lutheran
for the ones living here, they'll never get over it,'' said the rev. walter koehler, 61, the church's new pastor. ``it's not hatred, but it borders on that.''
roth and other dmx supporters take it all in stride
they think we're crazy,'' said roth, 36, wearing, as always, his clerical collar. ``they know we'll do whatever it takes.''
roth's latest brush with the law came march 4 during prince charles' visit to a pittsburgh area jobs center for the unemployed. roth and another dmx supporter were arrested while protesting outside, but were cleared of disorderly conduct charges
we're upsetting and making all sorts of impact without even having to lift a finger,'' boasted daniel solberg, 37, another defrocked lutheran minister and a dmx leader. his brother, actor david soul, periodically has lent his support
gone are all but a half dozen of the lutheran pastors who helped organize the church-sponsored ministry in the early 1980s. the group soon charged pittsburgh-area corporate giants like usx and mellon bank with abandoning once-prosperous steel towns along the monongahela and ohio rivers
this is a small but vocal minority. i think people understand that,'' said the rev. edward kappeler, 56, an official of the southwestern pennsylvania synod of the evangelical lutheran church in america. ``the broad consensus of the lutheran church is that the church is doing what it can in the areas the dmx has always professed to be concerned about.''
gone, too, are the unionists who backed the rebel clergymen's cause. ``it became a church battle, that's what happened,'' explained ron weisen, 51, a former united steelworkers local president
as for roth, he says his defrocking and going on welfare have helped him empathize more with the problems he was protesting and made him more credible among the unemployed
there are prices to be paid, particularly in the family,'' said roth, a father of four. ``but family is exactly why you do this. how can you look your children in the eyes and say, `well, we have to take care of ourselves'? it's very bad theology.''
the unorthodox crusade began in earnest on easter 1984 when dmx supporters stormed into an affluent pittsburgh church and railed against ``corporate evil.'' they declared that overseas investments by steelmakers and other businesses were contributing to the area's high jobless rate
the next sunday, and the next and the next, similar disruptions were staged at other churches in this rusting steel mill valley
as the hostilities escalated, roth's congregation sought and won his removal. refusing to leave, he was arrested at trinity lutheran's altar in november 1984 and jailed for 112 days for civil contempt of court
because of the turmoil, the synod's executive board ordered the 60-year-old stone church locked and the 145-member congregation disbanded. koehler arrived in september 1986, and the new parish was organized last october
koehler's first sermon touched on forgiveness, although he ``didn't beat it to the ground.''
he's since had his own faith and patience sorely tested. he said the words ``scab pastor'' have been spray-painted on church property, glue has been squeezed into door locks, a stained glass window was shattered by a rock, and an outside gas meter mysteriously was turned off one bitterly cold night
i was prepared for a lot worse than has happened,'' koehler said. ``i brainwashed myself before i came here that i was not going to let their nonsense get to me.''
while the dmx has not claimed responsibility for the vandalism, roth acknowledged ``people are still upset that this abomination of church is there. they're just reacting to the removal of this valid ministry.''
he's appealing the synod executive board's decision to declare the congregation defunct. he's also appealing two jail sentences that are pending as a result of past protests
i will be back as an ordained pastor. i will be at trinity without a doubt,'' he said, nodding emphatically. ``it's just a matter of how much more do they want to lose before i win.''
retarded men and women around the nation are being shown an explicit videotape about sex in hopes it will help keep them safe from aids
the video uses startling illustrations _ including still photographs of surrogates in specific sexual positions
you can't generalize or use words. they don't know what you're talking about,'' explained alice rose, program director of the cerebral palsy association of san francisco, which will present the video at 12 group homes
their ability to abstract information is impaired,'' added rebecca porper, a public health educator from the new york city department of health who appears in the film. ``you have to deal absolutely in black and white, with no grays, and it has to be reiterated in several ways, preferably multi-sensory.''
the young adult institute, the non-profit agency that created the 17-minute video, with help from the city health department, acknowledges the idea offends some people
someone called from iowa and said, `how dare you put homosexuals on the tape?''' said perry samowitz, the institute's training director. ``we don't want to come across as crazy liberals from new york who are promoting promiscuity. but what are the alternatives? we don't want our clients to die _ no matter who gives us flak.''
the main goal is ``to make sure a condom is worn'' if a retarded adult decides to have sex, samowitz said
for tina mills, who has down's syndrome and lives with 14 other mildly retarded people in their 20s and 30s at a suburban yonkers apartment building, talking about aids is scary. but after she saw the video, she said, ``i tried to urge that (condom use) to a friend at the workshop.''
there are times i don't really want to talk about it or think about it,'' agreed fellow resident dan sigman. ``it's kind of painful, but it's better to learn all about it. aids kills.''
no statistics indicate how many aids victims are retarded, according to chuck fallis, spokesman for the federal centers for disease control. ms. porper said she knew of eight aids cases among the retarded in the metropolitan area, and a retarded new yorker died last year of aids contracted through a blood transfusion, according to lou ganim, a spokesman for the state office of mental health and developmental disabilities
the risk of aids is no less real for the retarded. and so the film is explicit
in one photograph, male surrogates are positioned as if they were about to engage in anal sex so viewers can understand the link between that practice and aids. oral sex and the use of condoms in heterosexual intercourse are also illustrated
i'm sure we'll get one or two people who will go bananas about it,'' said ms. rose. ``a small proportion of people do not believe that their children, whether adults or not, have a right to be active or have knowledge of sexual activity.''
i don't dare bring it up with my parents,'' said abbie colpoys of the yonkers group home
my parents talk a lot about that kind of thing. they warn me about what could happen to me,'' said ms. mills. ``i say, `ma, please _ i can take care of myself. i care about myself.'''
teachers stress in group discussions that the film is not intended to advocate any act, and that abstinence is acceptable. role-playing is included to help participants refuse unsafe sex
it teaches them how to be sensitive and relate to people in a caring, responsible way,'' said joel m. levy, executive director of the yai, which runs 50 programs for the retarded in the new york area, including 24 group homes
group home residents also practice putting condoms on a plastic penis and are told to use condoms themselves, even when it's not clear where a romantic moment will lead
the mildly and moderately retarded know their judgment is impaired,'' said ms. porper. ``if you give them a choice they are incapable of making _ like when to put on a condom _ it raises tremendous anxieties in them.''
some professionals have qualms about the film's approach
i think the general feeling of our staff is that it was too negative, too scary,'' said cathy berger, prevention specialist with the wisconsin council on developmental disabilities. yai sent the tape to 150 agencies, and the wisconsin council was among five that returned it, said samowitz
they (the filmmakers) see this as a very serious issue and their intent is to make people aware of it by scaring them. we're concerned about that approach,'' said ms. berger
it also concerns yonkers group home resident sandy mintzer. she and her boyfriend understand safe sex, but cannot use condoms because of poor hand coordination _ a problem for some retarded people
it's hard to talk about because it's scary,'' said ms. mintzer, who adamantly refused to see the film a second time
sometimes, denial is an easier way of dealing with scary feelings,'' the residential supervisor, laura eldridge, told others in the group. ``but i don't feel it's healthy.''
some members of the wisconsin council also were bothered by the film's explicit nature or felt that it ``left some questions that might confuse people,'' said ms. berger
they agree the retarded need aids education, she said. ``but it's not like there's a canned program that works for everybody. agencies have different perspectives, and communities have different attitudes.''
the film is out of the question for roman catholic programs for the retarded because of religious doctrine against condoms and premarital sex, said monsignor james cassidy, director of health and hospitals for the new york archdiocese
we'd be against it purely from the medical point of view,'' said cassidy. ``condoms fail. if we relied solely on condoms, we'd have every darn one of the females pregnant.''
instead, abstinence is taught to the 350 retarded adults served through archdiocese programs. ``it's just a reinforcement of what we've been doing all along,'' said cassidy
ganim, the spokesman for the new york mental health office, felt ambivalent about the film
i certainly know it's explicit and some people have expressed concerns about that,'' he said. ``but by and large, what we have heard back about the tape has been positive. they've brought up the fact that there is a need for this kind of thing.''
dr. lloyd kolbe, chief of the cdc's office of school health and special projects, said no one has studied what kind of aids information is available for the retarded and what might be effective
kolbe said cdc guidelines issued in january suggested that schools address the issue of aids education for the disabled
we need to think about it,'' said kolbe. ``the questions, i think, are important ones.''
it's not like you should just forget about it and pretend aids doesn't exist,'' said lauren hoffman, a resident at the group home. ``a woman has to be prepared.''
rod matthews was a sullen, introverted boy, fascinated with death, obsessed with fire. shaun ouillette was outgoing and happy; he played hockey and talked of counseling troubled youths
sixteen months ago matthews beat ouillette to death with a baseball bat. last month the 15-year-old was found guilty of second-degree murder and given life in prison
the horrible crime wasn't the only link between murderer and victim. both took ritalin, a stimulant used to calm hyperactive children
and while the trial served as a stage to the debate over the drug, it also provided testimony on how ritalin, in combination with other treatment, can help children, and how its casual use can allow deeper problems to go undetected
matthews' attorney, john philip white, claimed the drug nudged the boy into the madness it took to plan and commit murder. the citizens commission on human rights, an anti-psychiatry group connected with the church of scientology, trumpeted the case as an example of the dangers it associates with the drug
a stream of psychiatrists and psychologists gave offsetting testimony. defense witnesses said matthews was psychotic, that the ritalin ``enhanced'' his obsession to kill. prosecution witnesses said the boy's emotional problems were not enough to obscure his notion of right and wrong. ritalin, they said, played no factor
ironically, ouillette's mother, jeanne quinn, says ritalin helped her son, calming him enough to allow the counseling and therapy that taught him how to control himself
guidelines by the american academy of pediatrics say ritalin should be prescribed after detailed diagnosis and used only in combination with counseling and careful monitoring. according to testimony, matthews received ritalin without other therapy
his mother, janet, portrayed him as a quiet child who said little more than yes or no in his early years. when he became a behavioral problem in the third grade, a pediatrican prescribed ritalin
mrs. matthews said there were no special psychological or physical tests, no monitoring of her son's progress over the next five years
mrs. matthews said her son went off the drug a few months before the killing, then asked for more pills a few weeks later. a bottle of ritalin was found in his school locker; no one knows if he was taking the drug at the time of the killing
in contrast, mrs. quinn said her son ``went through all kinds of tests'' before he was diagnosed as hyperactive and given ritalin at age 7
she said she attended sessions for parents with hyperactive children, watched her son's diet and diverted his energies into activities like hockey and bicycling
after four years, ouillette was weaned from the drug
we had taught him to learn self-discipline and self-control,'' she said
white said the effect ritalin had on his client remains a mystery, but he believes that reliance on the drug, instead of testing and therapy, played a role in the tragedy
the whole affair was a lost opportunity to spot a potential problem,'' he said. ``as a result, we've got one boy in prison and another boy dead.'' 
one hyperactive student is greatly helped by ritalin, so the teacher encourages the parents of others to try it _ and they tell other parents about the happy results. ritalin's success many have led to its excess: some fear it's now overused. the second story in a three-day series, `r' is for ritalin, looks at the increased role of a prescribed drug in the nation's schools
something new is tucked amid the workbooks, pencils and sandwiches in an increasing number of school backpacks each day. it is a pill, no bigger than button candy, prescribed to help youngsters get through their multiplication tables, spelling tests and geography lessons
the pill is ritalin, a stimulant that can assist hyperactive children in concentrating, completing their work and controlling frenzied outbursts that turn classrooms to chaos
some parents describe ritalin as a godsend
it was like the difference between day and night,'' said nancy anderson, a buffalo, minn., mother whose daughter, 11, and son, 8, take the drug. ``the first day sarah took ritalin was the first time she was able to read something and understand it. that night she told me and started crying
i cried, too.''
but ritalin's success may be leading to its excess. as many as 1 million children may take the drug, and happy endings like the andersons' are encouraging more doctors to prescribe it, sometimes with less triumphant results
many doctors say superficial diagnosis and limited follow-up have led to the medicating of the children who don't need it, or who need additional counseling to learn how to tame the confusion inside their minds
i know of several communities and school districts where people are excessively prescribing medication for children without adequately evaluating them,'' said russell barkely, director of psychology at the university of massachusetts medical center. barkely said these communities to the west and north of boston ``may be seeing the children once a year and renewing the prescription by telephone.''
the five states with the highest per-capita consumption of ritalin _ utah, maryland, georgia, minnesota and michigan _ have begun investigating its use
georgia officials alarmed by high ritalin use in suburban atlanta found school personnel were urging ritalin treatment on parents
we looked at what was driving the marketplace and wound up with the conclusion that it was the school systems,'' said andrew watry, executive director of georgia's composite state board of medical examiners. ``parents were calling us with a lot of anecdotal information about how their arms were twisted to take the medication.''
lavarne parker, a suburban atlanta mother, believes ritalin is used as a chemical billy club to subdue problem students. she has filed suit against the doctor and school officials who encouraged her to medicate her son
it's almost like someone said we've got a pill to give a child who won't do what you want him to do,'' she said
when susan marshall's son, bradley, had trouble in first-grade at hingham, mass., she sought medical help on the school's advice. her pediatrian prescribed ritalin
but bradley did not improve and, according to his mother, suffered from insomnia, depression and a loss of appetite. mrs. marshall finally took bradley to a neurologist who found the boy's problems were due to a hemiparesis, a limited brain injury not treatable by ritalin
the marshalls are suing the pediatrician
he simply prescribed ritalin,'' she said. ``we were not given a diagnosis.''
parents like mrs. marshall and mrs. parker claim ritalin carries harsh side effects, from facial tics and lost appetite to depression and suicide. their anxieties are fed by the citizens commission on human rights _ a group, supported by the church of scientology, that opposes psychiatric treatment and is conducting a nationwide media campaign against ritalin
doctors and government regulators dismiss most charges against ritalin as exaggerated and unsubstantiated, citing some 500 research papers that mostly agree side effects are temporary and minimal
manufactured by ciba-geigy corp. and known generically as methylphenidate, ritalin is one in a small group of drugs used to treat childhood behavioral disorders and narcolepsy. as a class ii drug, it is listed, along with amphetamines, morphine and the painkiller demerol, as a drug with legitimate use but high potential for abuse
prescribing drugs for problem children is not new. the roman physican galen suggested opium for overactive children in the first century. research in the 1930s indicated that treating hyperactive children with stimulants, usually amphetamines, helped calm them. ritalin was developed in 1955 as an alternative to amphetamines
what has changed in the last decade is the awareness _ some say overawareness _ of the malady that ritalin is used to treat
known variously over years as hyperactivity, hyperkinesis and minimal brain disfunction, the syndrome is now called attention deficit disorder, a catch-all of symptoms ranging from wild, destructive behavior to an inability to concentrate or, in educational jargon, ``stay on task.''
researchers say 3 to 10 percent of the nation's 45 million schoolchildren exhibit some symptoms of add
the american psychiatric association's diagnostic bible lists add symptoms such as fidgeting, difficulty awaiting turns at games, blurting out answers before being called on, excessive talking and a penchant for losing things
while many parents would recognize some of these noisome habits in their children, add parents say it is the intensity of the behavior that separates theirs from normal children
it's the constantness of it,'' said jean conner harrison, a west newbury, mass., mother who publishes a newsletter for add families. ``you are trapped in it. you can't take these children anywhere, you can't get babysitters to stay with them. it is so emotionally tough to get through this day by day.''
add is the single most researched area of child psychology. some 600 research papers on the subject were published last year. add seminars are commonly held around the country for doctors, educators and parents
regional diagnostic clinics have sprung up, often near research centers in states with high ritalin use. as a result, more and more children are being diagnosed with add and treated with medication
critics note with alarm that ritalin production has doubled since 1983. but the u.s. drug enforcement administration, which sets production levels, says that statistic sheds little light on how many people take a drug
a better gauge is number of prescriptions. an fda report shows 2.2 million prescriptions for ritalin and related drugs were filled and refilled in 1986. the figure does not show the number of people using the drug, but it does indicate an increase in use _ the number is 14 percent higher than in 1983
that's unusual,'' said carlene baum, an fda psychologist. ``the average annual increase in prescriptions for most drugs is 1 percent.''
no one is certain how many of the nation's children get a daily dose of ritalin. daniel safer, a johns hopkins university child psychiatrist who has studied surveys at various school districts, believes 600,000 to 800,000 schoolchildren receive stimulant medication, mostly ritalin
it's been going up steadily,'' said safer, ``and i don't see it going down.''
eds: this sty may be considered complete in one take. a second take follows for those desiring more detail
in 1971, 1.1 percent of baltimore county school students were taking ritalin, safer said. by 1983, the number was up to 3.5 percent
the increase is a multiple of factors: parent-teacher satisfaction, the ease of treatment and its relative success,'' he said
most maryland school districts recommend parents seek medical help only after teachers, counselors and administrators have met to discuss a problem student
we don't prescribe ritalin,'' said robert dubel, superintendent of the baltimore county school district. ``all we do is refer children to medical help, the same as we would if a child had problems seeing a blackboard. we would tell the parents and they would have the child's eyes examined.''
yet when baltimore county officials, threatened with a lawsuit, reviewed their policy late last year, they found such a measured response was not always the case
i am convinced that we probably do have some people out there who sidestep some of the procedures and say `you have to get that child on ritalin,''' said thomas farley, an assistant county attorney
in georgia, watry, the director of the medical examiners' board, tells of one school counselor who would ``pressure parents on a mass scale to use ritalin.''
he told parents he was playing the percentages because it had helped with so many cases,'' said watry
late last year a special study group for the georgia department of education recommended school personnel be warned against ``pressuring'' parents to seek medication and leave diagnosis and treatment to medical professionals
but often these professionals are not doing a complete job
the american academy of pediatrics recommends extensive testing and discussion among doctors, parents and educators before prescribing medication
guidelines also stress that medication is only part of the solution. counseling, therapy, tutoring, even special classes for parents are recommended
almost everybody in the field will say you have to do more than give the pill,'' said james satterfield, a los angeles-area psychiatrist whose research found hyperactive children responded dramatically better to a combination of therapy and ritalin
we've heard about pediatricians who have said, `here's six months of prescription, come back when it runs out,''' he said. ``that gives a message to parents that here's this magic pill, you don't need any other treatment.''
but some question if many of those getting treatment need it
thomas long, a psychologist and director of the national center for family studies at the catholic university of america, believes doctors choose medication when counseling and different parenting might be enough
we have created a society that relies on medication to solve our problems,'' he said. ``the first thing you go to when you have a problem is some kind of pill.''
each weekday morning our 7-year-old son tom starts breakfast with a tiny white tablet he calls his ``daydream pill.''
the pill has become part of our daily routine. there was a time when my wife and i, people who think twice before taking aspirin, would have been incredulous had you told us we'd be giving our child a behavior-modifying drug
as tom grew into an active toddler, he gave no indication anything was amiss; we were sure he was a superstar. with blond curls and a sturdy well-coordinated body, he was quick and good at everything: an early walker and talker, a cheerful elf full of eager questions
but by the time tom was ready for kindergarten, we were concerned. he couldn't seem to keep his mind on a task. he didn't like to play alone, and he didn't stay with an activity for more than a few minutes
we hoped it was just immaturity. perhaps we had spoiled him?
with his quick mind and pleasing personality, tom drifted through kindergarten. we wondered why he wasn't picking up academic skills as quickly as we'd anticipated, but his school reports were generally good and he was having a good year with soccer and t-ball
everything changed in first grade. he was one of 30 classmates, and most of the school day required independent seatwork
we realized something was very wrong when tom began collapsing into tantrums of free-floating rage and frustration after school. we were completely taken aback, especially because we had high confidence in his small, caring school
we were mystified by our little soccer player's rage. at what? was it the oversized class?
the school principal assured us that, although the class was large, the children were doing fine
we spoke to psychologist friends about whether some deep-seated anxiety could be surfacing
tom himself was unable to give us any clues until one night in the midst of an emotional collapse, he said, over and over, ``i'm dumb.''
fortunately for us all, tom's class took a group intelligence test about this time. tom's score was so high in comparison with his performance that the principal called us in. she wanted to do further testing and mentioned ``attention deficit,'' a term that seemed to fit the child we knew
the principal also mentioned ritalin, saying she had seen dramatic changes in kids like tom. we were appalled by the suggestion we give our boy a drug, skeptical that this was the proper way to approach a learning problem
instead, we tried a highly publicized diet and spent an agonizing month keeping tom from many of his favorite foods, ones with cyclamates and additives. the stress of the diet increased tom's rage and frustration
we next urged the school to institute behavioral techniques, such as rewarding tom for even brief periods of concentration. these helped, but only moderately, and we started to reconsider
after reading all the research we could find, and considering the side effects (such as the possibility tom would be one-quarter inch shorter as an adult), we concluded the risks of trying ritalin were minimal
a factor in our decision was our own dependence on our morning cups of coffee, which help us get going and stay focused. were we depriving tom of the equivalent of a morning cup of coffee?
the pediatrician said tom might temporarily lose his appetite or have trouble sleeping. none of this happened, and tom was surpringly amenable to taking the tiny pill
indeed, tom was the first to let us know it was making some difference. he started calling it his ``daydream pill,'' saying it helped him control the daydreams that distracted him in class. his teacher soon reported his behavior was improving, and we saw this reflected in his school work
still, we couldn't be certain it wasn't just a placebo effect on tom and the teacher
this year, with a new teacher who shared our lingering reservations, we withheld the ritalin for a couple of weeks. simultaneously, tom and his teacher reported he couldn't concentrate and urged us to return to the pill
with the increased demands of second grade, tom has begun taking an additional 5 milligrams at lunch. occasionally, when he's having trouble staying with his homework, he'll say, ``maybe i should take a pill.'' last week we filled yet another prescription at the pharmacy where we are now recognized as regulars
last month, tom proudly brought home a report card with b's in math and english and a's _ his first ever _ in reading and spelling. in categories such as deportment, handwriting and follows directions, which last year produced a string of f's for failure and n's for non-satisfactory, there were 2 n's and 13 s's _ for satisfactory
is ritalin a panacea? no. even with the pill, tom's attention deficit still requires the guidance of a skillful teacher
are we comfortable about him taking medicine? yes and no
we like the results but are uncomfortable treating a symptom, the cause of which no one knows. we are especially uncomfortable that the psychologists and doctors seem unconcerned why tom has trouble paying attention
will we keep giving him the pill? yes, at least while tom thinks it's helpful. we'll also keep trying to find a deeper understanding of what's involved
as tom says, ``it's not perfect, but it works, some.''
strat douthat is the ap southeast regional reporter, based in atlanta. his wife, attorney gail falk, helped write this article about their son, tom
for parents facing a decision on whether to medicate a child with ritalin, psychiatrists and pediatricians offer some advice: make sure the diagnosis is made carefully and the treatment involves more than just taking pills
ritalin is commonly prescribed for hyperactive children with attention deficit disorder, but too often they are diagnosed without proper testing and evaluation, they say
and if a treatment does not include counseling and educational therapies, it probably is faulty, the experts add
i think there are children given the drug who do not have add,'' said dr. jerry wiener, president of the american academy of child and adolescent psychiatry. ``and if they do, drugs alone are not going to resolve that. very often mistakes are made of making the diagnosis and then only prescribing the drug.''
parents, wiener said, should expect five things of their physician:
_ a complete and thorough diagnosis
_ information about possible side effects
_ close monitoring of the effects of medication through regular visits
_ information about alternative treatments
_ an explanation of the consequences if medication is not used
if the physician does not do these things, parents have every reason ... to seek medical help elsewhere,'' wiener said
the american psychiatric association's diagnostic and statistical manual of mental disorders says an add diagnosis must include signs of inattention and impulsivity, as well as onset before age 7 and duration of at least six months. other disorders must be ruled out
an add study group appointed by the georgia department of education called add ``one of the most time-consuming of the disorders of childhood to evaluate.''
dr. michael levine, a san antonio, texas, child hyperactivity expert, said he spends two hours taking history and 10 hours testing before making an add diagnosis
when you see johnny staring out the window or bouncing off the walls, you don't know if he's off-task because of a brain filter problem (treatable with ritalin), a learning disability or a behavioral problem,'' levine said
once an add diagnosis is made, experts say, too often the child is treated only with medications such as ritalin _ the prescribed way to go until as recently as 1970. the latest research shows that a more effective treatment combines medication with therapy and counseling
everyone agrees that you have to do something more than give a pill,'' said dr. james satterfield of encino, calif., who pioneered some add research. ``in the real world, most of the children get one treatment, seldom two, never three _ and the most common would be medication.''
daily doses of the drug ritalin are increasingly the treatment of choice for children diagnosed with attention deficit disorder. not surprisingly, more and more clinics are specializing in such diagnosis and treatment. and schools are often enthusiastic about ritalin's success. two stories offer inside looks at one such clinic, where an 11-year-old girl learned she would begin what might be years of ritalin therapy, and at a school where teachers credit ritalin with helping children conquer their emotional and academic despair. a third story looks at utah, the state with the youngest population, a reputation for moral conservatism _ and the highest per capita use of ritalin in the nation
her school principal had urged her mother to make the four-hour drive from rural northern michigan. now 11-year-old chrissie sat in a tiny, windowless office where a psychologist peppered her with questions
the morning would end with doctors at the attention deficit disorder clinic of children's hospital telling chrissie her baffling problems at home and in school would mean treatment with the stimulant ritalin, quite likely for years
but first doctors tested chrissie: spelling tests, math tests, reading tests, questions about her family life. they probed her moods, whether she ever felt like committing suicide (``once or twice,'' she said.) they examined her school grades, read reports from teachers
they even had chrissie, a sliver-thin, pretty girl with straight blond hair, draw a picture of herself. the 2-inch-high sketch spoke volumes to the psychologist about the youngster's poor self-image
finally the psychologist asked chrissie for three wishes
a horse ranch,'' the girl said after several moments. ``a happy life. and people who care who can help me through this tough time
i haven't really been happy since i was 2 or so. i yell at my parents. later i wish i hadn't done it. they're very good to me. so i haven't had a very happy life.''
chrissie, which is not the girl's real name, indeed had many problems, the doctors concluded. but she hardly fit the popular, often mistaken, stereotype of children who take ritalin
first, boys are eight times more likely than girls to be diagnosed as having add. second, chrissie wasn't ``bouncing off the walls.'' in fact, many youngsters recommended for ritalin treatment are not discipline problems and appear calm in most situations
chrissie, said psychologist arthur robin, is ``a classic case of a kid whose add was not caught as a young kid.'' pre-adolescents and teen-agers who unexplainedly struggle with school for years often arrive at add clinics deeply depressed as a result of their attention problems
the key was her inability to complete tasks and concentrate. tests suggested she was weak in math, easily frustrated, dangerously depressed, and had a poor self-image
chrissie knows she has troubles. ``i have quite a problem paying attention in school. i've had it since kindergarten,'' she told a visitor in a brief break from testing. ``i sometimes just have to get out of my seat. i go to the drinking fountain, and i'm not even thirsty. it's weird
if i have a problem, i'd really like to know about it.''
fewer than 100 such add clinics operate around the country, according to wade horn, a psychologist who heads one at children's hospital national medical center in washington, d.c. nearly all start with the assumption that add is essentially a physiological disease that in most cases can be treated chemically
some clinics simply juggle prescriptions, using placebos and ritalin or other stimulant drugs alternately to find the most effective treatment. they leave the followup and monitoring to others, often the family pediatrician
others, like the detroit clinic, employ pediatricians, psychologists and social workers to look at the child in totality. that means that counseling and changes in lessons or surroundings are often part of the treatment. but at the heart of these clinics is the conviction that ritalin therapy helps most patients
since it opened in september 1986, the add clinic here has examined some 600 patients and has a three-month waiting list, said dr. sheldon brenner, a pediatrician and co-director of the clinic. at least three-quarters were diagnosed as having add, and about 85 percent of those were placed on medication, usually ritalin
once treatment begins, doctors rely on teacher questionnaires, report cards and parents to monitor whether ritalin is helping the child in school and whether it is having side effects
chrissie's teacher wrote this description of her on a conners questionnaire, the standardized form used to evaluate children suspected of having attention deficit disorder:
chrissie is not a behavior problem,'' her teacher wrote. ``i just do not have her attention 90 percent of the time. ... on the day we had our first bit of snow last fall, i was trying to help her understand something. she looked at me and smiled, saying `i wonder what my kitten thinks of snow? she never saw it before.' sometimes it seems her mind is way off somewhere else.''
chrissie and her mother sat expressionless as the doctors later told them that ritalin and psychological counseling ``should make a difference.''
her mother expressed mild surprise over the prescription. ``ritalin has a bad name,'' she said after the doctors had left the room. ``i was somewhat surprised because i associated ritalin with hyperactivity.''
how is chrissie doing? after six weeks of ritalin and counseling, chrissie's teachers told doctors she had shown mild improvement in attention span and a marked improvement in her ability to sit still and stick to school work. even with an increase in dosage, to 30 milligrams a day, she has exhibited no side effects
progress, but no quick miracles, then, for chrissie. the ritalin therapy continues. iii-clinic</note>
one of jane easton's pupils takes the drug ritalin to calm his hyperactivity and help him pay attention. she challenged a visitor to guess who
chris was the obvious choice. seated with three other boys at a semicircular desk in a special education class at scotch elementary school, the third-grader fidgeted in his chair, got up several times to sharpen his pencil, drummed his fingers, asked questions repeatedly and never seemed to hear the answers
the guess was wrong. instead, the child on ritalin was a slender boy with flaming red hair who calmly sailed through a reading comprehension quiz and listened attentively to a lesson on homonyms. easton says he's doing so well he probably will leave handicapped classes forever in the fall
at scotch elementary, they believe in ritalin _ and teachers point to cases like these to vindicate their faith in the controversial drug
far from thinking ritalin creates passive ``zombies,'' as some critics have charged, teachers and parents alike in this affluent northwest detroit suburb seem convinced of ritalin's track record for turning emotional and academic despair into success
grades and attention span often improve, and some youngsters who might have spent entire school careers isolated in classes for the disabled have managed to rejoin their regular peers with the help of the drug
most of all, teachers like easton resent the assertion by some that ritalin is merely a cynical way for schools to silence problem children while claiming they are trying to help them
i read that this is the way we treat kids we can't handle. it's not true. it's just not true,'' said easton, whose daughter has taken the drug for four years
while an estimated 1-2 percent of the nation's 40 million schoolchildren take ritalin, dr. paul h. wender, a salt lake city psychiatrist and author of several books on attention deficit disorder, or add, believes 3-to-10 percent of all children have hyperactivity problems
at scotch elementary, approximately 5 percent of the 550 pupils drop by principal carl childress's office each day to take a pill
several elements help explain why ritalin is commonplace at scotch elementary; teachers and school administrators have attended seminars and taken other training to recognize symptoms of add. area doctors are not only willing to prescribe ritalin but also to work with teachers and schools to monitor its success. and parents generally seem to accept the professionalism, good faith and judgment of the teachers and doctors
when you first start talking to parents about this, they're devastated,'' said principal carl childress. ``then 90 percent react that it is a medical problem.''
childress tells of a youngster named george who has taken ritalin for two years. he had been assigned to a ``resource room,'' where handicapped children get individual instruction for part of each day
he had an incident every day of losing his temper, punching someone or screaming in vile terms,'' said childress. ``now he's out of special education. he's a winner.''
childress, like other educators, insists ``we never recommend medication.'' but that's only partly true. if the school's psychologist, social worker or reading specialist believes a child has add, they know which doctors will nearly always prescribe ritalin
at the top of the list is dr. ruth robin, a pediatrician who operates the attention deficit center in nearby southfield, mich. schools from all over michigan and northern ohio recommend her, and prospective patients often wait 6-8 weeks for an appointment. she now treats 1,500 youngsters for add, some as young as 3. almost invariably, she prescribes ritalin or similar medication
i work magic with the medicine,'' she said in an interview in her office. ``i'm willing to try things
we're talking about large numbers of kids who are getting a bum steer in life, from kindergarten on. some look like couch potatoes. they don't all look alike,'' she said
but even ritalin's advocates admit it isn't always well-monitored. teachers are supposed to provide crucial information enabling doctors to set the right dosage, or to determine if drugs are necessary at all to academic success
such monitoring is frequent when medication first begins. after that, ``there really isn't that much to do unless there's a problem,'' the doctor said
childress said robin and other add specialists typically send teachers questionnaires to fill out for the first 2-4 weeks of medication, then gradually less frequently until ``we feel we're on a steady course. at a certain point we step out of the picture unless the teacher notices a problem.''
still, ritalin remains a ``last resort,'' said childress. teachers might, for example, put distractible children in study carrels _ desks with three sides blocked off so the child can't see in front or to either side
but when ``we've exhausted all those things ... logged the classroom observations,'' childress said, ``we would just as soon get a recommendation to try something else.''
utah is a state of large, close-knit families whose religion frowns on the use of liquor and caffeine. it is also a state with the nation's largest appetite for the stimulant drug ritalin
the drug enforcement administration said that in 1986 pharmacies along the state's wasatch front received 25,000 grams of the drug used for hyperactive children, or 1,558 grams for every 100,000 population
that figure compares to 1,218 grams per 100,000 residents of maryland, the next highest ritalin state. in new york, the figure was 347 grams per 100,000
the reasons for utah's high use of ritalin are many. they may point the way for the future in other parts of the country
what we are doing here is, in some ways, ahead of many parts of the country,'' said paul wender, a psychiatrist and researcher at the university of utah
utah has the youngest population of any state, with nearly a quarter of its residents aged 5 to 17. it also leads the nation in the size of individual families, about 4.3 children per household
consequently it has the nation's most crowded classrooms with 24.6 students per teacher. although utah ranks near the top of the list in the amount of state money, 47 percent, going to education, it is last in per capita spending on education, at $2,372 per student
so when the fragile balance in these overcrowded classrooms is threatened by disruptive children, ``the pressures on parents and teachers are going to lead people to look for solutions ... and one of the solutions is medication,'' said stevan kukic, state director of special education
in the salt lake school district, an estimated 2 percent of the 60,000 students receive ritalin or one of its cousins for attention deficit disorder, a syndrome that includes hyperactive as well as inattentive pupils
it is becoming more acceptable in the parents' minds and the teachers' minds,'' said julie miller, a special education teacher whose son takes ritalin. ``when the teachers see the dramatic effect it can have on problem students, they want them medicated so they can learn.''
sam goldstein, a psychologist who saw 100 add children at his clinic last year, estimates a quarter of his patients are referred by the schools. another 25 percent come at the suggestion of other parents whose children take ritalin. half his patients were sent by pediatricans
utah's medical community also contributes to ritalin use. reseachers at the university of utah are considered leaders in add study. their philosophies are passed on to their students, many of whom later set up practice nearby
as a result, salt lake has three clinics that specialize in the diagnosis and treatment of add children _ many larger cities across the country have none. psychologists, psychiatrists and pediatricians share information and refer patients for treatment
in a community this size it is easier to make an impact with an idea, especially an idea that appeals to people,'' said goldstein
parents of add children describe their successes with ritalin as more than appealing. kathy miner cries when she talks about the effect ritalin has had on her 11-year-old son, jeremy
there has been such a remarkable change in this child,'' she said. ``from the time he was 7 he talked about suicide. now he's on the student council and is so thrilled with life.''
mrs. miner has joined others in a local support group for add parents. the gatherings can be emotional: laughter about the bruises and stitches their children have collected while rocketing around the house, tears as they talk about the difference treatment has brought
i wanted to share the knowledge with other families,'' said the group's founder, terri steineckert, whose son, tyler, 11, has taken ritalin for more than a year. ``it is very traumatic to put a child on drugs, but if you have a good experience, you're converted,'' she said. georgia</head>
fifteen years since six members of the alday family were murdered on their farm, shock has turned to bitter impatience as retrials of three defendants threaten to take the case into the next decade
the retrials, ordered despite what a federal court called obvious guilt, have burdened tiny, rural seminole county
tucked into georgia's southwest corner and with just 9,500 people, seminole county has about $1 million a year to spend. the cost of the appeals is expected to exceed $600,000. other counties are holding the retrials, but they send their bills to seminole, the site of the murders
the second retrial, of wayne coleman, 41, starts monday in decatur
judicial juggling replaced questions of guilt or innocence years ago, and that rankles here, where concepts of right and wrong are stark and pure
ned alday, 62, his brother aubrey, 57, and sons jerry, 35, jimmy, 30, and chester, 25, were shot to death in jerry's trailer as they arrived singly or in pairs may 14, 1973. jerry's wife, mary, 26, was raped there, driven to a field six miles away, raped and sodomized again and shot twice in the back
their graves, marked by a $20,000 black marble slab, lie near a cedar tree planted more than a century ago at spring hill baptist church by isaac alday
an irrigation well stands on the site of the trailer 12 miles from donalsonville
but faded ``remember the aldays'' stickers remain on a few vehicles, and in the local courthouse is a cartoon depicting the appellate judges who overturned the convictions as the three stooges. ``remember them in may during `respect for law week,''' reads the caption
there won't be justice for the alday family until (the killers) all fry,'' said eddie gail, nursing a soft drink at the local pool hall. ``the court found them guilty, they know they're guilty, and that should be the end of it.''
coleman, then 26 years old, his half-brother carl isaacs, 19, and george dungee, 35,, all escapees from a maryland prison farm, were arrested in west virginia shortly after the killings
mary alday's wristwatch was in dungee's pocket. the men had three of the weapons used to kill the aldays. coleman's confession was read in court
the three were tried separately in donalsonville and sentenced in 1974 to die
billy isaacs, carl's 15-year-old brother, had been picked up in baltimore county after the prison break. a witness to the murders, he turned state's evidence and was sentenced to 40 years in prison
billy testified that carl laughed after killing aubrey alday. ``i asked him what was so funny,'' billy recalled. ``he said, `that bastard begged for mercy.'''
he testified his brother shot four of the victims and that coleman and dungee killed one each. some of the aldays were shot in the head as many as seven times
in 1985 the 11th u.s. circuit court of appeals, while citing ``overwhelming evidence of ... guilt,'' ruled there also was ``overwhelming evidence that the community had prejudiced both guilt and sentence.''
a lower court had ruled that the convictions and sentences were based on ``the overwhelmingly uncontroverted evidence of their willful participation in what is generally regarded as the most heinous criminal orgy in the history of the state.''
but the appellate ruling held that the trials should have been moved because of pre-trial publicity and inflammatory statements by some officials. failure to overturn the convictions, it said, ``would mean an obviously guilty defendant would have no right to a fair trial.''
more than 100,000 people signed petitions calling for the impeachment of the three judges, but the u.s. supreme court upheld their decision
the judges and lawyers that did that are the ones who should be hung first,'' said mel johnson, who operates a crossroads store not far from where the aldays are buried
he said time had not dulled emotions
when people around here get to talking about it, they get so mad they almost start to fight,'' he said. ``it's still very much alive. and not a day goes by but what someone doesn't stop by here and ask for directions to the cemetery, people from all walks of life, some of them from as far as new york.''
according to retrial testimony, the defendants were heading back to maryland from florida in a stolen car. they were burglarizing the trailer when aldays started arriving
in 1977, carl isaacs, in a television documentary interview, said the four were after money but didn't want to go back to jail. ``we figured that they couldn't take us back to prison if they couldn't talk.''
isaacs was retried earlier this year in perry, convicted and sentenced again to death. dungee will be retried in columbus later
meanwhile, the bills for everything from lawyers to false teeth keep piling up
since 1985, seminole county has paid about $327,400, most of it to other counties for lodging the prisoners, holding hearings, transportation, security and lawyers' fees
county clerk bobby nichols said costs for the isaacs trial were about $160,000, and he wasn't optimistic that costs for coleman's retrial would be lower
(houston county, where isaacs was tried) charged us $890 just for opening and closing the courtroom. they called it extra custodial service. when isaacs needed a new suit to go to trial in, we paid for that.''
coleman has no teeth. at a recent competency hearing, for which seminole county also paid, his lawyers asked that he be provided dentures for the trial
in july of 1987, we provided him with upper and lower dentures at a cost of $350,'' nichols said with a frown. ``if it were up to me he wouldn't get another set.''
he said seminole county is feeling the pinch
we have been able to continue basic services thus far,'' he said. ``i don't know how much longer we will be able to. we depend on agriculture here, and agriculture is in disarray with foreclosures and all.''
the county borrowed $210,000 so it could function while it paid retrial costs
if we don't get a lot more help from the state it could leave us in a very precarious way,'' he said. the state has paid $153,000 so far
nichols said the cost of the initial trials was less than $10,000, and each lasted less than a week. lawyers say appeals could last another decade
at eds pool room, as in the rest of donalsonville, memories of the aldays and the killings are becoming the stuff of legend
the small group gathered there remembered ned alday as a man who could stretch facts to transparent thinness
but he only told lies on himself,'' said one patron quickly. ``they used to say about him that he had to hire (someone) to call his hogs because he told so many lies his hogs wouldn't believe him.''
there was a silence
people liked ned,'' eddie gail said. ``and those boys was good boys, as far as i knew. and she was a good woman.''
michael dukakis' cousins in greece like to tell how his father ran away from his home on the turkish mainland to a merchant uncle who lived on the greek island of mytilene, after being forbidden to leave for america
a telegram was sent home saying that young panos was safe. ``and the answer came, `tie him up in a bundle if necessary and send him back,''' said elly petridou, a retired bank employee who still lives on the island
but my grandfather _ panos' uncle _ knew the future lay in america and didn't obey,'' she said. ``instead, he found panos an english teacher and later on paid his fare from mytilene to america. ... and eventually his parents followed him there.''
that was early in this century. today, at least a few ``mike dukakis-president'' stickers are showing up as far away from america as this northern aegean island where his father lived, as greek interest grows in the massachusetts governor's campaign for the white house
greek television newscasts lead off with coverage of the u.s. primaries, and athens newspapers run front-page stories detailing dukakis' progress
politicians and analysts discuss the 54-year-old democrat's lack of experience in foreign affairs. and they study his campaign speeches for clues to what might be future american policy
dukakis, in interviews with greek media, stresses his greek heritage. but he avoids comment on eastern mediterranean disputes such as the greek-turkish disagreement over aegean oil rights and the divided island of cyprus
a mix of pride and caution marks the mood among the half-dozen cousins and their families who make up the dukakis clan in greece
we all think mike is an exceptional person and we're convinced he'll win the democratic nomination. but that's still a long way from getting to the white house,'' patra zourelli, a second cousin who lives on mytilene _ also known as lesbos _ said in an interview
from a political standpoint in the united states, ``i can tell you it's an advantage to be an immigrant's son,'' dukakis was recently quoted as telling the athens daily vrathyni. ``the minorities see in me their children's opportunity to get ahead.''
dukakis' father, panos, became a respected family doctor in brookline, mass. his mother, euterpe, now 83 and campaigning actively for her son, was one of the first greek-american women to qualify as a teacher
dukakis is probably unique in that his parents made it to the professional classes. ... usually it's the second generation which makes that jump,'' alexander kitroeff, a historian who teaches at queens college, new york, said in a telephone interview
dukakis' father was the youngest of four brothers who left greece as teen-agers in the early 1900s. it was a time when greeks flocked to america, working in textile factories, flower stalls and shoeshine parlors to escape dire poverty at home
mytilene, lying close to turkey and covered with millions of olive trees, boasts a literary tradition that began in the 7th century b.c. with sappho, europe's first woman poet. another lyric poet from the island, odysseus elytis, won the nobel prize for literature in 1979
the dukakis family came from pelopi, a cluster of stone houses reached by a dirt road winding up mytilene's highest mountain and still considered one of the poorest villages on the island
dukakis' grandfather moved away in the 1880s to make a better life on the nearby coast of turkey, where greeks prospered as store-owners and merchants
mike's grandfather and mine were cousins who both left the village of pelopi and settled in edremit on the turkish side. his grandfather ran a general store and mine ran a bakery,'' george grigoriou-dukakis, 76, a retired agronomist, said in an interview
the dukakis property at the top of the village was sold in 1933 and yiannis manolis, the villager who bought it, keeps the yellowed sale contract in his pocket
i want to stay around long enough to welcome michalis back here as president,'' said manolis, 81, who lives in a two-story house he built on the ruins of the dukakis home
there are no records surviving to clarify whether dukakis' father was born on mytilene _ then ruled by turkey _ or in edremit
dukakis' mother was born in the northern city of larissa, then a sleepy farm town but now a booming center for the thessaly region
cousin euterpe is a tough lady who'd be called a feminist if she were young now. ... her family all left for the states in the early 1900s after losing their land to the turks,'' said nikos milingos, a third cousin who runs a farm chemicals business
like most of the relatives, the milingos family first met dukakis when he came to greece in 1976 during his first term as governor. now they visit massachussetts regularly
we found him very warm and welcoming, but he's certainly a man of principle,'' said olympia milingos. ``when we went for dinner at their home in the days of energy-saving, euterpe told us to take sweaters because the heating would be low _ and it was.''
the greek-american community in the united states, numbering between 1 million and 3 million by various estimates, is pouring in funds to back its ``patrida'' (homeland) candidate
according to dukakis aides, around 25 percent of his first $15 million in campaign funds came from greek-americans
apart from the wish to claim a u.s. president of greek descent, many in greece say that dukakis' election would repair the damage to their self-image caused by former vice president spiro agnew
spiro agnew was an embarrassment to greece and the migrant tradition. it's a bad memory for us that we'd like to erase through dukakis,'' said former culture minister dimitris nianias, a member of parliament for mytilene
it is the evening of april 4, 1968. the rev. martin luther king jr. leans over a balcony railing at the lorraine motel. the crack of a single shot from a high-powered rifle shatters the air
suddenly, he's gone
this much is clearly documented. but who killed the 39-year-old civil rights leader and winner of the nobel peace prize?
james earl ray, the small-time thief who pleaded guilty, has spent the past 20 years trying to prove he didn't do it. he talks of a shadowy ``raoul.''
other principals in the case hold widely varying opinions: ray's attorneys disagree on whether he was the triggerman; the prosecutor acknowledges he wasn't confident about the case; the chairman of a congressional committee that studied the assassination says he still thinks ray was part of a larger, unsolved conspiracy
the questions remain. what of the cigarette butts found in the getaway car _ given that ray did not smoke? what of the clothing in two sizes in the car's trunk?
the fatal shot came from a communal bathroom at the rear of a flophouse across a narrow street from the lorraine motel. ray maintains he was not in that bathroom when the shot was fired
i was a few blocks away, trying to get a tire fixed on my car,'' he said in a recent interview with the associated press at brushy mountain state prison, where he is serving a 99-year sentence. ``when i started back to my room i saw a police roadblock had been set up; it was about that time that i heard on my car radio king had been shot and the police were looking for a man in a white mustang, the same kind of car i was driving, so i took off for atlanta.''
ray, who had checked into the rooming house the day king was killed, said he was in memphis to take part in an illicit gun-running scheme. he said the scheme was concocted by a mystery man named raoul, an international smuggler whom ray contends he met several months earlier at a waterfront bar in montreal
he also says raoul, whom he describes as a blond man with a latin american accent, set him up to be framed for king's murder
the fact is i don't know who killed king,'' said ray, who recently turned 60. ``i only pleaded guilty because i was desperate. i had been in isolation for eight months in the memphis jail, and percy foreman was pressuring me to cop a plea. he was telling me my family would get in trouble and i'd get the death penalty if i didn't do what he said.''
foreman, the houston attorney who represented ray when he entered his guilty plea march 10, 1969, angrily disputes these assertions
the s.o.b. got down on his knees and thanked me for saving his life when i told him i had gotten the prosecutor to go along with a guilty plea,'' foreman said when contacted in houston recently
foreman, now in his mid-80s, says he thinks ray was extremely fortunate not to have stood trial. he also rejects ray's story about raoul. ``i think he acted alone,'' he said
asked what might have motivated ray to commit such an act, foreman said, ``it was racism. his conversations simply steamed with racist remarks.''
ray, who was a fugitive from the missouri state penitentiary at the time king was killed, denies he harbored any ill will toward king and defies anyone to prove otherwise
king was just another politician to me,'' he said. ``why would i want to do something like kill a big-shot politician, me a fugitive, and bring all that heat down on myself?''
he admits buying the rifle, a remington gamemaster, 30.06 caliber, that authorities say was the murder weapon. but he says he bought, at a birmingham, ala., gun shop, at raoul's instruction and with money provided by raoul
i gave the rifle to raoul,'' ray said. ``if i had been buying it to kill king, you can bet i wouldn't have bought it at a gun shop. i would have gotten it from a fence, so it couldn't have been traced.''
birmingham lawyer arthur hanes sr. said he tends to believe that story. he represented ray for four months before foreman
i've never believed ray shot king,'' said hanes, a former fbi agent and one-time birmingham mayor. ``i personally stood in that flophouse bathroom and looked across to the motel balcony where the rev. king was standing when he was shot. it was a difficult angle. ray simply didn't have enough expertise with rifles to make a shot like that, in my opinion.''
hanes also said he had never heard ray utter a single racist statement
i've given this case a lot of thought, and i've concluded someone assisted ray,'' he added, ``but i can't say who.''
the case should have gone to trial, he said, ``to clear the air, if nothing else. i tried to get the judge to try the case, but he said there was too much pressure, from the government and the memphis business community, to accept a guilty plea and avoid the publicity that a trial would generate.''
the judge, w. preston battle, died a week after ray's guilty plea. however, the chief prosecutor, philip canale, acknowledged last week that, contrary to foreman's assertion, he had been happy to get a plea from ray
it would have been a big, time-consuming and expensive trial with dozens and dozens of witnesses from all over the country,'' said canale, now an assistant u.s. attorney in memphis. ``i have never regretted the guilty plea because we got a substantial sentence. also, i didn't want to take a chance on getting a cranky juror and having a mistrial.''
canale added that although he had no eyewitness and the evidence against ray was largely circumstantial, he doesn't buy the conspiracy theory
i think he acted alone,'' he said, noting that the fbi had found ray's fingerprint on the rifle discarded by the gunman near the scene of the crime
however, supporters of ray's story say his fingerprint was on the rifle because he had purchased it. they also note that, while ray is a lifelong non-smoker, viceroy cigarette butts were found in the rooming house bathroom and in his car ashtray, and that two sizes of clothing were found in his trunk
ray said the fact that raoul often used his car may explain the butts in the ashtray and clothes in the trunk. ``as for cigarettes in the bathroom i can't say because i was never in that bathroom,'' he said. ``my prints were never found in there, you know.''
then there were the two white mustangs. the late guy canipe, whose amusement company was located next door to the flophouse, told investigators he saw a fleeing man ditch a rifle and a small overnight bag in front of his store and then drive away in a white mustang, one of two that had been parked in front of the store that afternoon. he described the man as having dark hair and a beard
ray, who was captured in london two months after king's death, says the fact that the gunman ditched the rifle and his bag _ which ray says he had left in his room when he went to get the tire fixed _ shows somebody was trying to frame him
why would i have dumped my stuff there for the police to find when all i had to do was put it in the car and drive away?'' he asked
after two years of hearings, ending in 1978, the house select committee on assassinations couldn't answer that question. the committee issued a report saying ray probably had been part of a larger conspiracy
but while the committee couldn't say who else had participated in the plot, it did exonerate the cia and fbi, both of which had conducted extensive illegal surveillance and smear campaigns against king throughout the 1960s. former fbi director j. edgar hoover was known to have hated king
fbi agents testified that no evidence could be found of conspiracies involving the mafia, ku klux klan or foreign communists
some of king's friends, however, still feel that letting hoover's fbi investigate king's assassination was like letting a hungry fox guard a henhouse
i have no proof but i feel in my heart that the government, probably the fbi and j. edgar hoover, and perhaps the cia, were involved,'' says the rev. ralph david abernathy, who was with king when he died in a memphis hospital an hour after the shooting
it's just a pity but, given the way things were back then, we'll probably never know the whole truth about one of the greatest tragedies of our time.''
strat douthat is the ap southeast regional reporter, based in atlanta
james earl ray has spent most of his ``free time'' at brushy mountain state prison plotting ways to get out, either by going over the wall or into a courtroom
so far, he's been more successful at breaking out. in 1977, inmate no. 65477 managed to scale the wall and remain free for three days before being apprehended in the rugged hills near the prison
a couple of years earlier, he escaped from his cell through an air vent only to be captured inside the prison walls a few hours later
but the 60-year-old alton, ill., native hasn't been able to get back into court since march 10, 1969, the day he pleaded guilty to killing the rev. martin luther king jr
and although he is doggedly determined to win a day in court, ray apparently has become more resigned to prison life than he was in his escape-artist days, which included a 1967 breakout from the missouri state penitentiary, where he was serving 20 years for armed robbery
he's a good inmate,'' said james worthington, an officer at brushy mountain, a maximum security prison 40 miles west of knoxville. ``he does good time and doesn't cause us any trouble _ not of late, anyway.''
ray works in the prison laundry, earning $1 a day. he shares an 11-by-8-foot cell with another inmate and spends most of his weekends in the prison law library
i work five days a week, from 7 a.m. to 3 o'clock in the afternoon,'' he said in a recent interview with the associated press. ``we get an hour a day for exercise in the yard through the week and two hours on saturdays and sundays.''
he maintained, as he has ever since pleading guilty, that he didn't kill king and doesn't know who did. he said he pleaded guilty only because he was pressured into it
ray speaks in a quiet but determined voice when discussing his legal problems. although he has spent nearly half of his life behind bars he still looks fit: his hair is dark, with white sideburns, his dark blue eyes are alert and his body is trim in a blue denim uniform
it's always a good idea to keep fit in prison,'' he said, rubbing a scar on his left cheek, the result of an attack by three black inmates in 1980. two of his attackers got 60-year sentences for attempted murder, and the third was given 20 years
i got careless for a moment,'' he said, recalling the assault. ``like a fool i went into the law library when there were no guards present. but, then i was lucky, too; they stabbed me in the arm, face and chest but never hit an artery.''
worthington describes ray as a quiet loner who usually keeps to himself when he goes out to the prison yard for exercise with other prisoners
although married in 1983 to a nashville artist who was teaching art appreciation to inmates, ray hasn't had a visitor since last fall. to pass the time, he reads and paints _ mostly watercolor landscapes from memory
he recently helped prepare a second edition of his autobiography, which he said he wrote to tell his side of the story about the king assassination
as for his 99-year sentence, he said, ``i really don't think i should have had to spend all this time in prison. i didn't kill anybody.''
strat douthat is the ap southeast regional reporter, based in atlanta
a day of reckoning for the rival suitors of federated department stores inc. passed without ushering one of them _ campeau corp. or r.h. macy &amp; co. _ to the altar, but it appeared macy raised the stakes in the $6 billion takeover battle
federated's board of directors was expected to choose between the companies' final bids wednesday, but deliberations dragged on all day and into the night with no sign of an end to the 2-month-old contest
federated spokesman jim sluzewski said late wednesday evening he did not know when a decision would be announced
american stores co. stock soared amid market rumors that lucky stores inc. might be planning a ``pac-man'' takeover bid to counter its supermarket rival's acquisition offer
american stores has launched a $45-a-share tender offer for lucky, which would produce a deal worth about $1.74 billion. american later said it would boost the offer to $50 a share, or $1.93 billion, if lucky's management supported the acquistion
lucky declined to comment wednesday, but analysts said lucky might be considering making its own bid for american stores. in new york stock exchange trading, american stores jumped $2.75 a share to $59.75, while lucky fell $1.50 a share to $48.37{
the second consecutive monthly decline in orders to u.s. factories for manufactured goods is no cause for alarm, analysts say
the commerce department said wednesday that orders for durable and non-durable goods dropped 0.8 percent to a seasonally adjusted $210.86 billion last month following a 0.6 percent decline in january
economists said while businesses cut back on orders in the early part of the year, the cutbacks were moderate and may set the stage for faster growth
contracting for future construction projects jumped 10 percent in february, recouping january's 8 percent decline, a new report says
the survey, released wednesday by the f.w. dodge division of mcgraw-hill information systems co., estimated the annualized value of all newly started construction projects in february at $249.7 billion, the highest level since last october
prices farmers got for raw products this month were unchanged from february and up 7.4 percent from a year earlier, the agriculture department says
the department's agricultural statistics board reported wednesday higher prices for lettuce, cattle, eggs and broiler chickens, while farmers received lower prices for hogs, milk, wheat and sweet corn
consumer food prices are expected to rise 2 percent to 4 percent this year, compared with a 4.2 percent average increase in 1987, the government says
five japanese automakers have been dumping small trucks on the u.s. market, costing u.s. workers jobs and the u.s. auto industry $500 million in lost wages, sales and profits, a study commissioned by u.s. automakers says
the 42-page study released wednesday said the five japanese companies are illegally selling compact pickup trucks for 10 percent to 48 percent less in the united states than they charge in their japanese home market
one of the companies accused, toyota motor corp., immediately denied the charges. the study was conducted on behalf of the big three u.s. automakers
the internal revenue service says it will waive penalties for underpayments of estimated tax on most types of retirement income for 1987
the agency earlier had decided not to impose such penalties on wages earned in 1987, because of widespread confusion about the new tax law and a complex w-4 withholding form
in another decision affecting retirees, the irs said wednesday that owners of multiple individual retirement accounts who passed the age of 70{ in 1987 will be allowed more discretion in choosing from which account to take a distribution. such owners are required to take money from an ira by april 1
federal spending averaged nearly $3,433 per american in 1987, about $41 more than the year before, the census bureau says
alaska led, with u.s. spending there averaging $5,421, more than double the $2,536 spent per resident in last-place wisconsin, according to the report released wednesday
if it were a state, the district of columbia would be the easy winner, however, with spending averging $23,360 per capita
treasury secretary james a. baker iii says he strongly disagrees with proposals to forgive some of the third world's $1 trillion debt
i believe this path leads both debtors and creditors off the cliff,'' baker told a senate panel on wednesday. ``this approach would irreparably politicize the debt problem.''
he argued for a u.s. contribution to increase the capital of the world bank, the largest single source of aid loans to third world countries
thursday is the last day to qualify for the big airlines' triple-mileage programs, and travelers have been flocking to the skies to beat the deadline
to drum up business in the slow winter months, the major airlines offered to triple all mileage credits accumulated by participants in frequent-flier programs this year _ if the member took at least one round-trip or two one-way flights on that carrier by the end of the day thursday
the deadline, coupled with the approach of easter and school vacations, seems to have touched off a flying spree, travel experts said wednesday
mcdonnell douglas corp. became the pentagon's top research contractor in fiscal 1987, winning awards totaling $1.7 billion, the defense department says
among educational and non-profit entities, the massachusetts institute of technology continued to hold down the top ranking, winning research contracts during the year worth $407.6 million, the pentagon reported wednesday
overall, the pentagon increased its spending on research by more than 10 percent during fiscal 1987, with awards reaching a grand total of $21.8 billion. that compared with $19.8 billion in fiscal 1986
stock prices finished lower wednesday as an early advance was wiped out in a late-afternoon decline that sent the dow jones average of 30 industrials down 20.22 at 1,978.12
the dollar fell despite modest central bank intervention
bond prices were mostly lower in light trading
platinum futures prices soared, copper and precious metals futures advanced, energy futures were higher and livestock and meat prices retreated
a positive new report on u.s. stocks of refined oil products has helped lift oil prices out of a temporary slump
on the new york mercantile exchange, contracts for may delivery of west texas intermediate, the benchmark u.s. crude oil, settled wednesday at $17.08 per 42-gallon barrel, up 10 cents from tuesday's close
among refined products, the april contract for wholesale heating oil jumped 0.45 cent a gallon to 48.60 cents. unleaded gasoline for april rose by 0.39 cent a gallon to 48.65 cents
trading on the exchange was described as light, muted by the approach of the easter holiday weekend
the advance came on the heels of a modest decline on tuesday _ which had broken a four-day rally as many investors sold futures contracts and took profits
the recent strength stems from hopes that the pricing committee of the 13-nation organization of petroleum exporting countries will achieve an agreement to prop up prices, analysts say. the pricing panel is due to meet in vienna, austria, starting april 9
prices have risen in nine of the last 12 trading sessions on the mercantile exchange
traders said prices got an additional boost in wednesday's session from the latest weekly report on u.s. oil stocks compiled by the american petroleum institute, an industry group based in washington
the api statistics, released after the market closed on tuesday, showed substantial drawdowns in stocks of both gasoline and heating oil in the week ended march 25 compared with the previous week
the decrease in product inventories was seen as indicating a continued robust demand, analysts said
we had a fairly rational reaction here'' to the api figures, said bob baker, an oil futures analyst for prudential-bache securities inc
economists shrugged off an 0.8 percent decline in orders to u.s. factories for manufactured goods during february, even though it represented the second consecutive monthly decline
the financial markets put in a mixed performance wednesday. on wall street, the stock market faltered but the dollar showed signs of steadying in foreign exchange, where the british pound stole center stage. bond prices were little changed
orders for durable and non-durable goods dropped to a seasonally adjusted $210.86 billion last month following a 0.6 percent decline in january, the commerce department said
the february setback was the biggest since a 1.4 percent drop last august and marked the first time that factory orders have fallen for two consecutive months since the summer of 1986
economists said the declines indicated that businesses cut back on orders in the early part of the year to help trim high levels of unsold goods that had built up in the final quarter of 1987
while this process will dampen growth, economists said it appeared that the cutbacks had been moderate and would set the stage for faster growth in the months ahead
on wall street, the dow jones average of 30 industrials, up more than 10 points in the early going, closed with a 20.22-point loss at 1,978.12
investors were reluctant to take large positions ahead of the upcoming three-day easter weekend
the dollar showed signs of steadying after a wave of tumbles, but it was the pound that posted far greater gains, rising in new york to $1.8780 from $1.86425
in the past seven years, the pound has hit a low of $1.0470, in february 1985, and a high of $2.4525 in november 1980
in jumping to its highest levels in two years, the british currency has been boosted by a strong economy, britain's relatively high interest rates and prime minister margaret thatcher's unrelenting grip on inflation
bond prices eased slightly. the treasury's bellwether 30-year issue fell 7-32 point, or about $2.50 per $1,000 in face value, to yield 8.77 percent
oil prices rebounded from a temporary setback. on the new york mercantile exchange, contracts for may delivery of west texas intermediate, the benchmark u.s. crude oil, settled at $17.08 per 42-gallon barrel, up 10 cents from tuesday's close
switzerland has displaced west germany as the world's second most creditworthy nation behind japan, a new survey of international bankers reveals
the united states _ for many years the bankers' no. 1 darling _ remains stuck in fourth place. and in general the world's bankers seem to be taking a gloomier view of the world debt situation
in a survey of 112 nations, institutional investor, an american financial magazine, finds that the average country's credit rating in march has dropped considerably from a similar survey last september
every six months the new york-based monthly asks about 100 international banks to rate the creditworthiness of more than 100 nations on a scale of 0 to 100. in the magazine's march survey japan ranks first with a score of 94.6, and north korea 112th with 4.0
the global average rating was 38.9, down 0.4 points from last september, and down 1.1 points from march 1987. institutional investor notes that this is the fourth consecutive drop from the peak of 40.6 attained in march 1986
countries with higher credit ratings generally find it easier to borrow from international commercial banks and are likely to obtain more favorable credit terms
the most stable region in recent surveys has been western europe,'' the magazine says, ``but this time it registered the biggest gain of any region, rising 0.6 points to 73.9.''
one banker noted that a rising german mark may cause export difficulties for west germany and it faces greater unemployment difficulties than switzerland
portugal's rating rose 2.2 points, thanks largely to ``an austerity program... european community entry, and...full-fledged transition to democracy.''
despite japan's pre-eminence, the asia-pacific region, comprising 19 countries ``led the decliners with a sizable 1.4 point fall'' in the average country rating
australia fell 2.2 points, the second-largest drop in the survey, due mainly to ``continued balance of payments deficits... and the fact that its borrowing has now reached a very high percentage of gross national product.''
the middle east, comprising 14 nations, was up an average 0.4 points ``largely because no news is good news for the region
the biggest gainer was cyprus, up 1.9 points, because of... consistent improvement in the current account.''
in eastern europe ``the big gainer was rumania, up 2.2 points because of increased banker confidence that it would maintain its repayment schedule.''
africa had more gainers than losers _ 14 nations to 11 _ yet its overall rating fell 0.3 points.''
the congo fell 2.0 points, the third-biggest drop in the survey,'' probably due in large part to a lack of financial information on the country
in north america the united states dropped 1.5 points, due mainly to the budget and foreign trade deficits and the decline of the dollar
in latin america ``brazil fell 2.3 points, the biggest decline in the survey'' because of political uncertainties and the lack of a coherent economic policy in the third world's biggest debtor nation
here is how 112 nations rank for creditworthiness, according to the latest six-month survey of bankers by institutional investor magazine
approximately 100 banks were asked to rate each country on a scale of 0 to 100, and the magazine then ranked the nations by their average rating
