lucky stores inc. may turn the tables on rival grocer american stores co. to thwart the pursuer's $1.74 billion buyout offer, analysts say
talk of the rarely used ``pac-man defense'' pushed american stores stock up $2.75 to $59.75 a share on the new york stock exchange wednesday, while lucky lost $1.50 a share to close at $48.37{
earlier this week american stores launched a $45-a-share tender offer for lucky. but the salt lake city-based supermarket giant later said it was prepared to boost the offer to $50 a share, or $1.93 billion, if lucky's management supported the acquisition
lucky has declined to comment on the offers, but analysts said rumors focused on whether lucky might be considering making its own bid for american stores
a combination of the two companies would rival kroger co. as the nation's largest supermarket operation
lucky stores spokeswoman lissa perlman said the company ``doesn't comment on rumors.'' the only comment lucky has made is that its board is studying american stores' two proposals
there has been conjecture all along about what options lucky might have,'' said jonathan ziegler, an analyst with the investment firm sutro &amp; co. in san francisco
ziegler noted that lucky, which operates in the lucrative california market, would have to take on a huge amount of debt to acquire american stores
analysts specualted lucky might be trying to put american stores stock ``in play'' on wall street to take the spotlight off itself
the rumors came a day after american stores chairman l.s. skaggs complained of ``various reports'' that lucky might be considering a ``defensive acquisition'' of another company to make itself financial unattractive
in a letter tuesday to lucky's board of directors, skaggs cautioned against a maneuver that could interfere with his company's takeover plans and warned that any attempt to ``frustrate the choice given to your shareholders through a defensive acquisition'' would affect american's willingness to increase its tender offer to $50 a share
skaggs reiterated that american stores would consider divesting stores if it acquired lucky, in order to mitigate any antitrust concerns that might exist
american stores is the nation's third largest grocery retailer with 1,700 stores and annual sales of $15 billion. lucky is the sixth largest with 480 stores and sales of $7 billion
american stores filed a lawsuit last week in delaware charging lucky and its executives with breaching their fiduciary duties by ``following a course of conduct directed toward entrenching themselves in control of lucky stores.''
as part of defensive measures taken over a year ago to stave off corporate raider asher edelman, lucky voted senior management lucrative ``golden parachute'' contracts and announced a restructuring plan that included changing the company's state of incorporation from california to delaware and a buy-back of 27 percent of its outstanding shares
the company has noted that its bylaws also contain an anti-takeover provision limiting the voting power of any shareholder who acquires more than 10 percent of lucky's stock
lotus development corp. has announced its blueprint tool kit, an upgraded product by lotus development corp. to give its computer users easy access to a wide range of non-lotus data bases
i tend to view this as a building block kind of an announcement,'' said david readerman, an analyst at smith barney &amp; co. in new york. ``they are trying to build a better connection between third-party data bases and their own pc software tools.''
it fits in their long-term strategy,'' said john maxwell iii of dillon read &amp; co. inc. in new york. ``it's a positive step for the future.''
analysts say blueprint is part of lotus' strategy to expand applications for its software in a period of increased competition from spreadsheet manufacturers, such as borland international corp. of scotts valley, calif
lotus stock rebounded slightly following wednesday's announcement
the stock had tumbled nearly $7 a share since last week after the cambridge-based firm announced plans to delay release of the lotus 1-2-3 release 3 spreadsheet software until the fourth quarter. the delay caused analysts to cut 1988 per-share earnings estimates from about $1.95 to about $1.50
lotus stock closed up 50 cents a share to $22.50 in over-the-counter trading wednesday
the blueprint kit, scheduled to be released late this year, will aid data base manufacturers in creating drives that will greatly streamline the process of accessing software not specially designed for lotus systems, said lotus spokeswoman betsy kosheff
the drives will be sold to consumers by data base firms including oracle corp. of belmont, calif., which has formally announced plans to place a blueprint drive in its upcoming product line. other firms expressing interest in blueprint include microrim inc., pc publishing inc. and synex systems corp., according to the lotus statement
kosheff said the drive will allow lotus system users to hit one key to connect with various data bases, rather than the many steps now required. data obtained through blueprint drives will be compatible with existing and planned lotus software, including spreadsheets and graphics, she said
lotus spokesman philip greenough said blueprint is an enhancement of application connection, a lotus-created data base connection drive introduced in 1986
the blueprint drives will be available for use on all sizes of lotus computer systems, said greenough
the dollar fell against all major currencies in early european trading today. gold prices rose
