house and senate negotiators broke a longstanding deadlock today and moved to place sharp import curbs on toshiba corp. and a subsidiary for selling submarine-silencing equipment to the soviets
approval of the toshiba provision as part of a sweeping trade bill came despite reagan administration opposition and a major lobbying campaign by the japanese electronics manufacturer
on the eve of the action, several cabinet officials warned lawmakers that a stringent punishment for toshiba could precipitate a presidential veto of the 1,000-page trade bill. they said the president should have more flexibility in determining national security and trade relations with other countries
i was elected as a u.s. senator to represent the state of utah in the u.s. senate and not toshiba and not england and not the state department and not frank carlucci,'' declared sen. jake garn, r-utah, in urging lawmakers to defy administration opposition
he said he was embarrassed that a republican administration would fight the sanctions, adding, ``the state department has been kicked in the shins and instead of saying ouch they have chosen to surrender
the provision was accepted by a subcommittee of a house-senate conference committee working on a compromise version of the trade bill
it would ban for three years u.s. government procurement of toshiba corp. products. the company has massive sales within the united states of televisions, microwaves and other electronic products
it would ban import for three years of products manufactured by toshiba machine corp., the subsidiary involved with the norwegian firm of kongsberg vapenfabrikk in selling sophisticated computerized milling equipment to the soviets that the administration says has greatly submarine propeller noise
there would be exemptions for national security
the measure also provides for a two to five-year ban in the future on imports of products by foreign makers that violate the so-called cocom agreement under which western nations act to keep high-tech equipment with military uses out of communist hands. but the president could waive such action against parent companies in some cases
lawmakers are pushing to put the finishing touches on the trade bill before starting on their spring break
we're going to give it our best,'' sen. lloyd bentsen, d-texas, said wednesday as a house-senate conference committee plowed through a stack of proposals but stopped short of the big decisions
congress wants to have all the provisions wrapped up except a few minor loose ends before heading for its spring break at the end of the week
the committee, attempting to fashion a compromise between rival 1,000-page trade bills passed by the two houses, heard rep. richard gephardt, d-mo., appeal to lawmakers to save the heart of his controversial trade plan
the plan to force 10 percent annual reductions in unfair surpluses that other countries run with the united states formed the centerpiece of gephardt's abandoned campaign for president
he said any final version should focus on key countries that make unfair trade practices part of a systematic trade strategy. wholesale negotiations should be shunned in favor of working on major trade trouble spots, he said
mandatory retaliation is needed when negotiations fail, he said. ``you have to have a stick in the closet,'' he said. but he added that flexibility is necessary in dealing with trading partners and the president should have the power to waive retaliation
investor donald trump gave up his $22-a-share tender offer for the resorts international inc. stock he doesn't own, saying he is confident a takeover bid by entertainer-businessman merv griffin will never be approved
control of resorts international is now held by trump, who owns nearly all of resorts' 572,000 class b shares that have 100 votes each, giving him 88 percent of the company's voting power
on wednesday, griffin revised his offer for $36 a share for all of the company's class a stock and called for resorts to sell griffin 1.2 million new class b shares at the same price. the new stock would give griffin voting control
the company has 5.7 million class a common shares that have one vote each
trump said late wednesday he will return all tendered shares after his offer. the merger agreement expires at midnight tonight
trump said he will never sell his class b stock and will not pay more than $22 for class a stock
griffin said wednesday he is no longer making his offer contingent upon trump tendering his class b stock or terminating a five-year management contract valued at about $100 million for resorts' hotel-casinos in new jersey and the bahamas
consummation of the offer would result in griffin owning a majority of the voting power and more than 90 percent of the equity of resorts
trump would be able to participate in griffin's new offer only by converting his stock to class a shares
griffin, through his privately held investment firm, griffin co., made his revised offer to resorts' outside directors, noting he believes only those board members should vote on the proposal
the other directors have interests in mr. trump's competing bid,'' griffin said
three of resorts' six directors are nominees of trump, who is the company's chairman
resorts referred media inquiries to trump. trump's attorney, jack nusbaum of new york, said trump would continue to use his voting power to resist griffin's offer and it was unlikely resorts' outside directors would meet independently to consider the proposal
trump is offering $22 a share to buy the resorts stock he doesn't already own and take the company private
in mid-march, griffin countered with a bid of $35 a share, or $225 million, for all of the company's stock, but it was contingent upon trump tendering his stock and terminating the management pact. trump has repeatedly indicated he wouldn't agree to either contingency
griffin subsequently said he would boost his bid to $295 million, with resorts' board members able to decide how to apportion the additional $70 million between class a and class b holders. the move was seen as a way to pay a higher price to trump, but the new yorker again said he wasn't interested
long-distance calling options are many and prices are competitive, but residential consumers as well as small and larger businesses still can save money by shopping around, according to a private survey
the report by the telecommunications research &amp; action center shows that most of the long-distance companies offer various calling plans, each one benefiting different calling patterns
the nonprofit, consumer group recommends that residential consumers periodically compare available options _ annually for those whose long-distance costs are less than $10 per month and more often when monthly bills are more than $25
though cost gaps between competing companies and plans have narrowed, ``the risk in picking the wrong plan can result in paying substantially more in long-distance service,'' said samuel a. simon, a consultant to the consumer group
the survey outlined the options available from eight of the largest long-distance carriers and the costs, calculated in various call volumes, of the plans
the survey also compared costs for businesses that spend up to $8,000 a month on long-distance calling. for these business callers, some of the calling plans available _ including new ``virtual wats'' plans _ can save 25 percent over standard rates of even the lowest cost companies, trac says
unlike traditional wats service, the new ``virtual wats'' plans offered by all the major companies require no special installation or dedicated lines
the residential and small business comparisons include the option of access-code dialing, or casual calling, which allows a caller to reach a long-distance carrier other than their chosen one by dialing an access code, 10 plus a different three-digit number for each company. this option can be cheaper than some ``dial 1'' plans at lower call volumes, but volume discounts are generally not available with code dialing
a comparison of the costs for a sample residential monthly bill _ 20 calls totaling 380 minutes, 70 percent of which are calculated at night-weekend rates _ showed at&amp;t's reach out america bonus plan was the cheapest at $53.84
midamerica standard service followed at $54.06, us sprint standard service at $54.60, at&amp;t's reach out america basic plan at $55.14, us sprint 10333 and 10777 access at $55.24, mci standard rates at $55.62
when a sampling of 33 calls were priced, us sprint standard rates were least expensive, followed by us sprint 10333 and 10777 access, mci standard rates, mci's prime calling option and the at&amp;t reach out america plans
another sample of 20 calls, this time with 70 percent of the 380 minutes calculated at daytime rates, was analyzed to assess the costs a small business might pay. in that comparison, mci standard rates were least expensive at $88.88, followed by us sprint standard rates at $89.32, allnet standard service at $89.95, tdx standard service at $90.08, and mci 10222 access at $90.03
the survey's residential and small business results are available in a chart for $1, the business chart for $10. include a stamped, self-addressed, business-size envelope and mail to trac, p.o. box 12038, washington, d.c. 20005
cocoa prices reacted to forecasts of large world surpluses by falling thursday to their lowest levels in nearly six years, traders said
cocoa beans for may delivery fell to $1,692 a metric ton, $30 lower than overnight levels and their lowest price since mid-1982
traders said the market reflected the prospect of a fourth consecutive season of surpluses, with record world production forecast in the current season running from october 1987 to september 1988
international merchants gill and duffus said in a report released thursday that, based on expected record crops in the ivory coast, brazil and malaysia, it is forecasting 1987-88 world output to hit a record 2.106 million tons _ up six percent from 1986-87
they said this ``remarkable growth'' in production would cause output to exceed consumption by 122,000 metric tons, despite a 3.6 percent rise in consumption over 1986-87
such an imbalance would take accumulated inventories by the end of the present season to 713,000 tons, the highest since 1964-65, they said
the ivory coast crop is estimated to be 630,000 tons compared with 590,000 in 1986-87; brazil's 426,000 tons vs. 369,000; and malaysia's 190,000, up from 164,000
gill and duffus projected nigerian output will be 135,000 tons, up 55,000 tons from 1986-87 and the biggest since 1984-85. ghana's harvest is forecast at 185,000 tons, down slightly from 228,000 last season
the cocoa market has been regulated by supply and demand mechanisms since feb. 25 when intervention buying by the international cocoa organization was halted indefinitely because purchases had reached the maximum 250,000 tons permitted by treaty
importing and exporting member countries failed to agree on supplementary market-support schemes at a meeting here in march
the organization is not scheduled to meet again on the issue until september
domestic automakers were scheduled to produce 181,925 cars and trucks this week, down from last week's 237,295, ward's automotive reports said thursday
automakers produced 237,889 cars and trucks during the same week a year ago. they were were scheduled to make 116,970 cars this week, compared with 149,951 a week ago and 165,348 in the same week in 1987
truck production for the week was scheduled at 64,955, compared with last week's 87,344 and last year's 72,541
canadian automakers were to build 22,020 cars this week, compared with 26,492 last week and 16,670 in the same week last year. canadian truck production was scheduled at 15,319, compared with 20,266 last week and 17,948 in the same week last year
