in new public service commercials for the united way, a mugger tears a coat off the back of a homeless man, an assailant grabs an unsuspecting woman and an older man is felled at the office by a heart attack
by the end of the 30-second ads, the homeless man gets a new coat, the distraught woman dresses up to face the world again and the older man enjoys restored health on a beach
they each got help from agencies assisted by donations to the united way
roberta van der voort, a senior vice president of united way of america inc., said thursday that by showing people the ``vital link'' between their donations and good deeds, the ads may help dispell skepticism about charitable organizations
ruth wooden, president of the advertising council, the non-profit organization that oversees $1.1 billion a year in public service advertising, said the united way is the first organization to address the issues of homelessness and rape in a national advertising campaign
she said she expects ``exceptionally strong media play'' for the campaign with the media donating more than $70 million in free time and space this year, up from $40 million donated for the national united way campaign last year
the ads were created by the new york-based agency lowe marschalk inc., which took over responsibility for the campaign this year. the ads continue the theme ``the united way. it brings out the best in all of us.''
van der voort said the united way raised about $2.6 billion last year and channelled the money to 37,000 agencies that help people in some way
but she said research showed many people were unaware that united way donations helped organizations such as the salvation army provide coats to the homeless, rape crisis centers counsel abused women and the red cross provide training that often helps save the lives of heart attack victims
she said lowe marschalk was asked to ``tell a story in 30 seconds'' that demonstrates how donations help people in the community
twenty minutes ago, this man's last shred of dignity was stripped right off his back,'' a narrator says in the spot where a mugger tears the coat from a homeless man
where do you go when your world is this cold, this cruel,'' the voice asks as the homeless man shivers in the shadow of a stone column
the commercial then shows the man putting on a new coat, as lowe marschalk makes the connection it has been asked to draw in three succinct phrases
he got help at the salvation army. they got help from the united way. thank god, the united way got help from you,'' the narrator says
the advertising council is distributing the commercials and radio versions of the ads to networks, cable outlets and local stations across the country. print versions of the campaign should be ready in a month, said lowe marschalk's president, andrew j. langer
the agency has previously created public service campaigns for a free press, amnesty international and the city of new york
a company fined $604,000 for using foreign-made steel in hacksaws sold to the government will appeal a verdict that found it violated the buy american act, its attorney said thursday
it is not a rational interpretation of the buy american act,'' said jerome facher, who represented rule industries in the case
a u.s. district court jury on wednesday convicted rule industries and two of its executives of 302 violations of the act, which calls for goods purchased by the federal government for public use be manfactured with mostly american-made parts
the number of violations corresponds with the number of invoices the company submitted during its contracts with the general services administration in 1981 and 1982 totaling $1.3 million
the jury ruled the company was liable because it purchased 10-inch steel ``blanks'' from suppliers in sweden and japan. the blanks were milled, hardened and tempered in the united states
rulings in the case indicated that it would not have been a violation of the act had gloucester-based rule industries purchased sheets or coils of steel from foreign suppliers and cut the blanks from them
the act is really being interpreted in a bizarre fashion,'' facher said. ``it's a very complex and old piece of legislation that dates back to the depression and has never really been definitively interpreted by a court.''
the case is believed to be the first jury trial in the enforcement of the 55-year-old act, u.s. attorney frank l. mcnamara jr. said
mcnamara had filed a civil lawsuit in 1985 against rule industries, a diversified manufacturer of marine and hardware products; its president, william anastos, and its vice president, gary sable. each was charged with violating the act
the jury said the defendants falsely represented that domestic steel was used to fulfill four contracts with the gsa, the main contracting arm of the federal government
rule industries officials had said when the suit was filed the gsa was well aware of its steel-purchasing practices
during the trial, several former employees testified that rule industries executives hid the source of the steel by destroying containers shipped from overseas, blackening out foreign markings and removing shipping labels from packages
there were a number of very honest employees who got offended when their company lied to the government,'' said richard stearns, a first assistant u.s. attorney
the board of federated department stores inc. put off until friday a decision on whether to reaffirm its merger agreement with r.h. macy &amp; co. inc. or accept the competing bid of campeau corp
in a statement today, federated said both suitors presented revised bids of more than $6.6 billion each to the board at its day-long meeting wednesday
the board had been expected to announce today whether it would reaffirm its support for its agreement with macy or reverse itself and choose campeau's offer
however, federated said macy submitted another revised offer this morning and the board would meet again friday morning to consider both bids
for the first time since it announced its cash-and-stock offer a month ago, macy put a value on the stock end of its bid and also gave shareholders the option of taking all cash for their shares, federated said in a statement
in its bid today, macy offered $78.92 a share in cash for 80 percent of federated's 89.5 million outstanding shares, and said it would pay $60 in cash or exchange five shares in a new company, macy's-federated inc., for each remaining federated share
the deal had a blended value of $75.14 a share, or a total of $6.73 billion, federated said
in its latest bid, campeau offered to pay $74 a share for approximately 80 percent of federated's shares, and the same amount for the remaining 20 percent after a merger, federated said. that would make the toronto-based developer's bid worth $6.62 billion
thomas tashjian, an analyst with seidler amdec securities inc. in los angeles, said macy had an edge over campeau with the offers now on the table, but he cautioned, ``campeau could always come out and say they're going to offer a higher bid.''
wall street analysts had said macy would be forced to put a value on the ``stub'' _ or securities _ portion of its offer to compete with campeau. many investors, including arbitragers who hold a sizeable portion of federated stock, were leaning toward the certainty of campeau's all-cash offer
investors reacted enthusiastically to the higher bidding. federated stock was up $2.25 to $72.50 in early afternoon trading on the new york stock exchange
before wednesday's meeting, campeau offered $73 a share in cash, or $6.53 billion. campeau had said it would pay $82 each for 70.5 million federated shares and $37 for each of the remainder of federated's 89.5 million outstanding shares in a subsequent merger
campeau also had proposed a friendly merger under which it would pay $73 a share for 70.5 million shares in a tender offer and $73 for the remaining shares following the merger
macy's offer prior to the federated board meeting on wednesday was $77.35 a share in cash for 70.43 million federated shares, for a total of $5.4 billion. macy said it would exchange shares in the merged company and issue convertible debt securities for the remainder of federated's shares. analysts valued the offer at $6.3 billion
federated said macy presented an offer at the meeting similar to today's proposal, but which had an aggregate value of $73.88 a share or a total of $6.61 billion. that offer was superseded by today's bid
campeau had no comment on the latest macy bid, campeau spokeswoman joele frank said
federated gave macy chairman edward finkelstein and campeau chairman robert campeau the opportunity to address the board on wednesday, but the new york times reported in today's editions that campeau declined to appear. finkelstein spoke to the directors and presented ``his vision of the combined company,'' the times said
campeau has fought the merger agreement federated forged with macy a month ago with lawsuits and higher bids. if federated's directors again select macy's offer, toronto-based campeau is expected to continue in court the battle it began with a $47-a-share offer on jan. 25
macy's offer was scheduled to expire monday. the expiration of the campeau offer was uncertain, pending completion of financing requirements for the acquisition
federated had given both companies the chance to submit what it called ``final bids'' after campeau's most recent offer
on tuesday, the companies were in court after federated announced procedures for the submission of final offers. campeau objected to the guidelines on grounds they favored macy, but u.s. district judge leonard sand denied the canadian company's request for a temporary restraining order blocking the procedures
campeau argued the procedures were illegal because they embraced federated's ``poison pill'' takeover defense and agreements between federated and macy
federated asked that whichever company was not chosen either terminate its offer or extend it for 30 business days. an extension would give the advantage to whichever company federated backed, because shareholders would likely tender their shares to the suitor whose offer expired first
sand stipulated that federated could not invoke defensive measures _ including its controversial poison pill _ before the losing party had a chance to challenge those measures in court
the poison pill would make a takeover attempt more expensive by allowing the retailer's shareholders to buy more company stock at a discount, unless federated's management supported the bid. campeau had sought unsuccessfully in court to have the pill invalidated
campeau also objected to an agreement under which federated would pay macy ``break-up'' fees if a macy-federated merger failed for reasons other than a macy default
federated's divisions include bloomingdale's, burdine's, filene's, foley's, lazarus and rich's department stores; ralphs supermarkets; gold circle discount stores; and main street and children's place specialty stores
macy owns nearly 100 department and specialty stores
campeau, which started in real estate development in canada, moved into the u.s. retail market at the end of 1986 by acquiring allied stores corp
postal instant press inc., the nation's largest franchiser of printing centers, said thursday it has agreed to be taken private by a management-led investor group for $67.9 million, or $17.41 per share
the pact ends six weeks of on-again, off-again acquisition negotiations
an earlier, $17-per-share bid by the management group, headed by pip's chief executive thomas marotto, was permitted to expire two weeks ago when the company entered into talks with an unidentified third party that was offering $17.50 per share, or $68.25 million
however, pip said thursday that ``serious questions arose as to the firmness of that offer'' and marotto's group boosted its bid
pip has 3.9 million shares outstanding
marotto's group includes the chicago-based investment firm of golder thoma &amp; cressey, which specializes in leveraged buyouts in which the assets of the firm being acquired are pledged as collateral to line up takeover financing
pip has about 1,000 printing centers in the united states, canada and the united kingdom, all but a few of them franchised
last year, the company escaped a hostile bid by tarrytown, n.y.-based kane-miller corp
ford motor co. illegally charged $100 deductibles to perform some automobile repairs it should have done in new york state for free under the state's lemon law, a mid-level state appeals court ruled
the appellate division of the state's supreme court decided thursday that ford was ``unjustly enriched'' by charging new york consumers the deductibles and must make restitution
new york state attorney general robert abrams contended in court that the state's 1983 lemon law, designed to provide new yorkers with replacement vehicles or money back if their new cars exhibit irreparable flaws, did not allow ford to impose the deductibles
according to court papers, ford paid the cost of all repairs for its new cars during the first 12 months or 12,000 miles. but under an extended limited warranty, the automaker charged $100 each time it made repairs to the power train and other major components of cars with 12,000 to 18,000 miles or between one and two years old
abrams argued in court that the state's lemon law prohibits automakers from imposing a deductible for repairs on new cars during their first 18,000 miles or two years
a state supreme court justice in albany, harold hughes, ruled in december 1986 that the lemon law prohibits ford from imposing the deductibles, but he did not order the automaker to provide restitution
in the 5-0 ruling by the appellate division thursday, however, presiding justice a. franklin mahoney said he and his colleagues ``choose to exercise our discretion'' by ordering ford to give the money back
mahoney rejected arguments by ford attorneys that new york's lemon law is unconstitutional and that it violates interstate commerce laws
mahoney conceded that while ford may not have detailed records of all customers it improperly charged for repairs, ``it would not be impracticable to give purchasers during the relevant time period a general notice and a time period to come forward.''
mahoney sent the matter back to the state supreme court level to devise an ``appropriate restitution procedure'' for ford to follow
he was joined in his decision by state supreme court justices t. paul kane, john casey, leonard weiss and thomas mercure
nancy connell, a spokeswoman for abrams, said the attorney general's office has no accurate total of how many new yorkers were improperly charged the deductibles. but she said it's believed refunds could total ``in the millions of dollars.''
philip lacovara, a washington-based attorney who represented ford in the case, did not immediately return a telephone call seeking comment
the ruling could be appealed to the state's highest court, the court of appeals. represented rockefellers, sultan and cosby, but he did not actually represent them; also running on general news wires</note>
wall street ``whiz kid'' david bloom pleaded guilty to mail and securities fraud today for allegedly bilking investors out of $10 million which the 23-year-old sunk into art work, cars and two fully furnished homes for himself
i said i was a money manager, but i did not invest their money as i told them i would,'' the baby-faced 1986 duke university graduate told u.s. district judge david edelstein
bloom told duped investors that he also represented the rockefeller family, the sultan of brunei and bill cosby, even though he didn't
bloom, who was once profiled in a new york times magazine feature on new art collectors, faces five years in prison and a maximum fine of double the amount lost by investors at his may 12 sentencing. no sentencing agreement accompanied his guilty plea
wearing a dark gray suit, white shirt and blue tie, bloom stood with his hands behind his back and politely answered edelstein's questions about the scam during a 25-minute hearing
asked if he realized his ``money management'' operation was illegal, bloom responded, ``yes, your honor.''
according to court papers, bloom _ who was not licensed as an investment advisor _ used his clients' funds to buy $5.5 million in art work; a $1.9 million east hampton beach house; an $830,000 manhattan apartment; $800,000 in furnishings for the two homes; and two cars worth $200,000
the defendant also bought ``numerous items of expensive jewelry and deluxe trips to the caribbean'' for himself, family and friends, federal prosecutors charged
all the art work will be auctioned at sotheby's near the end of may, with the chance that some investors could still make a profit, said bloom's attorney, peter morrison
bloom was arrested jan. 14 on a federal complaint; he had 130 clients at his greater sutton investors at the time of his arrest
grain and soybean futures closed mixed thursday on the chicago board of trade in light trading ahead of two important government reports and the three-day holiday weekend, analysts said
the agriculture department's annual report on spring planting intentions and its quarterly report on grain stocks, both due out after the close on thursday, were expected to set the trend for corn and soybean futures prices for the next 30 days
together, the reports were expected to indicate whether futures prices should go higher to encourage more planting to meet the expected demand, or lower to discourage plantings, analysts said
the reports were to be released at 2 p.m. cst. the markets cannot react until monday, however, because they will be closed friday
soybean prices advanced in thursday's session while wheat and corn prices retreated
