westinghouse electric corp. said thursday it plans a broad series of joint ventures with siemens a.g., the giant european electrical equipment manufacturer
these agreements will strengthen the competitive position of both companies in today's global markets by combining our respective world-leading technologies and capabilities,'' westinghouse chairman john c. marous said in announcing the signing of a letter of intent
the two companies together will make, sell and service factory automation equipment, industrial circuit breakers and industrial controls, westinghouse said. the joint ventures, covering more than 20 products, will operate in selected world markets, including the united states
westinghouse, the largest u.s. electrical equipment manufacturer, said it will own 51 percent of the joint ventures, which will need the approval of government regulators and directors of both companies.
westinghouse and siemens have cooperated in various ways as customers and in licensing agreements for more than 50 years, marous said
the approximately 358,000 employees of munich-based siemens generated 1987 sales of $30.4 billion. the 110,000 employees of pittsburgh-based westinghouse generated 1987 sales of $10.7 billion
the joint ventures in factory automation will combine existing westinghouse operations that employ 2,700 people, 1,700 of them in the united states, and siemens operations in peabody, mass., and roswell, ga., employing 370 people
businesses will be created to fulfill plans for the other two areas, industrial circuit breakers and industrial controls, said westinghouse spokesman james p. schmitt
